{"code":1,"isDone":false,"toInsertArticleList":[{"createdTime":"2020-08-25 05:36:56","updatedTime":"2020-08-25 05:36:56","title":"Homogenization of iterated singular integrals with applications to random quasiconformal maps","link":"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11837","description":"<p> <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kari_Astala\">Kari Astala</a>, <a href=\"https://sites.math.washington.edu/~rohde/\">Steffen Rohde</a>, <a href=\"https://researchportal.helsinki.fi/en/persons/eero-saksman\">Eero Saksman</a> and I have (finally!) uploaded to the arXiv our preprint “<a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2006.11602\">Homogenization of iterated singular integrals with applications to random quasiconformal maps</a>“. This project started (and was largely completed) over a decade ago, but for various reasons it was not finalised until very recently. The motivation for this project was to study the behaviour of “random” quasiconformal maps. Recall that a (smooth) <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quasiconformal_mapping\">quasiconformal map</a> is a homeomorphism <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%3A+%7B%5Cbf+C%7D+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cbf+C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f: {\\bf C} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" title=\"{f: {\\bf C} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" class=\"latex\" /> that obeys the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beltrami_equation\">Beltrami equation</a> </p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpartial+f%7D%7B%5Cpartial+%5Coverline%7Bz%7D%7D+%3D+%5Cmu+%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpartial+f%7D%7B%5Cpartial+z%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial \\overline{z}} = \\mu \\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial z}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial \\overline{z}} = \\mu \\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial z}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> for some \n<em>Beltrami coefficient</em> \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmu%3A+%7B%5Cbf+C%7D+%5Crightarrow+D%280%2C1%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\mu: {\\bf C} \\rightarrow D(0,1)}\" title=\"{\\mu: {\\bf C} \\rightarrow D(0,1)}\" class=\"latex\" />; this can be viewed as a deformation of the Cauchy-Riemann equation \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpartial+f%7D%7B%5Cpartial+%5Coverline%7Bz%7D%7D+%3D+0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial \\overline{z}} = 0}\" title=\"{\\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial \\overline{z}} = 0}\" class=\"latex\" />. Assuming that \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%28z%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f(z)}\" title=\"{f(z)}\" class=\"latex\" /> is asymptotic to \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bz%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{z}\" title=\"{z}\" class=\"latex\" /> at infinity, one can (formally, at least) solve for \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f}\" title=\"{f}\" class=\"latex\" /> in terms of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmu%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\mu}\" title=\"{\\mu}\" class=\"latex\" /> using the \n<em>Beurling transform</em> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++Tf%28z%29+%3A%3D+%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpartial%7D%7B%5Cpartial+z%7D%28%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpartial+f%7D%7B%5Cpartial+%5Coverline%7Bz%7D%7D%29%5E%7B-1%7D%28z%29+%3D+-%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B%5Cpi%7D+p.v.+%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+C%7D+%5Cfrac%7Bf%28w%29%7D%7B%28w-z%29%5E2%7D%5C+dw&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  Tf(z) := \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial z}(\\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial \\overline{z}})^{-1}(z) = -\\frac{1}{\\pi} p.v. \\int_{\\bf C} \\frac{f(w)}{(w-z)^2}\\ dw\" title=\"\\displaystyle  Tf(z) := \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial z}(\\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial \\overline{z}})^{-1}(z) = -\\frac{1}{\\pi} p.v. \\int_{\\bf C} \\frac{f(w)}{(w-z)^2}\\ dw\" class=\"latex\" /></p> by the Neumann series \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpartial+f%7D%7B%5Cpartial+%5Coverline%7Bz%7D%7D+%3D+%5Cmu+%2B+%5Cmu+T+%5Cmu+%2B+%5Cmu+T+%5Cmu+T+%5Cmu+%2B+%5Cdots.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial \\overline{z}} = \\mu + \\mu T \\mu + \\mu T \\mu T \\mu + \\dots.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial \\overline{z}} = \\mu + \\mu T \\mu + \\mu T \\mu T \\mu + \\dots.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> We looked at the question of the asymptotic behaviour of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f}\" title=\"{f}\" class=\"latex\" /> if \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmu+%3D+%5Cmu_%5Cdelta%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\mu = \\mu_\\delta}\" title=\"{\\mu = \\mu_\\delta}\" class=\"latex\" /> is a random field that oscillates at some fine spatial scale \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cdelta%3E0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\delta>0}\" title=\"{\\delta>0}\" class=\"latex\" />. A simple model to keep in mind is \n<a name=\"mud\"><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cmu_%5Cdelta%28z%29+%3D+%5Cvarphi%28z%29+%5Csum_%7Bn+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%5E2%7D+%5Cepsilon_n+1_%7Bn%5Cdelta+%2B+%5B0%2C%5Cdelta%5D%5E2%7D%28z%29+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%281%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\mu_\\delta(z) = \\varphi(z) \\sum_{n \\in {\\bf Z}^2} \\epsilon_n 1_{n\\delta + [0,\\delta]^2}(z) \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (1)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\mu_\\delta(z) = \\varphi(z) \\sum_{n \\in {\\bf Z}^2} \\epsilon_n 1_{n\\delta + [0,\\delta]^2}(z) \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (1)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> </a> where \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cepsilon_n+%3D+%5Cpm+1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\epsilon_n = \\pm 1}\" title=\"{\\epsilon_n = \\pm 1}\" class=\"latex\" /> are independent random signs and \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cvarphi%3A+%7B%5Cbf+C%7D+%5Crightarrow+D%280%2C1%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\varphi: {\\bf C} \\rightarrow D(0,1)}\" title=\"{\\varphi: {\\bf C} \\rightarrow D(0,1)}\" class=\"latex\" /> is a bump function. For models such as these, we show that a homogenisation occurs in the limit \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cdelta+%5Crightarrow+0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\delta \\rightarrow 0}\" title=\"{\\delta \\rightarrow 0}\" class=\"latex\" />; each multilinear expression \n<a name=\"mudt\"><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cmu_%5Cdelta+T+%5Cmu_%5Cdelta+%5Cdots+T+%5Cmu_%5Cdelta+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%282%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\mu_\\delta T \\mu_\\delta \\dots T \\mu_\\delta \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (2)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\mu_\\delta T \\mu_\\delta \\dots T \\mu_\\delta \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (2)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> </a> converges weakly in probability (and almost surely, if we restrict \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cdelta%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\delta}\" title=\"{\\delta}\" class=\"latex\" /> to a lacunary sequence) to a deterministic limit, and the associated quasiconformal map \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%3D+f_%5Cdelta%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f = f_\\delta}\" title=\"{f = f_\\delta}\" class=\"latex\" /> similarly converges weakly in probability (or almost surely). (Results of this latter type were also recently obtained \n<a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/1905.07932\">by Ivrii and Markovic</a> by a more geometric method which is simpler, but is applied to a narrower class of Beltrami coefficients.) In the specific case \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11837#mud\">(1)</a>, the limiting quasiconformal map is just the identity map \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%28z%29%3Dz%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f(z)=z}\" title=\"{f(z)=z}\" class=\"latex\" />, but if for instance replaces the \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cepsilon_n%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\epsilon_n}\" title=\"{\\epsilon_n}\" class=\"latex\" /> by non-symmetric random variables then one can have significantly more complicated limits. The convergence theorem for multilinear expressions such as is not specific to the Beurling transform \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T}\" title=\"{T}\" class=\"latex\" />; any other translation and dilation invariant singular integral can be used here. \n<p> The random expression <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11837#mudt\">(2)</a> is somewhat reminiscent of a moment of a random matrix, and one can start computing it analogously. For instance, if one has a decomposition <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmu_%5Cdelta+%3D+%5Csum_%7Bn+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%5E2%7D+%5Cmu_%7B%5Cdelta%2Cn%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\mu_\\delta = \\sum_{n \\in {\\bf Z}^2} \\mu_{\\delta,n}}\" title=\"{\\mu_\\delta = \\sum_{n \\in {\\bf Z}^2} \\mu_{\\delta,n}}\" class=\"latex\" /> such as <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11837#mud\">(1)</a>, then <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11837#mudt\">(2)</a> expands out as a sum </p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Csum_%7Bn_1%2C%5Cdots%2Cn_k+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%5E2%7D+%5Cmu_%7B%5Cdelta%2Cn_1%7D+T+%5Cmu_%7B%5Cdelta%2Cn_2%7D+%5Cdots+T+%5Cmu_%7B%5Cdelta%2Cn_k%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{n_1,\\dots,n_k \\in {\\bf Z}^2} \\mu_{\\delta,n_1} T \\mu_{\\delta,n_2} \\dots T \\mu_{\\delta,n_k}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{n_1,\\dots,n_k \\in {\\bf Z}^2} \\mu_{\\delta,n_1} T \\mu_{\\delta,n_2} \\dots T \\mu_{\\delta,n_k}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> The random fluctuations of this sum can be treated by a routine second moment estimate, and the main task is to show that the expected value \n<a name=\"expect\"><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Csum_%7Bn_1%2C%5Cdots%2Cn_k+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%5E2%7D+%5Cmathop%7B%5Cbf+E%7D%28%5Cmu_%7B%5Cdelta%2Cn_1%7D+T+%5Cmu_%7B%5Cdelta%2Cn_2%7D+%5Cdots+T+%5Cmu_%7B%5Cdelta%2Cn_k%7D%29+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%283%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{n_1,\\dots,n_k \\in {\\bf Z}^2} \\mathop{\\bf E}(\\mu_{\\delta,n_1} T \\mu_{\\delta,n_2} \\dots T \\mu_{\\delta,n_k}) \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (3)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{n_1,\\dots,n_k \\in {\\bf Z}^2} \\mathop{\\bf E}(\\mu_{\\delta,n_1} T \\mu_{\\delta,n_2} \\dots T \\mu_{\\delta,n_k}) \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (3)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> </a> becomes asymptotically independent of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cdelta%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\delta}\" title=\"{\\delta}\" class=\"latex\" />. \n<p> If all the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bn_1%2C%5Cdots%2Cn_k%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{n_1,\\dots,n_k}\" title=\"{n_1,\\dots,n_k}\" class=\"latex\" /> were distinct then one could use independence to factor the expectation to get </p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Csum_%7Bn_1%2C%5Cdots%2Cn_k+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%5E2%7D+%5Cmathop%7B%5Cbf+E%7D%28%5Cmu_%7B%5Cdelta%2Cn_1%7D%29+T+%5Cmathop%7B%5Cbf+E%7D%28%5Cmu_%7B%5Cdelta%2Cn_2%7D%29+%5Cdots+T+%5Cmathop%7B%5Cbf+E%7D%28%5Cmu_%7B%5Cdelta%2Cn_k%7D%29+&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{n_1,\\dots,n_k \\in {\\bf Z}^2} \\mathop{\\bf E}(\\mu_{\\delta,n_1}) T \\mathop{\\bf E}(\\mu_{\\delta,n_2}) \\dots T \\mathop{\\bf E}(\\mu_{\\delta,n_k}) \" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{n_1,\\dots,n_k \\in {\\bf Z}^2} \\mathop{\\bf E}(\\mu_{\\delta,n_1}) T \\mathop{\\bf E}(\\mu_{\\delta,n_2}) \\dots T \\mathop{\\bf E}(\\mu_{\\delta,n_k}) \" class=\"latex\" /></p> which is a relatively straightforward expression to calculate (particularly in the model \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11837#mud\">(1)</a>, where all the expectations here in fact vanish). The main difficulty is that there are a number of configurations in \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11837#expect\">(3)</a> in which various of the \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bn_j%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{n_j}\" title=\"{n_j}\" class=\"latex\" /> collide with each other, preventing one from easily factoring the expression. A typical problematic contribution for instance would be a sum of the form \n<a name=\"non-eni\"><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Csum_%7Bn_1%2Cn_2+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%5E2%3A+n_1+%5Cneq+n_2%7D+%5Cmathop%7B%5Cbf+E%7D%28%5Cmu_%7B%5Cdelta%2Cn_1%7D+T+%5Cmu_%7B%5Cdelta%2Cn_2%7D+T+%5Cmu_%7B%5Cdelta%2Cn_1%7D+T+%5Cmu_%7B%5Cdelta%2Cn_2%7D%29.+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%284%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{n_1,n_2 \\in {\\bf Z}^2: n_1 \\neq n_2} \\mathop{\\bf E}(\\mu_{\\delta,n_1} T \\mu_{\\delta,n_2} T \\mu_{\\delta,n_1} T \\mu_{\\delta,n_2}). \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (4)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{n_1,n_2 \\in {\\bf Z}^2: n_1 \\neq n_2} \\mathop{\\bf E}(\\mu_{\\delta,n_1} T \\mu_{\\delta,n_2} T \\mu_{\\delta,n_1} T \\mu_{\\delta,n_2}). \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (4)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> </a> This is an example of what we call a \n<em>non-split</em> sum. This can be compared with the \n<em>split sum</em> \n<a name=\"eni\"><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Csum_%7Bn_1%2Cn_2+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%5E2%3A+n_1+%5Cneq+n_2%7D+%5Cmathop%7B%5Cbf+E%7D%28%5Cmu_%7B%5Cdelta%2Cn_1%7D+T+%5Cmu_%7B%5Cdelta%2Cn_1%7D+T+%5Cmu_%7B%5Cdelta%2Cn_2%7D+T+%5Cmu_%7B%5Cdelta%2Cn_2%7D%29.+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%285%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{n_1,n_2 \\in {\\bf Z}^2: n_1 \\neq n_2} \\mathop{\\bf E}(\\mu_{\\delta,n_1} T \\mu_{\\delta,n_1} T \\mu_{\\delta,n_2} T \\mu_{\\delta,n_2}). \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (5)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{n_1,n_2 \\in {\\bf Z}^2: n_1 \\neq n_2} \\mathop{\\bf E}(\\mu_{\\delta,n_1} T \\mu_{\\delta,n_1} T \\mu_{\\delta,n_2} T \\mu_{\\delta,n_2}). \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (5)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> </a> If we ignore the constraint \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bn_1+%5Cneq+n_2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{n_1 \\neq n_2}\" title=\"{n_1 \\neq n_2}\" class=\"latex\" /> in the latter sum, then it splits into \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++f_%5Cdelta+T+g_%5Cdelta+&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  f_\\delta T g_\\delta \" title=\"\\displaystyle  f_\\delta T g_\\delta \" class=\"latex\" /></p> where \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++f_%5Cdelta+%3A%3D+%5Csum_%7Bn_1+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%5E2%7D+%5Cmathop%7B%5Cbf+E%7D%28%5Cmu_%7B%5Cdelta%2Cn_1%7D+T+%5Cmu_%7B%5Cdelta%2Cn_1%7D%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  f_\\delta := \\sum_{n_1 \\in {\\bf Z}^2} \\mathop{\\bf E}(\\mu_{\\delta,n_1} T \\mu_{\\delta,n_1})\" title=\"\\displaystyle  f_\\delta := \\sum_{n_1 \\in {\\bf Z}^2} \\mathop{\\bf E}(\\mu_{\\delta,n_1} T \\mu_{\\delta,n_1})\" class=\"latex\" /></p> and \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++g_%5Cdelta+%3A%3D+%5Csum_%7Bn_2+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%5E2%7D+%5Cmathop%7B%5Cbf+E%7D%28%5Cmu_%7B%5Cdelta%2Cn_2%7D+T+%5Cmu_%7B%5Cdelta%2Cn_2%7D%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  g_\\delta := \\sum_{n_2 \\in {\\bf Z}^2} \\mathop{\\bf E}(\\mu_{\\delta,n_2} T \\mu_{\\delta,n_2})\" title=\"\\displaystyle  g_\\delta := \\sum_{n_2 \\in {\\bf Z}^2} \\mathop{\\bf E}(\\mu_{\\delta,n_2} T \\mu_{\\delta,n_2})\" class=\"latex\" /></p> and one can hope to treat this sum by an induction hypothesis. (To actually deal with constraints such as \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bn_1+%5Cneq+n_2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{n_1 \\neq n_2}\" title=\"{n_1 \\neq n_2}\" class=\"latex\" /> requires an inclusion-exclusion argument that creates some notational headaches but is ultimately manageable.) As the name suggests, the non-split configurations such as \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11837#non-eni\">(4)</a> cannot be factored in this fashion, and are the most difficult to handle. A direct computation using the triangle inequality (and a certain amount of combinatorics and induction) reveals that these sums are somewhat localised, in that dyadic portions such as \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Csum_%7Bn_1%2Cn_2+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%5E2%3A+%7Cn_1+-+n_2%7C+%5Csim+R%7D+%5Cmathop%7B%5Cbf+E%7D%28%5Cmu_%7B%5Cdelta%2Cn_1%7D+T+%5Cmu_%7B%5Cdelta%2Cn_2%7D+T+%5Cmu_%7B%5Cdelta%2Cn_1%7D+T+%5Cmu_%7B%5Cdelta%2Cn_2%7D%29+&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{n_1,n_2 \\in {\\bf Z}^2: |n_1 - n_2| \\sim R} \\mathop{\\bf E}(\\mu_{\\delta,n_1} T \\mu_{\\delta,n_2} T \\mu_{\\delta,n_1} T \\mu_{\\delta,n_2}) \" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{n_1,n_2 \\in {\\bf Z}^2: |n_1 - n_2| \\sim R} \\mathop{\\bf E}(\\mu_{\\delta,n_1} T \\mu_{\\delta,n_2} T \\mu_{\\delta,n_1} T \\mu_{\\delta,n_2}) \" class=\"latex\" /></p> exhibit power decay in \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BR%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{R}\" title=\"{R}\" class=\"latex\" /> (when measured in suitable function space norms), basically because of the large number of times one has to transition back and forth between \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bn_1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{n_1}\" title=\"{n_1}\" class=\"latex\" /> and \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bn_2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{n_2}\" title=\"{n_2}\" class=\"latex\" />. Thus, morally at least, the dominant contribution to a non-split sum such as \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11837#non-eni\">(4)</a> comes from the local portion when \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bn_2%3Dn_1%2BO%281%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{n_2=n_1+O(1)}\" title=\"{n_2=n_1+O(1)}\" class=\"latex\" />. From the translation and dilation invariance of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T}\" title=\"{T}\" class=\"latex\" /> this type of expression then simplifies to something like \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cvarphi%28z%29%5E4+%5Csum_%7Bn+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%5E2%7D+%5Ceta%28+%5Cfrac%7Bn-z%7D%7B%5Cdelta%7D+%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\varphi(z)^4 \\sum_{n \\in {\\bf Z}^2} \\eta( \\frac{n-z}{\\delta} )\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\varphi(z)^4 \\sum_{n \\in {\\bf Z}^2} \\eta( \\frac{n-z}{\\delta} )\" class=\"latex\" /></p> (plus negligible errors) for some reasonably decaying function \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Ceta%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\eta}\" title=\"{\\eta}\" class=\"latex\" />, and this can be shown to converge to a weak limit as \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cdelta+%5Crightarrow+0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\delta \\rightarrow 0}\" title=\"{\\delta \\rightarrow 0}\" class=\"latex\" />. \n<p> In principle all of these limits are computable, but the combinatorics is remarkably complicated, and while there is certainly some algebraic structure to the calculations, it does not seem to be easily describable in terms of an existing framework (e.g., that of free probability). </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p></p>","descriptionType":"html","publishedDate":"Tue, 23 Jun 2020 07:01:40 a2cf7e63.webp"},"publishedOrCreatedDate":1598305016219},{"createdTime":"2020-08-25 heuristic</em>, briefly mentioned in the <a href=\"https://terrytao.wordpress.com/2020/03/29/247b-notes-1-restriction-theory/\">preceding set of notes</a>, predicts that if a collection <img phases that are sufficiently “independent” of each other, then</p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7C%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+z_j%7C+%5Capprox+%28%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+%7Cz_j%7C%5E2%29%5E%7B1%2F2%7D%3B&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  |\\sum_{j=1}^n z_j| \\approx (\\sum_{j=1}^n |z_j|^2)^{1/2};\" title=\"\\displaystyle  |\\sum_{j=1}^n z_j| \\approx (\\sum_{j=1}^n |z_j|^2)^{1/2};\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p>similarly, if <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf_1%2C%5Cdots%2Cf_n%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f_1,\\dots,f_n}\" title=\"{f_1,\\dots,f_n}\" class=\"latex\" /> are a collection of functions in a Lebesgue space <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BL%5Ep%28X%2C%5Cmu%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{L^p(X,\\mu)}\" title=\"{L^p(X,\\mu)}\" class=\"latex\" /> that oscillate “independently” of each other, then we expect</p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+f_j+%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28X%2C%5Cmu%29%7D+%5Capprox+%5C%7C+%28%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+%7Cf_j%7C%5E2%29%5E%7B1%2F2%7D+%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28X%2C%5Cmu%29%7D.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n f_j \\|_{L^p(X,\\mu)} \\approx \\| (\\sum_{j=1}^n |f_j|^2)^{1/2} \\|_{L^p(X,\\mu)}.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n f_j \\|_{L^p(X,\\mu)} \\approx \\| (\\sum_{j=1}^n |f_j|^2)^{1/2} \\|_{L^p(X,\\mu)}.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p>We have already seen one instance in which this heuristic can be made precise, namely when the phases of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bz_j%2Cf_j%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{z_j,f_j}\" title=\"{z_j,f_j}\" class=\"latex\" /> are randomised by a random sign, so that Khintchine’s inequality (Lemma 4 from <a href=\"https://terrytao.wordpress.com/2020/03/29/247b-notes-1-restriction-theory/\">Notes 1</a>) can be applied. There are other contexts in which a <em>square function estimate</em></p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%28%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+%7Cf_j%7C%5E2%29%5E%7B1%2F2%7D+%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28X%2C%5Cmu%29%7D+%5Clesssim+%5C%7C+%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+f_j+%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28X%2C%5Cmu%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| (\\sum_{j=1}^n |f_j|^2)^{1/2} \\|_{L^p(X,\\mu)} \\lesssim \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n f_j \\|_{L^p(X,\\mu)}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| (\\sum_{j=1}^n |f_j|^2)^{1/2} \\|_{L^p(X,\\mu)} \\lesssim \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n f_j \\|_{L^p(X,\\mu)}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p>or a <em>reverse square function estimate</em></p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+f_j+%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28X%2C%5Cmu%29%7D+%5Clesssim+%5C%7C+%28%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+%7Cf_j%7C%5E2%29%5E%7B1%2F2%7D+%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28X%2C%5Cmu%29%7D+&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n f_j \\|_{L^p(X,\\mu)} \\lesssim \\| (\\sum_{j=1}^n |f_j|^2)^{1/2} \\|_{L^p(X,\\mu)} \" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n f_j \\|_{L^p(X,\\mu)} \\lesssim \\| (\\sum_{j=1}^n |f_j|^2)^{1/2} \\|_{L^p(X,\\mu)} \" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p>(or both) are known or conjectured to hold. For instance, the useful <em>Littlewood-Paley inequality</em> implies (among other things) that for any <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1+%3C+p+%3C+%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1 < p < \\infty}\" title=\"{1 < p < \\infty}\" class=\"latex\" />, we have the reverse square function estimate <a name=\"rse\"></a></p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+f_j+%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D+%5Clesssim_%7Bp%2Cd%7D+%5C%7C+%28%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+%7Cf_j%7C%5E2%29%5E%7B1%2F2%7D+%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D%2C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%281%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n f_j \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)} \\lesssim_{p,d} \\| (\\sum_{j=1}^n |f_j|^2)^{1/2} \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)}, \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (1)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n f_j \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)} \\lesssim_{p,d} \\| (\\sum_{j=1}^n |f_j|^2)^{1/2} \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)}, \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (1)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> whenever the Fourier transforms <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Chat+f_j%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\hat f_j}\" title=\"{\\hat f_j}\" class=\"latex\" /> of the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf_j%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f_j}\" title=\"{f_j}\" class=\"latex\" /> are supported on disjoint annuli <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7B+%5Cxi+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%3A+2%5E%7Bk_j%7D+%5Cleq+%7C%5Cxi%7C+%3C+2%5E%7Bk_j%2B1%7D+%5C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\{ \\xi \\in {\\bf R}^d: 2^{k_j} \\leq |\\xi| < 2^{k_j+1} \\}}\" title=\"{\\{ \\xi \\in {\\bf R}^d: 2^{k_j} \\leq |\\xi| < 2^{k_j+1} \\}}\" class=\"latex\" />, and we also have the matching square function estimate</p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%28%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+%7Cf_j%7C%5E2%29%5E%7B1%2F2%7D+%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D+%5Clesssim_%7Bp%2Cd%7D+%5C%7C+%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+f_j+%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D+&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| (\\sum_{j=1}^n |f_j|^2)^{1/2} \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)} \\lesssim_{p,d} \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n f_j \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)} \" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| (\\sum_{j=1}^n |f_j|^2)^{1/2} \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)} \\lesssim_{p,d} \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n f_j \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)} \" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p>if there is some separation between the annuli (for instance if the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk_j%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k_j}\" title=\"{k_j}\" class=\"latex\" /> are <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{2}\" title=\"{2}\" class=\"latex\" />-separated). We recall the proofs of these facts below the fold. In the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bp%3D2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{p=2}\" title=\"{p=2}\" class=\"latex\" /> case, we of course have Pythagoras’ theorem, which tells us that if the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf_j%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f_j}\" title=\"{f_j}\" class=\"latex\" /> are all orthogonal elements of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BL%5E2%28X%2C%5Cmu%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{L^2(X,\\mu)}\" title=\"{L^2(X,\\mu)}\" class=\"latex\" />, then</p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+f_j+%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28X%2C%5Cmu%29%7D+%3D+%28%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+%5C%7C+f_j+%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28X%2C%5Cmu%29%7D%5E2%29%5E%7B1%2F2%7D+%3D+%5C%7C+%28%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+%7Cf_j%7C%5E2%29%5E%7B1%2F2%7D+%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28X%2C%5Cmu%29%7D.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n f_j \\|_{L^2(X,\\mu)} = (\\sum_{j=1}^n \\| f_j \\|_{L^2(X,\\mu)}^2)^{1/2} = \\| (\\sum_{j=1}^n |f_j|^2)^{1/2} \\|_{L^2(X,\\mu)}.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n f_j \\|_{L^2(X,\\mu)} = (\\sum_{j=1}^n \\| f_j \\|_{L^2(X,\\mu)}^2)^{1/2} = \\| (\\sum_{j=1}^n |f_j|^2)^{1/2} \\|_{L^2(X,\\mu)}.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p>In particular, this identity holds if the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf_j+%5Cin+L%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f_j \\in L^2({\\bf R}^d)}\" title=\"{f_j \\in L^2({\\bf R}^d)}\" class=\"latex\" /> have <em>disjoint Fourier supports</em> in the sense that their Fourier transforms <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Chat+f_j%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\hat f_j}\" title=\"{\\hat f_j}\" class=\"latex\" /> are supported on disjoint sets. For <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bp%3D4%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{p=4}\" title=\"{p=4}\" class=\"latex\" />, the technique of <em>bi-orthogonality</em> can also give square function and reverse square function estimates in some cases, as we shall also see below the fold.<br /> In recent years, it has begun to be realised that in the regime <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bp+%3E+2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{p > 2}\" title=\"{p > 2}\" class=\"latex\" />, a variant of reverse square function estimates such as <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11649#rse\">(1)</a> is also useful, namely <em>decoupling estimates</em> such as <a name=\"decoup\"></a></p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+f_j+%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D+%5Clesssim_%7Bp%2Cd%7D+%28%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+%5C%7Cf_j%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D%5E2%29%5E%7B1%2F2%7D+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%282%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n f_j \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)} \\lesssim_{p,d} (\\sum_{j=1}^n \\|f_j\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)}^2)^{1/2} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (2)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n f_j \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)} \\lesssim_{p,d} (\\sum_{j=1}^n \\|f_j\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)}^2)^{1/2} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (2)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> (actually in practice we often permit small losses such as <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bn%5E%5Cvarepsilon%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{n^\\varepsilon}\" title=\"{n^\\varepsilon}\" class=\"latex\" /> on the right-hand side). An estimate such as <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11649#decoup\">(2)</a> is weaker than <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11649#rse\">(1)</a> when <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bp%5Cgeq+2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{p\\geq 2}\" title=\"{p\\geq 2}\" class=\"latex\" /> (or equal when <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bp%3D2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{p=2}\" title=\"{p=2}\" class=\"latex\" />), as can be seen by starting with the triangle inequality</p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+%7Cf_j%7C%5E2+%5C%7C_%7BL%5E%7Bp%2F2%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D+%5Cleq+%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+%5C%7C+%7Cf_j%7C%5E2+%5C%7C_%7BL%5E%7Bp%2F2%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D%2C&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n |f_j|^2 \\|_{L^{p/2}({\\bf R}^d)} \\leq \\sum_{j=1}^n \\| |f_j|^2 \\|_{L^{p/2}({\\bf R}^d)},\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n |f_j|^2 \\|_{L^{p/2}({\\bf R}^d)} \\leq \\sum_{j=1}^n \\| |f_j|^2 \\|_{L^{p/2}({\\bf R}^d)},\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p>and taking the square root of both side to conclude that <a name=\"rop\"></a></p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%28%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+%7Cf_j%7C%5E2%29%5E%7B1%2F2%7D+%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D+%5Cleq+%28%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+%5C%7Cf_j%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D%5E2%29%5E%7B1%2F2%7D.+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%283%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| (\\sum_{j=1}^n |f_j|^2)^{1/2} \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)} \\leq (\\sum_{j=1}^n \\|f_j\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)}^2)^{1/2}. \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (3)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| (\\sum_{j=1}^n |f_j|^2)^{1/2} \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)} \\leq (\\sum_{j=1}^n \\|f_j\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)}^2)^{1/2}. \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (3)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> However, the flip side of this weakness is that <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11649#decoup\">(2)</a> can be easier to prove. One key reason for this is the ability to <em>iterate</em> decoupling estimates such as <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11649#decoup\">(2)</a>, in a way that does not seem to be possible with reverse square function estimates such as <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11649#rse\">(1)</a>. For instance, suppose that one has a decoupling inequality such as <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11649#decoup\">(2)</a>, and furthermore each <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf_j%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f_j}\" title=\"{f_j}\" class=\"latex\" /> can be split further into components <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf_j%3D+%5Csum_%7Bk%3D1%7D%5Em+f_%7Bj%2Ck%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f_j= \\sum_{k=1}^m f_{j,k}}\" title=\"{f_j= \\sum_{k=1}^m f_{j,k}}\" class=\"latex\" /> for which one has the decoupling inequalities</p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%5Csum_%7Bk%3D1%7D%5Em+f_%7Bj%2Ck%7D+%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D+%5Clesssim_%7Bp%2Cd%7D+%28%5Csum_%7Bk%3D1%7D%5Em+%5C%7Cf_%7Bj%2Ck%7D%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D%5E2%29%5E%7B1%2F2%7D.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sum_{k=1}^m f_{j,k} \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)} \\lesssim_{p,d} (\\sum_{k=1}^m \\|f_{j,k}\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)}^2)^{1/2}.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sum_{k=1}^m f_{j,k} \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)} \\lesssim_{p,d} (\\sum_{k=1}^m \\|f_{j,k}\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)}^2)^{1/2}.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p>Then by inserting these bounds back into <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11649#decoup\">(2)</a> we see that we have the combined decoupling inequality</p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En%5Csum_%7Bk%3D1%7D%5Em+f_%7Bj%2Ck%7D+%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D+%5Clesssim_%7Bp%2Cd%7D+%28%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+%5Csum_%7Bk%3D1%7D%5Em+%5C%7Cf_%7Bj%2Ck%7D%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D%5E2%29%5E%7B1%2F2%7D.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n\\sum_{k=1}^m f_{j,k} \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)} \\lesssim_{p,d} (\\sum_{j=1}^n \\sum_{k=1}^m \\|f_{j,k}\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)}^2)^{1/2}.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n\\sum_{k=1}^m f_{j,k} \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)} \\lesssim_{p,d} (\\sum_{j=1}^n \\sum_{k=1}^m \\|f_{j,k}\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)}^2)^{1/2}.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p>This iterative feature of decoupling inequalities means that such inequalities work well with the method of <em>induction on scales</em>, that we introduced in the previous set of notes.<br /> In fact, decoupling estimates share many features in common with restriction theorems; in addition to induction on scales, there are several other techniques that first emerged in the restriction theory literature, such as wave packet decompositions, rescaling, and bilinear or multilinear reductions, that turned out to also be well suited to proving decoupling estimates. As with restriction, the <em>curvature</em> or <em>transversality</em> of the different Fourier supports of the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf_j%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f_j}\" title=\"{f_j}\" class=\"latex\" /> will be crucial in obtaining non-trivial estimates.<br /> Strikingly, in many important model cases, the optimal decoupling inequalities (except possibly for epsilon losses in the exponents) are now known. These estimates have in turn had a number of important applications, such as establishing certain discrete analogues of the restriction conjecture, or the first proof of the main conjecture for Vinogradov mean value theorems in analytic number theory.<br /> These notes only serve as a brief introduction to decoupling. A systematic exploration of this topic can be found in <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=3971577\">this recent text of Demeter</a>.<br /> <span id=\"more-11649\"></span></p> \n<p align=\"center\"><b> — 1. Square function and reverse square function estimates — </b></p> \n<p>We begin with a form of the Littlewood-Paley inequalities. Given a region <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5COmega+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\Omega \\in {\\bf R}^d}\" title=\"{\\Omega \\in {\\bf R}^d}\" class=\"latex\" />, we say that a tempered distribution <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f}\" title=\"{f}\" class=\"latex\" /> on <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf R}^d}\" title=\"{{\\bf R}^d}\" class=\"latex\" /> has <em>Fourier support in <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5COmega%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\Omega}\" title=\"{\\Omega}\" class=\"latex\" /></em> if its distributional Fourier transform <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Chat+f%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\hat f}\" title=\"{\\hat f}\" class=\"latex\" /> is supported in (the closure of) <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5COmega%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\Omega}\" title=\"{\\Omega}\" class=\"latex\" />.</p> \n<blockquote>\n <p><b>Theorem 1 (Littlewood-Paley inequalities)</b> <a name=\"lpi\"></a> Let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bd+%5Cgeq+1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{d \\geq 1}\" title=\"{d \\geq 1}\" class=\"latex\" />, let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk_1%2C%5Cdots%2Ck_n%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k_1,\\dots,k_n}\" title=\"{k_1,\\dots,k_n}\" class=\"latex\" /> be distinct integers, let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1+%3C+p+%3C+%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1 < p < \\infty}\" title=\"{1 < p < \\infty}\" class=\"latex\" />, and for each <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1+%5Cleq+j+%5Cleq+n%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1 \\leq j \\leq n}\" title=\"{1 \\leq j \\leq n}\" class=\"latex\" /> let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf_j+%5Cin+L%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f_j \\in L^p({\\bf R}^d)}\" title=\"{f_j \\in L^p({\\bf R}^d)}\" class=\"latex\" /> be a function with Fourier support in the annulus <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7B+%5Cxi+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%3A+2%5E%7Bk_j%7D+%5Cleq+%7C%5Cxi%7C+%5Cleq+2%5E%7Bk_j%2B1%7D%5C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\{ \\xi \\in {\\bf R}^d: 2^{k_j} \\leq |\\xi| \\leq 2^{k_j+1}\\}}\" title=\"{\\{ \\xi \\in {\\bf R}^d: 2^{k_j} \\leq |\\xi| \\leq 2^{k_j+1}\\}}\" class=\"latex\" />.</p> \n <ul> \n  <li>(i) (Reverse square function inequality) One has <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+f_j+%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D+%5Clesssim_%7Bp%2Cd%7D+%5C%7C+%28%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+%7Cf_j%7C%5E2%29%5E%7B1%2F2%7D+%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D.+&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n f_j \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)} \\lesssim_{p,d} \\| (\\sum_{j=1}^n |f_j|^2)^{1/2} \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)}. \" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n f_j \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)} \\lesssim_{p,d} \\| (\\sum_{j=1}^n |f_j|^2)^{1/2} \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)}. \" class=\"latex\" /></p> </li> \n  <li>(ii) (Square function inequality) If the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk_j%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k_j}\" title=\"{k_j}\" class=\"latex\" /> are <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{2}\" title=\"{2}\" class=\"latex\" />-separated (thus <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7Ck_j-k_%7Bj%27%7D%7C+%5Cgeq+2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{|k_j-k_{j'}| \\geq 2}\" title=\"{|k_j-k_{j'}| \\geq 2}\" class=\"latex\" /> for any <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1+%5Cleq+j+%3C+j%27+%5Cleq+n%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1 \\leq j < j' \\leq n}\" title=\"{1 \\leq j < j' \\leq n}\" class=\"latex\" />) then <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%28%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+%7Cf_j%7C%5E2%29%5E%7B1%2F2%7D+%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D+%5Clesssim_%7Bp%2Cd%7D+%5C%7C+%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+f_j+%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| (\\sum_{j=1}^n |f_j|^2)^{1/2} \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)} \\lesssim_{p,d} \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n f_j \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)}.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| (\\sum_{j=1}^n |f_j|^2)^{1/2} \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)} \\lesssim_{p,d} \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n f_j \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)}.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> </li> \n </ul> \n</blockquote> \n<p><em>Proof:</em> We begin with (ii). We use a randomisation argument. Let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cpsi+%5Cin+C%5E%5Cinfty_c%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\psi \\in C^\\infty_c({\\bf R}^d)}\" title=\"{\\psi \\in C^\\infty_c({\\bf R}^d)}\" class=\"latex\" /> be a bump function supported on the annulus <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7B+%5Cxi%3A+0.9+%5Cleq+%7C%5Cxi%7C+%5Cleq+2.1%5C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\{ \\xi: 0.9 \\leq |\\xi| \\leq 2.1\\}}\" title=\"{\\{ \\xi: 0.9 \\leq |\\xi| \\leq 2.1\\}}\" class=\"latex\" /> that equals one on <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7B+%5Cxi%3A+1+%5Cleq+%7C%5Cxi%7C+%5Cleq+2+%5C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\{ \\xi: 1 \\leq |\\xi| \\leq 2 \\}}\" title=\"{\\{ \\xi: 1 \\leq |\\xi| \\leq 2 \\}}\" class=\"latex\" />, and for each <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bj%3D1%2C%5Cdots%2Cn%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{j=1,\\dots,n}\" title=\"{j=1,\\dots,n}\" class=\"latex\" /> let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP_%7Bk_j%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P_{k_j}}\" title=\"{P_{k_j}}\" class=\"latex\" /> be the Fourier multiplier defined by</p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cwidehat%7BP_%7Bk_j%7D+f%7D%28%5Cxi%29+%3A%3D+%5Cpsi%28%5Cxi%2F2%5E%7Bk_j%7D%29+%5Chat+f%28%5Cxi%29%2C&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\widehat{P_{k_j} f}(\\xi) := \\psi(\\xi/2^{k_j}) \\hat f(\\xi),\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\widehat{P_{k_j} f}(\\xi) := \\psi(\\xi/2^{k_j}) \\hat f(\\xi),\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p>at least for functions <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f}\" title=\"{f}\" class=\"latex\" /> in the Schwartz class. Clearly the operator <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP_%7Bk_j%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P_{k_j}}\" title=\"{P_{k_j}}\" class=\"latex\" /> is given by convolution with a (<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk_j%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k_j}\" title=\"{k_j}\" class=\"latex\" />-dependent) Schwartz function, so this multiplier is bounded on every <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BL%5Ep%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{L^p}\" title=\"{L^p}\" class=\"latex\" /> space. Writing <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%3A%3D+%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+f_j%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f := \\sum_{j=1}^n f_j}\" title=\"{f := \\sum_{j=1}^n f_j}\" class=\"latex\" />, we see from the separation property of the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk_j%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k_j}\" title=\"{k_j}\" class=\"latex\" /> that we have the reproducing formula</p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++f_j+%3D+P_%7Bk_j%7D+f.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  f_j = P_{k_j} f.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  f_j = P_{k_j} f.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p>Now let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cepsilon_1%2C%5Cdots%2C%5Cepsilon_n+%5Cin+%5C%7B-1%2C%2B1%5C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\epsilon_1,\\dots,\\epsilon_n \\in \\{-1,+1\\}}\" title=\"{\\epsilon_1,\\dots,\\epsilon_n \\in \\{-1,+1\\}}\" class=\"latex\" /> be random signs drawn uniformly and independently at random, thus</p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+%5Cepsilon_j+f_j+%3D+%28%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+%5Cepsilon_j+P_%7Bk_j%7D%29+f.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{j=1}^n \\epsilon_j f_j = (\\sum_{j=1}^n \\epsilon_j P_{k_j}) f.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{j=1}^n \\epsilon_j f_j = (\\sum_{j=1}^n \\epsilon_j P_{k_j}) f.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p>The operator <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+%5Cepsilon_j+P_%7Bk_j%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\sum_{j=1}^n \\epsilon_j P_{k_j}}\" title=\"{\\sum_{j=1}^n \\epsilon_j P_{k_j}}\" class=\"latex\" /> is a Fourier multiplier with symbol <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+%5Cepsilon_n+%5Cpsi%28%5Cxi%2F2%5E%7Bk_j%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\sum_{j=1}^n \\epsilon_n \\psi(\\xi/2^{k_j})}\" title=\"{\\sum_{j=1}^n \\epsilon_n \\psi(\\xi/2^{k_j})}\" class=\"latex\" />. This symbol obeys the hypotheses of the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiplier_(Fourier_analysis)#Mikhlin_multiplier_theorem\">Hörmander-Miklin multiplier theorem</a>, uniformly in the choice of signs; since we are in the non-endpoint case <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1+%3C+p+%3C+%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1 < p < \\infty}\" title=\"{1 < p < \\infty}\" class=\"latex\" />, we thus have</p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+%5Cepsilon_j+f_j+%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D+%5Clesssim_%7Bp%2Cd%7D+%5C%7C+%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+f_j+%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n \\epsilon_j f_j \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)} \\lesssim_{p,d} \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n f_j \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n \\epsilon_j f_j \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)} \\lesssim_{p,d} \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n f_j \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p>uniformly in the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cepsilon_j%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\epsilon_j}\" title=\"{\\epsilon_j}\" class=\"latex\" />. Taking <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bp%5E%7Bth%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{p^{th}}\" title=\"{p^{th}}\" class=\"latex\" /> power means of this estimate using Khintchine’s inequality (Lemma 4 from <a href=\"https://terrytao.wordpress.com/2020/03/29/247b-notes-1-restriction-theory/\">Notes 1</a>), we obtain (ii) as desired.<br /> Now we turn to (i). By treating the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk_j%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k_j}\" title=\"{k_j}\" class=\"latex\" /> even and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk_j%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k_j}\" title=\"{k_j}\" class=\"latex\" /> odd cases separately and using the triangle inequality, we may assume without loss of generality that the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk_j%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k_j}\" title=\"{k_j}\" class=\"latex\" /> all have the same parity, so in particular are <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{2}\" title=\"{2}\" class=\"latex\" />-separated. (Why are we permitted to use this reduction for part (i) but not for part (ii)?) Now we use the projections <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP_%7Bk_j%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P_{k_j}}\" title=\"{P_{k_j}}\" class=\"latex\" /> from before in a slightly different way, noting that</p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++f_j+%3D+%5Cepsilon_j+P_%7Bk_j%7D+%5Csum_%7Bj%27%3D1%7D%5En+%5Cepsilon_%7Bj%27%7D+f_%7Bj%27%7D%2C&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  f_j = \\epsilon_j P_{k_j} \\sum_{j'=1}^n \\epsilon_{j'} f_{j'},\" title=\"\\displaystyle  f_j = \\epsilon_j P_{k_j} \\sum_{j'=1}^n \\epsilon_{j'} f_{j'},\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p>for any <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bj%3D1%2C%5Cdots%2Cn%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{j=1,\\dots,n}\" title=\"{j=1,\\dots,n}\" class=\"latex\" />, and hence</p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+f_j+%3D+%28%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+%5Cepsilon_j+P_%7Bk_j%7D%29+%5Csum_%7Bj%27%3D1%7D%5En+%5Cepsilon_%7Bj%27%7D+f_%7Bj%27%7D.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{j=1}^n f_j = (\\sum_{j=1}^n \\epsilon_j P_{k_j}) \\sum_{j'=1}^n \\epsilon_{j'} f_{j'}.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{j=1}^n f_j = (\\sum_{j=1}^n \\epsilon_j P_{k_j}) \\sum_{j'=1}^n \\epsilon_{j'} f_{j'}.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p>Applying the Hörmander-Mikhlin theorem as before, we conclude that</p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+f_j+%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D+%5Clesssim_%7Bp%2Cd%7D+%5C%7C+%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+%5Cepsilon_j+f_j+%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D+&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n f_j \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)} \\lesssim_{p,d} \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n \\epsilon_j f_j \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)} \" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n f_j \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)} \\lesssim_{p,d} \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n \\epsilon_j f_j \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)} \" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p>and on taking <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bp%5E%7Bth%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{p^{th}}\" title=\"{p^{th}}\" class=\"latex\" /> power means and using Khintchine’s inequality as before we conclude (i). <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5CBox&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\Box\" title=\"\\Box\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<blockquote>\n <p><b>Exercise 2 (Smooth Littlewood-Paley estimate)</b> <a name=\"smooth-ex\"></a> Let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bd+%5Cgeq+1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{d \\geq 1}\" title=\"{d \\geq 1}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1+%3C+p+%3C+%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1 < p < \\infty}\" title=\"{1 < p < \\infty}\" class=\"latex\" />, and let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cphi%5Cin+C%5E%5Cinfty_c%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\phi\\in C^\\infty_c({\\bf R}^d)}\" title=\"{\\phi\\in C^\\infty_c({\\bf R}^d)}\" class=\"latex\" /> be a bump function supported on <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BB%280%2C1%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{B(0,1)}\" title=\"{B(0,1)}\" class=\"latex\" /> that equals <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1}\" title=\"{1}\" class=\"latex\" /> on <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BB%280%2C1%2F2%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{B(0,1/2)}\" title=\"{B(0,1/2)}\" class=\"latex\" />. For any integer <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bj%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{j}\" title=\"{j}\" class=\"latex\" />, let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP_j%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P_j}\" title=\"{P_j}\" class=\"latex\" /> denote the Fourier multiplier, defined on Schwartz functions <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f}\" title=\"{f}\" class=\"latex\" /> by</p> \n <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cwidehat%7BP_j+f%7D%28%5Cxi%29+%3A%3D+%28%5Cphi%28%5Cxi%2F2%5Ej%29+-+%5Cphi%28%5Cxi%2F2%5E%7Bj-1%7D%29%29+%5Chat+f%28%5Cxi%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\widehat{P_j f}(\\xi) := (\\phi(\\xi/2^j) - \\phi(\\xi/2^{j-1})) \\hat f(\\xi)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\widehat{P_j f}(\\xi) := (\\phi(\\xi/2^j) - \\phi(\\xi/2^{j-1})) \\hat f(\\xi)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n <p>and extended to <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{L^p({\\bf R}^d)}\" title=\"{L^p({\\bf R}^d)}\" class=\"latex\" /> functions by continuity. Show that for any <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+L%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in L^p({\\bf R}^d)}\" title=\"{f \\in L^p({\\bf R}^d)}\" class=\"latex\" />, one has</p> \n <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%28%5Csum_%7Bj+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D+%7CP_j+f%7C%5E2%29%5E%7B1%2F2%7D+%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D+%5Csim_%7Bp%2Cd%7D+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| (\\sum_{j \\in {\\bf Z}} |P_j f|^2)^{1/2} \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)} \\sim_{p,d} \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| (\\sum_{j \\in {\\bf Z}} |P_j f|^2)^{1/2} \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)} \\sim_{p,d} \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n <p>(in particular, the left-hand side is finite).</p>\n</blockquote> \n<p>We remark that when <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bd%3D1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{d=1}\" title=\"{d=1}\" class=\"latex\" />, the condition that the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk_j%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k_j}\" title=\"{k_j}\" class=\"latex\" /> be <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{2}\" title=\"{2}\" class=\"latex\" />-separated can be removed from Theorem <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11649#lpi\">1</a>(ii), by using <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiplier_(Fourier_analysis)#Marcinkiewicz_multiplier_theorem\">the Marcinkiewicz multiplier theorem</a> in place of the Hörmander-Mikhlin multiplier theorem. But, perhaps surprisingly, the condition cannot be removed in higher dimensions, as a consequence of <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=296602\">Fefferman’s surprising result</a> on the unboundedness of the disk multiplier.</p> \n<blockquote>\n <p><b>Exercise 3 (Unboundedness of the disc multiplier)</b> Let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BD%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{D}\" title=\"{D}\" class=\"latex\" /> denote either the disk <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7B+%5Cxi%3A+%7C%5Cxi%7C+%5Cleq+1+%5C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\{ \\xi: |\\xi| \\leq 1 \\}}\" title=\"{\\{ \\xi: |\\xi| \\leq 1 \\}}\" class=\"latex\" /> or the annulus <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7B+%5Cxi%3A+1+%5Cleq+%7C%5Cxi%7C+%5Cleq+2+%5C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\{ \\xi: 1 \\leq |\\xi| \\leq 2 \\}}\" title=\"{\\{ \\xi: 1 \\leq |\\xi| \\leq 2 \\}}\" class=\"latex\" />. Let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP_%5COmega%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P_\\Omega}\" title=\"{P_\\Omega}\" class=\"latex\" /> denote the Fourier multiplier defined on Schwartz functions <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5E2%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R}^2)}\" title=\"{f \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R}^2)}\" class=\"latex\" /> by</p> \n <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cwidehat%7BP_%5COmega+f%7D%28%5Cxi%29+%3D+1_%5COmega%28%5Cxi%29+%5Chat+f%28%5Cxi%29.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\widehat{P_\\Omega f}(\\xi) = 1_\\Omega(\\xi) \\hat f(\\xi).\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\widehat{P_\\Omega f}(\\xi) = 1_\\Omega(\\xi) \\hat f(\\xi).\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n <p>Suppose that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1+%3C+p+%3C+%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1 < p < \\infty}\" title=\"{1 < p < \\infty}\" class=\"latex\" /> is such that <a name=\"disk\"></a></p> \n <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+P_D+f+%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5E2%29%7D+%5Clesssim_p+%5C%7C+f+%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5E2%29%7D+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%284%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| P_D f \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^2)} \\lesssim_p \\| f \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^2)} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (4)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| P_D f \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^2)} \\lesssim_p \\| f \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^2)} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (4)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n <p> for all <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5E2%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R}^2)}\" title=\"{f \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R}^2)}\" class=\"latex\" />.</p> \n <ul> \n  <li>(i) Show that for any collection <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BH_1%2C%5Cdots%2CH_n%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{H_1,\\dots,H_n}\" title=\"{H_1,\\dots,H_n}\" class=\"latex\" /> of half-planes in <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5E2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf R}^2}\" title=\"{{\\bf R}^2}\" class=\"latex\" />, and any functions <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf_1%2C%5Cdots%2Cf_n+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5E2%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f_1,\\dots,f_n \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R}^2)}\" title=\"{f_1,\\dots,f_n \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R}^2)}\" class=\"latex\" />, that <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%28%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+%7CP_%7BH_j%7D+f_j%7C%5E2%29%5E%7B1%2F2%7D+%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5E2%29%7D+%5Clesssim_p+%5C%7C+%28%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+%7Cf_j%7C%5E2%29%5E%7B1%2F2%7D+%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5E2%29%7D.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| (\\sum_{j=1}^n |P_{H_j} f_j|^2)^{1/2} \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^2)} \\lesssim_p \\| (\\sum_{j=1}^n |f_j|^2)^{1/2} \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^2)}.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| (\\sum_{j=1}^n |P_{H_j} f_j|^2)^{1/2} \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^2)} \\lesssim_p \\| (\\sum_{j=1}^n |f_j|^2)^{1/2} \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^2)}.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> <p>(<em>Hint:</em> first rescale the set <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BD%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{D}\" title=\"{D}\" class=\"latex\" /> by a large scaling factor <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BR%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{R}\" title=\"{R}\" class=\"latex\" />, apply the Marcinkiewicz-Zygmund theorem (Exercise 7 from <a href=\"https://terrytao.wordpress.com/2020/03/29/247b-notes-1-restriction-theory/\">Notes 1</a>), exploit the symmetries of the Fourier transform, then take a limit as <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BR+%5Crightarrow+%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{R \\rightarrow \\infty}\" title=\"{R \\rightarrow \\infty}\" class=\"latex\" />.) </p></li> \n  <li>(ii) Let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BR_1%2C%5Cdots%2CR_n%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{R_1,\\dots,R_n}\" title=\"{R_1,\\dots,R_n}\" class=\"latex\" /> be a collection of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cdelta+%5Ctimes+1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\delta \\times 1}\" title=\"{\\delta \\times 1}\" class=\"latex\" /> rectangles for some <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cdelta+%3C+1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\delta < 1}\" title=\"{\\delta < 1}\" class=\"latex\" />, and for each <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bj%3D1%2C%5Cdots%2Cn%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{j=1,\\dots,n}\" title=\"{j=1,\\dots,n}\" class=\"latex\" />, let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Ctilde+R_j%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\tilde R_j}\" title=\"{\\tilde R_j}\" class=\"latex\" /> be a rectangle formed from <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BR_j%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{R_j}\" title=\"{R_j}\" class=\"latex\" /> by translating by a distance <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{2}\" title=\"{2}\" class=\"latex\" /> in the direction of the long axis of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BR_j%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{R_j}\" title=\"{R_j}\" class=\"latex\" />. Use (i) to show that <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+1_%7B%5Ctilde+R_j%7D+%5C%7C_%7BL%5E%7Bp%2F2%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5E2%29%7D+%5Csim_p+%5C%7C+%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+1_%7BR_j%7D+%5C%7C_%7BL%5E%7Bp%2F2%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5E2%29%7D.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n 1_{\\tilde R_j} \\|_{L^{p/2}({\\bf R}^2)} \\sim_p \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n 1_{R_j} \\|_{L^{p/2}({\\bf R}^2)}.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n 1_{\\tilde R_j} \\|_{L^{p/2}({\\bf R}^2)} \\sim_p \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n 1_{R_j} \\|_{L^{p/2}({\\bf R}^2)}.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> <p>(Hint: a direct application of (i) will give just one side of this estimate, but then one can use symmetry to obtain the other side.) </p></li> \n  <li>(iii) In <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=296602\">Fefferman’s paper</a>, modifying a classic construction of a Besicovitch set, it was shown that for any <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cvarepsilon%3E0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\varepsilon>0}\" title=\"{\\varepsilon>0}\" class=\"latex\" />, there exists a collection of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1+%5Ctimes+%5Cdelta%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1 \\times \\delta}\" title=\"{1 \\times \\delta}\" class=\"latex\" /> rectangles <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BR_1%2C%5Cdots%2CR_n%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{R_1,\\dots,R_n}\" title=\"{R_1,\\dots,R_n}\" class=\"latex\" /> for some <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B0+%3C+%5Cdelta+%3C+1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{0 < \\delta < 1}\" title=\"{0 < \\delta < 1}\" class=\"latex\" /> with <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bn+%5Csim+1%2F%5Cdelta%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{n \\sim 1/\\delta}\" title=\"{n \\sim 1/\\delta}\" class=\"latex\" /> such that all the rectangles <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Ctilde+R_j%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\tilde R_j}\" title=\"{\\tilde R_j}\" class=\"latex\" /> are disjoint, but such that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cbigcup_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+R_j%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\bigcup_{j=1}^n R_j}\" title=\"{\\bigcup_{j=1}^n R_j}\" class=\"latex\" /> has measure <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BO%28%5Cvarepsilon%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{O(\\varepsilon)}\" title=\"{O(\\varepsilon)}\" class=\"latex\" />. Assuming this fact, conclude that the multiplier estimate <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11649#disk\">(4)</a> fails unless <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bp%3D2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{p=2}\" title=\"{p=2}\" class=\"latex\" />. </li> \n  <li>(iv) Show that Theorem <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11649#lpi\">1</a>(ii) fails when <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bd%3D2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{d=2}\" title=\"{d=2}\" class=\"latex\" /> and the requirement that the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk_j%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k_j}\" title=\"{k_j}\" class=\"latex\" /> be <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{2}\" title=\"{2}\" class=\"latex\" />-separated is removed.</li> \n </ul> \n</blockquote> \n<blockquote>\n <p><b>Exercise 4</b> <a name=\"lipi\"></a> Let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cvarphi+%5Cin+C%5E%5Cinfty_c%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\varphi \\in C^\\infty_c({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{\\varphi \\in C^\\infty_c({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" /> be a bump function supported on <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5B-1%2C2%5D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{[-1,2]}\" title=\"{[-1,2]}\" class=\"latex\" /> that equals one on <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5B0%2C1%5D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{[0,1]}\" title=\"{[0,1]}\" class=\"latex\" />. For each integer <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bn%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{n}\" title=\"{n}\" class=\"latex\" />, let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Ctilde+P_n%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\tilde P_n}\" title=\"{\\tilde P_n}\" class=\"latex\" /> be the Fourier multiplier defined for <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{f \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" /> by</p> \n <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cwidehat%7B%5Ctilde+P_n+f%7D%28%5Cxi%29+%3A%3D+%5Cvarphi%28%5Cxi+-+n%29+%5Chat+f%28%5Cxi%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\widehat{\\tilde P_n f}(\\xi) := \\varphi(\\xi - n) \\hat f(\\xi)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\widehat{\\tilde P_n f}(\\xi) := \\varphi(\\xi - n) \\hat f(\\xi)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n <p>and also define</p> \n <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cwidehat%7BP_%7B%5Bn%2Cn%2B1%5D%7D+f%7D%28%5Cxi%29+%3A%3D+1_%7B%5Bn%2Cn%2B1%5D%7D%28%5Cxi%29+%5Chat+f%28%5Cxi%29.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\widehat{P_{[n,n+1]} f}(\\xi) := 1_{[n,n+1]}(\\xi) \\hat f(\\xi).\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\widehat{P_{[n,n+1]} f}(\\xi) := 1_{[n,n+1]}(\\xi) \\hat f(\\xi).\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n <ul> \n  <li>(i) For any <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B2+%5Cleq+p+%5Cleq+%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{2 \\leq p \\leq \\infty}\" title=\"{2 \\leq p \\leq \\infty}\" class=\"latex\" />, establish the square function estimate <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%28%5Csum_%7Bn+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D+%7C%5Ctilde+P_n+f%7C%5E2%29%5E%7B1%2F2%7D+%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D+%5Clesssim+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| (\\sum_{n \\in {\\bf Z}} |\\tilde P_n f|^2)^{1/2} \\|_{L^p({\\bf R})} \\lesssim \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R})}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| (\\sum_{n \\in {\\bf Z}} |\\tilde P_n f|^2)^{1/2} \\|_{L^p({\\bf R})} \\lesssim \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> <p>for <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{f \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" />. (<em>Hint:</em> interpolate between the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bp%3D2%2Cp%3D%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{p=2,p=\\infty}\" title=\"{p=2,p=\\infty}\" class=\"latex\" /> cases, and for the latter use Plancherel’s theorem for Fourier series.) </p></li> \n  <li>(ii) For any <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B2+%5Cleq+p+%3C+%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{2 \\leq p < \\infty}\" title=\"{2 \\leq p < \\infty}\" class=\"latex\" />, establish the square function estimate <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%28%5Csum_%7Bn+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D+%7CP_%7B%5Bn%2Cn%2B1%5D%7D+f%7C%5E2%29%5E%7B1%2F2%7D+%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D+%5Clesssim_p+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| (\\sum_{n \\in {\\bf Z}} |P_{[n,n+1]} f|^2)^{1/2} \\|_{L^p({\\bf R})} \\lesssim_p \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R})}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| (\\sum_{n \\in {\\bf Z}} |P_{[n,n+1]} f|^2)^{1/2} \\|_{L^p({\\bf R})} \\lesssim_p \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> <p>for <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{f \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" />. (<em>Hint:</em> from the boundedness of the Hilbert transform, <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP_%7B%5B0%2C1%5D%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P_{[0,1]}}\" title=\"{P_{[0,1]}}\" class=\"latex\" /> is bounded in <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BL%5Ep%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{L^p}\" title=\"{L^p}\" class=\"latex\" />. Combine this with the Marcinkiewicz-Zygmund theorem (Exercise 7 from <a href=\"https://terrytao.wordpress.com/2020/03/29/247b-notes-1-restriction-theory/\">Notes 1</a>), then use the symmetries of the Fourier transform, part (i), and the identity <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP_%7B%5Bn%2Cn%2B1%5D%7D+%3D+P_%7B%5Bn%2Cn%2B1%5D%7D+%5Ctilde+P_n%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P_{[n,n+1]} = P_{[n,n+1]} \\tilde P_n}\" title=\"{P_{[n,n+1]} = P_{[n,n+1]} \\tilde P_n}\" class=\"latex\" />.) </p></li> \n  <li>(iii) For any <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1+%3C+p+%5Cleq+2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1 < p \\leq 2}\" title=\"{1 < p \\leq 2}\" class=\"latex\" />, establish the reverse square function estimate <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D+%5Clesssim_p+%5C%7C+%28%5Csum_%7Bn+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D+%7CP_%7B%5Bn%2Cn%2B1%5D%7D+f%7C%5E2%29%5E%7B1%2F2%7D+%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R})} \\lesssim_p \\| (\\sum_{n \\in {\\bf Z}} |P_{[n,n+1]} f|^2)^{1/2} \\|_{L^p({\\bf R})}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R})} \\lesssim_p \\| (\\sum_{n \\in {\\bf Z}} |P_{[n,n+1]} f|^2)^{1/2} \\|_{L^p({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> <p>for <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{f \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" />. (<em>Hint:</em> use duality as in the solution to Exercise <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11649#smooth-ex\">2</a> in this set of notes, or Exercise 11 in <a href=\"https://terrytao.wordpress.com/2020/03/29/247b-notes-1-restriction-theory/\">Notes 1</a>, and part (ii).) </p></li> \n  <li>(iv) Show that the estimate (ii) fails for <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1%3Cp%3C2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1<p<2}\" title=\"{1<p<2}\" class=\"latex\" />, and similarly the estimate (iii) fails for <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B2%3Cp%3C%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{2<p<\\infty}\" title=\"{2<p<\\infty}\" class=\"latex\" />.</li> \n </ul> \n</blockquote> \n<blockquote>\n <p><b>Remark 5</b> The inequalities in Exercise <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11649#lipi\">4</a> have been generalised by replacing the partition <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%3D+%5Cbigcup_n+%5Bn%2Cn%2B1%5D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf R} = \\bigcup_n [n,n+1]}\" title=\"{{\\bf R} = \\bigcup_n [n,n+1]}\" class=\"latex\" /> with an arbitrary partition of the real line into intervals; see <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=850681\">this paper of Rubio de Francia</a>.</p>\n</blockquote> \n<p>If <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf_1%2C%5Cdots%2Cf_n+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f_1,\\dots,f_n \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R}^d)}\" title=\"{f_1,\\dots,f_n \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R}^d)}\" class=\"latex\" /> are functions with disjoint Fourier supports, then as mentioned in the introduction, we have from Pythagoras’ theorem that</p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+f_j+%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D+%3D+%5C%7C+%28%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+%7Cf_j%7C%5E2%29%5E%7B1%2F2%7D+%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n f_j \\|_{L^2({\\bf R}^d)} = \\| (\\sum_{j=1}^n |f_j|^2)^{1/2} \\|_{L^2({\\bf R}^d)}.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n f_j \\|_{L^2({\\bf R}^d)} = \\| (\\sum_{j=1}^n |f_j|^2)^{1/2} \\|_{L^2({\\bf R}^d)}.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p>We have the following variants of this claim:</p> \n<blockquote>\n <p><b>Lemma 6 (<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BL%5E2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{L^2}\" title=\"{L^2}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BL%5E4%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{L^4}\" title=\"{L^4}\" class=\"latex\" /> reverse square function estimates)</b> <a name=\"bio\"></a> Let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf_1%2C%5Cdots%2Cf_n+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f_1,\\dots,f_n \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R}^d)}\" title=\"{f_1,\\dots,f_n \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R}^d)}\" class=\"latex\" /> have Fourier transforms supported on the sets <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5COmega_1%2C%5Cdots%2C%5COmega_n+%5Csubset+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\Omega_1,\\dots,\\Omega_n \\subset {\\bf R}^d}\" title=\"{\\Omega_1,\\dots,\\Omega_n \\subset {\\bf R}^d}\" class=\"latex\" /> respectively.</p> \n <ul> \n  <li>(i) (Almost orthogonality) If the sets <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5COmega_1%2C%5Cdots%2C%5COmega_n%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\Omega_1,\\dots,\\Omega_n}\" title=\"{\\Omega_1,\\dots,\\Omega_n}\" class=\"latex\" /> have overlap at most <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BA_2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{A_2}\" title=\"{A_2}\" class=\"latex\" /> (i.e., every <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cxi+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\xi \\in {\\bf R}^d}\" title=\"{\\xi \\in {\\bf R}^d}\" class=\"latex\" /> lies in at most <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BA_2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{A_2}\" title=\"{A_2}\" class=\"latex\" /> of the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5COmega_i%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\Omega_i}\" title=\"{\\Omega_i}\" class=\"latex\" />) for some <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BA_2%3E0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{A_2>0}\" title=\"{A_2>0}\" class=\"latex\" />, then <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+f_j+%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D+%5Cleq+A_2%5E%7B1%2F2%7D+%5C%7C+%28%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+%7Cf_j%7C%5E2%29%5E%7B1%2F2%7D+%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n f_j \\|_{L^2({\\bf R}^d)} \\leq A_2^{1/2} \\| (\\sum_{j=1}^n |f_j|^2)^{1/2} \\|_{L^2({\\bf R}^d)}.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n f_j \\|_{L^2({\\bf R}^d)} \\leq A_2^{1/2} \\| (\\sum_{j=1}^n |f_j|^2)^{1/2} \\|_{L^2({\\bf R}^d)}.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> </li> \n  <li>(ii) (Almost bi-orthogonality) If the sets <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5COmega_i%2B%5COmega_j+%3A%3D+%5C%7B+%5Cxi_i+%2B+%5Cxi_j%3A+%5Cxi_i+%5Cin+%5COmega_i%2C+%5Cxi_j+%5Cin+%5COmega_j%5C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\Omega_i+\\Omega_j := \\{ \\xi_i + \\xi_j: \\xi_i \\in \\Omega_i, \\xi_j \\in \\Omega_j\\}}\" title=\"{\\Omega_i+\\Omega_j := \\{ \\xi_i + \\xi_j: \\xi_i \\in \\Omega_i, \\xi_j \\in \\Omega_j\\}}\" class=\"latex\" /> with <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1+%5Cleq+i%2Cj+%5Cleq+n%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1 \\leq i,j \\leq n}\" title=\"{1 \\leq i,j \\leq n}\" class=\"latex\" /> have overlap at most <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BA_4%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{A_4}\" title=\"{A_4}\" class=\"latex\" /> for some <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BA_4%3E0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{A_4>0}\" title=\"{A_4>0}\" class=\"latex\" />, then <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+f_j+%5C%7C_%7BL%5E4%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D+%5Cleq+A_4%5E%7B1%2F4%7D+%5C%7C+%28%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+%7Cf_j%7C%5E2%29%5E%7B1%2F2%7D+%5C%7C_%7BL%5E4%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n f_j \\|_{L^4({\\bf R}^d)} \\leq A_4^{1/4} \\| (\\sum_{j=1}^n |f_j|^2)^{1/2} \\|_{L^4({\\bf R}^d)}.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n f_j \\|_{L^4({\\bf R}^d)} \\leq A_4^{1/4} \\| (\\sum_{j=1}^n |f_j|^2)^{1/2} \\|_{L^4({\\bf R}^d)}.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> </li> \n </ul> \n</blockquote> \n<p><em>Proof:</em> For (i), observe from Plancherel’s theorem that</p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+f_j+%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D+%3D+%5C%7C+%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+%5Chat+f_j+%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n f_j \\|_{L^2({\\bf R}^d)} = \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n \\hat f_j \\|_{L^2({\\bf R}^d)}.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n f_j \\|_{L^2({\\bf R}^d)} = \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n \\hat f_j \\|_{L^2({\\bf R}^d)}.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p>By hypothesis, for each frequency <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cxi+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\xi \\in {\\bf R}^d}\" title=\"{\\xi \\in {\\bf R}^d}\" class=\"latex\" /> at most <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BA_2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{A_2}\" title=\"{A_2}\" class=\"latex\" /> of the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Chat+f_j%28%5Cxi%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\hat f_j(\\xi)}\" title=\"{\\hat f_j(\\xi)}\" class=\"latex\" /> are non-zero, thus by
