src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B0+%3C+%5Cdelta+%3C+1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{0 < \\delta < 1}\" title=\"{0 < \\delta < 1}\" class=\"latex\" />, let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5COmega+%3D+%5Cphi%28%5CSigma%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\Omega = \\phi(\\Sigma)}\" title=\"{\\Omega = \\phi(\\Sigma)}\" class=\"latex\" /> for some <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cdelta%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\delta}\" title=\"{\\delta}\" class=\"latex\" />-separated subset <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5CSigma%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\Sigma}\" title=\"{\\Sigma}\" class=\"latex\" /> of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5B-1%2C1%5D%5E%7Bd-1%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{[-1,1]^{d-1}}\" title=\"{[-1,1]^{d-1}}\" class=\"latex\" />, where <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cphi%3A+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5E%7Bd-1%7D+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\phi: {\\bf R}^{d-1} \\rightarrow {\\bf R}^d}\" title=\"{\\phi: {\\bf R}^{d-1} \\rightarrow {\\bf R}^d}\" class=\"latex\" /> is the map <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cphi%28%5Cxi%29+%3A%3D+%28%5Cxi%2C+%7C%5Cxi%7C%5E2%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\phi(\\xi) := (\\xi, |\\xi|^2)}\" title=\"{\\phi(\\xi) := (\\xi, |\\xi|^2)}\" class=\"latex\" />, and to each <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Comega+%3D+%5Cphi%28%5Cxi%29+%5Cin+%5COmega%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\omega = \\phi(\\xi) \\in \\Omega}\" title=\"{\\omega = \\phi(\\xi) \\in \\Omega}\" class=\"latex\" /> let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BD_%5Comega%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{D_\\omega}\" title=\"{D_\\omega}\" class=\"latex\" /> be the disk</p> \n <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++D_%5Comega+%3A%3D+%5C%7B+%28%5Cxi%27%2C+%5Cxi_d%29%3A+%7C%5Cxi%27+-+%5Cxi%7C+%5Cleq+%5Cdelta%3B+%7C%5Cxi_d+-+%7C%5Cxi%7C%5E2+-+2+%5Cxi+%5Ccdot+%28%5Cxi%27-%5Cxi%29%7C+%5Cleq+%5Cdelta%5E2+%5C%7D.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  D_\\omega := \\{ (\\xi', \\xi_d): |\\xi' - \\xi| \\leq \\delta; |\\xi_d - |\\xi|^2 - 2 \\xi \\cdot (\\xi'-\\xi)| \\leq \\delta^2 \\}.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  D_\\omega := \\{ (\\xi', \\xi_d): |\\xi' - \\xi| \\leq \\delta; |\\xi_d - |\\xi|^2 - 2 \\xi \\cdot (\\xi'-\\xi)| \\leq \\delta^2 \\}.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n <p>Then one has</p> \n <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cmathrm%7BDec%7D_%7B%5Cfrac%7B2%28d%2B1%29%7D%7Bd-1%7D%7D%28+%5C%7B+D_%7B%5Comega%7D%3A+%5Comega+%5Cin+%5COmega+%5C%7D+%29+%5Clesssim_%7Bd%2C%5Cvarepsilon%7D+%5Cdelta%5E%7B-%5Cvarepsilon%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\mathrm{Dec}_{\\frac{2(d+1)}{d-1}}( \\{ D_{\\omega}: \\omega \\in \\Omega \\} ) \\lesssim_{d,\\varepsilon} \\delta^{-\\varepsilon}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\mathrm{Dec}_{\\frac{2(d+1)}{d-1}}( \\{ D_{\\omega}: \\omega \\in \\Omega \\} ) \\lesssim_{d,\\varepsilon} \\delta^{-\\varepsilon}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n <p>for any <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cvarepsilon%3E0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\varepsilon>0}\" title=\"{\\varepsilon>0}\" class=\"latex\" />.</p>\n</blockquote> \n<p>Clearly Theorem <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11649#parabb\">13</a> is the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bd%3D2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{d=2}\" title=\"{d=2}\" class=\"latex\" /> case of Theorem <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11649#decoupp\">24</a>.</p> \n<blockquote>\n <p><b>Exercise 25</b> Show that the exponent <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cfrac%7B2%28d%2B1%29%7D%7Bd-1%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\frac{2(d+1)}{d-1}}\" title=\"{\\frac{2(d+1)}{d-1}}\" class=\"latex\" /> in Theorem <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11649#decoupp\">24</a> cannot be replaced by any larger exponent.</p>\n</blockquote> \n<p>We will not prove Theorem <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11649#decoupp\">24</a> here; the proof in Bourgain-Demeter shares some features in common with the one given above (for instance, it focuses on a <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bd%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{d}\" title=\"{d}\" class=\"latex\" />-linear formulation of the decoupling problem, though not one that corresponds precisely to the bilinear formulation given above), but also involves some additional ingredients, such as the wave packet decomposition and the multilinear restriction theorem from <a href=\"https://terrytao.wordpress.com/2020/03/29/247b-notes-1-restriction-theory/\">Notes 1</a>.<br /> Somewhat analogously to how the multilinear Kakeya conjecture could be used in <a href=\"https://terrytao.wordpress.com/2020/03/29/247b-notes-1-restriction-theory/\">Notes 1</a> to establish the multilinear restriction conjecture (up to some epsilon losses) by an induction on scales argument, the decoupling theorem for the paraboloid can be used to establish decoupling theorems for other surfaces, such as the sphere:</p> \n<blockquote>\n <p><b>Exercise 26 (Decoupling for the sphere)</b> <a name=\"desphere\"></a> Let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bd+%5Cgeq+2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{d \\geq 2}\" title=\"{d \\geq 2}\" class=\"latex\" />, let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B0+%3C+%5Cdelta+%3C+1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{0 < \\delta < 1}\" title=\"{0 < \\delta < 1}\" class=\"latex\" />, and let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5COmega%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\Omega}\" title=\"{\\Omega}\" class=\"latex\" /> be a <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cdelta%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\delta}\" title=\"{\\delta}\" class=\"latex\" />-separated subset of the sphere <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS%5E%7Bd-1%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{S^{d-1}}\" title=\"{S^{d-1}}\" class=\"latex\" />. To each <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Comega+%5Cin+%5COmega%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\omega \\in \\Omega}\" title=\"{\\omega \\in \\Omega}\" class=\"latex\" />, let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Ctilde+D_%5Comega%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\tilde D_\\omega}\" title=\"{\\tilde D_\\omega}\" class=\"latex\" /> be the disk</p> \n <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Ctilde+D_%5Comega+%3A%3D+%5C%7B+%5Cxi%3A+%7C%5Cxi+%5Ccdot+%5Comega+-+1%7C+%5Cleq+%5Cdelta%3B+%7C%5Cxi+-+%28%5Cxi+%5Ccdot+%5Comega%29+%5Comega%7C+%5Cleq+%5Cdelta%5E2%5C%7D.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\tilde D_\\omega := \\{ \\xi: |\\xi \\cdot \\omega - 1| \\leq \\delta; |\\xi - (\\xi \\cdot \\omega) \\omega| \\leq \\delta^2\\}.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\tilde D_\\omega := \\{ \\xi: |\\xi \\cdot \\omega - 1| \\leq \\delta; |\\xi - (\\xi \\cdot \\omega) \\omega| \\leq \\delta^2\\}.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n <p>Assuming Theorem <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11649#decoupp\">24</a>, establish the bound <a name=\"stil\"></a></p> \n <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cmathrm%7BDec%7D_%7B%5Cfrac%7B2%28d%2B1%29%7D%7Bd-1%7D%7D%28+%5C%7B+%5Ctilde+D_%7B%5Comega%7D%3A+%5Comega+%5Cin+%5COmega+%5C%7D+%29+%5Clesssim_%7Bd%2C%5Cvarepsilon%7D+%5Cdelta%5E%7B-%5Cvarepsilon%7D+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%2823%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\mathrm{Dec}_{\\frac{2(d+1)}{d-1}}( \\{ \\tilde D_{\\omega}: \\omega \\in \\Omega \\} ) \\lesssim_{d,\\varepsilon} \\delta^{-\\varepsilon} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (23)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\mathrm{Dec}_{\\frac{2(d+1)}{d-1}}( \\{ \\tilde D_{\\omega}: \\omega \\in \\Omega \\} ) \\lesssim_{d,\\varepsilon} \\delta^{-\\varepsilon} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (23)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n <p> for any <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cvarepsilon%3E0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\varepsilon>0}\" title=\"{\\varepsilon>0}\" class=\"latex\" />. (<em>Hint:</em> if one lets <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Ctilde+D%28%5Cdelta%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\tilde D(\\delta)}\" title=\"{\\tilde D(\\delta)}\" class=\"latex\" /> denote the supremum over all expressions of the form of the left-hand side of <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11649#stil\">(23)</a>, use Exercise <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11649#elem\">10</a> and Theorem <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11649#decoupp\">24</a> to establish a bound of the form <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Ctilde+D%28%5Cdelta%29+%5Clesssim_%7Bd%2C%5Cvarepsilon%7D+%5Cdelta%5E%7B-%5Cvarepsilon%7D+%5Ctilde+D%28%5Csqrt%7B%5Cdelta%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\tilde D(\\delta) \\lesssim_{d,\\varepsilon} \\delta^{-\\varepsilon} \\tilde D(\\sqrt{\\delta})}\" title=\"{\\tilde D(\\delta) \\lesssim_{d,\\varepsilon} \\delta^{-\\varepsilon} \\tilde D(\\sqrt{\\delta})}\" class=\"latex\" />, taking advantage of the fact that a sphere resembles a paraboloid at small scales. This argument can also be found in <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=3374964\">the above-mentioned paper of Bourgain and Demeter</a>.)</p>\n</blockquote> \n<p>An induction on scales argument (somewhat similar to the one used to establish the multilinear Kakeya estimate in <a href=\"https://terrytao.wordpress.com/2020/03/29/247b-notes-1-restriction-theory/\">Notes 1</a>) can similarly be used to establish decoupling theorems for the cone</p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7B+%28%5Cxi_1%2C%5Cxi_2%2C%5Cxi_3%29%3A+%5Cxi_1%5E2+%2B+%5Cxi_2%5E2+%3D+%5Cxi_3%5E2%5C%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\{ (\\xi_1,\\xi_2,\\xi_3): \\xi_1^2 + \\xi_2^2 = \\xi_3^2\\}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\{ (\\xi_1,\\xi_2,\\xi_3): \\xi_1^2 + \\xi_2^2 = \\xi_3^2\\}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p>from the decoupling theorem for the parabola (Theorem <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11649#parabb\">13</a>). It will be convenient to rewrite the equation for the cone as <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cxi_1%5E2+%3D+%28%5Cxi_2%2B%5Cxi_3%29+%28%5Cxi_3-%5Cxi_2%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\xi_1^2 = (\\xi_2+\\xi_3) (\\xi_3-\\xi_2)}\" title=\"{\\xi_1^2 = (\\xi_2+\\xi_3) (\\xi_3-\\xi_2)}\" class=\"latex\" />, then perform a linear change of variables to work with the tilted cone</p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7B+%28%5Cxi_1%2C%5Cxi_2%2C%5Cxi_3%29%3A+%5Cxi_1%5E2+%3D+%5Cxi_2+%5Cxi_3+%5C%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\{ (\\xi_1,\\xi_2,\\xi_3): \\xi_1^2 = \\xi_2 \\xi_3 \\}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\{ (\\xi_1,\\xi_2,\\xi_3): \\xi_1^2 = \\xi_2 \\xi_3 \\}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p>which can be viewed as a projective version of the parabola <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7B+%28%5Cxi_1%2C%5Cxi_2%29%3A+%5Cxi_1%5E2+%3D+%5Cxi_2+%5C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\{ (\\xi_1,\\xi_2): \\xi_1^2 = \\xi_2 \\}}\" title=\"{\\{ (\\xi_1,\\xi_2): \\xi_1^2 = \\xi_2 \\}}\" class=\"latex\" />.</p> \n<blockquote>\n <p><b>Exercise 27 (Decoupling for the cone)</b> For <img over <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cdelta%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\delta}\" title=\"{\\delta}\" class=\"latex\" />-separated subsets of <img \\}.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\{ (\\xi_1,\\xi_2,\\xi_3): |\\frac{\\xi_1}{\\xi_3} - \\theta| \\leq \\delta; |\\frac{\\xi_2}{\\xi_3} - \\frac{\\xi_1^2}{\\xi^2_3}| \\leq \\delta^2; 1 \\leq \\xi_3 \\leq 1+\\nu \\}.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n <ul> \n  <li>(i) For any <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B0+%3C+%5Cdelta%2C%5Cnu+%5Cleq+1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{0 < src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BD_C%28%5Cnu%5E2%2C+%5Cnu%29+%5Clesssim_%5Cvarepsilon+%5Cnu%5E%7B-%5Cvarepsilon%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{D_C(\\nu^2, \\nu) (Hint: use Theorem <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11649#parabb\">13</a> and various parts of Exercise <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11649#elem\">10</a>, exploiting the geometric fact that thin slices of the tilted cone resemble the Cartesian product of a parabola and a short interval.) </li> \n  <li>(iii) For any <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B0+%3C+%5Cdelta_1%2C+%5Cdelta_2%2C+%5Cnu+%5Cleq+1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{0 < \\delta_1, \\delta_2, \\nu \\leq 1}\" title=\"{0 < \\delta_1, \\delta_2, \\nu \\leq 1}\" class=\"latex\" />, show that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BD_C%28%5Cdelta_1+%5Cdelta_2%2C+%5Cnu%29+%5Clesssim+D_C%28%5Cdelta_1%2C+%5Cnu%29+D_C%28%5Cdelta_2%2C%5Cnu%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{D_C(\\delta_1 \\delta_2, \\nu) \\lesssim D_C(\\delta_1, \\nu) D_C(\\delta_2,\\nu)}\" title=\"{D_C(\\delta_1 \\delta_2, \\nu) \\lesssim D_C(\\delta_1, \\nu) D_C(\\delta_2,\\nu)}\" class=\"latex\" />. (<em>Hint:</em> adapt the argument used to establish Exercise <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11649#mult\">16</a>, taking advantage of the invariance of the tilted light cone under src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28%5Cxi_1%2C%5Cxi_2%2C%5Cxi_3%29+%5Cmapsto+%28%5Clambda+%5Cxi_1%2C+%5Clambda%5E2+%5Cxi_2%2C+%5Cxi_3%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(\\xi_1,\\xi_2,\\xi_3) \\mapsto (\\lambda \\xi_1, \\lambda^2 \\xi_2, \\xi_3)}\" title=\"{(\\xi_1,\\xi_2,\\xi_3) \\mapsto (\\lambda \\xi_1, \\lambda^2 \\xi_2, \\xi_3)}\" class=\"latex\" /> and src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28%5Cxi_1%2C%5Cxi_2%2C%5Cxi_3%29+%5Cmapsto+%28%5Cxi_1+%2B+%5Ceta+%5Cxi_3%2C+%5Cxi_2+%2B+2+%5Ceta+%5Cxi_1+%2B+%5Ceta%5E2+%5Cxi_3%2C+%5Cxi_3%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" <li>(v) State and prove a generalisation of (iv) to higher dimensions, using Theorem <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11649#decoupp\">24</a> in place of Theorem <a above-mentioned paper of Bourgain and Demeter</a>.</p>\n</blockquote> \n<p>A separate generalization of Theorem <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11649#parabb\">13</a>, to the <em>moment curve</em></p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7B+%28t%2C+t%5E2%2C+%5Cdots%2C+t%5Ed%29%3A+t+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5C%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\{ (t, t^2, \\dots, t^d): t \\in {\\bf R}\\}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\{ (t, t^2, \\dots, t^d): t \\in {\\bf R}\\}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p>was obtained <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=3548534\">by Bourgain, Demeter, and Guth</a>:</p> \n<blockquote>\n <p><b>Theorem 28 (Decoupling for the moment curve)</b> <a name=\"moment\"></a> Let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bd+%5Cgeq+2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{d \\geq 2}\" title=\"{d \\geq 2}\" class=\"latex\" />, let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B0+%3C+%5Cdelta+%5Cleq+1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{0 < \\delta \\leq 1}\" title=\"{0 < \\delta \\leq 1}\" class=\"latex\" />, and let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5CSigma%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\Sigma}\" title=\"{\\Sigma}\" class=\"latex\" /> be a <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cdelta%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\delta}\" title=\"{\\delta}\" class=\"latex\" />-separated subset of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5B-1%2C1%5D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{[-1,1]}\" title=\"{[-1,1]}\" class=\"latex\" />. For each <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bt+%5Cin+%5CSigma%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{t \\in \\Sigma}\" title=\"{t \\in \\Sigma}\" class=\"latex\" />, let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BR_%7Bt%2C%5Cdelta%7D+%5Csubset+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{R_{t,\\delta} \\subset {\\bf R}^d}\" title=\"{R_{t,\\delta} \\subset {\\bf R}^d}\" class=\"latex\" /> denote the region</p> \n <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++R_%7Bt%2C%5Cdelta%7D+%3A%3D+%5C%7B+%5Cxi+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%3A+%7C%5Cxi+-+%5Cphi%28t%27%29%7C+%5Cleq+%5Cdelta%5Ed+%5Chbox%7B+for+some+%7D+t%27+%5Cin+%5Bt-%5Cdelta%2Ct%2B%5Cdelta%5D+%5C%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  R_{t,\\delta} := \\{ \\xi \\in {\\bf R}^d: |\\xi - \\phi(t')| \\leq \\delta^d \\hbox{ for some } t' \\in [t-\\delta,t+\\delta] \\}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  R_{t,\\delta} := \\{ \\xi \\in {\\bf R}^d: |\\xi - \\phi(t')| \\leq \\delta^d \\hbox{ for some } t' \\in [t-\\delta,t+\\delta] \\}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n <p>where <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cphi%3A+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\phi: {\\bf R} \\rightarrow {\\bf R}^d}\" title=\"{\\phi: {\\bf R} \\rightarrow {\\bf R}^d}\" class=\"latex\" /> is the map</p> \n <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cphi%28t%29+%3A%3D+%28t%2Ct%5E2%2C%5Cdots%2Ct%5Ed%29.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\phi(t) := (t,t^2,\\dots,t^d).\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\phi(t) := (t,t^2,\\dots,t^d).\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n <p>Then</p> \n <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cmathrm%7BDec%7D_%7Bd%28d%2B1%29%7D%28+%5C%7B+R_%7Bt%2C%5Cdelta%7D%3A+t+%5Cin+%5CSigma+%5C%7D+%29+%5Clesssim_%7Bd%2C%5Cvarepsilon%7D+%5Cdelta%5E%7B-%5Cvarepsilon%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\mathrm{Dec}_{d(d+1)}( \\{ R_{t,\\delta}: t \\in \\Sigma \\} ) \\lesssim_{d,\\varepsilon} \\delta^{-\\varepsilon}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\mathrm{Dec}_{d(d+1)}( \\{ R_{t,\\delta}: t \\in \\Sigma \\} ) \\lesssim_{d,\\varepsilon} \\delta^{-\\varepsilon}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n <p>for any <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cvarepsilon%3E0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\varepsilon>0}\" title=\"{\\varepsilon>0}\" class=\"latex\" />.</p>\n</blockquote> \n<blockquote>\n <p><b>Exercise 29</b> Show that the exponent <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bd%28d%2B1%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{d(d+1)}\" title=\"{d(d+1)}\" class=\"latex\" /> in Theorem <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11649#moment\">28</a> cannot be replaced by any higher exponent.</p>\n</blockquote> \n<p>It is not difficult to use Exercise <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11649#elem\">10</a> to deduce Theorem <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11649#parabb\">13</a> from the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bd%3D2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{d=2}\" title=\"{d=2}\" class=\"latex\" /> case of Theorem <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11649#moment\">28</a> (the only issue being that the regions <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BR_%7Bt%2C%5Cdelta%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{R_{t,\\delta}}\" title=\"{R_{t,\\delta}}\" class=\"latex\" /> are not quite the same the parallelograms <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Ctilde+R_%7B%28t%2Ct%5E2%29%2C%5Cdelta%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\tilde R_{(t,t^2),\\delta}}\" title=\"{\\tilde R_{(t,t^2),\\delta}}\" class=\"latex\" /> appearing in Theorem <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11649#parabb\">13</a>).<br /> The original proof of Theorem <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11649#moment\">28</a> by Bourgain-Demeter-Guth was rather intricate, using for instance a version of the multilinear Kakeya estimate from <a href=\"https://terrytao.wordpress.com/2020/03/29/247b-notes-1-restriction-theory/\">Notes 1</a>. A shorter proof, similar to the one used to prove Theorem <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11649#parabb\">13</a> in these notes, was recently given <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/1912.09798\">by Guo, Li, Yung, and Zorin-Kranich</a>, adapting the “nested efficient congruencing” method <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/1708.01220\">of Wooley</a>, which we will not discuss here, save to say that this method can be viewed as a <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bp%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{p}\" title=\"{p}\" class=\"latex\" />-adic counterpart to decoupling techniques. See also <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=3658168\">this paper of Wooley</a> for an alternate approach to (a slightly specialised version of) Theorem <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11649#moment\">28</a>.<br /> Perhaps the most striking application of Theorem <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11649#moment\">28</a> is the following conjecture of Vinogradov:</p> \n<blockquote>\n <p><b>Exercise 30 (Main conjecture for the Vinogradov mean value theorem)</b> Let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bd+%5Cgeq+2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{d \\geq 2}\" title=\"{d \\geq 2}\" class=\"latex\" />. For any <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bs+%5Cgeq+1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{s \\geq 1}\" title=\"{s \\geq 1}\" class=\"latex\" /> and any <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN+%5Cgeq+1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N \\geq 1}\" title=\"{N \\geq 1}\" class=\"latex\" />, let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BJ_%7Bs%2Cd%7D%28N%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{J_{s,d}(N)}\" title=\"{J_{s,d}(N)}\" class=\"latex\" /> denote the quantity</p> \n <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++J_%7Bs%2Cd%7D%28N%29+%3A%3D+%5Cint_%7B%5B0%2C1%5D%5Ed%7D+%7C%5Csum_%7Bn%3D1%7D%5EN+e%28+x_1+n+%2B+x_2+n%5E2+%2B+%5Cdots+%2B+x_d+n%5Ed+%29%7C%5E%7B2s%7D%5C+dx_1+%5Cdots+dx_n&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  J_{s,d}(N) := \\int_{[0,1]^d} |\\sum_{n=1}^N e( x_1 n + x_2 n^2 + \\dots + x_d n^d )|^{2s}\\ dx_1 \\dots dx_n\" title=\"\\displaystyle  J_{s,d}(N) := \\int_{[0,1]^d} |\\sum_{n=1}^N e( x_1 n + x_2 n^2 + \\dots + x_d n^d )|^{2s}\\ dx_1 \\dots dx_n\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n <ul>\n   where \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Be%28%5Ctheta%29+%3A%3D+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+%5Ctheta%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{e(\\theta) := e^{2\\pi i \\theta}}\" title=\"{e(\\theta) := e^{2\\pi i \\theta}}\" class=\"latex\" />. \n  <li>(i) If <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bs%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{s}\" title=\"{s}\" class=\"latex\" /> is a natural number, show that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BJ_%7Bs%2Cd%7D%28N%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{J_{s,d}(N)}\" title=\"{J_{s,d}(N)}\" class=\"latex\" /> is equal to the number of tuples <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28X_1%2C%5Cdots%2CX_%7B2s%7D%29+%5Cin+%5C%7B1%2C%5Cdots%2CN%5C%7D%5E%7B2s%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(X_1,\\dots,X_{2s}) \\in \\{1,\\dots,N\\}^{2s}}\" title=\"{(X_1,\\dots,X_{2s}) \\in \\{1,\\dots,N\\}^{2s}}\" class=\"latex\" /> of natural numbers between <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1}\" title=\"{1}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N}\" title=\"{N}\" class=\"latex\" /> obeying the system of equations <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++X_1%5Ei+%2B+%5Cdots+%2B+X_s%5Ei+%3D+X_%7Bs%2B1%7D%5Ei+%2B+%5Cdots+%2B+X_%7B2s%7D%5Ei&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  X_1^i + \\dots + X_s^i = X_{s+1}^i + \\dots + X_{2s}^i\" title=\"\\displaystyle  X_1^i + \\dots + X_s^i = X_{s+1}^i + \\dots + X_{2s}^i\" class=\"latex\" /></p> <p>for <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bi%3D1%2C%5Cdots%2Cd%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{i=1,\\dots,d}\" title=\"{i=1,\\dots,d}\" class=\"latex\" />. </p></li> \n  <li>(ii) Using Theorem <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11649#moment\">28</a>, establish the bound <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++J_%7Bd%28d%2B1%29%2F2%2Cd%7D%28N%29+%5Clesssim_%7Bd%2C%5Cvarepsilon%7D+N%5E%7Bd%28d%2B1%29%2B%5Cvarepsilon%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  J_{d(d+1)/2,d}(N) \\lesssim_{d,\\varepsilon} N^{d(d+1)+\\varepsilon}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  J_{d(d+1)/2,d}(N) \\lesssim_{d,\\varepsilon} N^{d(d+1)+\\varepsilon}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> <p>for all <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cvarepsilon+%3E0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\varepsilon >0}\" title=\"{\\varepsilon >0}\" class=\"latex\" />. (<em>Hint:</em> set <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cdelta+%3D+1%2FN%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\delta = 1/N}\" title=\"{\\delta = 1/N}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5CSigma+%3D+%5C%7Bi%2FN%3A+i%3D1%2C%5Cdots%2CN%5C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\Sigma = \\{i/N: i=1,\\dots,N\\}}\" title=\"{\\Sigma = \\{i/N: i=1,\\dots,N\\}}\" class=\"latex\" />, and apply the decoupling inequality to functions <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf_t%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f_t}\" title=\"{f_t}\" class=\"latex\" /> that are adapted to a small ball around <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cphi%28t%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\phi(t)}\" title=\"{\\phi(t)}\" class=\"latex\" />.) </p></li> \n  <li>(iii) More generally, establish the bound <a name=\"jsd\"> <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++J_%7Bs%2Cd%7D%28N%29+%5Clesssim_%7Bd%2Cs%2C%5Cvarepsilon%7D+N%5E%7Bs%2B%5Cvarepsilon%7D+%2B+N%5E%7B2s+-+%5Cfrac%7Bd%28d%2B1%29%7D%7B2%7D+%2B+%5Cvarepsilon%7D+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%2824%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  J_{s,d}(N) \\lesssim_{d,s,\\varepsilon} N^{s+\\varepsilon} + N^{2s - \\frac{d(d+1)}{2} + \\varepsilon} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (24)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  J_{s,d}(N) \\lesssim_{d,s,\\varepsilon} N^{s+\\varepsilon} + N^{2s - \\frac{d(d+1)}{2} + \\varepsilon} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (24)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> <p></p></a> for any <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bs+%5Cgeq+1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{s \\geq 1}\" title=\"{s \\geq 1}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cvarepsilon%3E0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\varepsilon>0}\" title=\"{\\varepsilon>0}\" class=\"latex\" />. Show that this bound is best possible up to the implied constant and the loss of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN%5E%5Cvarepsilon%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N^\\varepsilon}\" title=\"{N^\\varepsilon}\" class=\"latex\" /> factors.</li> \n </ul> \n</blockquote> \n<blockquote>\n <p><b>Remark 31</b> Estimates of the form <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11649#jsd\">(24)</a> are known as <em>mean value theorems</em>, and were first established by Vinogradov in 1937 in the case when <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bs%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{s}\" title=\"{s}\" class=\"latex\" /> was sufficiently large (and <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=29416\">by Hua</a> when <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bs%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{s}\" title=\"{s}\" class=\"latex\" /> was sufficiently small). These estimates in turn had several applications in analytic number theory, most notably the Waring problem and in establishing zero-free regions for the Riemann zeta function; see <a href=\"https://terrytao.wordpress.com/2015/02/07/254a-notes-5-bounding-exponential-sums-and-the-zeta-function/\">these previous lecture notes</a> for more discussion. The ranges of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bd%2Cs%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{d,s}\" title=\"{d,s}\" class=\"latex\" /> for which <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11649#jsd\">(24)</a> was established was improved over the years, with much recent progress by Wooley using his method of efficient congruencing; see <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=3939285\">this survey of Pierce</a> for a detailed history. In particular, these methods can supply an alternate proof of <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11649#jsd\">(24)</a>; see <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=3658168\">this paper of Wooley</a>.</p>\n</blockquote> \n<blockquote>\n <p><b>Exercise 32 (Discrete restriction)</b> Let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B0+%3C+%5Cdelta+%3C+1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{0 < \\delta < 1}\" title=\"{0 < \\delta < 1}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bd+%5Cgeq+2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{d \\geq 2}\" title=\"{d \\geq 2}\" class=\"latex\" />, and let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5COmega%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\Omega}\" title=\"{\\Omega}\" class=\"latex\" /> be a <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cdelta%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\delta}\" title=\"{\\delta}\" class=\"latex\" />-separated subset of either the unit sphere <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS%5E%7Bd-1%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{S^{d-1}}\" title=\"{S^{d-1}}\" class=\"latex\" /> or the paraboloid <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7B+%28%5Cxi%27%2C+%7C%5Cxi%27%7C%5E2%29%3A+%5Cxi%27+%5Cin+%5B-1%2C1%5D%5E%7Bd-1%7D+%5C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\{ (\\xi', |\\xi'|^2): \\xi' \\in [-1,1]^{d-1} \\}}\" title=\"{\\{ (\\xi', |\\xi'|^2): \\xi' \\in [-1,1]^{d-1} \\}}\" class=\"latex\" />. Using Theorem <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11649#decoupp\">24</a> and Exercise <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11649#desphere\">26</a>, show that for any radius <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BR+%5Cgeq+%5Cdelta%5E%7B-2%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{R \\geq \\delta^{-2}}\" title=\"{R \\geq \\delta^{-2}}\" class=\"latex\" /> and any complex numbers <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba_%5Comega%2C+%5Comega+%5Cin+%5COmega%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a_\\omega, \\omega \\in \\Omega}\" title=\"{a_\\omega, \\omega \\in \\Omega}\" class=\"latex\" />, one has the discrete restriction estimate</p> \n <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%28%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B%7CB%280%2CR%29%7C%7D+%5Cint_%7BB%280%2CR%29%7D+%7C%5Csum_%7B%5Comega+%5Cin+%5COmega%7D+a_%5Comega+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+x+%5Ccdot+%5Comega%7D%7C%5E%7B%5Cfrac%7B2%28d%2B1%29%7D%7Bd-1%7D%7D%5C+dx%29%5E%7B%5Cfrac%7Bd-1%7D%7B2%28d%2B1%29%7D%7D+&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  (\\frac{1}{|B(0,R)|} \\int_{B(0,R)} |\\sum_{\\omega \\in \\Omega} a_\\omega e^{2\\pi i x \\cdot \\omega}|^{\\frac{2(d+1)}{d-1}}\\ dx)^{\\frac{d-1}{2(d+1)}} \" title=\"\\displaystyle  (\\frac{1}{|B(0,R)|} \\int_{B(0,R)} |\\sum_{\\omega \\in \\Omega} a_\\omega e^{2\\pi i x \\cdot \\omega}|^{\\frac{2(d+1)}{d-1}}\\ dx)^{\\frac{d-1}{2(d+1)}} \" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+%5Clesssim_%5Cvarepsilon+%5Cdelta%5E%7B-%5Cvarepsilon%7D+%28%5Csum_%7B%5Comega+%5Cin+%5COmega%7D+%7Ca_%5Comega%7C%5E2%29%5E%7B1%2F2%7D.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle \\lesssim_\\varepsilon \\delta^{-\\varepsilon} (\\sum_{\\omega \\in \\Omega} |a_\\omega|^2)^{1/2}.\" title=\"\\displaystyle \\lesssim_\\varepsilon \\delta^{-\\varepsilon} (\\sum_{\\omega \\in \\Omega} |a_\\omega|^2)^{1/2}.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n <p>Explain why the exponent <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cfrac%7B2%28d%2B1%29%7D%7Bd-1%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\frac{2(d+1)}{d-1}}\" title=\"{\\frac{2(d+1)}{d-1}}\" class=\"latex\" /> here cannot be replaced by any larger exponent, and also explain why the exponent <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{2}\" title=\"{2}\" class=\"latex\" /> in the condition <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BR+%5Cgeq+%5Cdelta%5E%7B-2%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{R \\geq \\delta^{-2}}\" title=\"{R \\geq \\delta^{-2}}\" class=\"latex\" /> cannot be lowered.</p>\n</blockquote> \n<p>For further applications of decoupling estimates, such as restriction and Strichartz estimates on tori, and application to combinatorial incidence geometry, see <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=3971577\">the text of Demeter</a>.<br /> [These exercises will be moved to a more appropriate location at the end of the course, but are placed here for now so as not to affect numbering of existing exercises.]</p> \n<blockquote>\n <p><b>Exercise 33</b> Show that the inequality in <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11649#a2\">(8)</a> is actually an equality, if <img 05:36:56","updatedTime":"2020-08-25 05:36:56","title":"John Conway","link":"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11638","description":"<p>I was greatly saddened to learn that <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Horton_Conway\">John Conway</a> <a href=\"https://dailyvoice.com/new-jersey/mercer/obituaries/covid-19-kills-renowned-princeton-mathematician-game-of-life-inventor-john-conway-in-3-days/786461/\">died yesterday from COVID-19</a>, aged 82.</p>\n<p>My own mathematical areas of expertise are somewhat far from Conway&#8217;s; I have played for instance with finite simple groups on occasion, but have not studied his work on <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monstrous_moonshine\">moonshine</a> and the monster group.  But I have certainly encountered his results every so often in surprising contexts; most recently, when <a href=\"https://terrytao.wordpress.com/tag/collatz-conjecture/\">working on the Collatz conjecture</a>, I looked into Conway&#8217;s wonderfully preposterous <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FRACTRAN\">FRACTRAN language</a>, which can encode any Turing machine as an iteration of a Collatz-type map, showing in particular that there are generalisations of the Collatz conjecture that are undecidable in axiomatic frameworks such as ZFC.  [EDIT: also, my belief that the Navier-Stokes equations admit solutions that blow up in finite time is also highly influenced by the ability of <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conway%27s_Game_of_Life\">Conway&#8217;s game of life</a> <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Von_Neumann_cellular_automaton\">to generate</a> self-replicating &#8220;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Self-replicating_machine\">von Neumann machines</a>&#8220;.]</p>\n<p>I first met John as an incoming graduate student in Princeton in 1992; indeed, a talk he gave, on &#8220;Extreme proofs&#8221; (proofs that are in some sense &#8220;extreme points&#8221; in the &#8220;convex hull&#8221; of all proofs of a given result), may well have been the first research-level talk I ever attended, and one that set a high standard for all the subsequent talks I went to, with Conway&#8217;s ability to tease out deep and interesting mathematics from seemingly frivolous questions making a particular impact on me.  (Some version of this talk eventually became <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=3111964\">this paper of Conway and Shipman</a> many years later.)</p>\n<p>Conway was fond of hanging out in the Princeton graduate lounge at the time of my studies there, often tinkering with some game or device, and often enlisting any nearby graduate students to assist him with some experiment or other.  I have a vague memory of being drafted into holding various lengths of cloth with several other students in order to compute some element of a braid group; on another occasion he challenged me to a board game he recently invented (now known as &#8220;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phutball\">Phutball</a>&#8220;) with Elwyn Berlekamp and Richard Guy (who, by sad coincidence, both also passed away in the last 12 months).  I still remember being repeatedly obliterated in that game, which was a healthy and needed lesson in humility for me (and several of my fellow graduate students) at the time.  I also recall Conway spending several weeks trying to construct a strange periscope-type device to try to help him visualize four-dimensional objects by giving his eyes vertical parallax in addition to the usual horizontal parallax, although he later told me that the only thing the device made him experience was a headache.</p>\n<p>About ten years ago we ran into each other at some large mathematics conference, and lacking any other plans, we had a pleasant dinner together at the conference hotel.  We talked a little bit of math, but mostly the conversation was philosophical.  I regrettably do not remember precisely what we discussed, but it was very refreshing and stimulating to have an extremely frank and heartfelt interaction with someone with Conway&#8217;s level of insight and intellectual clarity.</p>\n<p>Conway was arguably an extreme point in the convex hull of all mathematicians.  He will very much be missed.</p>\n","descriptionType":"html","publishedDate":"Sun, 12 Apr 2020 20:46:49 +0000","feedId":3543,"bgimg":"","linkMd5":"16a9a157ddb2fc87c3bd38b373c56373","bgimgJsdelivr":"","metaImg":"","author":"Terence Tao","publishedOrCreatedDate":1598305016232},{"createdTime":"2020-08-25 05:36:56","updatedTime":"2020-08-25 05:36:56","title":"247B, Notes 3: pseudodifferential operators","link":"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11722","description":"<p> In contrast to previous notes, in this set of notes we shall focus exclusively on Fourier analysis in the one-dimensional setting <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bd%3D1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{d=1}\" title=\"{d=1}\" class=\"latex\" /> for simplicity of notation, although all of the results here have natural extensions to higher dimensions. Depending on the physical context, one can view the physical domain <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf R}}\" title=\"{{\\bf R}}\" class=\"latex\" /> as representing either space or time; we will mostly think in terms of the former interpretation, even though the standard terminology of “time-frequency analysis”, which we will make more prominent use of in later notes, clearly originates from the latter. </p> \n<p> In previous notes we have often performed various localisations in either physical space or Fourier space <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf R}}\" title=\"{{\\bf R}}\" class=\"latex\" />, for instance in order to take advantage of the uncertainty principle. One can formalise these operations in terms of the functional calculus of two basic operations on Schwartz functions <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{{\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" />, the <em>position operator</em> <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BX%3A+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{X: {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R}) \\rightarrow {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{X: {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R}) \\rightarrow {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" /> defined by </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%28Xf%29%28x%29+%3A%3D+x+f%28x%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  (Xf)(x) := x f(x)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  (Xf)(x) := x f(x)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> and the <em>momentum operator</em> <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BD%3A+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{D: {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R}) \\rightarrow {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{D: {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R}) \\rightarrow {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" />, defined by <a name=\"df\"></a></p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%28Df%29%28x%29+%3A%3D+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B2%5Cpi+i%7D+%5Cfrac%7Bd%7D%7Bdx%7D+f%28x%29.+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%281%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  (Df)(x) := \\frac{1}{2\\pi i} \\frac{d}{dx} f(x). \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (1)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  (Df)(x) := \\frac{1}{2\\pi i} \\frac{d}{dx} f(x). \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (1)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> (The terminology comes from quantum mechanics, where it is customary to also insert a small constant <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bh%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{h}\" title=\"{h}\" class=\"latex\" /> on the right-hand side of <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11722#df\">(1)</a> in accordance with <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matter_wave\">de Broglie’s law</a>. Such a normalisation is also used in several branches of mathematics, most notably semiclassical analysis and <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Microlocal_analysis\">microlocal analysis</a>, where it becomes profitable to consider the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Semiclassical_physics\">semiclassical limit</a> <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bh+%5Crightarrow+0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{h \\rightarrow 0}\" title=\"{h \\rightarrow 0}\" class=\"latex\" />, but we will not emphasise this perspective here.) The momentum operator can be viewed as the counterpart to the position operator, but in frequency space instead of physical space, since we have the standard identity </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cwidehat%7BDf%7D%28%5Cxi%29+%3D+%5Cxi+%5Chat+f%28%5Cxi%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\widehat{Df}(\\xi) = \\xi \\hat f(\\xi)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\widehat{Df}(\\xi) = \\xi \\hat f(\\xi)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> for any <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cxi+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\xi \\in {\\bf R}}\" title=\"{\\xi \\in {\\bf R}}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{f \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" />. We observe that both operators <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BX%2CD%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{X,D}\" title=\"{X,D}\" class=\"latex\" /> are formally self-adjoint in the sense that </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Clangle+Xf%2C+g+%5Crangle+%3D+%5Clangle+f%2C+Xg+%5Crangle%3B+%5Cquad+%5Clangle+Df%2C+g+%5Crangle+%3D+%5Clangle+f%2C+Dg+%5Crangle&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\langle Xf, g \\rangle = \\langle f, Xg \\rangle; \\quad \\langle Df, g \\rangle = \\langle f, Dg \\rangle\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\langle Xf, g \\rangle = \\langle f, Xg \\rangle; \\quad \\langle Df, g \\rangle = \\langle f, Dg \\rangle\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> for all <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%2Cg+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f,g \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{f,g \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" />, where we use the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BL%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{L^2({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{L^2({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" /> Hermitian inner product </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Clangle+f%2C+g%5Crangle+%3A%3D+%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+f%28x%29+%5Coverline%7Bg%28x%29%7D%5C+dx.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\langle f, g\\rangle := \\int_{\\bf R} f(x) \\overline{g(x)}\\ dx.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\langle f, g\\rangle := \\int_{\\bf R} f(x) \\overline{g(x)}\\ dx.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> Clearly, for any polynomial <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP%28x%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P(x)}\" title=\"{P(x)}\" class=\"latex\" /> of one real variable <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x}\" title=\"{x}\" class=\"latex\" /> (with complex coefficients), the operator <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP%28X%29%3A+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P(X): {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R}) \\rightarrow {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{P(X): {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R}) \\rightarrow {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" /> is given by the spatial multiplier operator </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%28P%28X%29+f%29%28x%29+%3D+P%28x%29+f%28x%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  (P(X) f)(x) = P(x) f(x)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  (P(X) f)(x) = P(x) f(x)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> and similarly the operator <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP%28D%29%3A+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P(D): {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R}) \\rightarrow {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{P(D): {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R}) \\rightarrow {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" /> is given by the Fourier multiplier operator </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cwidehat%7BP%28D%29+f%7D%28%5Cxi%29+%3D+P%28%5Cxi%29+%5Chat+f%28%5Cxi%29.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\widehat{P(D) f}(\\xi) = P(\\xi) \\hat f(\\xi).\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\widehat{P(D) f}(\\xi) = P(\\xi) \\hat f(\\xi).\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> Inspired by this, if <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bm%3A+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cbf+C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{m: {\\bf R} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" title=\"{m: {\\bf R} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" class=\"latex\" /> is any smooth function that obeys the derivative bounds <a name=\"deriv\"></a></p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cfrac%7Bd%5Ej%7D%7Bdx%5Ej%7D+m%28x%29+%5Clesssim_%7Bm%2Cj%7D+%5Clangle+x+%5Crangle%5E%7BO_%7Bm%2Cj%7D%281%29%7D+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%282%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\frac{d^j}{dx^j} m(x) \\lesssim_{m,j} \\langle x \\rangle^{O_{m,j}(1)} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (2)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\frac{d^j}{dx^j} m(x) \\lesssim_{m,j} \\langle x \\rangle^{O_{m,j}(1)} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (2)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> for all <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bj+%5Cgeq+0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{j \\geq 0}\" title=\"{j \\geq 0}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x \\in {\\bf R}}\" title=\"{x \\in {\\bf R}}\" class=\"latex\" /> (that is to say, all derivatives of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bm%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{m}\" title=\"{m}\" class=\"latex\" /> grow at most polynomially), then we can define the spatial multiplier operator <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bm%28X%29%3A+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{m(X): {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R}) \\rightarrow {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{m(X): {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R}) \\rightarrow {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" /> by the formula </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%28m%28X%29+f%29%28x%29+%3A%3D+m%28x%29+f%28x%29%3B&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  (m(X) f)(x) := m(x) f(x);\" title=\"\\displaystyle  (m(X) f)(x) := m(x) f(x);\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> one can easily verify from several applications of the Leibniz rule that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bm%28X%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{m(X)}\" title=\"{m(X)}\" class=\"latex\" /> maps Schwartz functions to Schwartz functions. We refer to <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bm%28x%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{m(x)}\" title=\"{m(x)}\" class=\"latex\" /> as the <em>symbol</em> of this spatial multiplier operator. In a similar fashion, we define the Fourier multiplier operator <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bm%28D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{m(D)}\" title=\"{m(D)}\" class=\"latex\" /> associated to the symbol <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bm%28%5Cxi%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{m(\\xi)}\" title=\"{m(\\xi)}\" class=\"latex\" /> by the formula </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cwidehat%7Bm%28D%29+f%7D%28%5Cxi%29+%3A%3D+m%28%5Cxi%29+%5Chat+f%28%5Cxi%29.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\widehat{m(D) f}(\\xi) := m(\\xi) \\hat f(\\xi).\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\widehat{m(D) f}(\\xi) := m(\\xi) \\hat f(\\xi).\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> For instance, any constant coefficient linear differential operators <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Csum_%7Bk%3D0%7D%5En+c_k+%5Cfrac%7Bd%5Ek%7D%7Bdx%5Ek%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\sum_{k=0}^n c_k \\frac{d^k}{dx^k}}\" title=\"{\\sum_{k=0}^n c_k \\frac{d^k}{dx^k}}\" class=\"latex\" /> can be written in this notation as </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+%5Csum_%7Bk%3D0%7D%5En+c_k+%5Cfrac%7Bd%5Ek%7D%7Bdx%5Ek%7D+%3D%5Csum_%7Bk%3D0%7D%5En+c_k+%282%5Cpi+i+D%29%5Ek%3B&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle \\sum_{k=0}^n c_k \\frac{d^k}{dx^k} =\\sum_{k=0}^n c_k (2\\pi i D)^k;\" title=\"\\displaystyle \\sum_{k=0}^n c_k \\frac{d^k}{dx^k} =\\sum_{k=0}^n c_k (2\\pi i D)^k;\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> however there are many Fourier multiplier operators that are not of this form, such as fractional derivative operators <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Clangle+D+%5Crangle%5Es+%3D+%281-+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B4%5Cpi%5E2%7D+%5Cfrac%7Bd%5E2%7D%7Bdx%5E2%7D%29%5E%7Bs%2F2%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\langle D \\rangle^s = (1- \\frac{1}{4\\pi^2} \\frac{d^2}{dx^2})^{s/2}}\" title=\"{\\langle D \\rangle^s = (1- \\frac{1}{4\\pi^2} \\frac{d^2}{dx^2})^{s/2}}\" class=\"latex\" /> for non-integer values of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bs%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{s}\" title=\"{s}\" class=\"latex\" />, which is a Fourier multiplier operator with symbol <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Clangle+%5Cxi+%5Crangle%5Es%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\langle \\xi \\rangle^s}\" title=\"{\\langle \\xi \\rangle^s}\" class=\"latex\" />. It is also very common to use spatial cutoffs <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cpsi%28X%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\psi(X)}\" title=\"{\\psi(X)}\" class=\"latex\" /> and Fourier cutoffs <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cpsi%28D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\psi(D)}\" title=\"{\\psi(D)}\" class=\"latex\" /> for various bump functions <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cpsi%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\psi}\" title=\"{\\psi}\" class=\"latex\" /> to localise functions in either space or frequency; we have seen several examples of such cutoffs in action in previous notes (often in the higher dimensional setting <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bd%3E1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{d>1}\" title=\"{d>1}\" class=\"latex\" />).</p> \n<p> We observe that the maps <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bm+%5Cmapsto+m%28X%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{m \\mapsto m(X)}\" title=\"{m \\mapsto m(X)}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bm+%5Cmapsto+m%28D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{m \\mapsto m(D)}\" title=\"{m \\mapsto m(D)}\" class=\"latex\" /> are ring homomorphisms, thus for instance </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%28m_1+%2B+m_2%29%28D%29+%3D+m_1%28D%29+%2B+m_2%28D%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  (m_1 + m_2)(D) = m_1(D) + m_2(D)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  (m_1 + m_2)(D) = m_1(D) + m_2(D)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> and </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%28m_1+m_2%29%28D%29+%3D+m_1%28D%29+m_2%28D%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  (m_1 m_2)(D) = m_1(D) m_2(D)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  (m_1 m_2)(D) = m_1(D) m_2(D)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> for any <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bm_1%2Cm_2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{m_1,m_2}\" title=\"{m_1,m_2}\" class=\"latex\" /> obeying the derivative bounds <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11722#deriv\">(2)</a>; also <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bm%28D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{m(D)}\" title=\"{m(D)}\" class=\"latex\" /> is formally adjoint to <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Coverline%7Bm%28D%29%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\overline{m(D)}}\" title=\"{\\overline{m(D)}}\" class=\"latex\" /> in the sense that </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Clangle+m%28D%29+f%2C+g+%5Crangle+%3D+%5Clangle+f%2C+%5Coverline%7Bm%7D%28D%29+g+%5Crangle&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\langle m(D) f, g \\rangle = \\langle f, \\overline{m}(D) g \\rangle\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\langle m(D) f, g \\rangle = \\langle f, \\overline{m}(D) g \\rangle\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> for <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%2Cg+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f,g \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{f,g \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" />, and similarly for <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bm%28X%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{m(X)}\" title=\"{m(X)}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Coverline%7Bm%7D%28X%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\overline{m}(X)}\" title=\"{\\overline{m}(X)}\" class=\"latex\" />. One can interpret these facts as part of the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Functional_calculus\">functional calculus</a> of the operators <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BX%2CD%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{X,D}\" title=\"{X,D}\" class=\"latex\" />, which can be interpreted as densely defined self-adjoint operators on <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BL%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{L^2({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{L^2({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" />. However, in this set of notes we will not develop the spectral theory necessary in order to fully set out this functional calculus rigorously.</p> \n<p> In the field of PDE and ODE, it is also very common to study <em>variable coefficient</em> linear differential operators <a name=\"ckk\"></a></p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Csum_%7Bk%3D0%7D%5En+c_k%28x%29+%5Cfrac%7Bd%5Ek%7D%7Bdx%5Ek%7D+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%283%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{k=0}^n c_k(x) \\frac{d^k}{dx^k} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (3)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{k=0}^n c_k(x) \\frac{d^k}{dx^k} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (3)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> where the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bc_0%2C%5Cdots%2Cc_n%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{c_0,\\dots,c_n}\" title=\"{c_0,\\dots,c_n}\" class=\"latex\" /> are now functions of the spatial variable <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x}\" title=\"{x}\" class=\"latex\" /> obeying the derivative bounds <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11722#deriv\">(2)</a>. A simple example is the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantum_harmonic_oscillator\">quantum harmonic oscillator Hamiltonian</a> <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B-%5Cfrac%7Bd%5E2%7D%7Bdx%5E2%7D+%2B+x%5E2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{-\\frac{d^2}{dx^2} + x^2}\" title=\"{-\\frac{d^2}{dx^2} + x^2}\" class=\"latex\" />. One can rewrite this operator in our notation as </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Csum_%7Bk%3D0%7D%5En+c_k%28X%29+%282%5Cpi+i+D%29%5Ek&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{k=0}^n c_k(X) (2\\pi i D)^k\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{k=0}^n c_k(X) (2\\pi i D)^k\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> and so it is natural to interpret this operator as a combination <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%28X%2CD%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a(X,D)}\" title=\"{a(X,D)}\" class=\"latex\" /> of both the position operator <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BX%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{X}\" title=\"{X}\" class=\"latex\" /> and the momentum operator <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BD%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{D}\" title=\"{D}\" class=\"latex\" />, where the <em>symbol</em> <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%3A+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Ctimes+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cbf+C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a: {\\bf R} \\times {\\bf R} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" title=\"{a: {\\bf R} \\times {\\bf R} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" class=\"latex\" /> this operator is the function <a name=\"akk\"></a></p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++a%28x%2C%5Cxi%29+%3A%3D+%5Csum_%7Bk%3D0%7D%5En+c_k%28x%29+%282%5Cpi+i+%5Cxi%29%5Ek.+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%284%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  a(x,\\xi) := \\sum_{k=0}^n c_k(x) (2\\pi i \\xi)^k. \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (4)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  a(x,\\xi) := \\sum_{k=0}^n c_k(x) (2\\pi i \\xi)^k. \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (4)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> Indeed, from the Fourier inversion formula </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++f%28x%29+%3D+%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Chat+f%28%5Cxi%29+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+x+%5Cxi%7D%5C+d%5Cxi&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  f(x) = \\int_{\\bf R} \\hat f(\\xi) e^{2\\pi i x \\xi}\\ d\\xi\" title=\"\\displaystyle  f(x) = \\int_{\\bf R} \\hat f(\\xi) e^{2\\pi i x \\xi}\\ d\\xi\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> for any <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{f \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" /> we have </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%282%5Cpi+i+D%29%5Ek+f%28x%29+%3D+%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%282%5Cpi+i+%5Cxi%29%5Ek+%5Chat+f%28%5Cxi%29+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+x+%5Cxi%7D%5C+d%5Cxi&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  (2\\pi i D)^k f(x) = \\int_{\\bf R} (2\\pi i \\xi)^k \\hat f(\\xi) e^{2\\pi i x \\xi}\\ d\\xi\" title=\"\\displaystyle  (2\\pi i D)^k f(x) = \\int_{\\bf R} (2\\pi i \\xi)^k \\hat f(\\xi) e^{2\\pi i x \\xi}\\ d\\xi\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> and hence on multiplying by <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bc_k%28x%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{c_k(x)}\" title=\"{c_k(x)}\" class=\"latex\" /> and summing we have </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+%28%5Csum_%7Bk%3D0%7D%5En+c_k%28X%29+%282%5Cpi+i+D%29%5Ek%29+f%28x%29+%3D+%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+a%28x%2C%5Cxi%29+%5Chat+f%28%5Cxi%29+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+x+%5Cxi%7D%5C+d%5Cxi.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle (\\sum_{k=0}^n c_k(X) (2\\pi i D)^k) f(x) = \\int_{\\bf R} a(x,\\xi) \\hat f(\\xi) e^{2\\pi i x \\xi}\\ d\\xi.\" title=\"\\displaystyle (\\sum_{k=0}^n c_k(X) (2\\pi i D)^k) f(x) = \\int_{\\bf R} a(x,\\xi) \\hat f(\\xi) e^{2\\pi i x \\xi}\\ d\\xi.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> Inspired by this, we can introduce the <em>Kohn-Nirenberg quantisation</em> by defining the operator <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%28X%2CD%29+%3D+a_%7BKN%7D%28X%2CD%29%3A+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a(X,D) = a_{KN}(X,D): {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R}) \\rightarrow {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{a(X,D) = a_{KN}(X,D): {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R}) \\rightarrow {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" /> by the formula <a name=\"axd\"></a></p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++a%28X%2CD%29+f%28x%29+%3D+%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+a%28x%2C%5Cxi%29+%5Chat+f%28%5Cxi%29+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+x+%5Cxi%7D%5C+d%5Cxi+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%285%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  a(X,D) f(x) = \\int_{\\bf R} a(x,\\xi) \\hat f(\\xi) e^{2\\pi i x \\xi}\\ d\\xi \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (5)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  a(X,D) f(x) = \\int_{\\bf R} a(x,\\xi) \\hat f(\\xi) e^{2\\pi i x \\xi}\\ d\\xi \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (5)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> whenever <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{f \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%3A+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Ctimes+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cbf+C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a: {\\bf R} \\times {\\bf R} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" title=\"{a: {\\bf R} \\times {\\bf R} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" class=\"latex\" /> is any smooth function obeying the derivative bounds <a name=\"deriv-2\"></a></p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpartial%5Ej%7D%7B%5Cpartial+x%5Ej%7D+%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpartial%5El%7D%7B%5Cpartial+%5Cxi%5El%7D+a%28x%2C%5Cxi%29+%5Clesssim_%7Ba%2Cj%2Cl%7D+%5Clangle+x+%5Crangle%5E%7BO_%7Ba%2Cj%7D%281%29%7D+%5Clangle+%5Cxi+%5Crangle%5E%7BO_%7Ba%2Cj%2Cl%7D%281%29%7D+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%286%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\frac{\\partial^j}{\\partial x^j} \\frac{\\partial^l}{\\partial \\xi^l} a(x,\\xi) \\lesssim_{a,j,l} \\langle x \\rangle^{O_{a,j}(1)} \\langle \\xi \\rangle^{O_{a,j,l}(1)} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (6)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\frac{\\partial^j}{\\partial x^j} \\frac{\\partial^l}{\\partial \\xi^l} a(x,\\xi) \\lesssim_{a,j,l} \\langle x \\rangle^{O_{a,j}(1)} \\langle \\xi \\rangle^{O_{a,j,l}(1)} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (6)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> for all <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bj%2Cl+%5Cgeq+0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{j,l \\geq 0}\" title=\"{j,l \\geq 0}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x \\in {\\bf R}}\" title=\"{x \\in {\\bf R}}\" class=\"latex\" /> (note carefully that the exponent in <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x}\" title=\"{x}\" class=\"latex\" /> on the right-hand side is required to be uniform in <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bl%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{l}\" title=\"{l}\" class=\"latex\" />). This quantisation clearly generalises both the spatial multiplier operators <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bm%28X%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{m(X)}\" title=\"{m(X)}\" class=\"latex\" /> and the Fourier multiplier operators <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bm%28D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{m(D)}\" title=\"{m(D)}\" class=\"latex\" /> defined earlier, which correspond to the cases when the symbol <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%28x%2C%5Cxi%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a(x,\\xi)}\" title=\"{a(x,\\xi)}\" class=\"latex\" /> is a function of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x}\" title=\"{x}\" class=\"latex\" /> only or <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cxi%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\xi}\" title=\"{\\xi}\" class=\"latex\" /> only respectively. Thus we have combined the physical space <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%3D+%5C%7B+x%3A+x+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf R} = \\{ x: x \\in {\\bf R}\\}}\" title=\"{{\\bf R} = \\{ x: x \\in {\\bf R}\\}}\" class=\"latex\" /> and the frequency space <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%3D+%5C%7B+%5Cxi%3A+%5Cxi+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf R} = \\{ \\xi: \\xi \\in {\\bf R}\\}}\" title=\"{{\\bf R} = \\{ \\xi: \\xi \\in {\\bf R}\\}}\" class=\"latex\" /> into a single domain, known as <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phase_space\">phase space</a> <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Ctimes+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%3D+%5C%7B+%28x%2C%5Cxi%29%3A+x%2C%5Cxi+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf R} \\times {\\bf R} = \\{ (x,\\xi): x,\\xi \\in {\\bf R} \\}}\" title=\"{{\\bf R} \\times {\\bf R} = \\{ (x,\\xi): x,\\xi \\in {\\bf R} \\}}\" class=\"latex\" />. The term “time-frequency analysis” encompasses analysis based on decompositions and other manipulations of phase space, in much the same way that “Fourier analysis” encompasses analysis based on decompositions and other manipulations of frequency space. We remark that the Kohn-Nirenberg quantization is not the only choice of quantization one could use; see Remark <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11722#weyl\">19</a> below.</p> \n<blockquote>\n <p><b>Exercise 1</b> <a name=\"unq\"></a> </p> \n <ul> \n  <li>(i) Show that for <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a}\" title=\"{a}\" class=\"latex\" /> obeying <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11722#deriv-2\">(6)</a>, that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%28X%2CD%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a(X,D)}\" title=\"{a(X,D)}\" class=\"latex\" /> does indeed map <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{{\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" /> to <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{{\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" />. </li> \n  <li>(ii) Show that the symbol <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a}\" title=\"{a}\" class=\"latex\" /> is uniquely determined by the operator <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%28X%2CD%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a(X,D)}\" title=\"{a(X,D)}\" class=\"latex\" />. That is to say, if <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%2Cb%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a,b}\" title=\"{a,b}\" class=\"latex\" /> are two functions obeying <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11722#deriv-2\">(6)</a> with <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%28X%2CD%29+f+%3D+b%28X%2CD%29+f%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a(X,D) f = b(X,D) f}\" title=\"{a(X,D) f = b(X,D) f}\" class=\"latex\" /> for all <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{f \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" />, then <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%3Db%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a=b}\" title=\"{a=b}\" class=\"latex\" />. (<em>Hint:</em> apply <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%28X%2CD%29-b%28X%2CD%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a(X,D)-b(X,D)}\" title=\"{a(X,D)-b(X,D)}\" class=\"latex\" /> to a suitable truncation of a plane wave <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx+%5Cmapsto+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+x+%5Cxi%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x \\mapsto e^{2\\pi i x \\xi}}\" title=\"{x \\mapsto e^{2\\pi i x \\xi}}\" class=\"latex\" /> and then take limits.) </li> \n </ul> \n</blockquote>  \n<p> In principle, the quantisations <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%28X%2CD%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a(X,D)}\" title=\"{a(X,D)}\" class=\"latex\" /> are potentially very useful for such tasks as inverting variable coefficient linear operators, or to localize a function simultaneously in physical and Fourier space. However, a fundamental difficulty arises: map from symbols <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a}\" title=\"{a}\" class=\"latex\" /> to operators <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%28X%2CD%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a(X,D)}\" title=\"{a(X,D)}\" class=\"latex\" /> is now no longer a ring homomorphism, in particular <a name=\"ringho\"></a></p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%28a_1+a_2%29%28X%2CD%29+%5Cneq+a_1%28X%2CD%29+a_2%28X%2CD%29+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%287%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  (a_1 a_2)(X,D) \\neq a_1(X,D) a_2(X,D) \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (7)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  (a_1 a_2)(X,D) \\neq a_1(X,D) a_2(X,D) \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (7)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> in general. Fundamentally, this is due to the fact that pointwise multiplication of symbols is a commutative operation, whereas the composition of operators such as <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BX%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{X}\" title=\"{X}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BD%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{D}\" title=\"{D}\" class=\"latex\" /> does not necessarily commute. This lack of commutativity can be measured by introducing the <em>commutator</em> </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5BA%2CB%5D+%3A%3D+AB+-+BA&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  [A,B] := AB - BA\" title=\"\\displaystyle  [A,B] := AB - BA\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> of two operators <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BA%2CB%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{A,B}\" title=\"{A,B}\" class=\"latex\" />, and noting from the product rule that </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5BX%2CD%5D+%3D+-%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B2%5Cpi+i%7D+%5Cneq+0.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  [X,D] = -\\frac{1}{2\\pi i} \\neq 0.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  [X,D] = -\\frac{1}{2\\pi i} \\neq 0.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> (In the language of Lie groups and Lie algebras, this tells us that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BX%2CD%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{X,D}\" title=\"{X,D}\" class=\"latex\" /> are (up to complex constants) the standard Lie algebra generators of the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heisenberg_group\">Heisenberg group</a>.) From a quantum mechanical perspective, this lack of commutativity is the root cause of the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uncertainty_principle\">uncertainty principle</a> that prevents one from simultaneously localizing in both position and momentum past a certain point. Here is one basic way of formalising this principle:</p> \n<blockquote>\n <p><b>Exercise 2 (Heisenberg uncertainty principle)</b> <a name=\"hup\"></a> For any <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx_0%2C+%5Cxi_0+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x_0, \\xi_0 \\in {\\bf R}}\" title=\"{x_0, \\xi_0 \\in {\\bf R}}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+%5Cmathcal%7BS%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in \\mathcal{S}({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{f \\in \\mathcal{S}({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" />, show that </p> \n <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%28X-x_0%29+f+%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D+%5C%7C+%28D-%5Cxi_0%29+f%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D+%5Cgeq+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B4%5Cpi%7D+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D%5E2.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| (X-x_0) f \\|_{L^2({\\bf R})} \\| (D-\\xi_0) f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R})} \\geq \\frac{1}{4\\pi} \\|f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R})}^2.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| (X-x_0) f \\|_{L^2({\\bf R})} \\| (D-\\xi_0) f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R})} \\geq \\frac{1}{4\\pi} \\|f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R})}^2.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n <p> (<em>Hint:</em> evaluate the expression <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Clangle+%5BX-x_0%2C+D+-+%5Cxi_0%5D+f%2C+f+%5Crangle%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\langle [X-x_0, D - \\xi_0] f, f \\rangle}\" title=\"{\\langle [X-x_0, D - \\xi_0] f, f \\rangle}\" class=\"latex\" /> in two different ways and apply the Cauchy-Schwarz inequality.) Informally, this exercise asserts that the spatial uncertainty <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5CDelta+x%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\Delta x}\" title=\"{\\Delta x}\" class=\"latex\" /> and the frequency uncertainty <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5CDelta+%5Cxi%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\Delta \\xi}\" title=\"{\\Delta \\xi}\" class=\"latex\" /> of a function obey the Heisenberg uncertainty relation <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5CDelta+x+%5CDelta+%5Cxi+%5Cgtrsim+1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\Delta x \\Delta \\xi \\gtrsim 1}\" title=\"{\\Delta x \\Delta \\xi \\gtrsim 1}\" class=\"latex\" />. </p>\n</blockquote>  \n<p> Nevertheless, one still has the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Correspondence_principle\">correspondence principle</a>, which asserts that in certain regimes (which, with our choice of normalisations, corresponds to the high-frequency regime), quantum mechanics continues to behave like a commutative theory, and one can sometimes proceed as if the operators <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BX%2CD%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{X,D}\" title=\"{X,D}\" class=\"latex\" /> (and the various operators <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%28X%2CD%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a(X,D)}\" title=\"{a(X,D)}\" class=\"latex\" /> constructed from them) commute up to “lower order” errors. This can be formalised using the <em>pseudodifferential calculus</em>, which we give below the fold, in which we restrict the symbol <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a}\" title=\"{a}\" class=\"latex\" /> to certain “symbol classes” of various orders (which then restricts <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%28X%2CD%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a(X,D)}\" title=\"{a(X,D)}\" class=\"latex\" /> to be <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pseudo-differential_operator\">pseudodifferential operators</a> of various orders), and obtains approximate identities such as </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%28a_1+a_2%29%28X%2CD%29+%5Capprox+a_1%28X%2CD%29+a_2%28X%2CD%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  (a_1 a_2)(X,D) \\approx a_1(X,D) a_2(X,D)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  (a_1 a_2)(X,D) \\approx a_1(X,D) a_2(X,D)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> where the error between the left and right-hand sides is of “lower order” and can in fact enjoys a useful asymptotic expansion. As a first approximation to this calculus, one can think of functions <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{f \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" /> as having some sort of “<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phase_portrait\">phase space portrait</a>” <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Ctilde+f%28x%2C%5Cxi%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\tilde f(x,\\xi)}\" title=\"{\\tilde f(x,\\xi)}\" class=\"latex\" /> which somehow combines the physical space representation <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx+%5Cmapsto+f%28x%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x \\mapsto f(x)}\" title=\"{x \\mapsto f(x)}\" class=\"latex\" /> with its Fourier representation <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cxi+%5Cmapsto+f%28%5Cxi%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\xi \\mapsto f(\\xi)}\" title=\"{\\xi \\mapsto f(\\xi)}\" class=\"latex\" />, and pseudodifferential operators <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%28X%2CD%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a(X,D)}\" title=\"{a(X,D)}\" class=\"latex\" /> behave approximately like “phase space multiplier operators” in this representation in the sense that </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cwidetilde%7Ba%28X%2CD%29+f%7D%28x%2C%5Cxi%29+%5Capprox+a%28x%2C%5Cxi%29+%5Ctilde+f%28x%2C%5Cxi%29.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\widetilde{a(X,D) f}(x,\\xi) \\approx a(x,\\xi) \\tilde f(x,\\xi).\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\widetilde{a(X,D) f}(x,\\xi) \\approx a(x,\\xi) \\tilde f(x,\\xi).\"
