class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> Unfortunately the uncertainty principle (or the non-commutativity of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BX%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{X}\" title=\"{X}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BD%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{D}\" title=\"{D}\" class=\"latex\" />) prevents us from making these approximations perfectly precise, and it is not always clear how to even define a phase space portrait <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Ctilde+f%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\tilde f}\" title=\"{\\tilde f}\" class=\"latex\" /> of a function <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f}\" title=\"{f}\" class=\"latex\" /> precisely (although there are certain popular candidates for such a portrait, such as the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fourier%E2%80%93Bros%E2%80%93Iagolnitzer_transform\">FBI transform</a> (also known as the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gabor_transform\">Gabor transform</a> in signal processing literature), or the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wigner_quasiprobability_distribution\">Wigner quasiprobability distribution</a>, each of which have some advantages and disadvantages). Nevertheless even if the concept of a phase space portrait is somewhat fuzzy, it is of great conceptual benefit both within mathematics and outside of it. For instance, the musical score one assigns a piece of music can be viewed as a phase space portrait of the sound waves generated by that music.</p> \n<p> To complement the pseudodifferential calculus we have the basic <em>Calderón-Vaillancourt theorem</em>, which asserts that pseudodifferential operators of order zero are Calderón-Zygmund operators and thus bounded on <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{L^p({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{L^p({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" /> for <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1+%3C+p+%3C+%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1 < p < \\infty}\" title=\"{1 < p < \\infty}\" class=\"latex\" />. The standard proof of this theorem is a classic application of one of the basic techniques in harmonic analysis, namely the exploitation of <em>almost orthogonality</em>; the proof we will give here will achieve this through the elegant device of the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cotlar%E2%80%93Stein_lemma\">Cotlar-Stein lemma</a>. </p> \n<p> Pseudodifferential operators (especially when generalised to higher dimensions <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bd+%5Cgeq+1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{d \\geq 1}\" title=\"{d \\geq 1}\" class=\"latex\" />) are a fundamental tool in the theory of linear PDE, as well as related fields such as semiclassical analysis, microlocal analysis, and geometric quantisation. There is an even wider class of operators that is also of interest, namely the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fourier_integral_operator\">Fourier integral operators</a>, which roughly speaking not only approximately multiply the phase space portrait <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Ctilde+f%28x%2C%5Cxi%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\tilde f(x,\\xi)}\" title=\"{\\tilde f(x,\\xi)}\" class=\"latex\" /> of a function by some multiplier <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%28x%2C%5Cxi%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a(x,\\xi)}\" title=\"{a(x,\\xi)}\" class=\"latex\" />, but also move the portrait around by a <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Canonical_transformation\">canonical transformation</a>. However, the development of theory of these operators is beyond the scope of these notes; see for instance the texts <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=1481433\">of Hormander</a> or <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=2809923\">Eskin</a>. </p> \n<p> This set of notes is only the briefest introduction to the theory of pseudodifferential operators. Many texts are available that cover the theory in more detail, for instance <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=1766415\">this text of Taylor</a>. </p> \n<p> <span id=\"more-11722\"></span> </p>  \n<p align=\"center\"><b> — 1. Pseudodifferential operators — </b></p> \n<p> The Kohn-Nirenberg quantisation <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%28X%2CD%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a(X,D)}\" title=\"{a(X,D)}\" class=\"latex\" /> was defined above for any symbol <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%3A+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Ctimes+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cbf+C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a: {\\bf R} \\times {\\bf R} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" title=\"{a: {\\bf R} \\times {\\bf R} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" class=\"latex\" /> obeying the very loose estimates <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11722#deriv-2\">(6)</a>. To obtain a clean theory it is convenient to focus attention to more restrictive classes of symbols. There are many such classes one can consider, but we shall only work with the classical symbol classes: </p> \n<blockquote>\n <p><b>Definition 3 (Classical symbol class)</b> <a name=\"symb\"></a> Let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\alpha \\in {\\bf R}}\" title=\"{\\alpha \\in {\\bf R}}\" class=\"latex\" />. A function <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%3A+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Ctimes+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cbf+C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a: {\\bf R} \\times {\\bf R} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" title=\"{a: {\\bf R} \\times {\\bf R} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" class=\"latex\" /> is said to be a (classical) <em>symbol of order <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\alpha}\" title=\"{\\alpha}\" class=\"latex\" /></em> if it is smooth and one has the derivative bounds <a name=\"class-symb\"></a></p> \n <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpartial%5Ej%7D%7B%5Cpartial+x%5Ej%7D+%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpartial%5El%7D%7B%5Cpartial+%5Cxi%5El%7D+a%28x%2C%5Cxi%29+%5Clesssim_%7Ba%2Cj%2Cl%7D+%5Clangle+%5Cxi+%5Crangle%5E%7B%5Calpha+-+l%7D+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%288%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\frac{\\partial^j}{\\partial x^j} \\frac{\\partial^l}{\\partial \\xi^l} a(x,\\xi) \\lesssim_{a,j,l} \\langle \\xi \\rangle^{\\alpha - l} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (8)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\frac{\\partial^j}{\\partial x^j} \\frac{\\partial^l}{\\partial \\xi^l} a(x,\\xi) \\lesssim_{a,j,l} \\langle \\xi \\rangle^{\\alpha - l} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (8)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n <p> for all <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bj%2Cl+%5Cgeq+0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{j,l \\geq 0}\" title=\"{j,l \\geq 0}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28x%2C%5Cxi%29+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Ctimes+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(x,\\xi) \\in {\\bf R} \\times {\\bf R}}\" title=\"{(x,\\xi) \\in {\\bf R} \\times {\\bf R}}\" class=\"latex\" />. (Informally: <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a}\" title=\"{a}\" class=\"latex\" /> “behaves like” <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Clangle+%5Cxi+%5Crangle%5E%5Calpha%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\langle \\xi \\rangle^\\alpha}\" title=\"{\\langle \\xi \\rangle^\\alpha}\" class=\"latex\" />, with each derivative in the frequency variable gaining an additional decay factor of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Clangle+%5Cxi+%5Crangle%5E%7B-1%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\langle \\xi \\rangle^{-1}}\" title=\"{\\langle \\xi \\rangle^{-1}}\" class=\"latex\" />, but with each derivative in the spatial variable exhibiting no gain.) The collection of all symbols of order <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\alpha}\" title=\"{\\alpha}\" class=\"latex\" /> will be denoted <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%5E%5Calpha%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\mathcal S}^\\alpha}\" title=\"{{\\mathcal S}^\\alpha}\" class=\"latex\" />. If <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a}\" title=\"{a}\" class=\"latex\" /> is a symbol of order <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\alpha}\" title=\"{\\alpha}\" class=\"latex\" />, the operator <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%28X%2CD%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a(X,D)}\" title=\"{a(X,D)}\" class=\"latex\" /> is referred to as a <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pseudo-differential_operator\">pseudodifferential operator</a> of order <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\alpha}\" title=\"{\\alpha}\" class=\"latex\" />. </p>\n</blockquote>  \n<p> As a major motivating example, any variable coefficient linear differential operator <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11722#ckk\">(3)</a> of order <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bn%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{n}\" title=\"{n}\" class=\"latex\" /> will be a pseudodifferential operator of order <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bn%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{n}\" title=\"{n}\" class=\"latex\" />, so long as the coefficients <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bc_0%2C%5Cdots%2Cc_n%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{c_0,\\dots,c_n}\" title=\"{c_0,\\dots,c_n}\" class=\"latex\" /> obey the bounds <a name=\"cb\"></a></p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cfrac%7Bd%5Ej%7D%7Bd+x%5Ej%7D+c_k%28x%29+%5Clesssim_%7Bc_k%2C+j%7D+1+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%289%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\frac{d^j}{d x^j} c_k(x) \\lesssim_{c_k, j} 1 \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (9)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\frac{d^j}{d x^j} c_k(x) \\lesssim_{c_k, j} 1 \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (9)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> for <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bj+%5Cgeq+0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{j \\geq 0}\" title=\"{j \\geq 0}\" class=\"latex\" />, <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%3D0%2C%5Cdots%2Cn%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k=0,\\dots,n}\" title=\"{k=0,\\dots,n}\" class=\"latex\" />, and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x \\in {\\bf R}}\" title=\"{x \\in {\\bf R}}\" class=\"latex\" />. (This would then exclude operators with unbounded coefficients, such as the harmonic oscillator, but can handle localised versions of these operators, and in any event there are other symbol classes in the literature that can be used to handle certain types of differential operators with unbounded coefficients.) Also, a fractional differential operator such as <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%281+-+4%5Cpi%5E2+%5Cfrac%7Bd%5E2%7D%7Bdx%5E2%7D%29%5E%7B%5Calpha%2F2%7D+%3D+%5Clangle+D+%5Crangle%5E%5Calpha%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(1 - 4\\pi^2 \\frac{d^2}{dx^2})^{\\alpha/2} = \\langle D \\rangle^\\alpha}\" title=\"{(1 - 4\\pi^2 \\frac{d^2}{dx^2})^{\\alpha/2} = \\langle D \\rangle^\\alpha}\" class=\"latex\" /> will be a pseudodifferential operator of order <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\alpha}\" title=\"{\\alpha}\" class=\"latex\" /> for any <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\alpha \\in {\\bf R}}\" title=\"{\\alpha \\in {\\bf R}}\" class=\"latex\" />. We refer the reader to <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=1232192\">Stein’s text</a> for a discussion of more exotic symbol classes than the one given here. </p> \n<p> The space of pseudodifferential operators of order <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\alpha}\" title=\"{\\alpha}\" class=\"latex\" /> form a vector space that is non-decreasing in <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\alpha}\" title=\"{\\alpha}\" class=\"latex\" />: any pseudodifferential operator of order <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\alpha}\" title=\"{\\alpha}\" class=\"latex\" /> is automatically also of order <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cbeta%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\beta}\" title=\"{\\beta}\" class=\"latex\" /> for any <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cbeta%3E%5Calpha%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\beta>\\alpha}\" title=\"{\\beta>\\alpha}\" class=\"latex\" />. (Thus, strictly speaking, it would be more appropriate to say that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%28X%2CD%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a(X,D)}\" title=\"{a(X,D)}\" class=\"latex\" /> is a pseudodifferential operator of order <em>at most</em> <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\alpha}\" title=\"{\\alpha}\" class=\"latex\" /> if <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba+%5Cin+S%5E%5Calpha%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a \\in S^\\alpha}\" title=\"{a \\in S^\\alpha}\" class=\"latex\" />, but we will not adopt this convention for brevity.) The intuition to keep in mind is that a pseudodifferential operator of order <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\alpha}\" title=\"{\\alpha}\" class=\"latex\" /> behaves like a variable coefficient linear differential operator of order <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\alpha}\" title=\"{\\alpha}\" class=\"latex\" />, with the obvious caveat that in the latter case <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\alpha}\" title=\"{\\alpha}\" class=\"latex\" /> is restricted to be a natural number, whereas in the former <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\alpha}\" title=\"{\\alpha}\" class=\"latex\" /> can be any real number. This intuition will be supported by the various components of the <em>pseudodifferential calculus</em> that we shall develop later, for instance we will show that the composition of a pseudodifferential operator of order <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\alpha}\" title=\"{\\alpha}\" class=\"latex\" /> and a pseudodifferential operator of order <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cbeta%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\beta}\" title=\"{\\beta}\" class=\"latex\" /> is a pseudodifferential operator of order <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha%2B%5Cbeta%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\alpha+\\beta}\" title=\"{\\alpha+\\beta}\" class=\"latex\" />. </p> \n<p> Before we set out this calculus, though, we give a fundamental <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BL%5Ep%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{L^p}\" title=\"{L^p}\" class=\"latex\" /> estimate, which can be viewed as a variable coefficient version of the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiplier_(Fourier_analysis)#Mikhlin_multiplier_theorem\">Hörmander-Mikhlin multiplier theorem</a>: </p> \n<blockquote>\n <p><b>Theorem 4 (Calderón-Vallaincourt theorem)</b> <a name=\"cv\"></a> Let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1+%3C+p+%3C+%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1 < p < \\infty}\" title=\"{1 < p < \\infty}\" class=\"latex\" />, and let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%28X%2CD%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a(X,D)}\" title=\"{a(X,D)}\" class=\"latex\" /> be a pseudodifferential operator of order <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{0}\" title=\"{0}\" class=\"latex\" />. Then one has <a name=\"clp\"></a></p> \n <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+a%28X%2CD%29+f%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D+%5Clesssim_%7Ba%2Cp%7D+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%2810%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| a(X,D) f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R})} \\lesssim_{a,p} \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R})} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (10)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| a(X,D) f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R})} \\lesssim_{a,p} \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R})} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (10)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n <p> for all <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{f \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" />. In particular, <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%28X%2CD%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a(X,D)}\" title=\"{a(X,D)}\" class=\"latex\" /> extends to a bounded linear operator on each <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{L^p({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{L^p({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" /> space with <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1+%3C+p+%3C+%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1 < p < \\infty}\" title=\"{1 < p < \\infty}\" class=\"latex\" />. </p>\n</blockquote>  \n<p> We now begin the proof of this theorem. The first step is a dyadic decomposition of Littlewood-Paley type. Let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cphi+%5Cin+C%5E%5Cinfty_c%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\phi \\in C^\\infty_c({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{\\phi \\in C^\\infty_c({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" /> be a bump function supported on <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5B-1%2C1%5D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{[-1,1]}\" title=\"{[-1,1]}\" class=\"latex\" /> that equals <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1}\" title=\"{1}\" class=\"latex\" /> on <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5B-1%2F2%2C1%2F2%5D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{[-1/2,1/2]}\" title=\"{[-1/2,1/2]}\" class=\"latex\" />. Then we can write </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++a%28x%2C%5Cxi%29+%3D+%5Csum_%7Bk%3D0%7D%5E%5Cinfty+a_k%28x%2C%5Cxi%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  a(x,\\xi) = \\sum_{k=0}^\\infty a_k(x,\\xi)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  a(x,\\xi) = \\sum_{k=0}^\\infty a_k(x,\\xi)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> where </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++a_0%28x%2C%5Cxi%29+%3A%3D+%5Cphi%28%5Cxi%29+a%28x%2C%5Cxi%29+&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  a_0(x,\\xi) := \\phi(\\xi) a(x,\\xi) \" title=\"\\displaystyle  a_0(x,\\xi) := \\phi(\\xi) a(x,\\xi) \" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> and </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++a_k%28x%2C%5Cxi%29+%3A%3D+%28%5Cphi%28%5Cxi%2F2%5Ek%29+-+%5Cphi%28%5Cxi%2F2%5E%7Bk-1%7D%29%29+a%28x%2C%5Cxi%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  a_k(x,\\xi) := (\\phi(\\xi/2^k) - \\phi(\\xi/2^{k-1})) a(x,\\xi)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  a_k(x,\\xi) := (\\phi(\\xi/2^k) - \\phi(\\xi/2^{k-1})) a(x,\\xi)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> for <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk+%5Cgeq+1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k \\geq 1}\" title=\"{k \\geq 1}\" class=\"latex\" />. From dominated convergence, implies that </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++a%28X%2CD%29+f%28x%29+%3D+%5Csum_%7Bk%3D0%7D%5E%5Cinfty+a_k%28X%2CD%29+f%28x%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  a(X,D) f(x) = \\sum_{k=0}^\\infty a_k(X,D) f(x)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  a(X,D) f(x) = \\sum_{k=0}^\\infty a_k(X,D) f(x)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> pointwise for <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{f \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" />. Thus by Fatou’s lemma, it will suffice to show that </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%5Csum_%7Bk%3D0%7D%5EK+a_k%28X%2CD%29+f+%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D+%5Clesssim_%7Ba%2Cp%7D+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sum_{k=0}^K a_k(X,D) f \\|_{L^p({\\bf R})} \\lesssim_{a,p} \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R})}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sum_{k=0}^K a_k(X,D) f \\|_{L^p({\\bf R})} \\lesssim_{a,p} \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> uniformly in <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BK%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{K}\" title=\"{K}\" class=\"latex\" />. Observe from Definition <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11722#symb\">3</a> and the Leibniz rule that each <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba_k%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a_k}\" title=\"{a_k}\" class=\"latex\" /> is supported in the strip <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7B+%28x%2C%5Cxi%29%3A+%5Clangle+%5Cxi+%5Crangle+%5Csim+2%5Ek+%5C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\{ (x,\\xi): \\langle \\xi \\rangle \\sim 2^k \\}}\" title=\"{\\{ (x,\\xi): \\langle \\xi \\rangle \\sim 2^k \\}}\" class=\"latex\" /> and obeys the derivative estimates <a name=\"akderiv\"></a></p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpartial%5Ej%7D%7B%5Cpartial+x%5Ej%7D+%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpartial%5El%7D%7B%5Cpartial+%5Cxi%5El%7D+a_k%28x%2C%5Cxi%29+%5Clesssim_%7Ba%2Cj%2Cl%7D+2%5E%7B-kl%7D+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%2811%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\frac{\\partial^j}{\\partial x^j} \\frac{\\partial^l}{\\partial \\xi^l} a_k(x,\\xi) \\lesssim_{a,j,l} 2^{-kl} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (11)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\frac{\\partial^j}{\\partial x^j} \\frac{\\partial^l}{\\partial \\xi^l} a_k(x,\\xi) \\lesssim_{a,j,l} 2^{-kl} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (11)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> for all <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%2C%5Cxi%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x,\\xi}\" title=\"{x,\\xi}\" class=\"latex\" />.</p> \n<p> From <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11722#axd\">(5)</a> and Fubini’s theorem we can express <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba_k%28X%2CD%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a_k(X,D)}\" title=\"{a_k(X,D)}\" class=\"latex\" /> as an integral operator <a name=\"akxd\"></a></p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++a_k%28X%2CD%29+f%28x%29+%3D+%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+K_k%28x%2Cy%29+f%28y%29%5C+dy+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%2812%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  a_k(X,D) f(x) = \\int_{\\bf R} K_k(x,y) f(y)\\ dy \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (12)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  a_k(X,D) f(x) = \\int_{\\bf R} K_k(x,y) f(y)\\ dy \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (12)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> for <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+%5Cmathcal%7BS%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in \\mathcal{S}({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{f \\in \\mathcal{S}({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" />, where the integral kernel <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BK_k%28x%2Cy%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{K_k(x,y)}\" title=\"{K_k(x,y)}\" class=\"latex\" /> is given by the formula <a name=\"kiwi\"></a></p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++K_k%28x%2Cy%29+%3A%3D+%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+a_k%28x%2C%5Cxi%29+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+%28x-y%29+%5Cxi%7D%5C+d%5Cxi.+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%2813%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  K_k(x,y) := \\int_{\\bf R} a_k(x,\\xi) e^{2\\pi i (x-y) \\xi}\\ d\\xi. \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (13)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  K_k(x,y) := \\int_{\\bf R} a_k(x,\\xi) e^{2\\pi i (x-y) \\xi}\\ d\\xi. \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (13)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> We can obtain several estimates on this kernel. Firstly, from the triangle inequality, <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11722#akderiv\">(11)</a>, and the support property of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba_k%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a_k}\" title=\"{a_k}\" class=\"latex\" /> we have the trivial bound </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++K_k%28x%2Cy%29+%5Clesssim_a+2%5Ek.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  K_k(x,y) \\lesssim_a 2^k.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  K_k(x,y) \\lesssim_a 2^k.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> When <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx+%5Cneq+y%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x \\neq y}\" title=\"{x \\neq y}\" class=\"latex\" />, we may integrate by parts repeatedly, gaining factors of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BO%28%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B%7Cx-y%7C%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{O(\\frac{1}{|x-y|})}\" title=\"{O(\\frac{1}{|x-y|})}\" class=\"latex\" /> at the cost of applying a <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cxi%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\xi}\" title=\"{\\xi}\" class=\"latex\" /> derivative to <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba_k%28x%2C%5Cxi%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a_k(x,\\xi)}\" title=\"{a_k(x,\\xi)}\" class=\"latex\" /> for each such factor, and then if one applies the triangle inequality, <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11722#akderiv\">(11)</a>, and support property of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba_k%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a_k}\" title=\"{a_k}\" class=\"latex\" /> as before we conclude that <a name=\"k1\"></a></p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++K_k%28x%2Cy%29+%5Clesssim_%7Ba%2Cl%7D+2%5Ek+%282%5Ek+%7Cx-y%7C%29%5E%7B-l%7D+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%2814%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  K_k(x,y) \\lesssim_{a,l} 2^k (2^k |x-y|)^{-l} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (14)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  K_k(x,y) \\lesssim_{a,l} 2^k (2^k |x-y|)^{-l} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (14)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> for any <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bl+%5Cgeq+0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{l \\geq 0}\" title=\"{l \\geq 0}\" class=\"latex\" />; by combining the estimates, we conclude that <a name=\"k2\"></a></p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++K_k%28x%2Cy%29+%5Clesssim_%7Ba%2Cl%7D+2%5Ek+%5Clangle+2%5Ek+%7Cx-y%7C%5Crangle%5E%7B-l%7D+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%2815%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  K_k(x,y) \\lesssim_{a,l} 2^k \\langle 2^k |x-y|\\rangle^{-l} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (15)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  K_k(x,y) \\lesssim_{a,l} 2^k \\langle 2^k |x-y|\\rangle^{-l} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (15)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> for all <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%2Cy+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x,y \\in {\\bf R}}\" title=\"{x,y \\in {\\bf R}}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bl+%5Cgeq+0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{l \\geq 0}\" title=\"{l \\geq 0}\" class=\"latex\" />. Differentiating <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11722#kiwi\">(13)</a> in <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x}\" title=\"{x}\" class=\"latex\" /> or <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7By%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{y}\" title=\"{y}\" class=\"latex\" />, and repeating the above arguments, we also obtain the estimates <a name=\"k3\"></a></p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpartial+K_k%7D%7B%5Cpartial+x%7D%28x%2Cy%29%2C+%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpartial+K_k%7D%7B%5Cpartial+y%7D%28x%2Cy%29+%5Clesssim_%7Ba%2Cl%7D+2%5E%7B2k%7D+%5Clangle+2%5Ek+%7Cx-y%7C%5Crangle%5E%7B-l%7D.+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%2816%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\frac{\\partial K_k}{\\partial x}(x,y), \\frac{\\partial K_k}{\\partial y}(x,y) \\lesssim_{a,l} 2^{2k} \\langle 2^k |x-y|\\rangle^{-l}. \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (16)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\frac{\\partial K_k}{\\partial x}(x,y), \\frac{\\partial K_k}{\\partial y}(x,y) \\lesssim_{a,l} 2^{2k} \\langle 2^k |x-y|\\rangle^{-l}. \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (16)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> Since the function <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx+%5Cmapsto+2%5Ek+%5Clangle+2%5Ek+%7Cx%7C+%5Crangle%5E%7B-2%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x \\mapsto 2^k \\langle 2^k |x| \\rangle^{-2}}\" title=\"{x \\mapsto 2^k \\langle 2^k |x| \\rangle^{-2}}\" class=\"latex\" /> has an <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BL%5E1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{L^1}\" title=\"{L^1}\" class=\"latex\" /> norm of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BO%281%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{O(1)}\" title=\"{O(1)}\" class=\"latex\" /> for any <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k}\" title=\"{k}\" class=\"latex\" />, we now see from <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11722#akxd\">(12)</a> and Young’s inequality that <a name=\"akxd-bound\"></a></p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+a_k%28X%2CD%29+f%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D+%5Clesssim_a+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D.+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%2817%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| a_k(X,D) f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R})} \\lesssim_a \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R})}. \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (17)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| a_k(X,D) f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R})} \\lesssim_a \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R})}. \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (17)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> Thus each component <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba_k%28X%2CD%29+f%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a_k(X,D) f}\" title=\"{a_k(X,D) f}\" class=\"latex\" /> of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Csum_%7Bk%3D0%7D%5EK+a_k%28X%2CD%29+f%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\sum_{k=0}^K a_k(X,D) f}\" title=\"{\\sum_{k=0}^K a_k(X,D) f}\" class=\"latex\" /> is under control (so for instance we may now discard the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%3D0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k=0}\" title=\"{k=0}\" class=\"latex\" /> term); the difficulty is to sum in <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k}\" title=\"{k}\" class=\"latex\" /> without losing any <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BK%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{K}\" title=\"{K}\" class=\"latex\" />-dependent factors. To do this, we first observe from <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11722#k1\">(14)</a>, <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11722#k2\">(15)</a> and a routine summation of that the total kernel <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BK%28x%2Cy%29+%3A%3D+%5Csum_%7Bk%3D0%7D%5EK+K_k%28x%2Cy%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{K(x,y) := \\sum_{k=0}^K K_k(x,y)}\" title=\"{K(x,y) := \\sum_{k=0}^K K_k(x,y)}\" class=\"latex\" /> (which is the integral kernel for <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Csum_%7Bk%3D0%7D%5EK+a_k%28X%2CD%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\sum_{k=0}^K a_k(X,D)}\" title=\"{\\sum_{k=0}^K a_k(X,D)}\" class=\"latex\" />) obeys the pointwise bound </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++K%28x%2Cy%29+%5Clesssim_a+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B%7Cx-y%7C%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  K(x,y) \\lesssim_a \\frac{1}{|x-y|}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  K(x,y) \\lesssim_a \\frac{1}{|x-y|}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> as well as the pointwise derivative bound </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpartial+K%7D%7B%5Cpartial+x%7D%28x%2Cy%29%2C+%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpartial+K%7D%7B%5Cpartial+y%7D%28x%2Cy%29+%5Clesssim_%7Ba%7D+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B%7Cx-y%7C%5E2%7D.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\frac{\\partial K}{\\partial x}(x,y), \\frac{\\partial K}{\\partial y}(x,y) \\lesssim_{a} \\frac{1}{|x-y|^2}.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\frac{\\partial K}{\\partial x}(x,y), \\frac{\\partial K}{\\partial y}(x,y) \\lesssim_{a} \\frac{1}{|x-y|^2}.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> These are the usual kernel bounds for one-dimensional Calderón-Zygmund theory. From that theory we conclude that in order to prove the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BL%5Ep%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{L^p}\" title=\"{L^p}\" class=\"latex\" /> estimate <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11722#clp\">(10)</a>, it suffices to establish the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bp%3D2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{p=2}\" title=\"{p=2}\" class=\"latex\" /> case <a name=\"p2\"></a></p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%5Csum_%7Bk%3D0%7D%5EK+a_k%28X%2CD%29+f%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D+%5Clesssim_%7Ba%7D+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D.+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%2818%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sum_{k=0}^K a_k(X,D) f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R})} \\lesssim_{a} \\|f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R})}. \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (18)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sum_{k=0}^K a_k(X,D) f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R})} \\lesssim_{a} \\|f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R})}. \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (18)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> From <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11722#akxd-bound\">(17)</a>, we have already established a preliminary bound </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+a_k%28X%2CD%29+f%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D+%5Clesssim_%7Ba%7D+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| a_k(X,D) f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R})} \\lesssim_{a} \\|f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R})}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| a_k(X,D) f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R})} \\lesssim_{a} \\|f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> for each <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k}\" title=\"{k}\" class=\"latex\" />, but a direct application of the triangle inequality will cost us a <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BK%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{K}\" title=\"{K}\" class=\"latex\" />-dependent factor, which we cannot afford. To do better, we need some “orthogonality” between the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba_k%28X%2CD%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a_k(X,D)}\" title=\"{a_k(X,D)}\" class=\"latex\" />. The intuition here is that each component <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba_k%28X%2CD%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a_k(X,D)}\" title=\"{a_k(X,D)}\" class=\"latex\" /> only interacts with the portion of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BL%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{L^2({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{L^2({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" /> that corresponds to frequencies <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cxi%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\xi}\" title=\"{\\xi}\" class=\"latex\" /> of magnitude <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Clangle+%5Cxi+%5Crangle+%5Csim+2%5Ek%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\langle \\xi \\rangle \\sim 2^k}\" title=\"{\\langle \\xi \\rangle \\sim 2^k}\" class=\"latex\" />, and that these regions are somehow “orthogonal” to each other. Informally, this suggests that <a name=\"approx\"></a></p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++a_k%28X%2CD%29+%5Capprox+P_k+a_k%28X%2CD%29+P_k+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%2819%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  a_k(X,D) \\approx P_k a_k(X,D) P_k \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (19)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  a_k(X,D) \\approx P_k a_k(X,D) P_k \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (19)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> where <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP_k%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P_k}\" title=\"{P_k}\" class=\"latex\" /> is something like a Littlewood-Paley projection operator to frequencies <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Clangle+%5Cxi+%5Crangle+%5Csim+2%5Ek%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\langle \\xi \\rangle \\sim 2^k}\" title=\"{\\langle \\xi \\rangle \\sim 2^k}\" class=\"latex\" />. If we accepted this heuristic, then we could informally use the Littlewood-Paley inequality (or <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BL%5E2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{L^2}\" title=\"{L^2}\" class=\"latex\" /> decoupling theory) to calculate </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%5Csum_%7Bk%3D0%7D%5EK+a_k%28X%2CD%29+f+%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D+%5Capprox+%5C%7C+%5Csum_%7Bk%3D0%7D%5EK+P_k+a_k%28X%2CD%29+P_k+f+%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D+&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sum_{k=0}^K a_k(X,D) f \\|_{L^2({\\bf R})} \\approx \\| \\sum_{k=0}^K P_k a_k(X,D) P_k f \\|_{L^2({\\bf R})} \" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sum_{k=0}^K a_k(X,D) f \\|_{L^2({\\bf R})} \\approx \\| \\sum_{k=0}^K P_k a_k(X,D) P_k f \\|_{L^2({\\bf R})} \" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Clessapprox+%28%5Csum_%7Bk%3D0%7D%5EK+%5C%7C+a_k%28X%2CD%29+P_k+f+%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D%5E2%29%5E%7B1%2F2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\lessapprox (\\sum_{k=0}^K \\| a_k(X,D) P_k f \\|_{L^2({\\bf R})}^2)^{1/2}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\lessapprox (\\sum_{k=0}^K \\| a_k(X,D) P_k f \\|_{L^2({\\bf R})}^2)^{1/2}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Clessapprox+%28%5Csum_%7Bk%3D0%7D%5EK+%5C%7C+P_k+f+%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D%5E2%29%5E%7B1%2F2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\lessapprox (\\sum_{k=0}^K \\| P_k f \\|_{L^2({\\bf R})}^2)^{1/2}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\lessapprox (\\sum_{k=0}^K \\| P_k f \\|_{L^2({\\bf R})}^2)^{1/2}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Clessapprox+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\lessapprox \\|f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R})}.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\lessapprox \\|f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R})}.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> It is possible to make this approximation <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11722#approx\">(19)</a> more precise and establish <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11722#p2\">(18)</a>: see Exercise <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11722#lp-a\">7</a>. However, we will take the opportunity to showcase another elegant way to exploit “almost orthogonality”, known as the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cotlar%E2%80%93Stein_lemma\">Cotlar-Stein lemma</a>:</p> \n<blockquote>\n <p><b>Lemma 5 (Cotlar-Stein lemma)</b> Let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT_1%2C%5Cdots%2CT_n%3A+H+%5Crightarrow+H%27%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T_1,\\dots,T_n: H \\rightarrow H'}\" title=\"{T_1,\\dots,T_n: H \\rightarrow H'}\" class=\"latex\" /> be bounded linear maps from one Hilbert space <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BH%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{H}\" title=\"{H}\" class=\"latex\" /> to another <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BH%27%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{H'}\" title=\"{H'}\" class=\"latex\" />. Suppose that the maps <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT_i%5E%2A+T_j%3A+H+%5Crightarrow+H%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T_i^* T_j: H \\rightarrow H}\" title=\"{T_i^* T_j: H \\rightarrow H}\" class=\"latex\" /> obey the operator norm bounds <a name=\"hi\"></a></p> \n <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+%5C%7CT_i%5E%2A+T_j%5C%7C_%7Bop%7D%5E%7B1%2F2%7D+%5Cleq+A+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%2820%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{j=1}^n \\|T_i^* T_j\\|_{op}^{1/2} \\leq A \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (20)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{j=1}^n \\|T_i^* T_j\\|_{op}^{1/2} \\leq A \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (20)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n <p> for all <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bi%3D1%2C%5Cdots%2Cn%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{i=1,\\dots,n}\" title=\"{i=1,\\dots,n}\" class=\"latex\" /> and some <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BA+%5Cgeq+0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{A \\geq 0}\" title=\"{A \\geq 0}\" class=\"latex\" />, and similarly the maps <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT_i+T_j%5E%2A%3A+H%27+%5Crightarrow+H%27%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T_i T_j^*: H' \\rightarrow H'}\" title=\"{T_i T_j^*: H' \\rightarrow H'}\" class=\"latex\" /> obey the operator norm bounds <a name=\"lo\"></a></p> \n <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+%5C%7CT_i+T_j%5E%2A%5C%7C_%7Bop%7D%5E%7B1%2F2%7D+%5Cleq+B+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%2821%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{j=1}^n \\|T_i T_j^*\\|_{op}^{1/2} \\leq B \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (21)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{j=1}^n \\|T_i T_j^*\\|_{op}^{1/2} \\leq B \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (21)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n <p> for all <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bi%3D1%2C%5Cdots%2Cn%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{i=1,\\dots,n}\" title=\"{i=1,\\dots,n}\" class=\"latex\" /> and some <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BB+%5Cgeq+0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{B \\geq 0}\" title=\"{B \\geq 0}\" class=\"latex\" />. Then we have </p> \n <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+T_j+%5C%7C_%7Bop%7D+%5Cleq+%5Csqrt%7BAB%7D.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n T_j \\|_{op} \\leq \\sqrt{AB}.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sum_{j=1}^n T_j \\|_{op} \\leq \\sqrt{AB}.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n</blockquote>  \n<p> Note that if the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT_i%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T_i}\" title=\"{T_i}\" class=\"latex\" /> had pairwise orthogonal ranges then <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT_i%5E%2A+T_j%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T_i^* T_j}\" title=\"{T_i^* T_j}\" class=\"latex\" /> would vanish whenever <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bi+%5Cneq+j%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{i \\neq j}\" title=\"{i \\neq j}\" class=\"latex\" />, and similarly if the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT_i%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T_i}\" title=\"{T_i}\" class=\"latex\" /> had pairwise orthogonal coranges then the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT_i+T_j%5E%2A%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T_i T_j^*}\" title=\"{T_i T_j^*}\" class=\"latex\" /> would vanish whenever <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bi+%5Cneq+j%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{i \\neq j}\" title=\"{i \\neq j}\" class=\"latex\" />. Thus the hypotheses of the Cotlar-Stein lemma are indeed some quantitative form of “almost orthogonality” of the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT_i%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T_i}\" title=\"{T_i}\" class=\"latex\" />. </p> \n<p> <em>Proof:</em> We use the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BTT%5E%2A%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{TT^*}\" title=\"{TT^*}\" class=\"latex\" /> method (which asserts that for a bounded linear map <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T}\" title=\"{T}\" class=\"latex\" /> between Hilbert spaces, the operator norm of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BTT%5E%2A%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{TT^*}\" title=\"{TT^*}\" class=\"latex\" /> or <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT%5E%2A+T%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T^* T}\" title=\"{T^* T}\" class=\"latex\" /> is the square of that of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T}\" title=\"{T}\" class=\"latex\" /> or <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT%5E%2A%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T^*}\" title=\"{T^*}\" class=\"latex\" />). Applying this method to a single operator <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT_i%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T_i}\" title=\"{T_i}\" class=\"latex\" /> we have </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7CT_i%5C%7C_%7Bop%7D+%3D+%5C%7C+T_i%5E%2A+T_i+%5C%7C_%7Bop%7D%5E%7B1%2F2%7D+%5Cleq+A+&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\|T_i\\|_{op} = \\| T_i^* T_i \\|_{op}^{1/2} \\leq A \" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\|T_i\\|_{op} = \\| T_i^* T_i \\|_{op}^{1/2} \\leq A \" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> and similarly <a name=\"opa\"></a></p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7CT_i%5C%7C_%7Bop%7D+%3D+%5C%7C+T_i+T_i%5E%2A+%5C%7C_%7Bop%7D%5E%7B1%2F2%7D+%5Cleq+B.+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%2822%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\|T_i\\|_{op} = \\| T_i T_i^* \\|_{op}^{1/2} \\leq B. \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (22)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\|T_i\\|_{op} = \\| T_i T_i^* \\|_{op}^{1/2} \\leq B. \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (22)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> Taking geometric means we have <a name=\"tia\"></a></p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7CT_i%5C%7C_%7Bop%7D+%5Cleq+%5Csqrt%7BAB%7D%2C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%2823%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\|T_i\\|_{op} \\leq \\sqrt{AB}, \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (23)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\|T_i\\|_{op} \\leq \\sqrt{AB}, \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (23)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> then by the triangle inequality we have <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7C%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+T_j+%5C%7C_%7Bop%7D+%5Cleq+n+%5Csqrt%7BAB%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\|\\sum_{j=1}^n T_j \\|_{op} \\leq n \\sqrt{AB}}\" title=\"{\\|\\sum_{j=1}^n T_j \\|_{op} \\leq n \\sqrt{AB}}\" class=\"latex\" />. This loses a factor of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bn%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{n}\" title=\"{n}\" class=\"latex\" /> over the trivial bound. We can reduce this loss to <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Csqrt%7Bn%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\sqrt{n}}\" title=\"{\\sqrt{n}}\" class=\"latex\" /> by a further application of the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BTT%5E%2A%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{TT^*}\" title=\"{TT^*}\" class=\"latex\" /> method as follows. Writing <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT+%3A%3D+%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+T_j%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T := \\sum_{j=1}^n T_j}\" title=\"{T := \\sum_{j=1}^n T_j}\" class=\"latex\" />, we have </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+T+%5C%7C_%7Bop%7D+%3D+%5C%7C+TT%5E%2A+%5C%7C_%7Bop%7D%5E%7B1%2F2%7D+%5Cleq+%28%5Csum_%7Bi%3D1%7D%5En+%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+%5C%7C+T_i+T_j%5E%2A+%5C%7C_%7Bop%7D%29%5E%7B1%2F2%7D+%5Cleq+%28nB%5E2%29%5E%7B1%2F2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| T \\|_{op} = \\| TT^* \\|_{op}^{1/2} \\leq (\\sum_{i=1}^n \\sum_{j=1}^n \\| T_i T_j^* \\|_{op})^{1/2} \\leq (nB^2)^{1/2}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| T \\|_{op} = \\| TT^* \\|_{op}^{1/2} \\leq (\\sum_{i=1}^n \\sum_{j=1}^n \\| T_i T_j^* \\|_{op})^{1/2} \\leq (nB^2)^{1/2}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> and similarly </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+T+%5C%7C_%7Bop%7D+%3D+%5C%7C+T%5E%2AT+%5C%7C_%7Bop%7D%5E%7B1%2F2%7D+%5Cleq+%28%5Csum_%7Bi%3D1%7D%5En+%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+%5C%7C+T_i%5E%2A+T_j+%5C%7C_%7Bop%7D%29%5E%7B1%2F2%7D+%5Cleq+%28nA%5E2%29%5E%7B1%2F2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| T \\|_{op} = \\| T^*T \\|_{op}^{1/2} \\leq (\\sum_{i=1}^n \\sum_{j=1}^n \\| T_i^* T_j \\|_{op})^{1/2} \\leq (nA^2)^{1/2}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| T \\|_{op} = \\| T^*T \\|_{op}^{1/2} \\leq (\\sum_{i=1}^n \\sum_{j=1}^n \\| T_i^* T_j \\|_{op})^{1/2} \\leq (nA^2)^{1/2}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> so on taking geometric means we have <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7CT%5C%7C_%7Bop%7D+%5Cleq+n%5E%7B1%2F2%7D+%5Csqrt%7BAB%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\|T\\|_{op} \\leq n^{1/2} \\sqrt{AB}}\" title=\"{\\|T\\|_{op} \\leq n^{1/2} \\sqrt{AB}}\" class=\"latex\" />. </p> \n<p> We now reduce the loss in <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bn%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{n}\" title=\"{n}\" class=\"latex\" /> all the way to <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1}\" title=\"{1}\" class=\"latex\" /> by iterating the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BTT%5E%2A%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{TT^*}\" title=\"{TT^*}\" class=\"latex\" /> method (this is an instance of a neat trick in analysis, namely the <a href=\"https://terrytao.wordpress.com/2008/08/25/tricks-wiki-article-the-tensor-product-trick/\">tensor power trick</a>). For any integer <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bm%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{m}\" title=\"{m}\" class=\"latex\" /> that is a power of two, we see from iterating the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BTT%5E%2A%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{TT^*}\" title=\"{TT^*}\" class=\"latex\" /> method that </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+T+%5C%7C_%7Bop%7D+%3D+%5C%7C+%28T%5E%2A+T%29%5Em+%5C%7C_%7Bop%7D%5E%7B1%2F2m%7D.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| T \\|_{op} = \\| (T^* T)^m \\|_{op}^{1/2m}.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| T \\|_{op} = \\| (T^* T)^m \\|_{op}^{1/2m}.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> (In fact, this identity holds for any natural number <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bm%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{m}\" title=\"{m}\" class=\"latex\" />, not just powers of two, as can be seen from spectral theory, but powers of two will suffice for the argument here.) We expand out the right-hand side and bound using the triangle inequality by </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%28%5Csum_%7Bi_1%2C%5Cdots%2Ci_%7B2m%7D+%3D+1%2C%5Cdots%2Cn%7D+%5C%7C+T%5E%2A_%7Bi_1%7D+T_%7Bi_2%7D+T%5E%2A_%7Bi_3%7D+%5Cdots+T%5E%2A_%7Bi_%7B2m-1%7D%7D+T_%7Bi_%7B2m%7D%7D+%5C%7C_%7Bop%7D%29%5E%7B1%2F2m%7D.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  (\\sum_{i_1,\\dots,i_{2m} = 1,\\dots,n} \\| T^*_{i_1} T_{i_2} T^*_{i_3} \\dots T^*_{i_{2m-1}} T_{i_{2m}} \\|_{op})^{1/2m}.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  (\\sum_{i_1,\\dots,i_{2m} = 1,\\dots,n} \\| T^*_{i_1} T_{i_2} T^*_{i_3} \\dots T^*_{i_{2m-1}} T_{i_{2m}} \\|_{op})^{1/2m}.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> On the one hand, we can bound the norm <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7C+T%5E%2A_%7Bi_1%7D+T_%7Bi_2%7D+T%5E%2A_%7Bi_3%7D+%5Cdots+T%5E%2A_%7Bi_%7B2m-1%7D%7D+T_%7Bi_%7B2m%7D%7D+%5C%7C_%7Bop%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\| T^*_{i_1} T_{i_2} T^*_{i_3} \\dots T^*_{i_{2m-1}} T_{i_{2m}} \\|_{op}}\" title=\"{\\| T^*_{i_1} T_{i_2} T^*_{i_3} \\dots T^*_{i_{2m-1}} T_{i_{2m}} \\|_{op}}\" class=\"latex\" /> by </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+T%5E%2A_%7Bi_1%7D+T_%7Bi_2%7D+%5C%7C_%7Bop%7D+%5C%7C+T%5E%2A_%7Bi_3%7D+T_%7Bi_4%7D+%5C%7C_%7Bop%7D+%5Cdots+%5C%7C+T%5E%2A_%7Bi_%7B2m-1%7D%7D+T_%7Bi_%7B2m%7D%7D+%5C%7C_%7Bop%7D%3B&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| T^*_{i_1} T_{i_2} \\|_{op} \\| T^*_{i_3} T_{i_4} \\|_{op} \\dots \\| T^*_{i_{2m-1}} T_{i_{2m}} \\|_{op};\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| T^*_{i_1} T_{i_2} \\|_{op} \\| T^*_{i_3} T_{i_4} \\|_{op} \\dots \\| T^*_{i_{2m-1}} T_{i_{2m}} \\|_{op};\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> grouping things slightly differently and using <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11722#opa\">(22)</a> twice, we can also bound this norm by </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++B+%5C%7C+T_%7Bi_2%7D+T%5E%2A_%7Bi_3%7D+%5C%7C_%7Bop%7D+%5Cdots+%5C%7C+T_%7Bi_%7B2m-2%7D%7D+T%5E%2A_%7Bi_%7B2m-1%7D%7D+%5C%7C_%7Bop%7D+B.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  B \\| T_{i_2} T^*_{i_3} \\|_{op} \\dots \\| T_{i_{2m-2}} T^*_{i_{2m-1}} \\|_{op} B.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  B \\| T_{i_2} T^*_{i_3} \\|_{op} \\dots \\| T_{i_{2m-2}} T^*_{i_{2m-1}} \\|_{op} B.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> Taking the geometric mean, we can bound the norm by </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+B+%5C%7C+T%5E%2A_%7Bi_1%7D+T_%7Bi_2%7D+%5C%7C_%7Bop%7D%5E%7B1%2F2%7D+%5C%7C+T_%7Bi_2%7D+T%5E%2A_%7Bi_3%7D+%5C%7C_%7Bop%7D%5E%7B1%2F2%7D+%5Cdots+%5C%7C+T_%7Bi_%7B2m-2%7D%7D+T%5E%2A_%7Bi_%7B2m-1%7D%7D+%5C%7C_%7Bop%7D%5E%7B1%2F2%7D+%5C%7C+T%5E%2A_%7Bi_%7B2m-1%7D%7D+T_%7Bi_%7B2m%7D%7D+%5C%7C_%7Bop%7D%5E%7B1%2F2%7D.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle B \\| T^*_{i_1} T_{i_2} \\|_{op}^{1/2} \\| T_{i_2} T^*_{i_3} \\|_{op}^{1/2} \\dots \\| T_{i_{2m-2}} T^*_{i_{2m-1}} \\|_{op}^{1/2} \\| T^*_{i_{2m-1}} T_{i_{2m}} \\|_{op}^{1/2}.\" title=\"\\displaystyle B \\| T^*_{i_1} T_{i_2} \\|_{op}^{1/2} \\| T_{i_2} T^*_{i_3} \\|_{op}^{1/2} \\dots \\| T_{i_{2m-2}} T^*_{i_{2m-1}} \\|_{op}^{1/2} \\| T^*_{i_{2m-1}} T_{i_{2m}} \\|_{op}^{1/2}.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> Summing in <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bi_%7B2m%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{i_{2m}}\" title=\"{i_{2m}}\" class=\"latex\" /> using <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11722#hi\">(20)</a>, then in <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bi_%7B2m-1%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{i_{2m-1}}\" title=\"{i_{2m-1}}\" class=\"latex\" /> using <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11722#lo\">(21)</a> and so forth until the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bi_1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{i_1}\" title=\"{i_1}\" class=\"latex\" /> sum (which is just summed with a loss of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bn%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{n}\" title=\"{n}\" class=\"latex\" />), we conclude that </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7CT%5C%7C_%7Bop%7D+%5Cleq+%28B+n+A+B+A+%5Cdots+B+A%29%5E%7B1%2F2m%7D+%3D+n%5E%7B1%2F2m%7D+%5Csqrt%7BAB%7D.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\|T\\|_{op} \\leq (B n A B A \\dots B A)^{1/2m} = n^{1/2m} \\sqrt{AB}.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\|T\\|_{op} \\leq (B n A B A \\dots B A)^{1/2m} = n^{1/2m} \\sqrt{AB}.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> Sending <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bm+%5Crightarrow+%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{m \\rightarrow \\infty}\" title=\"{m \\rightarrow \\infty}\" class=\"latex\" />, we obtain the claim. <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5CBox&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\Box\" title=\"\\Box\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<blockquote>\n <p><b>Remark 6</b> There is a refinement of the Cotlar-Stein lemma for infinite series <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Csum_%7Bi%3D1%7D%5E%5Cinfty+T_i%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\sum_{i=1}^\\infty T_i}\" title=\"{\\sum_{i=1}^\\infty T_i}\" class=\"latex\" /> of operators obeying the hypotheses of the lemma, in which it is shown that the series actually converges in the strong operator topology (though not necessarily in the operator norm topology); this refinement was first observed by Meyer, and can be found for instance <a href=\"https://www.math.tamu.edu/~comech/papers/CotlarStein/CotlarStein.pdf\">in this note of Comech</a>. </p>\n</blockquote>  \n<p> We will shortly establish the bounds </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+a_k%28X%2CD%29+a_j%28X%2CD%29%5E%2A+f%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D%2C+%5C%7C+a_k%28X%2CD%29%5E%2A+a_j%28X%2CD%29+f%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D+&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| a_k(X,D) a_j(X,D)^* f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R})}, \\| a_k(X,D)^* a_j(X,D) f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R})} \" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| a_k(X,D) a_j(X,D)^* f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R})}, \\| a_k(X,D)^* a_j(X,D) f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R})} \" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+%5Clesssim_%7Ba%7D+2%5E%7B-%7Cj-k%7C%7D+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle \\lesssim_{a} 2^{-|j-k|} \\|f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R})}\" title=\"\\displaystyle \\lesssim_{a} 2^{-|j-k|} \\|f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> for any <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bj%2Ck+%5Cgeq+1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{j,k \\geq 1}\" title=\"{j,k \\geq 1}\" class=\"latex\" />. The claim <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11722#p2\">(18)</a> then follows from the Cotlar-Stein lemma (using <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11722#akxd-bound\">(17)</a> to dispose of the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba_0%28X%2CD%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a_0(X,D)}\" title=\"{a_0(X,D)}\" class=\"latex\" /> term).</p> \n<p> We shall just show that </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+a_k%28X%2CD%29%5E%2A+a_j%28X%2CD%29+f%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D+%5Clesssim_%7Ba%7D+2%5E%7B-%28j-k%29%7D+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D%3B&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| a_k(X,D)^* a_j(X,D) f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R})} \\lesssim_{a} 2^{-(j-k)} \\|f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R})};\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| a_k(X,D)^* a_j(X,D) f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R})} \\lesssim_{a} 2^{-(j-k)} \\|f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R})};\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> when <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bj+%5Cgeq+k%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{j \\geq k}\" title=\"{j \\geq k}\" class=\"latex\" />; the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bj+%3C+k%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{j < k}\" title=\"{j < k}\" class=\"latex\" /> case is treated similarly, as is the treatment of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba_k%28X%2CD%29+a_j%28X%2CD%29%5E%2A%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a_k(X,D) a_j(X,D)^*}\" title=\"{a_k(X,D) a_j(X,D)^*}\" class=\"latex\" /> (in fact this latter operator vanishes when <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7Cj-k%7C+%5Cgeq+3%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{|j-k| \\geq 3}\" title=\"{|j-k| \\geq 3}\" class=\"latex\" />, though we will not really need this fact). We have </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+a_k%28X%2CD%29%5E%2A+a_j%28X%2CD%29+f%28x%29+%3D+%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+K_%7Bk%5E%2Aj%7D%28x%2Cz%29+f%28z%29%5C+dz&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle a_k(X,D)^* a_j(X,D) f(x) = \\int_{\\bf R} K_{k^*j}(x,z) f(z)\\ dz\" title=\"\\displaystyle a_k(X,D)^* a_j(X,D) f(x) = \\int_{\\bf R} K_{k^*j}(x,z) f(z)\\ dz\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> where </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++K_%7Bk%5E%2Aj%7D%28x%2Cz%29+%3A%3D+%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Coverline%7BK_k%7D%28y%2Cx%29+K_j%28y%2Cz%29%5C+dy.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  K_{k^*j}(x,z) := \\int_{\\bf R} \\overline{K_k}(y,x) K_j(y,z)\\ dy.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  K_{k^*j}(x,z) := \\int_{\\bf R} \\overline{K_k}(y,x) K_j(y,z)\\ dy.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> A direct application of <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11722#k2\">(15)</a> and the triangle inequality gives the bounds </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+K_%7Bk%5E%2Aj%7D%28x%2Cz%29+%5Clesssim_%7Ba%7D+2%5Ek+%5Clangle+2%5Ek%28x-z%29+%5Crangle%5E%7B-10%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle K_{k^*j}(x,z) \\lesssim_{a} 2^k \\langle 2^k(x-z) \\rangle^{-10}\" title=\"\\displaystyle K_{k^*j}(x,z) \\lesssim_{a} 2^k \\langle 2^k(x-z) \\rangle^{-10}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> (say), which when combined with Young’s inequality does not give the desired gain of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B2%5E%7B-%28j-k%29%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{2^{-(j-k)}}\" title=\"{2^{-(j-k)}}\" class=\"latex\" />. To recover this gain we begin integrating by parts. From <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11722#kiwi\">(13)</a> we have </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++K_j%28y%2Cz%29+%3D%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpartial%7D%7B%5Cpartial+y%7D+%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Cfrac%7Ba_j%28y%2C%5Cxi%29%7D%7B2%5Cpi+i+%5Cxi%7D+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+%28y-z%29+%5Cxi%7D%5C+d%5Cxi+-+%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpartial%7D%7B%5Cpartial+y%7D+%5Cfrac%7Ba_j%28y%2C%5Cxi%29%7D%7B2%5Cpi+i+%5Cxi%7D+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+%28y-z%29+%5Cxi%7D%5C+d%5Cxi.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  K_j(y,z) =\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial y} \\int_{\\bf R} \\frac{a_j(y,\\xi)}{2\\pi i \\xi} e^{2\\pi i (y-z) \\xi}\\ d\\xi - \\int_{\\bf R} \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial y} \\frac{a_j(y,\\xi)}{2\\pi i \\xi} e^{2\\pi i (y-z) \\xi}\\ d\\xi.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  K_j(y,z) =\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial y} \\int_{\\bf R} \\frac{a_j(y,\\xi)}{2\\pi i \\xi} e^{2\\pi i (y-z) \\xi}\\ d\\xi - \\int_{\\bf R} \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial y} \\frac{a_j(y,\\xi)}{2\\pi i \\xi} e^{2\\pi i (y-z) \\xi}\\ d\\xi.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> Note that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpartial%7D%7B%5Cpartial+y%7D+%5Cfrac%7Ba_j%28y%2C%5Cxi%29%7D%7B2%5Cpi+i+%5Cxi%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial y} \\frac{a_j(y,\\xi)}{2\\pi i \\xi}}\" title=\"{\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial y} \\frac{a_j(y,\\xi)}{2\\pi i \\xi}}\" class=\"latex\" /> obeys similar estimates to <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba_j%28y%2C%5Cxi%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a_j(y,\\xi)}\" title=\"{a_j(y,\\xi)}\" class=\"latex\" /> but with an additional gain of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B2%5E%7B-j%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{2^{-j}}\" title=\"{2^{-j}}\" class=\"latex\" />. Thus the contribution of this term to <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BK_%7Bk%5E%2Aj%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{K_{k^*j}}\" title=\"{K_{k^*j}}\" class=\"latex\" /> will be acceptable. The contribution of the other term, after an integration by parts, is </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++-%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%28%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpartial%7D%7B%5Cpartial+y%7D+%5Coverline%7BK_k%7D%28y%2Cx%29%29+%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Cfrac%7Ba_j%28y%2C%5Cxi%29%7D%7B2%5Cpi+i+%5Cxi%7D+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+%28y-z%29+%5Cxi%7D%5C+d%5Cxi%5C+dy.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  -\\int_{\\bf R} (\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial y} \\overline{K_k}(y,x)) \\int_{\\bf R} \\frac{a_j(y,\\xi)}{2\\pi i \\xi} e^{2\\pi i (y-z) \\xi}\\ d\\xi\\ dy.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  -\\int_{\\bf R} (\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial y} \\overline{K_k}(y,x)) \\int_{\\bf R} \\frac{a_j(y,\\xi)}{2\\pi i \\xi} e^{2\\pi i (y-z) \\xi}\\ d\\xi\\ dy.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> The kernel <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Cfrac%7Ba_j%28y%2C%5Cxi%29%7D%7B2%5Cpi+i+%5Cxi%7D+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+%28y-z%29+%5Cxi%7D%5C+d%5Cxi%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\int_{\\bf R} \\frac{a_j(y,\\xi)}{2\\pi i \\xi} e^{2\\pi i (y-z) \\xi}\\ d\\xi}\" title=\"{\\int_{\\bf R} \\frac{a_j(y,\\xi)}{2\\pi i \\xi} e^{2\\pi i (y-z) \\xi}\\ d\\xi}\" class=\"latex\" /> obeys the same bounds as <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11722#k2\">(15)</a> but with an additional gain of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B2%5E%7B-j%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{2^{-j}}\" title=\"{2^{-j}}\" class=\"latex\" />; similarly from <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11722#k3\">(16)</a> the expression <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpartial%7D%7B%5Cpartial+y%7D+%5Coverline%7BK_k%7D%28y%2Cx%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial y} \\overline{K_k}(y,x)}\" title=\"{\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial y} \\overline{K_k}(y,x)}\" class=\"latex\" /> obeys the same bounds as <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11722#k2\">(15)</a> but with an additional loss of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B2%5Ek%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{2^k}\" title=\"{2^k}\" class=\"latex\" />. The claim follows. This concludes the proof of the Calderón-Vaillancourt theorem.</p> \n<blockquote>\n <p><b>Exercise 7</b> <a name=\"lp-a\"></a> With the hypotheses as above, and with <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP_j%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P_j}\" title=\"{P_j}\" class=\"latex\" /> a suitable Littlewood-Paley projection to frequencies <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Clangle+%5Cxi+%5Crangle+%5Csim+2%5Ej%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\langle \\xi \\rangle \\sim 2^j}\" title=\"{\\langle \\xi \\rangle \\sim 2^j}\" class=\"latex\" />, establish the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BL%5E2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{L^2}\" title=\"{L^2}\" class=\"latex\" /> operator norm bounds </p> \n <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+P_j+a_k%28X%2CD%29+f+%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D%2C+%5C%7C+a_k%28X%2CD%29+P_j+f+%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D+%5Clesssim_a+2%5E%7B-%7Cj-k%7C%7D+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| P_j a_k(X,D) f \\|_{L^2({\\bf R})}, \\| a_k(X,D) P_j f \\|_{L^2({\\bf R})} \\lesssim_a 2^{-|j-k|} \\|f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R})}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| P_j a_k(X,D) f \\|_{L^2({\\bf R})}, \\| a_k(X,D) P_j f \\|_{L^2({\\bf R})} \\lesssim_a 2^{-|j-k|} \\|f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n <p> for all <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bj%2Ck+%5Cgeq+0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{j,k \\geq 0}\" title=\"{j,k \\geq 0}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{f \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" />. Use this to provide an alternate proof of <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11722#p2\">(18)</a> that does not require the Cotlar-Stein lemma. </p>\n</blockquote>  \n<p> Now we give a preliminary composition estimate: </p> \n<blockquote>\n <p><b>Theorem 8 (Preliminary composition)</b> <a name=\"precomp\"></a> Let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%28X%2CD%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a(X,D)}\" title=\"{a(X,D)}\" class=\"latex\" /> be a pseudodifferential operator of some order <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\alpha \\in {\\bf R}}\" title=\"{\\alpha \\in {\\bf R}}\" class=\"latex\" />, and let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bb%28X%2CD%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{b(X,D)}\" title=\"{b(X,D)}\" class=\"latex\" /> be a pseudodifferential operator of some order <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cbeta+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\beta \\in {\\bf R}}\" title=\"{\\beta \\in {\\bf R}}\" class=\"latex\" />. Then the composition <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%28X%2CD%29+b%28X%2CD%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a(X,D) b(X,D)}\" title=\"{a(X,D) b(X,D)}\" class=\"latex\" /> is a pseudodifferential operator of order <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha%2B%5Cbeta%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\alpha+\\beta}\" title=\"{\\alpha+\\beta}\" class=\"latex\" />, thus there exists <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%2Ab+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%5E%7B%5Calpha%2B%5Cbeta%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a*b \\in {\\mathcal S}^{\\alpha+\\beta}}\" title=\"{a*b \\in {\\mathcal S}^{\\alpha+\\beta}}\" class=\"latex\" /> such that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28a%2Ab%29%28X%2CD%29+%3D+a%28X%2CD%29+b%28X%2CD%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(a*b)(X,D) = a(X,D) b(X,D)}\" title=\"{(a*b)(X,D) = a(X,D) b(X,D)}\" class=\"latex\" /> (note from Exercise <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11722#unq\">1</a> that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%2Ab%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a*b}\" title=\"{a*b}\" class=\"latex\" /> is uniquely determined). </p>\n</blockquote>  \n<p> <em>Proof:</em> We begin with some technical reductions in order to justify some later exchanges of integrals. We can express the symbol <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%28x%2C%5Cxi%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a(x,\\xi)}\" title=\"{a(x,\\xi)}\" class=\"latex\" /> as a locally uniform limit of truncated symbols <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba_R%28x%2C%5Cxi%29+%3A%3D+a%28x%2C%5Cxi%29+%5Cphi%28x%2FR%29+%5Cphi%28%5Cxi%2FR%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a_R(x,\\xi) := a(x,\\xi) \\phi(x/R) \\phi(\\xi/R)}\" title=\"{a_R(x,\\xi) := a(x,\\xi) \\phi(x/R) \\phi(\\xi/R)}\" class=\"latex\" /> as <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BR+%5Crightarrow+%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{R \\rightarrow \\infty}\" title=\"{R \\rightarrow \\infty}\" class=\"latex\" />, where <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cphi+%5Cin+C%5E%5Cinfty_c%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\phi \\in C^\\infty_c({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{\\phi \\in C^\\infty_c({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" /> is a bump function equal to <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1}\" title=\"{1}\" class=\"latex\" /> near the origin; from the product rule we see that the symbol estimates <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11722#class-symb\">(8)</a> are obeyed by the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba_R%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a_R}\" title=\"{a_R}\" class=\"latex\" /> uniformly in <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BR%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{R}\" title=\"{R}\" class=\"latex\" /> as long as <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BR+%5Cgeq+1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{R \\geq 1}\" title=\"{R \\geq 1}\" class=\"latex\" />. If <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f}\" title=\"{f}\" class=\"latex\" /> is Schwartz, then so is <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bb%28X%2CD%29+f%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{b(X,D) f}\" title=\"{b(X,D) f}\" class=\"latex\" />, and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba_R%28X%2CD%29+b%28X%2CD%29+f%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a_R(X,D) b(X,D) f}\" title=\"{a_R(X,D) b(X,D) f}\" class=\"latex\" /> can be verified to converge pointwise to <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%28X%2CD%29+b%28X%2CD%29+f%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a(X,D) b(X,D) f}\" title=\"{a(X,D) b(X,D) f}\" class=\"latex\" />. If one can show that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba_R%28X%2CD%29+b%28X%2CD%29+%3D+c_R%28X%2CD%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a_R(X,D) b(X,D) = c_R(X,D)}\" title=\"{a_R(X,D) b(X,D) = c_R(X,D)}\" class=\"latex\" /> for some pseudodifferential operator <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bc_R%28X%2CD%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{c_R(X,D)}\" title=\"{c_R(X,D)}\" class=\"latex\" /> of order <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha%2B%5Cbeta%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\alpha+\\beta}\" title=\"{\\alpha+\\beta}\" class=\"latex\" />, with all the required symbol estimates <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11722#class-symb\">(8)</a> on <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bc_R%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{c_R}\" title=\"{c_R}\" class=\"latex\" /> obeyed uniformly in <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BR%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{R}\" title=\"{R}\" class=\"latex\" />, then the claim will follow by using the Arzelà-Ascoli theorem to extract a locally uniformly convergent susbequence of the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bc_R%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{c_R}\" title=\"{c_R}\" class=\"latex\" /> and taking a limit. The upshot of this is that we may assume without loss of generality that the symbol <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%28x%2C%5Cxi%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a(x,\\xi)}\" title=\"{a(x,\\xi)}\" class=\"latex\" /> is compactly supported in <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%2C%5Cxi%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x,\\xi}\" title=\"{x,\\xi}\" class=\"latex\" />, so long as our estimates do not depend on the size of this compact support, but only on the constants in the symbol bounds <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11722#class-symb\">(8)</a> for <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a}\" title=\"{a}\" class=\"latex\" />. </p> \n<p> Similarly, we may approximate <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bb%28x%2C%5Cxi%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{b(x,\\xi)}\" title=\"{b(x,\\xi)}\" class=\"latex\" /> locally uniformly as the limit of symbols <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bb_R%28x%2C%5Cxi%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{b_R(x,\\xi)}\" title=\"{b_R(x,\\xi)}\" class=\"latex\" /> that are compactly supprted in <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%2C%5Cxi%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x,\\xi}\" title=\"{x,\\xi}\" class=\"latex\" />, which makes <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bb_R%28X%2CD%29+f%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{b_R(X,D) f}\" title=\"{b_R(X,D) f}\" class=\"latex\" /> converge locally uniformly to <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bb%28X%2CD%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{b(X,D)}\" title=\"{b(X,D)}\" class=\"latex\" />; from the compact support of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%28x%2C%5Cxi%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a(x,\\xi)}\" title=\"{a(x,\\xi)}\" class=\"latex\" /> this also shows that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%28X%2CD%29+b_R%28X%2CD%29+f%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a(X,D) b_R(X,D) f}\" title=\"{a(X,D) b_R(X,D) f}\" class=\"latex\" /> converges pointwise to <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%28X%2CD%29+b%28X%2CD%29+f%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a(X,D) b(X,D) f}\" title=\"{a(X,D) b(X,D) f}\" class=\"latex\" />. From the same limiting argument as before, we may thus assume that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bb%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{b}\" title=\"{b}\" class=\"latex\" /> is compactly supported in <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%2C%5Cxi%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x,\\xi}\" title=\"{x,\\xi}\" class=\"latex\" />, so long as our estimates do not depend on the size of this support, but only on the constants in the symbol bounds <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11722#class-symb\">(8)</a> for <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bb%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{b}\" title=\"{b}\" class=\"latex\" />. </p> \n<p> For <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{f \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" />, we have </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++b%28X%2CD%29+f%28y%29+%3D+%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+b%28y%2C%5Cxi%29+%5Chat+f%28%5Cxi%29+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+y+%5Cxi%7D%5C+d%5Cxi&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  b(X,D) f(y) = \\int_{\\bf R} b(y,\\xi) \\hat f(\\xi) e^{2\\pi i y \\xi}\\ d\\xi\" title=\"\\displaystyle  b(X,D) f(y) = \\int_{\\bf R} b(y,\\xi) \\hat f(\\xi) e^{2\\pi i y \\xi}\\ d\\xi\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> hence on taking Fourier transforms </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cwidehat%7Bb%28X%2CD%29+f%7D%28%5Ceta%29+%3D+%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+b%28y%2C%5Cxi%29+%5Chat+f%28%5Cxi%29+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+%28y+%5Cxi-+y%5Ceta%29%7D%5C+d%5Cxi+dy&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\widehat{b(X,D) f}(\\eta) = \\int_{\\bf R} \\int_{\\bf R} b(y,\\xi) \\hat f(\\xi) e^{2\\pi i (y \\xi- y\\eta)}\\ d\\xi dy\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\widehat{b(X,D) f}(\\eta) = \\int_{\\bf R} \\int_{\\bf R} b(y,\\xi) \\hat f(\\xi) e^{2\\pi i (y \\xi- y\\eta)}\\ d\\xi dy\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> hence </p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img
