see <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=611747\">this deep paper of Fefferman and Phong</a>. </p>\n</blockquote>  \n<blockquote>\n <p><b>Remark 19</b> <a name=\"weyl\"></a> Throughout this set of notes we have used the Kohn-Nirenberg quantization </p> \n <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++a_%7BKN%7D%28X%2CD%29+f%28x%29+%3D+%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+a%28x%2C%5Cxi%29+%5Chat+f%28%5Cxi%29+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+x+%5Cxi%7D%5C+d%5Cxi&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  a_{KN}(X,D) f(x) = \\int_{\\bf R} a(x,\\xi) \\hat f(\\xi) e^{2\\pi i x \\xi}\\ d\\xi\" title=\"\\displaystyle  a_{KN}(X,D) f(x) = \\int_{\\bf R} a(x,\\xi) \\hat f(\\xi) e^{2\\pi i x \\xi}\\ d\\xi\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n <p> or equivalently (taking <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a}\" title=\"{a}\" class=\"latex\" /> to be compactly supported for sake of discussion) </p> \n <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++a_%7BKN%7D%28X%2CD%29+f%28x%29+%3D+%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%28%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+a%28x%2C%5Cxi%29+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+%28x-y%29+%5Cxi%7D%5C+d%5Cxi%29+f%28y%29+dy.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  a_{KN}(X,D) f(x) = \\int_{\\bf R} (\\int_{\\bf R} a(x,\\xi) e^{2\\pi i (x-y) \\xi}\\ d\\xi) f(y) dy.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  a_{KN}(X,D) f(x) = \\int_{\\bf R} (\\int_{\\bf R} a(x,\\xi) e^{2\\pi i (x-y) \\xi}\\ d\\xi) f(y) dy.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n <p> However, this is not the only quantization that one could use. For instance, one could also use the adjoint Kohn-Nirenberg quantization </p> \n <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++a_%7BKN%5E%2A%7D%28X%2CD%29+f%28x%29+%3A%3D+%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%28%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+a%28y%2C%5Cxi%29+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+%28x-y%29+%5Cxi%7D%5C+d%5Cxi%29+f%28y%29+dy&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  a_{KN^*}(X,D) f(x) := \\int_{\\bf R} (\\int_{\\bf R} a(y,\\xi) e^{2\\pi i (x-y) \\xi}\\ d\\xi) f(y) dy\" title=\"\\displaystyle  a_{KN^*}(X,D) f(x) := \\int_{\\bf R} (\\int_{\\bf R} a(y,\\xi) e^{2\\pi i (x-y) \\xi}\\ d\\xi) f(y) dy\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n <p> which one can easily relate to the Kohn-Nirenberg quantization by the identity </p> \n <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++a_%7BKN%5E%2A%7D%28X%2CD%29+%3D+%5Coverline%7Ba%7D_%7BKN%7D%28X%2CD%29%5E%2A.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  a_{KN^*}(X,D) = \\overline{a}_{KN}(X,D)^*.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  a_{KN^*}(X,D) = \\overline{a}_{KN}(X,D)^*.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n <p> In particular, from Exercise <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11722#adj-p\">11</a> we see that if <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a}\" title=\"{a}\" class=\"latex\" /> is a symbol of order <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\alpha}\" title=\"{\\alpha}\" class=\"latex\" />, then <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba_%7BKN%7D%28X%2CD%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a_{KN}(X,D)}\" title=\"{a_{KN}(X,D)}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba_%7BKN%5E%2A%7D%28X%2CD%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a_{KN^*}(X,D)}\" title=\"{a_{KN^*}(X,D)}\" class=\"latex\" /> only differ by pseudodifferential operators of order <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha-1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\alpha-1}\" title=\"{\\alpha-1}\" class=\"latex\" /> (and that both quantizations produce the same class of pseudodifferential operators of a given order). The operators <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT_%5Cphi%5E%2A+a+T_%5Cphi%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T_\\phi^* a T_\\phi}\" title=\"{T_\\phi^* a T_\\phi}\" class=\"latex\" /> appearing earlier can also be viewed as a quantization of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a}\" title=\"{a}\" class=\"latex\" /> (known as the <em>anti-Wick quantization</em> of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a}\" title=\"{a}\" class=\"latex\" /> associated to the test function <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cphi%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\phi}\" title=\"{\\phi}\" class=\"latex\" />). But perhaps the most popular quantization used in the literature is the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wigner%E2%80%93Weyl_transform\">Weyl quantization</a> </p> \n <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++a_%7BW%7D%28X%2CD%29+f%28x%29+%3A%3D+%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%28%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+a%28%5Cfrac%7Bx%2By%7D%7B2%7D%2C%5Cxi%29+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+%28x-y%29+%5Cxi%7D%5C+d%5Cxi%29+f%28y%29+dy&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  a_{W}(X,D) f(x) := \\int_{\\bf R} (\\int_{\\bf R} a(\\frac{x+y}{2},\\xi) e^{2\\pi i (x-y) \\xi}\\ d\\xi) f(y) dy\" title=\"\\displaystyle  a_{W}(X,D) f(x) := \\int_{\\bf R} (\\int_{\\bf R} a(\\frac{x+y}{2},\\xi) e^{2\\pi i (x-y) \\xi}\\ d\\xi) f(y) dy\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n <p> which in some sense “splits the difference” between the Kohn-Nirenberg and adjoint Kohn-Nirenberg quantizations, being completely symmetric between the input spatial variable <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7By%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{y}\" title=\"{y}\" class=\"latex\" /> and output spatial variable <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x}\" title=\"{x}\" class=\"latex\" />. (Strictly speaking, this formula is only well-defined for say compactly supported symbols <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a}\" title=\"{a}\" class=\"latex\" />; for more general symbols <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a}\" title=\"{a}\" class=\"latex\" /> one can define <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba_W%28X%2CD%29+f%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a_W(X,D) f}\" title=\"{a_W(X,D) f}\" class=\"latex\" /> in the weak sense as the distribution for which </p> \n <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Clangle+a_%7BW%7D%28X%2CD%29+f%2C+g+%5Crangle+%3D+%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%28%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+a%28%5Cfrac%7Bx%2By%7D%7B2%7D%2C%5Cxi%29+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+%28x-y%29+%5Cxi%7D+f%28y%29+%5Coverline%7Bg%28x%29%7D%5C+dx+dy%29%5C+d%5Cxi&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\langle a_{W}(X,D) f, g \\rangle = \\int_{\\bf R} (\\int_{\\bf R} \\int_{\\bf R} a(\\frac{x+y}{2},\\xi) e^{2\\pi i (x-y) \\xi} f(y) \\overline{g(x)}\\ dx dy)\\ d\\xi\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\langle a_{W}(X,D) f, g \\rangle = \\int_{\\bf R} (\\int_{\\bf R} \\int_{\\bf R} a(\\frac{x+y}{2},\\xi) e^{2\\pi i (x-y) \\xi} f(y) \\overline{g(x)}\\ dx dy)\\ d\\xi\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n <p> for <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%2Cg+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f,g \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{f,g \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" /> (it is not difficult to use integration by parts to show that the expression in parentheses is rapidly decreasing in <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cxi%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\xi}\" title=\"{\\xi}\" class=\"latex\" />, hence absolutely integrable). In particular there is now no error term in the analogue of Exercise <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11722#adj-p\">11</a>: </p> \n <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++a_W%28X%2CD%29%5E%2A+%3D+%5Coverline%7Ba%7D_W%28X%2CD%29.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  a_W(X,D)^* = \\overline{a}_W(X,D).\" title=\"\\displaystyle  a_W(X,D)^* = \\overline{a}_W(X,D).\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n <p> All of the preceding theory for the Kohn-Nirenberg quantization can be adapted to the Weyl quantization with minor changes (for instance, the definition of the Wigner transform <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BW_%5Cphi%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{W_\\phi}\" title=\"{W_\\phi}\" class=\"latex\" /> changes slightly, and the operation <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cast%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\ast}\" title=\"{\\ast}\" class=\"latex\" /> defined in <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11722#ast-def\">(24)</a> is replaced with the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moyal_product\">Moyal product</a>), and as seen in Exercise <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11722#knw\">20</a> below, the two quantizations again produce the same classes of pseudodifferential operators, with symbols agreeing up to lower order terms. </p>\n</blockquote>  \n<blockquote>\n <p><b>Exercise 20 (Kohn-Nirenberg and Weyl quantizations are equivalent up to lower order)</b> <a name=\"knw\"></a> Let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\alpha}\" title=\"{\\alpha}\" class=\"latex\" /> be a real number. </p> \n <ul> \n  <li>(i) If <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a}\" title=\"{a}\" class=\"latex\" /> is a symbol of order <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\alpha}\" title=\"{\\alpha}\" class=\"latex\" />, show that there exists a symbol <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Ctilde+a%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\tilde a}\" title=\"{\\tilde a}\" class=\"latex\" /> of order <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\alpha}\" title=\"{\\alpha}\" class=\"latex\" /> such that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba_%7BKN%7D%28X%2CD%29+%3D+%5Ctilde+a_W%28X%2CD%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a_{KN}(X,D) = \\tilde a_W(X,D)}\" title=\"{a_{KN}(X,D) = \\tilde a_W(X,D)}\" class=\"latex\" />. Furthermore, show that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba-%5Ctilde+a%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a-\\tilde a}\" title=\"{a-\\tilde a}\" class=\"latex\" /> is a symbol of order <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha-1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\alpha-1}\" title=\"{\\alpha-1}\" class=\"latex\" />. </li> \n  <li>(ii) If <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a}\" title=\"{a}\" class=\"latex\" /> is a symbol of order <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\alpha}\" title=\"{\\alpha}\" class=\"latex\" />, show that there exists a symbol <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Ctilde+a%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\tilde a}\" title=\"{\\tilde a}\" class=\"latex\" /> of order <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\alpha}\" title=\"{\\alpha}\" class=\"latex\" /> such that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba_%7BW%7D%28X%2CD%29+%3D+%5Ctilde+a_%7BKN%7D%28X%2CD%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a_{W}(X,D) = \\tilde a_{KN}(X,D)}\" title=\"{a_{W}(X,D) = \\tilde a_{KN}(X,D)}\" class=\"latex\" />. Furthermore, show that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba-%5Ctilde+a%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a-\\tilde a}\" title=\"{a-\\tilde a}\" class=\"latex\" /> is a symbol of order <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha-1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\alpha-1}\" title=\"{\\alpha-1}\" class=\"latex\" />. </li> \n </ul> \n</blockquote>  \n<blockquote>\n <p><b>Exercise 21 (Comparison of quantizations)</b> Let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bj%2Ck+%5Cgeq+0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{j,k \\geq 0}\" title=\"{j,k \\geq 0}\" class=\"latex\" /> be natural numbers, and let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a}\" title=\"{a}\" class=\"latex\" /> be the monomial <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%28x%2C%5Cxi%29+%3A%3D+x%5Ej+%5Cxi%5Ek%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a(x,\\xi) := x^j \\xi^k}\" title=\"{a(x,\\xi) := x^j \\xi^k}\" class=\"latex\" />. </p> \n <ul> \n  <li>(i) Show that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba_%7BKN%7D%28X%2CD%29+%3D+X%5Ej+D%5Ek%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a_{KN}(X,D) = X^j D^k}\" title=\"{a_{KN}(X,D) = X^j D^k}\" class=\"latex\" />. </li> \n  <li>(ii) Show that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba_%7BKN%5E%2A%7D%28X%2CD%29+%3D+D%5Ek+X%5Ej%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a_{KN^*}(X,D) = D^k X^j}\" title=\"{a_{KN^*}(X,D) = D^k X^j}\" class=\"latex\" />. </li> \n  <li>(iii) Show that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba_W%28X%2CD%29+%3D+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B%5Cbinom%7Bj%2Bk%7D%7Bk%7D%7D+%5Csum+W_1+%5Cdots+W_%7Bk%2Bj%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a_W(X,D) = \\frac{1}{\\binom{j+k}{k}} \\sum W_1 \\dots W_{k+j}}\" title=\"{a_W(X,D) = \\frac{1}{\\binom{j+k}{k}} \\sum W_1 \\dots W_{k+j}}\" class=\"latex\" />, where <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28W_1%2C%5Cdots%2CW_%7Bk%2Bj%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(W_1,\\dots,W_{k+j})}\" title=\"{(W_1,\\dots,W_{k+j})}\" class=\"latex\" /> ranges over all tuples of operators consisting of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bj%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{j}\" title=\"{j}\" class=\"latex\" /> copies of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BX%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{X}\" title=\"{X}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k}\" title=\"{k}\" class=\"latex\" /> copies of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BD%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{D}\" title=\"{D}\" class=\"latex\" />. For instance, if <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28j%2Ck%29%3D%281%2C2%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(j,k)=(1,2)}\" title=\"{(j,k)=(1,2)}\" class=\"latex\" />, then <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++a_W%28X%2CD%29+%3D+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B3%7D+%28XDD+%2B+DXD+%2B+DDX%29.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  a_W(X,D) = \\frac{1}{3} (XDD + DXD + DDX).\" title=\"\\displaystyle  a_W(X,D) = \\frac{1}{3} (XDD + DXD + DDX).\" class=\"latex\" /></p> </li> \n </ul> \n <p> Informally, the Kohn-Nirenberg quantization always applies position operators to the left of momentum operators; the adjoint Kohn-Nirenberg quantization always applies position operators to the right of momentum operators; and the Weyl quantization averages equally over all possible orderings. (Taking formal generating functions, we also see (formally, at least) that the quantization of a plane wave <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Be%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+%28x+%5Ceta+%2B+y+%5Cxi%29%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{e^{2\\pi i (x \\eta + y \\xi)}}\" title=\"{e^{2\\pi i (x \\eta + y \\xi)}}\" class=\"latex\" /> for real numbers <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Ceta%2Cy%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\eta,y}\" title=\"{\\eta,y}\" class=\"latex\" /> is equal to <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Be%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+%5Ceta+X%7D+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+y+D%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{e^{2\\pi i \\eta X} e^{2\\pi i y D}}\" title=\"{e^{2\\pi i \\eta X} e^{2\\pi i y D}}\" class=\"latex\" /> in the Kohn-Nirenberg quantization, <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Be%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+yD%7D+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+%5Ceta+X%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{e^{2\\pi i yD} e^{2\\pi i \\eta X}}\" title=\"{e^{2\\pi i yD} e^{2\\pi i \\eta X}}\" class=\"latex\" /> in the adjoint Kohn-Nirenberg quantization, and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Be%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i%28%5Ceta+X+%2B+yD%29%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{e^{2\\pi i(\\eta X + yD)}}\" title=\"{e^{2\\pi i(\\eta X + yD)}}\" class=\"latex\" /> in the Weyl quantization.) </p>\n</blockquote>  \n<blockquote>\n <p><b>Exercise 22 (Gabor-type transforms and symmetries)</b> Let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cphi%2C+f+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\phi, f \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{\\phi, f \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" />. </p> \n <ul> \n  <li>(i) (Physical translation) If <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx_0+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x_0 \\in {\\bf R}}\" title=\"{x_0 \\in {\\bf R}}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bg+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{g \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{g \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" /> is the function <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bg%28x%29+%3A%3D+f%28x-x_0%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{g(x) := f(x-x_0)}\" title=\"{g(x) := f(x-x_0)}\" class=\"latex\" />, show that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT_%5Cphi+g%28x%2C%5Cxi%29+%3D+e%5E%7B-2%5Cpi+i+x_0+%5Cxi%7D+T_%5Cphi+f%28x-x_0%2C%5Cxi%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T_\\phi g(x,\\xi) = e^{-2\\pi i x_0 \\xi} T_\\phi f(x-x_0,\\xi)}\" title=\"{T_\\phi g(x,\\xi) = e^{-2\\pi i x_0 \\xi} T_\\phi f(x-x_0,\\xi)}\" class=\"latex\" /> for all <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28x%2C%5Cxi%29+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Ctimes+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(x,\\xi) \\in {\\bf R} \\times {\\bf R}}\" title=\"{(x,\\xi) \\in {\\bf R} \\times {\\bf R}}\" class=\"latex\" />. </li> \n  <li>(ii) (Frequency modulation) If <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cxi_0+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\xi_0 \\in {\\bf R}}\" title=\"{\\xi_0 \\in {\\bf R}}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bg+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{g \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{g \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" /> is the function <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bg%28x%29+%3A%3D+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+%5Cxi_0+x%7D+f%28x%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{g(x) := e^{2\\pi i \\xi_0 x} f(x)}\" title=\"{g(x) := e^{2\\pi i \\xi_0 x} f(x)}\" class=\"latex\" />, show that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT_%5Cphi+g%28x%2C%5Cxi%29+%3D+T_%5Cphi+f%28x%2C%5Cxi-%5Cxi_0%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T_\\phi g(x,\\xi) = T_\\phi f(x,\\xi-\\xi_0)}\" title=\"{T_\\phi g(x,\\xi) = T_\\phi f(x,\\xi-\\xi_0)}\" class=\"latex\" /> for all <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28x%2C%5Cxi%29+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Ctimes+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(x,\\xi) \\in {\\bf R} \\times {\\bf R}}\" title=\"{(x,\\xi) \\in {\\bf R} \\times {\\bf R}}\" class=\"latex\" />. </li> \n  <li>(iii) (Dilation) If <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Clambda%3E0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\lambda>0}\" title=\"{\\lambda>0}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bg+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{g \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{g \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" /> is the function <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bg%28x%29+%3A%3D+%5Clambda%5E%7B-1%2F2%7D+f%28%5Clambda%5E%7B-1%7D+x%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{g(x) := \\lambda^{-1/2} f(\\lambda^{-1} x)}\" title=\"{g(x) := \\lambda^{-1/2} f(\\lambda^{-1} x)}\" class=\"latex\" />, show that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT_%7B%5Cphi_%5Clambda%7Dg%28x%2C%5Cxi%29+%3D+T_%5Cphi+f%28%5Clambda%5E%7B-1%7D+x%2C+%5Clambda+%5Cxi%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T_{\\phi_\\lambda}g(x,\\xi) = T_\\phi f(\\lambda^{-1} x, \\lambda \\xi)}\" title=\"{T_{\\phi_\\lambda}g(x,\\xi) = T_\\phi f(\\lambda^{-1} x, \\lambda \\xi)}\" class=\"latex\" /> for all <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28x%2C%5Cxi%29+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Ctimes+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(x,\\xi) \\in {\\bf R} \\times {\\bf R}}\" title=\"{(x,\\xi) \\in {\\bf R} \\times {\\bf R}}\" class=\"latex\" />, where <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cphi_%5Clambda+%3A%3D+%5Clambda%5E%7B-1%2F2%7D+%5Cphi%28%5Clambda%5E%7B-1%7D+x%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\phi_\\lambda := \\lambda^{-1/2} \\phi(\\lambda^{-1} x)}\" title=\"{\\phi_\\lambda := \\lambda^{-1/2} \\phi(\\lambda^{-1} x)}\" class=\"latex\" />. </li> \n  <li>(iv) (Fourier transform) If <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bg+%3D+%5Chat+f%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{g = \\hat f}\" title=\"{g = \\hat f}\" class=\"latex\" />, show that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT_%7B%5Chat+%5Cphi%7D+g%28x%2C%5Cxi%29+%3D+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+x+%5Cxi%7D+T_%5Cphi+f%28-%5Cxi%2C+x%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T_{\\hat \\phi} g(x,\\xi) = e^{2\\pi i x \\xi} T_\\phi f(-\\xi, x)}\" title=\"{T_{\\hat \\phi} g(x,\\xi) = e^{2\\pi i x \\xi} T_\\phi f(-\\xi, x)}\" class=\"latex\" />. </li> \n  <li>(v) (Quadratic phase modulation) If <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a \\in {\\bf R}}\" title=\"{a \\in {\\bf R}}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bg+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{g \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{g \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" /> is the function <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bg%28x%29+%3A%3D+e%5E%7B%5Cpi+i+a+x%5E2%7D+f%28x%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{g(x) := e^{\\pi i a x^2} f(x)}\" title=\"{g(x) := e^{\\pi i a x^2} f(x)}\" class=\"latex\" />, show that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT_%7B%5Ctilde+%5Cphi%7D+g%28x%2C%5Cxi%29+%3D+e%5E%7B-%5Cpi+i+ax%5E2%7D+T_%5Cphi+f%28x%2C+%5Cxi-ax%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T_{\\tilde \\phi} g(x,\\xi) = e^{-\\pi i ax^2} T_\\phi f(x, \\xi-ax)}\" title=\"{T_{\\tilde \\phi} g(x,\\xi) = e^{-\\pi i ax^2} T_\\phi f(x, \\xi-ax)}\" class=\"latex\" /> for all <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28x%2C%5Cxi%29+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Ctimes+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(x,\\xi) \\in {\\bf R} \\times {\\bf R}}\" title=\"{(x,\\xi) \\in {\\bf R} \\times {\\bf R}}\" class=\"latex\" />, where <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Ctilde+%5Cphi%28x%29+%3A%3D+e%5E%7B%5Cpi+i+ax%5E2%7D+%5Cphi%28x%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\tilde \\phi(x) := e^{\\pi i ax^2} \\phi(x)}\" title=\"{\\tilde \\phi(x) := e^{\\pi i ax^2} \\phi(x)}\" class=\"latex\" />. </li> \n </ul> \n <p> We remark that the group generated by the transformations (i)-(v) is the (Weil representation of the) <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metaplectic_group\">metaplectic group</a> <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BMp_2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{Mp_2}\" title=\"{Mp_2}\" class=\"latex\" />. </p>\n</blockquote>  \n<blockquote>\n <p><b>Remark 23</b> Ignoring the changes in the Gabor test function <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cphi%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\phi}\" title=\"{\\phi}\" class=\"latex\" />, as well as the various phases appearing on the right-hand side, we conclude from the above exercise that basic transformations on functions seem to correspond to various area-preserving maps of phase space; for instance, the Fourier transform is associated to the rotation <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28-%5Cxi%2Cx%29+%5Cmapsto+%28x%2C%5Cxi%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(-\\xi,x) \\mapsto (x,\\xi)}\" title=\"{(-\\xi,x) \\mapsto (x,\\xi)}\" class=\"latex\" />, which is consistent in particular with the fact that a fourfold iteration of the Fourier transform yields the identity operator. This is in fact a quite general phenomenon, with something asymptotically resembling such identities available for an important class of operators known as <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fourier_integral_operator\">Fourier integral operators</a> (but in higher dimensions one replaces the adjective with “area-preserving” with “<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Symplectomorphism\">symplectomorphism</a>” or “<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Canonical_transformation\">canonical transformation</a>“). However, as stated previously, the systematic development of the theory of Fourier integral operators is beyond the scope of this course. </p>\n</blockquote>  \n<blockquote>\n <p><b>Remark 24</b> Virtually all of the above theory extends to higher dimensions, and also to general smooth manifolds <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BM%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{M}\" title=\"{M}\" class=\"latex\" /> as domains. In the latter case, the natural analogue of phase space is the cotangent bundle <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT%5E%2A+M%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T^* M}\" title=\"{T^* M}\" class=\"latex\" />, and the symplectic geometry of this bundle then plays a fundamental role in the theory (as already hinted at by the appearance of the Poisson bracket in Remark <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11722#ph\">10</a>. See for instance <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=983366\">this text of Folland for more discussion</a>. </p>\n</blockquote>","descriptionType":"html","publishedDate":"Sat, eaderx11/cdn33@2020_2/2020/08/24/21-37-26-733_8e4cdea76ba379f3.webp","https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cphi_%5Clambda+%3A%3D+%5Clambda%5E%7B-1%2F2%7D+%5Cphi%28%5Clambda%5E%7B-1%7D+x%29%7D&bg=ffffff&fg=000000&s=0":"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/myreaderx14/cdn82@2020_3/2020/08/24/21-37-36-685_bcefa8b64d1ee017.webp","https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bg+%3D+%5Chat+f%7D&bg=ffffff&fg=000000&s=0":"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/myreaderx2/cdn22@2020_6/2020/08/24/21-37-21-176_d6022db8f7b61516.webp","https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT_%7B%5Chat+%5Cphi%7D+g%28x%2C%5Cxi%29+%3D+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+x+%5Cxi%7D+T_%5Cphi+f%28-%5Cxi%2C+x%29%7D&bg=ffffff&fg=000000&s=0":"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/myreaderx24/cdn59@2020_3/2020/08/24/21-37-01-426_a300e700ee832b33.webp","https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D&bg=ffffff&fg=000000&s=0":"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/myreaderx24/cdn73@2020_5/2020/08/24/21-37-20-157_8bf1b951eeb0237e.webp","https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bg%28x%29+%3A%3D+e%5E%7B%5Cpi+i+a+x%5E2%7D+f%28x%29%7D&bg=ffffff&fg=000000&s=0":"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/myreaderx10/cdn25@2020_3/2020/08/24/21-37-37-981_96ba3673fb9987ba.webp","https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT_%7B%5Ctilde+%5Cphi%7D+g%28x%2C%5Cxi%29+%3D+e%5E%7B-%5Cpi+i+ax%5E2%7D+T_%5Cphi+f%28x%2C+%5Cxi-ax%29%7D&bg=ffffff&fg=000000&s=0":"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/myreaderx25/cdn51@2020_4/2020/08/24/21-37-06-585_3dab4766c326ed62.webp","https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Ctilde+%5Cphi%28x%29+%3A%3D+e%5E%7B%5Cpi+i+ax%5E2%7D+%5Cphi%28x%29%7D&bg=ffffff&fg=000000&s=0":"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/myreaderx30/cdn98@2020_5/2020/08/24/21-37-35-542_ee0976ade5bdb6b5.webp","https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BMp_2%7D&bg=ffffff&fg=000000&s=0":"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/myreaderx25/cdn73@2020_4/2020/08/24/21-37-37-072_f844fdd9d9bef820.webp","https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28-%5Cxi%2Cx%29+%5Cmapsto+%28x%2C%5Cxi%29%7D&bg=ffffff&fg=000000&s=0":"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/myreaderx8/cdn80@2020_1/2020/08/24/21-37-04-774_9e00f02e8dabe30c.webp","https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BM%7D&bg=ffffff&fg=000000&s=0":"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/myreaderx19/cdn36@2020_6/2020/08/24/21-37-06-922_9032b1b6a2013e64.webp","https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT%5E%2A+M%7D&bg=ffffff&fg=000000&s=0":"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/myreaderx30/cdn6@2020_1/2020/08/24/21-37-36-031_553f617f389e1d05.webp"},"publishedOrCreatedDate":1598305016281},{"createdTime":"2020-08-25 05:36:56","updatedTime":"2020-08-25 05:36:56","title":"Higher uniformity of bounded multiplicative functions in short intervals on average","link":"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11868","description":"<p> <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kaisa_Matom%C3%A4ki\">Kaisa Matomäki</a>, <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maksym_Radziwill\">Maksym Radziwill</a>, <a href=\"https://www.maths.ox.ac.uk/people/joni.teravainen\">Joni Teräväinen</a>, <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tamar_Ziegler\">Tamar Ziegler</a> and I have uploaded to the arXiv our paper <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2007.15644\">Higher uniformity of bounded multiplicative functions in short intervals on average</a>. This paper (which originated from a working group at an <a href=\"https://aimath.org/workshops/upcoming/sarnakconjecture/\">AIM workshop on Sarnak’s conjecture</a>) focuses on the <em>local Fourier uniformity conjecture</em> for bounded multiplicative functions such as the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liouville_function\">Liouville function</a> <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Clambda%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\lambda}\" title=\"{\\lambda}\" class=\"latex\" />. One form of this conjecture is the assertion that <a name=\"one-form\"></a></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><a name=\"one-form\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cint_0%5EX+%5C%7C+%5Clambda+%5C%7C_%7BU%5Ek%28%5Bx%2Cx%2BH%5D%29%7D%5C+dx+%3D+o%28X%29+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%281%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\int_0^X \\| \\lambda \\|_{U^k([x,x+H])}\\ dx = o(X) \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (1)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\int_0^X \\| \\lambda \\|_{U^k([x,x+H])}\\ dx = o(X) \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (1)\" class=\"latex\" /></a></p>\n<a name=\"one-form\"> </a> as \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BX+%5Crightarrow+%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{X \\rightarrow \\infty}\" title=\"{X \\rightarrow \\infty}\" class=\"latex\" /> for any fixed \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk+%5Cgeq+0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k \\geq 0}\" title=\"{k \\geq 0}\" class=\"latex\" /> and any \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BH+%3D+H%28X%29+%5Cleq+X%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{H = H(X) \\leq X}\" title=\"{H = H(X) \\leq X}\" class=\"latex\" /> that goes to infinity as \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BX+%5Crightarrow+%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{X \\rightarrow \\infty}\" title=\"{X \\rightarrow \\infty}\" class=\"latex\" />, where \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BU%5Ek%28%5Bx%2Cx%2BH%5D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{U^k([x,x+H])}\" title=\"{U^k([x,x+H])}\" class=\"latex\" /> is the (normalized) \n<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gowers_norm\">Gowers uniformity norm</a>. Among other things this conjecture implies (logarithmically averaged version of) the Chowla and Sarnak conjectures for the Liouville function (or the Möbius function), see \n<a href=\"https://terrytao.wordpress.com/2016/05/16/equivalence-of-the-logarithmically-averaged-chowla-and-sarnak-conjectures/\">this previous blog post</a>. \n<p></p>\n<p> The conjecture gets more difficult as <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k}\" title=\"{k}\" class=\"latex\" /> increases, and also becomes more difficult the more slowly <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BH%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{H}\" title=\"{H}\" class=\"latex\" /> grows with <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BX%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{X}\" title=\"{X}\" class=\"latex\" />. The <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%3D0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k=0}\" title=\"{k=0}\" class=\"latex\" /> conjecture is equivalent to the assertion </p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cint_0%5EX+%7C%5Csum_%7Bx+%5Cleq+n+%5Cleq+x%2BH%7D+%5Clambda%28n%29%7C+%5C+dx+%3D+o%28HX%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\int_0^X |\\sum_{x \\leq n \\leq x+H} \\lambda(n)| \\ dx = o(HX)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\int_0^X |\\sum_{x \\leq n \\leq x+H} \\lambda(n)| \\ dx = o(HX)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> which was proven (for arbitrarily slowly growing \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BH%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{H}\" title=\"{H}\" class=\"latex\" />) in a landmark paper of \n<a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=3488742\">Matomäki and Radziwill</a>, discussed for instance in \n<a href=\"https://terrytao.wordpress.com/2019/12/17/254a-notes-10-mean-values-of-nonpretentious-multiplicative-functions/\">this blog post</a>. \n<p> For <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%3D1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k=1}\" title=\"{k=1}\" class=\"latex\" />, the conjecture is equivalent to the assertion <a name=\"ox\"></a></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><a name=\"ox\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cint_0%5EX+%5Csup_%5Calpha+%7C%5Csum_%7Bx+%5Cleq+n+%5Cleq+x%2BH%7D+%5Clambda%28n%29+e%28-%5Calpha+n%29%7C+%5C+dx+%3D+o%28HX%29.+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%282%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\int_0^X \\sup_\\alpha |\\sum_{x \\leq n \\leq x+H} \\lambda(n) e(-\\alpha n)| \\ dx = o(HX). \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (2)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\int_0^X \\sup_\\alpha |\\sum_{x \\leq n \\leq x+H} \\lambda(n) e(-\\alpha n)| \\ dx = o(HX). \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (2)\" class=\"latex\" /></a></p>\n<a name=\"ox\"> </a> This remains open for sufficiently slowly growing \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BH%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{H}\" title=\"{H}\" class=\"latex\" /> (and it would be a major breakthrough in particular if one could obtain this bound for \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BH%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{H}\" title=\"{H}\" class=\"latex\" /> as small as \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Clog%5E%5Cvarepsilon+X%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\log^\\varepsilon X}\" title=\"{\\log^\\varepsilon X}\" class=\"latex\" /> for any fixed \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cvarepsilon%3E0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\varepsilon>0}\" title=\"{\\varepsilon>0}\" class=\"latex\" />, particularly if applicable to more general bounded multiplicative functions than \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Clambda%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\lambda}\" title=\"{\\lambda}\" class=\"latex\" />, as this would have new implications for a generalization of the Chowla conjecture known as the Elliott conjecture). Recently, \n<a href=\"https://terrytao.wordpress.com/2018/12/05/fourier-uniformity-of-bounded-multiplicative-functions-in-short-intervals-on-average/\">Kaisa, Maks and myself were able to establish this conjecture</a> in the range \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BH+%5Cgeq+X%5E%5Cvarepsilon%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{H \\geq X^\\varepsilon}\" title=\"{H \\geq X^\\varepsilon}\" class=\"latex\" /> (in fact we have since worked out in the current paper that we can get \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BH%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{H}\" title=\"{H}\" class=\"latex\" /> as small as \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cexp%28%5Clog%5E%7B5%2F8%2B%5Cvarepsilon%7D+X%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\exp(\\log^{5/8+\\varepsilon} X)}\" title=\"{\\exp(\\log^{5/8+\\varepsilon} X)}\" class=\"latex\" />). In our current paper we establish Fourier uniformity conjecture for higher \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k}\" title=\"{k}\" class=\"latex\" /> for the same range of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BH%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{H}\" title=\"{H}\" class=\"latex\" />. This in particular implies local orthogonality to polynomial phases, \n<a name=\"ox-2\"><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cint_0%5EX+%5Csup_%7BP+%5Cin+%5Cmathrm%7BPoly%7D_%7B%5Cleq+k-1%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D+%7C%5Csum_%7Bx+%5Cleq+n+%5Cleq+x%2BH%7D+%5Clambda%28n%29+e%28-P%28n%29%29%7C+%5C+dx+%3D+o%28HX%29+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%283%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\int_0^X \\sup_{P \\in \\mathrm{Poly}_{\\leq k-1}({\\bf R} \\rightarrow {\\bf R})} |\\sum_{x \\leq n \\leq x+H} \\lambda(n) e(-P(n))| \\ dx = o(HX) \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (3)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\int_0^X \\sup_{P \\in \\mathrm{Poly}_{\\leq k-1}({\\bf R} \\rightarrow {\\bf R})} |\\sum_{x \\leq n \\leq x+H} \\lambda(n) e(-P(n))| \\ dx = o(HX) \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (3)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> </a> where \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathrm%7BPoly%7D_%7B%5Cleq+k-1%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\mathrm{Poly}_{\\leq k-1}({\\bf R} \\rightarrow {\\bf R})}\" title=\"{\\mathrm{Poly}_{\\leq k-1}({\\bf R} \\rightarrow {\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" /> denotes the polynomials of degree at most \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk-1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k-1}\" title=\"{k-1}\" class=\"latex\" />, but the full conjecture is a bit stronger than this, establishing the more general statement \n<a name=\"ox-3\"><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cint_0%5EX+%5Csup_%7Bg+%5Cin+%5Cmathrm%7BPoly%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Crightarrow+G%29%7D+%7C%5Csum_%7Bx+%5Cleq+n+%5Cleq+x%2BH%7D+%5Clambda%28n%29+%5Coverline%7BF%7D%28g%28n%29+%5CGamma%29%7C+%5C+dx+%3D+o%28HX%29+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%284%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\int_0^X \\sup_{g \\in \\mathrm{Poly}({\\bf R} \\rightarrow G)} |\\sum_{x \\leq n \\leq x+H} \\lambda(n) \\overline{F}(g(n) \\Gamma)| \\ dx = o(HX) \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (4)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\int_0^X \\sup_{g \\in \\mathrm{Poly}({\\bf R} \\rightarrow G)} |\\sum_{x \\leq n \\leq x+H} \\lambda(n) \\overline{F}(g(n) \\Gamma)| \\ dx = o(HX) \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (4)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> </a> for any degree \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k}\" title=\"{k}\" class=\"latex\" /> filtered nilmanifold \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BG%2F%5CGamma%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{G/\\Gamma}\" title=\"{G/\\Gamma}\" class=\"latex\" /> and Lipschitz function \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BF%3A+G%2F%5CGamma+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cbf+C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{F: G/\\Gamma \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" title=\"{F: G/\\Gamma \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" class=\"latex\" />, where \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bg%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{g}\" title=\"{g}\" class=\"latex\" /> now ranges over polynomial maps from \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf R}}\" title=\"{{\\bf R}}\" class=\"latex\" /> to \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BG%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{G}\" title=\"{G}\" class=\"latex\" />. The method of proof follows the same general strategy as in \n<a href=\"https://terrytao.wordpress.com/2018/12/05/fourier-uniformity-of-bounded-multiplicative-functions-in-short-intervals-on-average/\">the previous paper with Kaisa and Maks</a>. (The equivalence of \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11868#ox-3\">(4)</a> and \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11868#one-form\">(1)</a> follows from the inverse conjecture for the Gowers norms, proven in \n<a href=\"https://terrytao.wordpress.com/2010/09/21/an-inverse-theorem-for-the-gowers-us1n-norm/\">this paper</a>.) We quickly sketch first the proof of \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11868#ox-2\">(3)</a>, using very informal language to avoid many technicalities regarding the precise quantitative form of various estimates. If the estimate \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11868#ox-2\">(3)</a> fails, then we have the correlation estimate \n<p></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7C%5Csum_%7Bx+%5Cleq+n+%5Cleq+x%2BH%7D+%5Clambda%28n%29+e%28-P_x%28n%29%29%7C+%5Cgg+H&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  |\\sum_{x \\leq n \\leq x+H} \\lambda(n) e(-P_x(n))| \\gg H\" title=\"\\displaystyle  |\\sum_{x \\leq n \\leq x+H} \\lambda(n) e(-P_x(n))| \\gg H\" class=\"latex\" /></p> for many \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx+%5Csim+X%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x \\sim X}\" title=\"{x \\sim X}\" class=\"latex\" /> and some polynomial \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP_x%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P_x}\" title=\"{P_x}\" class=\"latex\" /> depending on \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x}\" title=\"{x}\" class=\"latex\" />. The difficulty here is to understand how \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP_x%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P_x}\" title=\"{P_x}\" class=\"latex\" /> can depend on \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x}\" title=\"{x}\" class=\"latex\" />. We write the above correlation estimate more suggestively as \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Clambda%28n%29+%5Csim_%7B%5Bx%2Cx%2BH%5D%7D+e%28P_x%28n%29%29.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\lambda(n) \\sim_{[x,x+H]} e(P_x(n)).\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\lambda(n) \\sim_{[x,x+H]} e(P_x(n)).\" class=\"latex\" /></p> Because of the multiplicativity \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Clambda%28np%29+%3D+-%5Clambda%28p%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\lambda(np) = -\\lambda(p)}\" title=\"{\\lambda(np) = -\\lambda(p)}\" class=\"latex\" /> at small primes \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bp%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{p}\" title=\"{p}\" class=\"latex\" />, one expects to have a relation of the form \n<a name=\"rela\"><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++e%28P_%7Bx%27%7D%28p%27n%29%29+%5Csim_%7B%5Bx%2Fp%2Cx%2Fp%2BH%2Fp%5D%7D+e%28P_x%28pn%29%29+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%285%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  e(P_{x'}(p'n)) \\sim_{[x/p,x/p+H/p]} e(P_x(pn)) \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (5)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  e(P_{x'}(p'n)) \\sim_{[x/p,x/p+H/p]} e(P_x(pn)) \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (5)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> </a> for many \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%2Cx%27%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x,x'}\" title=\"{x,x'}\" class=\"latex\" /> for which \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%2Fp+%5Capprox+x%27%2Fp%27%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x/p \\approx x'/p'}\" title=\"{x/p \\approx x'/p'}\" class=\"latex\" /> for some small primes \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bp%2Cp%27%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{p,p'}\" title=\"{p,p'}\" class=\"latex\" />. (This can be formalised using an inequality of Elliott related to the Turan-Kubilius theorem.) This gives a relationship between \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP_x%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P_x}\" title=\"{P_x}\" class=\"latex\" /> and \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP_%7Bx%27%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P_{x'}}\" title=\"{P_{x'}}\" class=\"latex\" /> for “edges” \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%2Cx%27%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x,x'}\" title=\"{x,x'}\" class=\"latex\" /> in a rather sparse “graph” connecting the elements of say \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5BX%2F2%2CX%5D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{[X/2,X]}\" title=\"{[X/2,X]}\" class=\"latex\" />. Using some graph theory one can locate some non-trivial “cycles” in this graph that eventually lead (in conjunction to a certain technical but important “Chinese remainder theorem” step to modify the \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP_x%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P_x}\" title=\"{P_x}\" class=\"latex\" /> to eliminate a rather serious “aliasing” issue that was already \n<a href=\"https://terrytao.wordpress.com/2018/12/05/fourier-uniformity-of-bounded-multiplicative-functions-in-short-intervals-on-average/\">discussed in this previous post</a>) to obtain functional equations of the form \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++P_x%28a_x+%5Ccdot%29+%5Capprox+P_x%28b_x+%5Ccdot%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  P_x(a_x \\cdot) \\approx P_x(b_x \\cdot)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  P_x(a_x \\cdot) \\approx P_x(b_x \\cdot)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> for some large and close (but not identical) integers \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba_x%2Cb_x%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a_x,b_x}\" title=\"{a_x,b_x}\" class=\"latex\" />, where \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Capprox%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\approx}\" title=\"{\\approx}\" class=\"latex\" /> should be viewed as a first approximation (ignoring a certain “profinite” or “major arc” term for simplicity) as “differing by a slowly varying polynomial” and the polynomials \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP_x%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P_x}\" title=\"{P_x}\" class=\"latex\" /> should now be viewed as taking values on the reals rather than the integers. This functional equation can be solved to obtain a relation of the form \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++P_x%28t%29+%5Capprox+T_x+%5Clog+t&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  P_x(t) \\approx T_x \\log t\" title=\"\\displaystyle  P_x(t) \\approx T_x \\log t\" class=\"latex\" /></p> for some real number \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT_x%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T_x}\" title=\"{T_x}\" class=\"latex\" /> of polynomial size, and with further analysis of the relation \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11868#rela\">(5)</a> one can make \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT_x%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T_x}\" title=\"{T_x}\" class=\"latex\" /> basically independent of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x}\" title=\"{x}\" class=\"latex\" />. This simplifies \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11868#ox-2\">(3)</a> to something like \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cint_0%5EX+%5Csup_%7BP+%5Cin+%5Cmathrm%7BPoly%7D_%7B%5Cleq+k-1%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D+%7C%5Csum_%7Bx+%5Cleq+n+%5Cleq+x%2BH%7D+%5Clambda%28n%29+n%5E%7B-iT%7D%7C+%5C+dx+%3D+o%28HX%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\int_0^X \\sup_{P \\in \\mathrm{Poly}_{\\leq k-1}({\\bf R} \\rightarrow {\\bf R})} |\\sum_{x \\leq n \\leq x+H} \\lambda(n) n^{-iT}| \\ dx = o(HX)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\int_0^X \\sup_{P \\in \\mathrm{Poly}_{\\leq k-1}({\\bf R} \\rightarrow {\\bf R})} |\\sum_{x \\leq n \\leq x+H} \\lambda(n) n^{-iT}| \\ dx = o(HX)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> and this is now of a form that can be treated by the theorem of Matomäki and Radziwill (because \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bn+%5Cmapsto+%5Clambda%28n%29+n%5E%7B-iT%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{n \\mapsto \\lambda(n) n^{-iT}}\" title=\"{n \\mapsto \\lambda(n) n^{-iT}}\" class=\"latex\" /> is a bounded multiplicative function). (Actually because of the profinite term mentioned previously, one also has to insert a Dirichlet character of bounded conductor into this latter conclusion, but we will ignore this technicality.) \n<p> Now we apply the same strategy to <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11868#ox-3\">(4)</a>. For abelian <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BG%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{G}\" title=\"{G}\" class=\"latex\" /> the claim follows easily from <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11868#ox-2\">(3)</a>, so we focus on the non-abelian case. One now has a polynomial sequence <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bg_x+%5Cin+%5Cmathrm%7BPoly%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Crightarrow+G%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{g_x \\in \\mathrm{Poly}({\\bf R} \\rightarrow G)}\" title=\"{g_x \\in \\mathrm{Poly}({\\bf R} \\rightarrow G)}\" class=\"latex\" /> attached to many <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx+%5Csim+X%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x \\sim X}\" title=\"{x \\sim X}\" class=\"latex\" />, and after a somewhat complicated adaptation of the above arguments one again ends up with an approximate functional equation <a name=\"gxax\"></a></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><a name=\"gxax\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++g_x%28a_x+%5Ccdot%29+%5CGamma+%5Capprox+g_x%28b_x+%5Ccdot%29+%5CGamma+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%286%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  g_x(a_x \\cdot) \\Gamma \\approx g_x(b_x \\cdot) \\Gamma \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (6)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  g_x(a_x \\cdot) \\Gamma \\approx g_x(b_x \\cdot) \\Gamma \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (6)\" class=\"latex\" /></a></p>\n<a name=\"gxax\"> </a> where the relation \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Capprox%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\approx}\" title=\"{\\approx}\" class=\"latex\" /> is rather technical and will not be detailed here. A new difficulty arises in that there are some unwanted solutions to this equation, such as \n<p></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++g_x%28t%29+%3D+%5Cgamma%5E%7B%5Cfrac%7B%5Clog%28a_x+t%29%7D%7B%5Clog%28a_x%2Fb_x%29%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  g_x(t) = \\gamma^{\\frac{\\log(a_x t)}{\\log(a_x/b_x)}}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  g_x(t) = \\gamma^{\\frac{\\log(a_x t)}{\\log(a_x/b_x)}}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> for some \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cgamma+%5Cin+%5CGamma%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\gamma \\in \\Gamma}\" title=\"{\\gamma \\in \\Gamma}\" class=\"latex\" />, which do not necessarily lead to multiplicative characters like \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bn%5E%7B-iT%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{n^{-iT}}\" title=\"{n^{-iT}}\" class=\"latex\" /> as in the polynomial case, but instead to some unfriendly looking “generalized multiplicative characters” (think of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Be%28%5Clfloor+%5Calpha+%5Clog+n+%5Crfloor+%5Cbeta+%5Clog+n%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{e(\\lfloor \\alpha \\log n \\rfloor \\beta \\log n)}\" title=\"{e(\\lfloor \\alpha \\log n \\rfloor \\beta \\log n)}\" class=\"latex\" /> as a rough caricature). To avoid this problem, we rework the graph theory portion of the argument to produce not just one functional equation of the form \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11868#gxax\">(6)</a>for each \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x}\" title=\"{x}\" class=\"latex\" />, but \n<em>many</em>, leading to dilation invariances \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++g_x%28%281%2B%5Ctheta%29+t%29+%5CGamma+%5Capprox+g_x%28t%29+%5CGamma&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  g_x((1+\\theta) t) \\Gamma \\approx g_x(t) \\Gamma\" title=\"\\displaystyle  g_x((1+\\theta) t) \\Gamma \\approx g_x(t) \\Gamma\" class=\"latex\" /></p> for a “dense” set of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Ctheta%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\theta}\" title=\"{\\theta}\" class=\"latex\" />. From a certain amount of Lie algebra theory (ultimately arising from an understanding of the behaviour of the exponential map on nilpotent matrices, and exploiting the hypothesis that \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BG%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{G}\" title=\"{G}\" class=\"latex\" /> is non-abelian) one can conclude that (after some initial preparations to avoid degenerate cases) \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bg_x%28t%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{g_x(t)}\" title=\"{g_x(t)}\" class=\"latex\" /> must behave like \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cgamma_x%5E%7B%5Clog+t%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\gamma_x^{\\log t}}\" title=\"{\\gamma_x^{\\log t}}\" class=\"latex\" /> for some \n<em>central</em> element \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cgamma_x%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\gamma_x}\" title=\"{\\gamma_x}\" class=\"latex\" /> of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BG%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{G}\" title=\"{G}\" class=\"latex\" />. This eventually brings one back to the multiplicative characters \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bn%5E%7B-iT%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{n^{-iT}}\" title=\"{n^{-iT}}\" class=\"latex\" /> that arose in the polynomial case, and the arguments now proceed as before. \n<p> We give two applications of this higher order Fourier uniformity. One regards the growth of the number </p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++s%28k%29+%3A%3D+%7C%5C%7B+%28%5Clambda%28n%2B1%29%2C%5Cdots%2C%5Clambda%28n%2Bk%29%29%3A+n+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+N%7D+%5C%7D%7C&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  s(k) := |\\{ (\\lambda(n+1),\\dots,\\lambda(n+k)): n \\in {\\bf N} \\}|\" title=\"\\displaystyle  s(k) := |\\{ (\\lambda(n+1),\\dots,\\lambda(n+k)): n \\in {\\bf N} \\}|\" class=\"latex\" /></p> of length \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k}\" title=\"{k}\" class=\"latex\" /> sign patterns in the Liouville function. The Chowla conjecture implies that \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bs%28k%29+%3D+2%5Ek%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{s(k) = 2^k}\" title=\"{s(k) = 2^k}\" class=\"latex\" />, but even the weaker conjecture of Sarnak that \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bs%28k%29+%5Cgg+%281%2B%5Cvarepsilon%29%5Ek%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{s(k) \\gg (1+\\varepsilon)^k}\" title=\"{s(k) \\gg (1+\\varepsilon)^k}\" class=\"latex\" /> for some \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cvarepsilon%3E0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\varepsilon>0}\" title=\"{\\varepsilon>0}\" class=\"latex\" /> remains open. Until recently, the best asymptotic lower bound on \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bs%28k%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{s(k)}\" title=\"{s(k)}\" class=\"latex\" /> was \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bs%28k%29+%5Cgg+k%5E2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{s(k) \\gg k^2}\" title=\"{s(k) \\gg k^2}\" class=\"latex\" />, \n<a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/1901.06460\">due to McNamara</a>; with our result, we can now show \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bs%28k%29+%5Cgg_A+k%5EA%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{s(k) \\gg_A k^A}\" title=\"{s(k) \\gg_A k^A}\" class=\"latex\" /> for any \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BA%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{A}\" title=\"{A}\" class=\"latex\" /> (in fact we can get \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bs%28k%29+%5Cgg_%5Cvarepsilon+%5Cexp%28%5Clog%5E%7B8%2F5-%5Cvarepsilon%7D+k%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{s(k) \\gg_\\varepsilon \\exp(\\log^{8/5-\\varepsilon} k)}\" title=\"{s(k) \\gg_\\varepsilon \\exp(\\log^{8/5-\\varepsilon} k)}\" class=\"latex\" /> for any \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cvarepsilon%3E0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\varepsilon>0}\" title=\"{\\varepsilon>0}\" class=\"latex\" />). The idea is to repeat the now-standard argument to exploit multiplicativity at small primes to deduce Chowla-type conjectures from Fourier uniformity conjectures, noting that the Chowla conjecture would give all the sign patterns one could hope for. The usual argument here uses the “entropy decrement argument” to eliminate a certain error term (involving the large but mean zero factor \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bp+1_%7Bp%7Cn%7D-1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{p 1_{p|n}-1}\" title=\"{p 1_{p|n}-1}\" class=\"latex\" />). However the observation is that if there are extremely few sign patterns of length \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k}\" title=\"{k}\" class=\"latex\" />, then the entropy decrement argument is unnecessary (there isn’t much entropy to begin with), and a more low-tech moment method argument (similar to the derivation of Chowla’s conjecture from Sarnak’s conjecture, as discussed for instance in \n<a href=\"https://terrytao.wordpress.com/2012/10/14/the-chowla-conjecture-and-the-sarnak-conjecture/\">this post</a>) gives enough of Chowla’s conjecture to produce plenty of length \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k}\" title=\"{k}\" class=\"latex\" /> sign patterns. If there are not extremely few sign patterns of length \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k}\" title=\"{k}\" class=\"latex\" /> then we are done anyway. One quirk of this argument is that the sign patterns it produces may only appear exactly once; in contrast with preceding arguments, we were not able to produce a large number of sign patterns that each occur infinitely often. \n<p> The second application is to obtain cancellation for various polynomial averages involving the Liouville function <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Clambda%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\lambda}\" title=\"{\\lambda}\" class=\"latex\" /> or von Mangoldt function <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5CLambda%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\Lambda}\" title=\"{\\Lambda}\" class=\"latex\" />, such as </p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7B%5Cbf+E%7D_%7Bn+%5Cleq+X%7D+%7B%5Cbf+E%7D_%7Bm+%5Cleq+X%5E%7B1%2Fd%7D%7D+%5Clambda%28n%2BP_1%28m%29%29+%5Clambda%28n%2BP_2%28m%29%29+%5Cdots+%5Clambda%28n%2BP_k%28m%29%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  {\\bf E}_{n \\leq X} {\\bf E}_{m \\leq X^{1/d}} \\lambda(n+P_1(m)) \\lambda(n+P_2(m)) \\dots \\lambda(n+P_k(m))\" title=\"\\displaystyle  {\\bf E}_{n \\leq X} {\\bf E}_{m \\leq X^{1/d}} \\lambda(n+P_1(m)) \\lambda(n+P_2(m)) \\dots \\lambda(n+P_k(m))\" class=\"latex\" /></p> or \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7B%5Cbf+E%7D_%7Bn+%5Cleq+X%7D+%7B%5Cbf+E%7D_%7Bm+%5Cleq+X%5E%7B1%2Fd%7D%7D+%5Clambda%28n%2BP_1%28m%29%29+%5CLambda%28n%2BP_2%28m%29%29+%5Cdots+%5CLambda%28n%2BP_k%28m%29%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  {\\bf E}_{n \\leq X} {\\bf E}_{m \\leq X^{1/d}} \\lambda(n+P_1(m)) \\Lambda(n+P_2(m)) \\dots \\Lambda(n+P_k(m))\" title=\"\\displaystyle  {\\bf E}_{n \\leq X} {\\bf E}_{m \\leq X^{1/d}} \\lambda(n+P_1(m)) \\Lambda(n+P_2(m)) \\dots \\Lambda(n+P_k(m))\" class=\"latex\" /></p> where \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP_1%2C%5Cdots%2CP_k%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P_1,\\dots,P_k}\" title=\"{P_1,\\dots,P_k}\" class=\"latex\" /> are polynomials of degree at most \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bd%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{d}\" title=\"{d}\" class=\"latex\" />, no two of which differ by a constant (the latter is essential to avoid having to establish the Chowla or Hardy-Littlewood conjectures, which of course remain open). Results of this type were previously obtained \n<a href=\"https://terrytao.wordpress.com/2016/03/27/concatenation-theorems-for-anti-gowers-uniform-functions-and-host-kra-characteristic-factors-polynomial-patterns-in-primes/\">by Tamar Ziegler and myself</a> in the “true complexity zero” case when the polynomials \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P}\" title=\"{P}\" class=\"latex\" /> had distinct degrees, in which one could use the \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%3D0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k=0}\" title=\"{k=0}\" class=\"latex\" /> theory of Matomäki and Radziwill; now that higher \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k}\" title=\"{k}\" class=\"latex\" /> is available at the scale \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BH%3DX%5E%7B1%2Fd%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{H=X^{1/d}}\" title=\"{H=X^{1/d}}\" class=\"latex\" /> we can now remove this restriction. \n<p></p> \n<p></p>","descriptionType":"html","publishedDate":"Fri, 31 Jul 2020 03:12:29 +0000","feedId":3543,"bgimg":"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Clambda%7D&bg=ffffff&fg=000000&s=0","linkMd5":"6ce0d4aaedc31dc2fce5fda6a45f5cfd","bgimgJsdelivr":"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/myreaderx27/cdn52@2020_2/2020/08/24/21-36-56-731_88bf0bf93ad78962.webp","destWidth":9,"destHeight":11,"sourceBytes":168,"destBytes":190,"author":"Terence
