05:36:56","updatedTime":"2020-08-25 05:36:56","title":"Mathematics Seminars List","link":"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11620","description":"<p>My student, <a href=\"https://www.math.ucla.edu/people/grad/jdedios\">Jaume de Dios</a>, has set up <a href=\"http://jaume.dedios.cat/math-seminars/\">a web site</a> to collect upcoming mathematics seminars from any institution that are open online.  (For instance, it has a talk that I will be giving in an hour.)   There is a form for adding further talks to the site; please feel free to contribute (or make other suggestions) in order to make the seminar list more useful.</p>\n<p>UPDATE: Here are some other lists of mathematical seminars online:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"http://math.mit.edu/~aosun/online_seminars.html\">Online seminars</a> (curated by Ao Sun and Mingchen Xia at MIT)</li>\n<li><a href=\"http://dermenjian.com/seminars/\">Algebraic Combinatorics Online Seminars</a> (maybe using the same data set as the preceding link?)</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://s.wayne.edu/isaksen/online-mathematics-seminars/\">Online mathematics seminars</a> (curated by Dan Isaksen at Wayne State University)</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://mathseminars.org/\">Math seminars</a> (run by Edgar Costa and David Roe at MIT)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Perhaps further links of this type could be added in the comments.  It would perhaps make sense to somehow unify these lists into a single one that can be updated through crowdsourcing.</p>\n<p>EDIT: See also IPAM&#8217;s <a href=\"https://www.ipam.ucla.edu/news/running-virtual-seminars-a-mathematicians-guide/\">advice page on running virtual seminars</a>.</p>\n","descriptionType":"html","publishedDate":"Tue, 07 Apr 2020 23:09:43 +0000","feedId":3543,"bgimg":"","linkMd5":"675304c6c025c52bb75c3820b493a0cb","bgimgJsdelivr":"","metaImg":"","author":"Terence Tao","publishedOrCreatedDate":1598305016232},{"createdTime":"2020-08-25 05:36:56","updatedTime":"2020-08-25 05:36:56","title":"Pointwise ergodic theorems for non-conventional bilinear polynomial averages","link":"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11875","description":"<p> <a href=\"https://www.math.princeton.edu/people/benjamin-krause\">Ben Krause</a>, <a href=\"https://sites.math.rutgers.edu/~mm2809/\">Mariusz Mirek</a>, and I have uploaded to the arXiv our paper <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2008.00857\">Pointwise ergodic theorems for non-conventional bilinear polynomial averages</a>. This paper is a contribution to the decades-long program of extending the classical ergodic theorems to “non-conventional” ergodic averages. Here, the focus is on pointwise convergence theorems, and in particular looking for extensions of the pointwise ergodic theorem of Birkhoff: </p>\n<p> </p>\n<blockquote>\n <b>Theorem 1 (Birkhoff ergodic theorem)</b> Let \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28X%2C%5Cmu%2CT%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(X,\\mu,T)}\" title=\"{(X,\\mu,T)}\" class=\"latex\" /> be a measure-preserving system (by which we mean \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28X%2C%5Cmu%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(X,\\mu)}\" title=\"{(X,\\mu)}\" class=\"latex\" /> is a \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Csigma%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\sigma}\" title=\"{\\sigma}\" class=\"latex\" />-finite measure space, and \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT%3A+X+%5Crightarrow+X%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T: X \\rightarrow X}\" title=\"{T: X \\rightarrow X}\" class=\"latex\" /> is invertible and measure-preserving), and let \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+L%5Ep%28X%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in L^p(X)}\" title=\"{f \\in L^p(X)}\" class=\"latex\" /> for any \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1+%5Cleq+p+%3C+%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1 \\leq p < \\infty}\" title=\"{1 \\leq p < \\infty}\" class=\"latex\" />. Then the averages \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7BN%7D+%5Csum_%7Bn%3D1%7D%5EN+f%28T%5En+x%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\frac{1}{N} \\sum_{n=1}^N f(T^n x)}\" title=\"{\\frac{1}{N} \\sum_{n=1}^N f(T^n x)}\" class=\"latex\" /> converge pointwise for \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmu%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\mu}\" title=\"{\\mu}\" class=\"latex\" />-almost every \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx+%5Cin+X%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x \\in X}\" title=\"{x \\in X}\" class=\"latex\" />. \n</blockquote> \n<p></p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> Pointwise ergodic theorems have an inherently harmonic analysis content to them, as they are closely tied to maximal inequalities. For instance, the Birkhoff ergodic theorem is closely tied to the Hardy-Littlewood maximal inequality. </p>\n<p> The above theorem was generalized <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=937581\">by Bourgain</a> (conceding the endpoint <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bp%3D1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{p=1}\" title=\"{p=1}\" class=\"latex\" />, where pointwise almost everywhere convergence is <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=2680392\">now known</a> <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=2788358\">to fail</a>) to polynomial averages: </p>\n<p> </p>\n<blockquote>\n <b>Theorem 2 (Pointwise ergodic theorem for polynomial averages)</b> \n <a name=\"poly-1\"></a> Let \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28X%2C%5Cmu%2CT%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(X,\\mu,T)}\" title=\"{(X,\\mu,T)}\" class=\"latex\" /> be a measure-preserving system, and let \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+L%5Ep%28X%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in L^p(X)}\" title=\"{f \\in L^p(X)}\" class=\"latex\" /> for any \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1+%3C+p+%3C+%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1 < p < \\infty}\" title=\"{1 < p < \\infty}\" class=\"latex\" />. Let \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%5B%7B%5Cmathrm+n%7D%5D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P \\in {\\bf Z}[{\\mathrm n}]}\" title=\"{P \\in {\\bf Z}[{\\mathrm n}]}\" class=\"latex\" /> be a polynpmial with integer coefficients. Then the averages \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7BN%7D+%5Csum_%7Bn%3D1%7D%5EN+f%28T%5E%7BP%28n%29%7D+x%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\frac{1}{N} \\sum_{n=1}^N f(T^{P(n)} x)}\" title=\"{\\frac{1}{N} \\sum_{n=1}^N f(T^{P(n)} x)}\" class=\"latex\" /> converge pointwise for \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmu%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\mu}\" title=\"{\\mu}\" class=\"latex\" />-almost every \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx+%5Cin+X%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x \\in X}\" title=\"{x \\in X}\" class=\"latex\" />. \n</blockquote> \n<p></p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> For bilinear averages, we have a separate 1990 <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=1037434\">result of Bourgain</a> (for <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BL%5E%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{L^\\infty}\" title=\"{L^\\infty}\" class=\"latex\" /> functions), extended to other <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BL%5Ep%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{L^p}\" title=\"{L^p}\" class=\"latex\" /> spaces <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=1745019\">by Lacey</a>, and with an alternate proof given, <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=2417419\">by Demeter</a>: </p>\n<p> </p>\n<blockquote>\n <b>Theorem 3 (Pointwise ergodic theorem for two linear polynomials)</b> \n <a name=\"poly-2\"></a> Let \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28X%2C%5Cmu%2CT%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(X,\\mu,T)}\" title=\"{(X,\\mu,T)}\" class=\"latex\" /> be a measure-preserving system with finite measure, and let \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+L%5E%7Bp_1%7D%28X%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in L^{p_1}(X)}\" title=\"{f \\in L^{p_1}(X)}\" class=\"latex\" />, \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bg+%5Cin+L%5E%7Bp_2%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{g \\in L^{p_2}}\" title=\"{g \\in L^{p_2}}\" class=\"latex\" /> for some \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1+%3C+p_1%2Cp_2+%5Cleq+%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1 < p_1,p_2 \\leq \\infty}\" title=\"{1 < p_1,p_2 \\leq \\infty}\" class=\"latex\" /> with \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7Bp_1%7D%2B%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7Bp_2%7D+%3C+%5Cfrac%7B3%7D%7B2%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\frac{1}{p_1}+\\frac{1}{p_2} < \\frac{3}{2}}\" title=\"{\\frac{1}{p_1}+\\frac{1}{p_2} < \\frac{3}{2}}\" class=\"latex\" />. Then for any integers \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%2Cb%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a,b}\" title=\"{a,b}\" class=\"latex\" />, the averages \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7BN%7D+%5Csum_%7Bn%3D1%7D%5EN+f%28T%5E%7Ban%7D+x%29+g%28T%5E%7Bbn%7D+x%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\frac{1}{N} \\sum_{n=1}^N f(T^{an} x) g(T^{bn} x)}\" title=\"{\\frac{1}{N} \\sum_{n=1}^N f(T^{an} x) g(T^{bn} x)}\" class=\"latex\" /> converge pointwise almost everywhere. \n</blockquote> \n<p></p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> It has been an open question for some time (see e.g., Problem 11 of <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=3613710\">this survey of Frantzikinakis</a>) to extend this result to other bilinear ergodic averages. In our paper we are able to achieve this in the partially linear case: </p>\n<p> </p>\n<blockquote>\n <b>Theorem 4 (Pointwise ergodic theorem for one linear and one nonlinear polynomial)</b> \n <a name=\"poly-3\"></a> Let \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28X%2C%5Cmu%2CT%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(X,\\mu,T)}\" title=\"{(X,\\mu,T)}\" class=\"latex\" /> be a measure-preserving system, and let \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+L%5E%7Bp_1%7D%28X%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in L^{p_1}(X)}\" title=\"{f \\in L^{p_1}(X)}\" class=\"latex\" />, \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bg+%5Cin+L%5E%7Bp_2%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{g \\in L^{p_2}}\" title=\"{g \\in L^{p_2}}\" class=\"latex\" /> for some \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1+%3C+p_1%2Cp_2+%3C+%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1 < p_1,p_2 < \\infty}\" title=\"{1 < p_1,p_2 < \\infty}\" class=\"latex\" /> with \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7Bp_1%7D%2B%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7Bp_2%7D+%5Cleq+1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\frac{1}{p_1}+\\frac{1}{p_2} \\leq 1}\" title=\"{\\frac{1}{p_1}+\\frac{1}{p_2} \\leq 1}\" class=\"latex\" />. Then for any polynomial \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%5B%7B%5Cmathrm+n%7D%5D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P \\in {\\bf Z}[{\\mathrm n}]}\" title=\"{P \\in {\\bf Z}[{\\mathrm n}]}\" class=\"latex\" /> of degree \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bd+%5Cgeq+2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{d \\geq 2}\" title=\"{d \\geq 2}\" class=\"latex\" />, the averages \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7BN%7D+%5Csum_%7Bn%3D1%7D%5EN+f%28T%5E%7Bn%7D+x%29+g%28T%5E%7BP%28n%29%7D+x%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\frac{1}{N} \\sum_{n=1}^N f(T^{n} x) g(T^{P(n)} x)}\" title=\"{\\frac{1}{N} \\sum_{n=1}^N f(T^{n} x) g(T^{P(n)} x)}\" class=\"latex\" /> converge pointwise almost everywhere. \n</blockquote> \n<p></p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> We actually prove a bit more than this, namely a maximal function estimate and a variational estimate, together with some additional estimates that “break duality” by applying in certain ranges with <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7Bp_1%7D%2B%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7Bp_2%7D%3E1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\frac{1}{p_1}+\\frac{1}{p_2}>1}\" title=\"{\\frac{1}{p_1}+\\frac{1}{p_2}>1}\" class=\"latex\" />, but we will not discuss these extensions here. A good model case to keep in mind is when <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bp_1%3Dp_2%3D2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{p_1=p_2=2}\" title=\"{p_1=p_2=2}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP%28n%29+%3D+n%5E2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P(n) = n^2}\" title=\"{P(n) = n^2}\" class=\"latex\" /> (which is the case we started with). We note that norm convergence for these averages was established much earlier <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=1412607\">by Furstenberg and Weiss</a> (in the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bd%3D2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{d=2}\" title=\"{d=2}\" class=\"latex\" /> case at least), and in fact norm convergence for arbitrary polynomial averages is now known thanks to the work of <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=2191208\">Host-Kra</a>, <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=2151605\">Leibman</a>, and <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=2912715\">Walsh</a>. </p>\n<p> Our proof of Theorem <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11875#poly-3\">4</a> is much closer in spirit to Theorem <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11875#poly-1\">2</a> than to Theorem <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11875#poly-2\">3</a>. The property of the averages shared in common by Theorems <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11875#poly-1\">2</a>, <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11875#poly-3\">4</a> is that they have “true complexity zero”, in the sense that they can only be only be large if the functions <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%2Cg%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f,g}\" title=\"{f,g}\" class=\"latex\" /> involved are “major arc” or “profinite”, in that they behave periodically over very long intervals (or like a linear combination of such periodic functions). In contrast, the average in Theorem <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11875#poly-2\">3</a> has “true complexity one”, in the sense that they can also be large if <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%2Cg%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f,g}\" title=\"{f,g}\" class=\"latex\" /> are “almost periodic” (a linear combination of eigenfunctions, or plane waves), and as such all proofs of the latter theorem have relied (either explicitly or implicitly) on some form of time-frequency analysis. In principle, the true complexity zero property reduces one to study the behaviour of averages on major arcs. However, until recently the available estimates to quantify this true complexity zero property were not strong enough to achieve a good reduction of this form, and even once one was in the major arc setting the bilinear averages in Theorem <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11875#poly-3\">4</a> were still quite complicated, exhibiting a mixture of both continuous and arithmetic aspects, both of which being genuinely bilinear in nature. </p>\n<p> After applying standard reductions such as the Calderón transference principle, the key task is to establish a suitably “scale-invariant” maximal (or variational) inequality on the integer shift system (in which <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BX+%3D+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{X = {\\bf Z}}\" title=\"{X = {\\bf Z}}\" class=\"latex\" /> with counting measure, and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT%28n%29+%3D+n-1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T(n) = n-1}\" title=\"{T(n) = n-1}\" class=\"latex\" />). A model problem is to establish the maximal inequality <a name=\"anfg\"></a></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><a name=\"anfg\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%5Csup_N+%7CA_N%28f%2Cg%29%7C+%5C%7C_%7B%5Cell%5E1%28%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D+%5Clesssim+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7B%5Cell%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D%5C%7Cg%5C%7C_%7B%5Cell%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%281%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sup_N |A_N(f,g)| \\|_{\\ell^1({\\bf Z})} \\lesssim \\|f\\|_{\\ell^2({\\bf Z})}\\|g\\|_{\\ell^2({\\bf Z})} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (1)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sup_N |A_N(f,g)| \\|_{\\ell^1({\\bf Z})} \\lesssim \\|f\\|_{\\ell^2({\\bf Z})}\\|g\\|_{\\ell^2({\\bf Z})} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (1)\" class=\"latex\" /></a></p>\n<a name=\"anfg\"> </a> where \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N}\" title=\"{N}\" class=\"latex\" /> ranges over powers of two and \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BA_N%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{A_N}\" title=\"{A_N}\" class=\"latex\" /> is the bilinear operator \n<p></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++A_N%28f%2Cg%29%28x%29+%3A%3D+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7BN%7D+%5Csum_%7Bn%3D1%7D%5EN+f%28x-n%29+g%28x-n%5E2%29.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  A_N(f,g)(x) := \\frac{1}{N} \\sum_{n=1}^N f(x-n) g(x-n^2).\" title=\"\\displaystyle  A_N(f,g)(x) := \\frac{1}{N} \\sum_{n=1}^N f(x-n) g(x-n^2).\" class=\"latex\" /></p> The single scale estimate \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+A_N%28f%2Cg%29+%5C%7C_%7B%5Cell%5E1%28%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D+%5Clesssim+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7B%5Cell%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D%5C%7Cg%5C%7C_%7B%5Cell%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| A_N(f,g) \\|_{\\ell^1({\\bf Z})} \\lesssim \\|f\\|_{\\ell^2({\\bf Z})}\\|g\\|_{\\ell^2({\\bf Z})}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| A_N(f,g) \\|_{\\ell^1({\\bf Z})} \\lesssim \\|f\\|_{\\ell^2({\\bf Z})}\\|g\\|_{\\ell^2({\\bf Z})}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> or equivalently (by duality) \n<a name=\"fgh\"><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7BN%7D+%5Csum_%7Bn%3D1%7D%5EN+%5Csum_%7Bx+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D+h%28x%29+f%28x-n%29+g%28x-n%5E2%29+%5Clesssim+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7B%5Cell%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D%5C%7Cg%5C%7C_%7B%5Cell%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D+%5C%7Ch%5C%7C_%7B%5Cell%5E%5Cinfty%28%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%282%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\frac{1}{N} \\sum_{n=1}^N \\sum_{x \\in {\\bf Z}} h(x) f(x-n) g(x-n^2) \\lesssim \\|f\\|_{\\ell^2({\\bf Z})}\\|g\\|_{\\ell^2({\\bf Z})} \\|h\\|_{\\ell^\\infty({\\bf Z})} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (2)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\frac{1}{N} \\sum_{n=1}^N \\sum_{x \\in {\\bf Z}} h(x) f(x-n) g(x-n^2) \\lesssim \\|f\\|_{\\ell^2({\\bf Z})}\\|g\\|_{\\ell^2({\\bf Z})} \\|h\\|_{\\ell^\\infty({\\bf Z})} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (2)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> </a> is immediate from Hölder’s inequality; the difficulty is how to take the supremum over scales \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N}\" title=\"{N}\" class=\"latex\" />. \n<p> The first step is to understand when the single-scale estimate <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11875#fgh\">(2)</a> can come close to equality. A key example to keep in mind is when <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%28x%29+%3D+e%28ax%2Fq%29+F%28x%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f(x) = e(ax/q) F(x)}\" title=\"{f(x) = e(ax/q) F(x)}\" class=\"latex\" />, <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bg%28x%29+%3D+e%28bx%2Fq%29+G%28x%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{g(x) = e(bx/q) G(x)}\" title=\"{g(x) = e(bx/q) G(x)}\" class=\"latex\" />, <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bh%28x%29+%3D+e%28cx%2Fq%29+H%28x%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{h(x) = e(cx/q) H(x)}\" title=\"{h(x) = e(cx/q) H(x)}\" class=\"latex\" /> where <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bq%3DO%281%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{q=O(1)}\" title=\"{q=O(1)}\" class=\"latex\" /> is a small modulus, <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%2Cb%2Cc%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a,b,c}\" title=\"{a,b,c}\" class=\"latex\" /> are such that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%2Bb%2Bc%3D0+%5Chbox%7B+mod+%7D+q%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a+b+c=0 \\hbox{ mod } q}\" title=\"{a+b+c=0 \\hbox{ mod } q}\" class=\"latex\" />, <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BG%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{G}\" title=\"{G}\" class=\"latex\" /> is a smooth cutoff to an interval <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BI%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{I}\" title=\"{I}\" class=\"latex\" /> of length <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BO%28N%5E2%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{O(N^2)}\" title=\"{O(N^2)}\" class=\"latex\" />, and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BF%3DH%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{F=H}\" title=\"{F=H}\" class=\"latex\" /> is also supported on <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BI%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{I}\" title=\"{I}\" class=\"latex\" /> and behaves like a constant on intervals of length <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BO%28N%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{O(N)}\" title=\"{O(N)}\" class=\"latex\" />. Then one can check that (barring some unusual cancellation) <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11875#fgh\">(2)</a> is basically sharp for this example. A remarkable result <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/1903.02592\">of Peluse and Prendiville</a> (generalised to arbitrary nonlinear polynomials <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P}\" title=\"{P}\" class=\"latex\" /> <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/1909.00309\">by Peluse</a>) asserts, roughly speaking, that this example basically the only way in which <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11875#fgh\">(2)</a> can be saturated, at least when <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%2Cg%2Ch%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f,g,h}\" title=\"{f,g,h}\" class=\"latex\" /> are supported on a common interval <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BI%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{I}\" title=\"{I}\" class=\"latex\" /> of length <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BO%28N%5E2%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{O(N^2)}\" title=\"{O(N^2)}\" class=\"latex\" /> and are normalised in <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cell%5E%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\ell^\\infty}\" title=\"{\\ell^\\infty}\" class=\"latex\" /> rather than <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cell%5E2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\ell^2}\" title=\"{\\ell^2}\" class=\"latex\" />. (Strictly speaking, the above paper of Peluse and Prendiville only says something like this regarding the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%2Ch%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f,h}\" title=\"{f,h}\" class=\"latex\" /> factors; the corresponding statement for <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bg%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{g}\" title=\"{g}\" class=\"latex\" /> was established in a <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2003.04122\">subsequent paper of Peluse and Prendiville</a>.) The argument requires tools from additive combinatorics such as the Gowers uniformity norms, and hinges in particular on the “degree lowering argument” of Peluse and Prendiville, which I discussed in <a href=\"https://terrytao.wordpress.com/2020/03/08/cut-norms-and-degree-lowering/\">this previous blog post</a>. Crucially for our application, the estimates are very quantitative, with all bounds being polynomial in the ratio between the left and right hand sides of <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11875#fgh\">(2)</a> (or more precisely, the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cell%5E%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\ell^\\infty}\" title=\"{\\ell^\\infty}\" class=\"latex\" />-normalized version of <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11875#fgh\">(2)</a>). </p>\n<p> For our applications we had to extend the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cell%5E%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\ell^\\infty}\" title=\"{\\ell^\\infty}\" class=\"latex\" /> inverse theory of Peluse and Prendiville to an <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cell%5E2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\ell^2}\" title=\"{\\ell^2}\" class=\"latex\" /> theory. This turned out to require a certain amount of “sleight of hand”. Firstly, one can dualise the theorem of Peluse and Prendiville to show that the “dual function” </p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++A%5E%2A_N%28h%2Cg%29%28x%29+%3D+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7BN%7D+%5Csum_%7Bn%3D1%7D%5EN+h%28x%2Bn%29+g%28x%2Bn-n%5E2%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  A^*_N(h,g)(x) = \\frac{1}{N} \\sum_{n=1}^N h(x+n) g(x+n-n^2)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  A^*_N(h,g)(x) = \\frac{1}{N} \\sum_{n=1}^N h(x+n) g(x+n-n^2)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> can be well approximated in \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cell%5E1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\ell^1}\" title=\"{\\ell^1}\" class=\"latex\" /> by a function that has Fourier support on “major arcs” if \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bg%2Ch%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{g,h}\" title=\"{g,h}\" class=\"latex\" /> enjoy \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cell%5E%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\ell^\\infty}\" title=\"{\\ell^\\infty}\" class=\"latex\" /> control. To get the required extension to \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cell%5E2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\ell^2}\" title=\"{\\ell^2}\" class=\"latex\" /> in the \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f}\" title=\"{f}\" class=\"latex\" /> aspect one has to improve the control on the error from \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cell%5E1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\ell^1}\" title=\"{\\ell^1}\" class=\"latex\" /> to \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cell%5E2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\ell^2}\" title=\"{\\ell^2}\" class=\"latex\" />; this can be done by some interpolation theory combined with the useful Fourier multiplier theory \n<a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=2188130\">of Ionescu and Wainger</a> on major arcs. Then, by further interpolation using recent \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cell%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\ell^p({\\bf Z})}\" title=\"{\\ell^p({\\bf Z})}\" class=\"latex\" /> improving estimates of \n<a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/1910.14630\">Han, Kovac, Lacey, Madrid, and Yang</a> for linear averages such as \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx+%5Cmapsto+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7BN%7D+%5Csum_%7Bn%3D1%7D%5EN+g%28x%2Bn-n%5E2%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x \\mapsto \\frac{1}{N} \\sum_{n=1}^N g(x+n-n^2)}\" title=\"{x \\mapsto \\frac{1}{N} \\sum_{n=1}^N g(x+n-n^2)}\" class=\"latex\" />, one can relax the \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cell%5E%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\ell^\\infty}\" title=\"{\\ell^\\infty}\" class=\"latex\" /> hypothesis on \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bg%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{g}\" title=\"{g}\" class=\"latex\" /> to an \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cell%5E2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\ell^2}\" title=\"{\\ell^2}\" class=\"latex\" /> hypothesis, and then by undoing the duality one obtains a good inverse theorem for \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11875#fgh\">(2)</a> for the function \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f}\" title=\"{f}\" class=\"latex\" />; a modification of the arguments also gives something similar for \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bg%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{g}\" title=\"{g}\" class=\"latex\" />. \n<p> Using these inverse theorems (and the Ionescu-Wainger multiplier theory) one still has to understand the “major arc” portion of <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11875#anfg\">(1)</a>; a model case arises when <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%2Cg%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f,g}\" title=\"{f,g}\" class=\"latex\" /> are supported near rational numbers <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%2Fq%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a/q}\" title=\"{a/q}\" class=\"latex\" /> with <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bq+%5Csim+2%5El%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{q \\sim 2^l}\" title=\"{q \\sim 2^l}\" class=\"latex\" /> for some moderately large <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bl%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{l}\" title=\"{l}\" class=\"latex\" />. The inverse theory gives good control (with an exponential decay in <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bl%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{l}\" title=\"{l}\" class=\"latex\" />) on individual scales <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N}\" title=\"{N}\" class=\"latex\" />, and one can leverage this with a Rademacher-Menshov type argument (see e.g., <a href=\"https://terrytao.wordpress.com/2020/05/14/247b-notes-4-almost-everywhere-convergence-of-fourier-series/\">this blog post</a>) and some closer analysis of the bilinear Fourier symbol of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BA_N%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{A_N}\" title=\"{A_N}\" class=\"latex\" /> to eventually handle all “small” scales, with <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N}\" title=\"{N}\" class=\"latex\" /> ranging up to say <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B2%5E%7B2%5Eu%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{2^{2^u}}\" title=\"{2^{2^u}}\" class=\"latex\" /> where <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bu+%3D+C+2%5E%7B%5Crho+l%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{u = C 2^{\\rho l}}\" title=\"{u = C 2^{\\rho l}}\" class=\"latex\" /> for some small constant <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Crho%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\rho}\" title=\"{\\rho}\" class=\"latex\" /> and large constant <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BC%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{C}\" title=\"{C}\" class=\"latex\" />. For the “large” scales, it becomes feasible to place all the major arcs simultaneously under a single common denominator <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BQ%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{Q}\" title=\"{Q}\" class=\"latex\" />, and then a quantitative version of the Shannon sampling theorem allows one to transfer the problem from the integers <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf Z}}\" title=\"{{\\bf Z}}\" class=\"latex\" /> to the locally compact abelian group <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Ctimes+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%2FQ%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf R} \\times {\\bf Z}/Q{\\bf Z}}\" title=\"{{\\bf R} \\times {\\bf Z}/Q{\\bf Z}}\" class=\"latex\" />. Actually it was conceptually clearer for us to work instead with the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adele_ring#Alternative_definition_for_number_fields\">adelic integers</a> <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cmathbf+A%7D_%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D+%3D%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Ctimes+%5Chat+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\mathbf A}_{\\bf Z} ={\\bf R} \\times \\hat {\\bf Z}}\" title=\"{{\\mathbf A}_{\\bf Z} ={\\bf R} \\times \\hat {\\bf Z}}\" class=\"latex\" />, which is the inverse limit of the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Ctimes+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%2FQ%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf R} \\times {\\bf Z}/Q{\\bf Z}}\" title=\"{{\\bf R} \\times {\\bf Z}/Q{\\bf Z}}\" class=\"latex\" />. Once one transfers to the adelic integers, the bilinear operators involved split up as tensor products of the “continuous” bilinear operator </p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++A_%7BN%2C%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D%28f%2Cg%29%28x%29+%3A%3D+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7BN%7D+%5Cint_0%5EN+f%28x-t%29+g%28x-t%5E2%29%5C+dt&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  A_{N,{\\bf R}}(f,g)(x) := \\frac{1}{N} \\int_0^N f(x-t) g(x-t^2)\\ dt\" title=\"\\displaystyle  A_{N,{\\bf R}}(f,g)(x) := \\frac{1}{N} \\int_0^N f(x-t) g(x-t^2)\\ dt\" class=\"latex\" /></p> on \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf R}}\" title=\"{{\\bf R}}\" class=\"latex\" />, and the “arithmetic” bilinear operator \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++A_%7B%5Chat+Z%7D%28f%2Cg%29%28x%29+%3A%3D+%5Cint_%7B%5Chat+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D+f%28x-y%29+g%28x-y%5E2%29+d%5Cmu_%7B%5Chat+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D%28y%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  A_{\\hat Z}(f,g)(x) := \\int_{\\hat {\\bf Z}} f(x-y) g(x-y^2) d\\mu_{\\hat {\\bf Z}}(y)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  A_{\\hat Z}(f,g)(x) := \\int_{\\hat {\\bf Z}} f(x-y) g(x-y^2) d\\mu_{\\hat {\\bf Z}}(y)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> on the \n<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Profinite_integers\">profinite integers</a> \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Chat+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\hat {\\bf Z}}\" title=\"{\\hat {\\bf Z}}\" class=\"latex\" />, equipped with probability Haar measure \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmu_%7B%5Chat+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\mu_{\\hat {\\bf Z}}}\" title=\"{\\mu_{\\hat {\\bf Z}}}\" class=\"latex\" />. After a number of standard manipulations (interpolation, Fubini’s theorem, Holder’s inequality, variational inequalities, etc.) the task of estimating this tensor product boils down to establishing an \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BL%5Eq%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{L^q}\" title=\"{L^q}\" class=\"latex\" /> improving estimate \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+A_%7B%5Chat+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D%28f%2Cg%29+%5C%7C_%7BL%5Eq%28%5Chat+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D+%5Clesssim+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28%5Chat+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D+%5C%7Cg%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28%5Chat+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| A_{\\hat {\\bf Z}}(f,g) \\|_{L^q(\\hat {\\bf Z})} \\lesssim \\|f\\|_{L^2(\\hat {\\bf Z})} \\|g\\|_{L^2(\\hat {\\bf Z})}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| A_{\\hat {\\bf Z}}(f,g) \\|_{L^q(\\hat {\\bf Z})} \\lesssim \\|f\\|_{L^2(\\hat {\\bf Z})} \\|g\\|_{L^2(\\hat {\\bf Z})}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> for some \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bq%3E2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{q>2}\" title=\"{q>2}\" class=\"latex\" />. Splitting the profinite integers \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Chat+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\hat {\\bf Z}}\" title=\"{\\hat {\\bf Z}}\" class=\"latex\" /> into the product of the \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bp%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{p}\" title=\"{p}\" class=\"latex\" />-adic integers \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D_p%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf Z}_p}\" title=\"{{\\bf Z}_p}\" class=\"latex\" />, it suffices to establish this claim for each \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D_p%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf Z}_p}\" title=\"{{\\bf Z}_p}\" class=\"latex\" /> separately (so long as we keep the implied constant equal to \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1}\" title=\"{1}\" class=\"latex\" /> for sufficiently large \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bp%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{p}\" title=\"{p}\" class=\"latex\" />). This turns out to be possible using an arithmetic version of the Peluse-Prendiville inverse theorem as well as an arithmetic \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BL%5Eq%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{L^q}\" title=\"{L^q}\" class=\"latex\" /> improving estimate for linear averaging operators which ultimately arises from some estimates on the distribution of polynomials on the \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bp%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{p}\" title=\"{p}\" class=\"latex\" />-adic field \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+Q%7D_p%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf Q}_p}\" title=\"{{\\bf Q}_p}\" class=\"latex\" />, which are a variant of some estimates \n<a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=3000832\">of Kowalski and Wright</a>. \n<p></p> 05:36:56","updatedTime":"2020-08-25 05:36:56","title":"The sunflower lemma via Shannon entropy","link":"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11852","description":"<p> A family <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BA_1%2C%5Cdots%2CA_r%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{A_1,\\dots,A_r}\" title=\"{A_1,\\dots,A_r}\" class=\"latex\" /> of sets for some <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Br+%5Cgeq+1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{r \\geq 1}\" title=\"{r \\geq 1}\" class=\"latex\" /> is a <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sunflower_(mathematics)\">sunflower</a> if there is a <em>core set</em> <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BA_0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{A_0}\" title=\"{A_0}\" class=\"latex\" /> contained in each of the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BA_i%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{A_i}\" title=\"{A_i}\" class=\"latex\" /> such that the <em>petal sets</em> <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BA_i+%5Cbackslash+A_0%2C+i%3D1%2C%5Cdots%2Cr%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{A_i \\backslash A_0, i=1,\\dots,r}\" title=\"{A_i \\backslash A_0, i=1,\\dots,r}\" class=\"latex\" /> are disjoint. If <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%2Cr+%5Cgeq+1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k,r \\geq 1}\" title=\"{k,r \\geq 1}\" class=\"latex\" />, let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathrm%7BSun%7D%28k%2Cr%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\mathrm{Sun}(k,r)}\" title=\"{\\mathrm{Sun}(k,r)}\" class=\"latex\" /> denote the smallest natural number with the property that any family of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathrm%7BSun%7D%28k%2Cr%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\mathrm{Sun}(k,r)}\" title=\"{\\mathrm{Sun}(k,r)}\" class=\"latex\" /> distinct sets of cardinality at most <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k}\" title=\"{k}\" class=\"latex\" /> contains <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Br%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{r}\" title=\"{r}\" class=\"latex\" /> distinct elements <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BA_1%2C%5Cdots%2CA_r%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{A_1,\\dots,A_r}\" title=\"{A_1,\\dots,A_r}\" class=\"latex\" /> that form a sunflower. The celebrated <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=111692\">Erdös-Rado theorem</a> asserts that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathrm%7BSun%7D%28k%2Cr%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\mathrm{Sun}(k,r)}\" title=\"{\\mathrm{Sun}(k,r)}\" class=\"latex\" /> is finite; in fact Erdös and Rado gave the bounds <a name=\"ease\"><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%28r-1%29%5Ek+%5Cleq+%5Cmathrm%7BSun%7D%28k%2Cr%29+%5Cleq+%28r-1%29%5Ek+k%21+%2B+1.+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%281%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  (r-1)^k \\leq \\mathrm{Sun}(k,r) \\leq (r-1)^k k! + 1. \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (1)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  (r-1)^k \\leq \\mathrm{Sun}(k,r) \\leq (r-1)^k k! + 1. \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (1)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> </a> The <em>sunflower conjecture</em> asserts in fact that the upper bound can be improved to <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathrm%7BSun%7D%28k%2Cr%29+%5Cleq+O%281%29%5Ek+r%5Ek%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\mathrm{Sun}(k,r) \\leq O(1)^k r^k}\" title=\"{\\mathrm{Sun}(k,r) \\leq O(1)^k r^k}\" class=\"latex\" />. This remains open at present despite much effort (including a <a href=\"https://polymathprojects.org/tag/polymath10/\">Polymath project</a>); after a long series of improvements to the upper bound, the best general bound known currently is <a name=\"rao\"><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cmathrm%7BSun%7D%28k%2Cr%29+%5Cleq+O%28+r+%5Clog%28kr%29+%29%5Ek+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%282%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\mathrm{Sun}(k,r) \\leq O( r \\log(kr) )^k \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (2)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\mathrm{Sun}(k,r) \\leq O( r \\log(kr) )^k \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (2)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> </a> for all <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%2Cr+%5Cgeq+2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k,r \\geq 2}\" title=\"{k,r \\geq 2}\" class=\"latex\" />, established in 2019 <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/1909.04774\">by Rao</a> (building upon a recent breakthrough a month previously <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/1908.08483\">of Alweiss, Lovett, Wu, and Zhang</a>). Here we remove the easy cases <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%3D1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k=1}\" title=\"{k=1}\" class=\"latex\" /> or <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Br%3D1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{r=1}\" title=\"{r=1}\" class=\"latex\" /> in order to make the logarithmic factor <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Clog%28kr%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\log(kr)}\" title=\"{\\log(kr)}\" class=\"latex\" /> a little cleaner. </p>\n<p> Rao’s argument used the Shannon noiseless coding theorem. It turns out that the argument can be arranged in the very slightly different language of Shannon entropy, and I would like to present it here. The argument proceeds by locating the core and petals of the sunflower separately (this strategy is also followed in Alweiss-Lovett-Wu-Zhang). In both cases the following definition will be key. In this post all random variables, such as random sets, will be understood to be discrete random variables taking values in a finite range. We always use boldface symbols to denote random variables, and non-boldface for deterministic quantities. </p>\n<p> \n <blockquote>\n  <b>Definition 1 (Spread set)</b> Let \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BR+%3E+1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{R > 1}\" title=\"{R > 1}\" class=\"latex\" />. A random set \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+A%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf A}}\" title=\"{{\\bf A}}\" class=\"latex\" /> is said to be \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BR%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{R}\" title=\"{R}\" class=\"latex\" />-spread if one has \n  <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7B%5Cmathbb+P%7D%28+S+%5Csubset+%7B%5Cbf+A%7D%29+%5Cleq+R%5E%7B-%7CS%7C%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathbb P}( S \\subset {\\bf A}) \\leq R^{-|S|}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathbb P}( S \\subset {\\bf A}) \\leq R^{-|S|}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> for all sets \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{S}\" title=\"{S}\" class=\"latex\" />. A family \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28A_i%29_%7Bi+%5Cin+I%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(A_i)_{i \\in I}}\" title=\"{(A_i)_{i \\in I}}\" class=\"latex\" /> of sets is said to be \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BR%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{R}\" title=\"{R}\" class=\"latex\" />-spread if \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BI%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{I}\" title=\"{I}\" class=\"latex\" /> is non-empty and the random variable \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BA_%7B%5Cbf+i%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{A_{\\bf i}}\" title=\"{A_{\\bf i}}\" class=\"latex\" /> is \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BR%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{R}\" title=\"{R}\" class=\"latex\" />-spread, where \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+i%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf i}}\" title=\"{{\\bf i}}\" class=\"latex\" /> is drawn uniformly from \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BI%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{I}\" title=\"{I}\" class=\"latex\" />. \n </blockquote> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> The core can then be selected greedily in such a way that the remainder of a family becomes spread: </p>\n<p> \n <blockquote>\n  <b>Lemma 2 (Locating the core)</b> \n  <a name=\"core\"></a> Let \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28A_i%29_%7Bi+%5Cin+I%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(A_i)_{i \\in I}}\" title=\"{(A_i)_{i \\in I}}\" class=\"latex\" /> be a family of subsets of a finite set \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BX%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{X}\" title=\"{X}\" class=\"latex\" />, each of cardinality at most \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k}\" title=\"{k}\" class=\"latex\" />, and let \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BR+%3E+1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{R > 1}\" title=\"{R > 1}\" class=\"latex\" />. Then there exists a “core” set \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS_0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{S_0}\" title=\"{S_0}\" class=\"latex\" /> of cardinality at most \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k}\" title=\"{k}\" class=\"latex\" /> such that the set \n  <a name=\"j-fam\"><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++J+%3A%3D+%5C%7B+i+%5Cin+I%3A+S_0+%5Csubset+A_i+%5C%7D+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%283%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  J := \\{ i \\in I: S_0 \\subset A_i \\} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (3)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  J := \\{ i \\in I: S_0 \\subset A_i \\} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (3)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> </a> has cardinality at least \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BR%5E%7B-%7CS_0%7C%7D+%7CI%7C%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{R^{-|S_0|} |I|}\" title=\"{R^{-|S_0|} |I|}\" class=\"latex\" />, and such that the family \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28A_j+%5Cbackslash+S_0%29_%7Bj+%5Cin+J%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(A_j \\backslash S_0)_{j \\in J}}\" title=\"{(A_j \\backslash S_0)_{j \\in J}}\" class=\"latex\" /> is \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BR%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{R}\" title=\"{R}\" class=\"latex\" />-spread. Furthermore, if \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7CI%7C+%3E+R%5Ek%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{|I| > R^k}\" title=\"{|I| > R^k}\" class=\"latex\" /> and the \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BA_i%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{A_i}\" title=\"{A_i}\" class=\"latex\" /> are distinct, then \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7CS_0%7C+%3C+k%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{|S_0| < k}\" title=\"{|S_0| < k}\" class=\"latex\" />. \n </blockquote> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> <em>Proof:</em> We may assume <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BI%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{I}\" title=\"{I}\" class=\"latex\" /> is non-empty, as the claim is trivial otherwise. For any <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS+%5Csubset+X%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{S \\subset X}\" title=\"{S \\subset X}\" class=\"latex\" />, define the quantity </p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++Q%28S%29+%3A%3D+R%5E%7B%7CS%7C%7D+%7C%5C%7B+i+%5Cin+I%3A+S+%5Csubset+A_i%5C%7D%7C%2C&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  Q(S) := R^{|S|} |\\{ i \\in I: S \\subset A_i\\}|,\" title=\"\\displaystyle  Q(S) := R^{|S|} |\\{ i \\in I: S \\subset A_i\\}|,\" class=\"latex\" /></p> and let \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS_0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{S_0}\" title=\"{S_0}\" class=\"latex\" /> be a subset of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BX%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{X}\" title=\"{X}\" class=\"latex\" /> that maximizes \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BQ%28S_0%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{Q(S_0)}\" title=\"{Q(S_0)}\" class=\"latex\" />. Since \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BQ%28%5Cemptyset%29+%3D+%7CI%7C+%3E+0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{Q(\\emptyset) = |I| > 0}\" title=\"{Q(\\emptyset) = |I| > 0}\" class=\"latex\" /> and \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BQ%28S%29%3D0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{Q(S)=0}\" title=\"{Q(S)=0}\" class=\"latex\" /> when \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7CS%7C+%3Ek%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{|S| >k}\" title=\"{|S| >k}\" class=\"latex\" />, we see that \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B0+%5Cleq+%7CS_0%7C+%5Cleq+K%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{0 \\leq |S_0| \\leq K}\" title=\"{0 \\leq |S_0| \\leq K}\" class=\"latex\" />. If the \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BA_i%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{A_i}\" title=\"{A_i}\" class=\"latex\" /> are distinct and \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7CI%7C+%3E+R%5Ek%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{|I| > R^k}\" title=\"{|I| > R^k}\" class=\"latex\" />, then we also have \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BQ%28S%29+%5Cleq+R%5Ek+%3C+%7CI%7C+%3D+Q%28%5Cemptyset%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{Q(S) \\leq R^k < |I| = Q(\\emptyset)}\" title=\"{Q(S) \\leq R^k < |I| = Q(\\emptyset)}\" class=\"latex\" /> when \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7CS%7C%3Dk%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{|S|=k}\" title=\"{|S|=k}\" class=\"latex\" />, thus in this case we have \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7CS_0%7C+%3C+k%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{|S_0| < k}\" title=\"{|S_0| < k}\" class=\"latex\" />. \n<p> Let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BJ%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{J}\" title=\"{J}\" class=\"latex\" /> be the set <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11852#j-fam\">(3)</a>. Since <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BQ%28S_0%29+%5Cgeq+Q%28%5Cemptyset%29%3E0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{Q(S_0) \\geq Q(\\emptyset)>0}\" title=\"{Q(S_0) \\geq Q(\\emptyset)>0}\" class=\"latex\" />, <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BJ%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{J}\" title=\"{J}\" class=\"latex\" /> is non-empty. It remains to check that the family <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28A_j+%5Cbackslash+S_0%29_%7Bj+%5Cin+J%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(A_j \\backslash S_0)_{j \\in J}}\" title=\"{(A_j \\backslash S_0)_{j \\in J}}\" class=\"latex\" /> is <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BR%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{R}\" title=\"{R}\" class=\"latex\" />-spread. But for any <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS+%5Csubset+X%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{S \\subset X}\" title=\"{S \\subset X}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+j%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf j}}\" title=\"{{\\bf j}}\" class=\"latex\" /> drawn uniformly at random from <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BJ%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{J}\" title=\"{J}\" class=\"latex\" /> one has </p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7B%5Cmathbb+P%7D%28+S+%5Csubset+A_%7B%5Cbf+j%7D+%5Cbackslash+S_0+%29+%3D+%5Cfrac%7B%7C%5C%7B+i+%5Cin+I%3A+S_0+%5Ccup+S+%5Csubset+A_i%5C%7D%7C%7D%7B%7C%5C%7B+i+%5Cin+I%3A+S_0+%5Csubset+A_i%5C%7D%7C%7D+%3D+R%5E%7B%7CS_0%7C-%7CS_0+%5Ccup+S%7C%7D+%5Cfrac%7BQ%28S%29%7D%7BQ%28S_0%29%7D.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathbb P}( S \\subset A_{\\bf j} \\backslash S_0 ) = \\frac{|\\{ i \\in I: S_0 \\cup S \\subset A_i\\}|}{|\\{ i \\in I: S_0 \\subset A_i\\}|} = R^{|S_0|-|S_0 \\cup S|} \\frac{Q(S)}{Q(S_0)}.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathbb P}( S \\subset A_{\\bf j} \\backslash S_0 ) = \\frac{|\\{ i \\in I: S_0 \\cup S \\subset A_i\\}|}{|\\{ i \\in I: S_0 \\subset A_i\\}|} = R^{|S_0|-|S_0 \\cup S|} \\frac{Q(S)}{Q(S_0)}.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> Since \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BQ%28S%29+%5Cleq+Q%28S_0%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{Q(S) \\leq Q(S_0)}\" title=\"{Q(S) \\leq Q(S_0)}\" class=\"latex\" /> and \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7CS_0%7C-%7CS_0+%5Ccup+S%7C+%5Cgeq+-+%7CS%7C%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{|S_0|-|S_0 \\cup S| \\geq - |S|}\" title=\"{|S_0|-|S_0 \\cup S| \\geq - |S|}\" class=\"latex\" />, we obtain the claim \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5CBox&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\Box\" title=\"\\Box\" class=\"latex\" /> \n<p> In view of the above lemma, the bound <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11852#rao\">(2)</a> will then follow from </p>\n<p> \n <blockquote>\n  <b>Proposition 3 (Locating the petals)</b> \n  <a name=\"petals\"></a> Let \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Br%2C+k+%5Cgeq+2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{r, k \\geq 2}\" title=\"{r, k \\geq 2}\" class=\"latex\" /> be natural numbers, and suppose that \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BR+%5Cgeq+C+r+%5Clog%28kr%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{R \\geq C r \\log(kr)}\" title=\"{R \\geq C r \\log(kr)}\" class=\"latex\" /> for a sufficiently large constant \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BC%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{C}\" title=\"{C}\" class=\"latex\" />. Let \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28A_i%29_%7Bi+%5Cin+I%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(A_i)_{i \\in I}}\" title=\"{(A_i)_{i \\in I}}\" class=\"latex\" /> be a finite family of subsets of a finite set \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BX%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{X}\" title=\"{X}\" class=\"latex\" />, each of cardinality at most \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k}\" title=\"{k}\" class=\"latex\" /> which is \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BR%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{R}\" title=\"{R}\" class=\"latex\" />-spread. Then there exist \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bi_1%2C%5Cdots%2Ci_r+%5Cin+I%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{i_1,\\dots,i_r \\in I}\" title=\"{i_1,\\dots,i_r \\in I}\" class=\"latex\" /> such that \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BA_%7Bi_1%7D%2C%5Cdots%2CA_%7Bi_r%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{A_{i_1},\\dots,A_{i_r}}\" title=\"{A_{i_1},\\dots,A_{i_r}}\" class=\"latex\" /> is disjoint. \n </blockquote> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> Indeed, to prove <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11852#rao\">(2)</a>, we assume that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28A_i%29_%7Bi+%5Cin+I%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(A_i)_{i \\in I}}\" title=\"{(A_i)_{i \\in I}}\" class=\"latex\" /> is a family of sets of cardinality greater than <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BR%5Ek%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{R^k}\" title=\"{R^k}\" class=\"latex\" /> for some <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BR+%5Cgeq+Cr+%5Clog%28kr%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{R \\geq Cr \\log(kr)}\" title=\"{R \\geq Cr \\log(kr)}\" class=\"latex\" />; by discarding redundant elements and sets we may assume that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BI%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{I}\" title=\"{I}\" class=\"latex\" /> is finite and that all the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BA_i%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{A_i}\" title=\"{A_i}\" class=\"latex\" /> are contained in a common finite set <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BX%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{X}\" title=\"{X}\" class=\"latex\" />. Apply Lemma <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11852#core\">2</a> to find a set <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS_0+%5Csubset+X%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{S_0 \\subset X}\" title=\"{S_0 \\subset X}\" class=\"latex\" /> of cardinality <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7CS_0%7C+%3C+k%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{|S_0| < k}\" title=\"{|S_0| < k}\" class=\"latex\" /> such that the family <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28A_j+%5Cbackslash+S_0%29_%7Bj+%5Cin+J%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(A_j \\backslash S_0)_{j \\in J}}\" title=\"{(A_j \\backslash S_0)_{j \\in J}}\" class=\"latex\" /> is <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BR%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{R}\" title=\"{R}\" class=\"latex\" />-spread. By Proposition <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11852#petals\">3</a> we can find <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bj_1%2C%5Cdots%2Cj_r+%5Cin+J%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{j_1,\\dots,j_r \\in J}\" title=\"{j_1,\\dots,j_r \\in J}\" class=\"latex\" /> such that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BA_%7Bj_1%7D+%5Cbackslash+S_0%2C%5Cdots%2CA_%7Bj_r%7D+%5Cbackslash+S_0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{A_{j_1} \\backslash S_0,\\dots,A_{j_r} \\backslash S_0}\" title=\"{A_{j_1} \\backslash S_0,\\dots,A_{j_r} \\backslash S_0}\" class=\"latex\" /> are disjoint; since these sets have cardinality <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk+-+%7CS_0%7C+%3E+0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k - |S_0| > 0}\" title=\"{k - |S_0| > 0}\" class=\"latex\" />, this implies that the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bj_1%2C%5Cdots%2Cj_r%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{j_1,\\dots,j_r}\" title=\"{j_1,\\dots,j_r}\" class=\"latex\" /> are distinct. Hence <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BA_%7Bj_1%7D%2C%5Cdots%2CA_%7Bj_r%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{A_{j_1},\\dots,A_{j_r}}\" title=\"{A_{j_1},\\dots,A_{j_r}}\" class=\"latex\" /> form a sunflower as required. </p>\n<p> \n <blockquote>\n  <b>Remark 4</b> Proposition \n  <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11852#petals\">3</a> is easy to prove if we strengthen the condition on \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BR%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{R}\" title=\"{R}\" class=\"latex\" /> to \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BR+%3E+k%28r-1%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{R > k(r-1)}\" title=\"{R > k(r-1)}\" class=\"latex\" />. In this case, we have \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathop%7B%5Cbf+P%7D_%7Bi+%5Cin+I%7D%28+x+%5Cin+A_i%29+%3C+1%2Fk%28r-1%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\mathop{\\bf P}_{i \\in I}( x \\in A_i) < 1/k(r-1)}\" title=\"{\\mathop{\\bf P}_{i \\in I}( x \\in A_i) < 1/k(r-1)}\" class=\"latex\" /> for every \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx+%5Cin+X%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x \\in X}\" title=\"{x \\in X}\" class=\"latex\" />, hence by the union bound we see that for any \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bi_1%2C%5Cdots%2Ci_j+%5Cin+I%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{i_1,\\dots,i_j \\in I}\" title=\"{i_1,\\dots,i_j \\in I}\" class=\"latex\" /> with \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bj+%5Cleq+r-1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{j \\leq r-1}\" title=\"{j \\leq r-1}\" class=\"latex\" /> there exists \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bi_%7Bj%2B1%7D+%5Cin+I%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{i_{j+1} \\in I}\" title=\"{i_{j+1} \\in I}\" class=\"latex\" /> such that \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BA_%7Bi_%7Bj%2B1%7D%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{A_{i_{j+1}}}\" title=\"{A_{i_{j+1}}}\" class=\"latex\" /> is disjoint from the set \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BA_%7Bi_1%7D+%5Ccup+%5Cdots+%5Ccup+A_%7Bi_j%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{A_{i_1} \\cup \\dots \\cup A_{i_j}}\" title=\"{A_{i_1} \\cup \\dots \\cup A_{i_j}}\" class=\"latex\" />, which has cardinality at most \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%28r-1%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k(r-1)}\" title=\"{k(r-1)}\" class=\"latex\" />. Iterating this, we obtain the conclusion of Proposition \n  <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11852#petals\">3</a> in this case. This recovers a bound of the form \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathrm%7BSun%7D%28k%2Cr%29+%5Cleq+%28k%28r-1%29%29%5Ek%2B1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\mathrm{Sun}(k,r) \\leq (k(r-1))^k+1}\" title=\"{\\mathrm{Sun}(k,r) \\leq (k(r-1))^k+1}\" class=\"latex\" />, and by pursuing this idea a little further one can recover the original upper bound \n  <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11852#ease\">(1)</a> of Erdös and Rado. \n </blockquote> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> It remains to prove Proposition <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11852#petals\">3</a>. In fact we can locate the petals one at a time, placing each petal inside a random set. </p>\n<p> \n <blockquote>\n  <b>Proposition 5 (Locating a single petal)</b> \n  <a name=\"petal-single\"></a> Let the notation and hypotheses be as in Proposition \n  <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11852#petals\">3</a>. Let \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+V%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf V}}\" title=\"{{\\bf V}}\" class=\"latex\" /> be a random subset of \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BX%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{X}\" title=\"{X}\" class=\"latex\" />, such that each \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx+%5Cin+X%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x \\in X}\" title=\"{x \\in X}\" class=\"latex\" /> lies in \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+V%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf V}}\" title=\"{{\\bf V}}\" class=\"latex\" /> with an independent probability of \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1%2Fr%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1/r}\" title=\"{1/r}\" class=\"latex\" />. Then with probability greater than \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1-1%2Fr%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1-1/r}\" title=\"{1-1/r}\" class=\"latex\" />, \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+V%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf V}}\" title=\"{{\\bf V}}\" class=\"latex\" /> contains one of the \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BA_i%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{A_i}\" title=\"{A_i}\" class=\"latex\" />. \n </blockquote> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> To see that Proposition <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11852#petal-single\">5</a> implies Proposition <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11852#petals\">3</a>, we randomly partition <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BX%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{X}\" title=\"{X}\" class=\"latex\" /> into <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+V%7D_1+%5Ccup+%5Cdots+%5Ccup+%7B%5Cbf+V%7D_r%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf V}_1 \\cup \\dots \\cup {\\bf V}_r}\" title=\"{{\\bf V}_1 \\cup \\dots \\cup {\\bf V}_r}\" class=\"latex\" /> by placing each <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx+%5Cin+X%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x \\in X}\" title=\"{x \\in X}\" class=\"latex\" /> into one of the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+V%7D_j%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf V}_j}\" title=\"{{\\bf V}_j}\" class=\"latex\" />, <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bj%3D1%2C%5Cdots%2Cr%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{j=1,\\dots,r}\" title=\"{j=1,\\dots,r}\" class=\"latex\" /> chosen uniformly and independently at random. By Proposition <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11852#petal-single\">5</a> and the union bound, we see that with positive probability, it is simultaneously true for all <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bj%3D1%2C%5Cdots%2Cr%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{j=1,\\dots,r}\" title=\"{j=1,\\dots,r}\" class=\"latex\" /> that each <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+V%7D_j%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf V}_j}\" title=\"{{\\bf V}_j}\" class=\"latex\" /> contains one of the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BA_i%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{A_i}\" title=\"{A_i}\" class=\"latex\" />. Selecting one such <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BA_i%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{A_i}\" title=\"{A_i}\" class=\"latex\" /> for each <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+V%7D_j%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf V}_j}\" title=\"{{\\bf V}_j}\" class=\"latex\" />, we obtain the required disjoint petals. </p>\n<p> We will prove Proposition <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11852#petal-single\">5</a> by gradually increasing the density of the random set and arranging the sets <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BA_i%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{A_i}\" title=\"{A_i}\" class=\"latex\" /> to get quickly absorbed by this random set. The key iteration step is </p>\n<p> \n <blockquote>\n  <b>Proposition 6 (Refinement inequality)</b> \n  <a name=\"Refinement\"></a> Let \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BR+%3E+1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{R > 1}\" title=\"{R > 1}\" class=\"latex\" /> and \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B0+%3C+%5Cdelta+%3C+1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{0 < \\delta < 1}\" title=\"{0 < \\delta < 1}\" class=\"latex\" />. Let \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+A%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf A}}\" title=\"{{\\bf A}}\" class=\"latex\" /> be a random subset of a finite set \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BX%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{X}\" title=\"{X}\" class=\"latex\" /> which is \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BR%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{R}\" title=\"{R}\" class=\"latex\" />-spread, and let \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+V%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf V}}\" title=\"{{\\bf V}}\" class=\"latex\" /> be a random subset of \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BX%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{X}\" title=\"{X}\" class=\"latex\" /> independent of \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+A%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf A}}\" title=\"{{\\bf A}}\" class=\"latex\" />, such that each \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx+%5Cin+X%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x \\in X}\" title=\"{x \\in X}\" class=\"latex\" /> lies in \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+V%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf V}}\" title=\"{{\\bf V}}\" class=\"latex\" /> with an independent probability of \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cdelta%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\delta}\" title=\"{\\delta}\" class=\"latex\" />. Then there exists another random subset \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+A%7D%27%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf A}'}\" title=\"{{\\bf A}'}\" class=\"latex\" /> of \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BX%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{X}\" title=\"{X}\" class=\"latex\" /> with the same distribution as \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+A%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf A}}\" title=\"{{\\bf A}}\" class=\"latex\" />, such that \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+A%7D%27+%5Cbackslash+%7B%5Cbf+V%7D+%5Csubset+%7B%5Cbf+A%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf A}' \\backslash {\\bf V} \\subset {\\bf A}}\" title=\"{{\\bf A}' \\backslash {\\bf V} \\subset {\\bf A}}\" class=\"latex\" /> and \n  <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D+%7C%7B%5Cbf+A%7D%27+%5Cbackslash+%7B%5Cbf+V%7D%7C+%5Cleq+%5Cfrac%7B5%7D%7B%5Clog%28R%5Cdelta%29%7D+%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D+%7C%7B%5Cbf+A%7D%7C.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathbb E} |{\\bf A}' \\backslash {\\bf V}| \\leq \\frac{5}{\\log(R\\delta)} {\\mathbb E} |{\\bf A}|.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathbb E} |{\\bf A}' \\backslash {\\bf V}| \\leq \\frac{5}{\\log(R\\delta)} {\\mathbb E} |{\\bf A}|.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n </blockquote> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> Note that a direct application of the first moment method gives only the bound </p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D+%7C%7B%5Cbf+A%7D+%5Cbackslash+%7B%5Cbf+V%7D%7C+%5Cleq+%281-%5Cdelta%29+%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D+%7C%7B%5Cbf+A%7D%7C%2C&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathbb E} |{\\bf A} \\backslash {\\bf V}| \\leq (1-\\delta) {\\mathbb E} |{\\bf A}|,\" title=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathbb E} |{\\bf A} \\backslash {\\bf V}| \\leq (1-\\delta) {\\mathbb E} |{\\bf A}|,\" class=\"latex\" /></p> but the point is that by switching from \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+A%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf A}}\" title=\"{{\\bf A}}\" class=\"latex\" /> to an equivalent \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+A%7D%27%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf A}'}\" title=\"{{\\bf A}'}\" class=\"latex\" /> we can replace the \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1-%5Cdelta%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1-\\delta}\" title=\"{1-\\delta}\" class=\"latex\" /> factor by a quantity significantly smaller than \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1}\" title=\"{1}\" class=\"latex\" />. \n<p> One can iterate the above proposition, repeatedly replacing <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+A%7D%2C+X%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf A}, X}\" title=\"{{\\bf A}, X}\" class=\"latex\" /> with <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+A%7D%27+%5Cbackslash+%7B%5Cbf+V%7D%2C+X+%5Cbackslash+%7B%5Cbf+V%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf A}' \\backslash {\\bf V}, X \\backslash {\\bf V}}\" title=\"{{\\bf A}' \\backslash {\\bf V}, X \\backslash {\\bf V}}\" class=\"latex\" /> (noting that this preserves the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BR%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{R}\" title=\"{R}\" class=\"latex\" />-spread nature <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+A%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf A}}\" title=\"{{\\bf A}}\" class=\"latex\" />) to conclude </p>\n<p> \n <blockquote>\n  <b>Corollary 7 (Iterated refinement inequality)</b> \n  <a name=\"Refinement-2\"></a> Let \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BR+%3E+1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{R > 1}\" title=\"{R > 1}\" class=\"latex\" />, \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B0+%3C+%5Cdelta+%3C+1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{0 < \\delta < 1}\" title=\"{0 < \\delta < 1}\" class=\"latex\" />, and \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bm+%5Cgeq+1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{m \\geq 1}\" title=\"{m \\geq 1}\" class=\"latex\" />. Let \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+A%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf A}}\" title=\"{{\\bf A}}\" class=\"latex\" /> be a random subset of a finite set \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BX%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{X}\" title=\"{X}\" class=\"latex\" /> which is \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BR%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{R}\" title=\"{R}\" class=\"latex\" />-spread, and let \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+V%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf V}}\" title=\"{{\\bf V}}\" class=\"latex\" /> be a random subset of \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BX%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{X}\" title=\"{X}\" class=\"latex\" /> independent of \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+A%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf A}}\" title=\"{{\\bf A}}\" class=\"latex\" />, such that each \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx+%5Cin+X%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x \\in X}\" title=\"{x \\in X}\" class=\"latex\" /> lies in \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+V%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf V}}\" title=\"{{\\bf V}}\" class=\"latex\" /> with an independent probability of \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1-%281-%5Cdelta%29%5Em%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1-(1-\\delta)^m}\" title=\"{1-(1-\\delta)^m}\" class=\"latex\" />. Then there exists another random subset \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+A%7D%27%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf A}'}\" title=\"{{\\bf A}'}\" class=\"latex\" /> of \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BX%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{X}\" title=\"{X}\" class=\"latex\" /> with the same distribution as \n  <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+A%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf A}}\" title=\"{{\\bf A}}\" class=\"latex\" />, such that \n  <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D+%7C%7B%5Cbf+A%7D%27+%5Cbackslash+%7B%5Cbf+V%7D%7C+%5Cleq+%28%5Cfrac%7B5%7D%7B%5Clog%28R%5Cdelta%29%7D%29%5Em+%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D+%7C%7B%5Cbf+A%7D%7C.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathbb E} |{\\bf A}' \\backslash {\\bf V}| \\leq (\\frac{5}{\\log(R\\delta)})^m {\\mathbb E} |{\\bf A}|.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathbb E} |{\\bf A}' \\backslash {\\bf V}| \\leq (\\frac{5}{\\log(R\\delta)})^m {\\mathbb E} |{\\bf A}|.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n </blockquote> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> Now we can prove Proposition <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11852#petal-single\">5</a>. Let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bm%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{m}\" title=\"{m}\" class=\"latex\" /> be chosen shortly. Applying Corollary <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11852#Refinement-2\">7</a> with <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+A%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf A}}\" title=\"{{\\bf A}}\" class=\"latex\" /> drawn uniformly at random from the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28A_i%29_%7Bi+%5Cin+I%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(A_i)_{i \\in I}}\" title=\"{(A_i)_{i \\in I}}\" class=\"latex\" />, and setting <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1-%281-%5Cdelta%29%5Em+%3D+1%2Fr%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1-(1-\\delta)^m = 1/r}\" title=\"{1-(1-\\delta)^m = 1/r}\" class=\"latex\" />, or equivalently <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cdelta+%3D+1+-+%281+-+1%2Fr%29%5E%7B1%2Fm%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\delta = 1 - (1 - 1/r)^{1/m}}\" title=\"{\\delta = 1 - (1 - 1/r)^{1/m}}\" class=\"latex\" />, we have </p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D+%7C%7B%5Cbf+A%7D%27+%5Cbackslash+%7B%5Cbf+V%7D%7C+%5Cleq+%28%5Cfrac%7B5%7D%7B%5Clog%28R%5Cdelta%29%7D%29%5Em+k.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathbb E} |{\\bf A}' \\backslash {\\bf V}| \\leq (\\frac{5}{\\log(R\\delta)})^m k.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathbb E} |{\\bf A}' \\backslash {\\bf V}| \\leq (\\frac{5}{\\log(R\\delta)})^m k.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> In particular, if we set \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bm+%3D+%5Clceil+%5Clog+kr+%5Crceil%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{m = \\lceil \\log kr \\rceil}\" title=\"{m = \\lceil \\log kr \\rceil}\" class=\"latex\" />, so that \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cdelta+%5Csim+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7Br+%5Clog+kr%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\delta \\sim \\frac{1}{r \\log kr}}\" title=\"{\\delta \\sim \\frac{1}{r \\log kr}}\" class=\"latex\" />, then by choice of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BR%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{R}\" title=\"{R}\" class=\"latex\" /> we have \n<img
