alt=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathbb H}( A_{\\bf n} \\backslash {\\bf W} | {\\bf n}, A_{\\bf n} \\cap A_{{\\bf n}'}, {\\bf n}', {\\bf W}' ) \\leq {\\mathbb H}( A_{\\bf n} \\backslash {\\bf W} | A_{{\\bf n}} ) \\leq {\\mathbb E} |A_{\\bf n}|.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathbb H}( A_{\\bf n} \\backslash {\\bf W} | {\\bf n}, A_{\\bf n} \\cap A_{{\\bf n}'}, {\\bf n}', {\\bf W}' ) \\leq {\\mathbb H}( A_{\\bf n} \\backslash {\\bf W} | A_{{\\bf n}} ) \\leq {\\mathbb E} |A_{\\bf n}|.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> Putting all this together, we conclude \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7B%5Cmathbb+H%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+n%7D%29+%5Cleq+%7B%5Cmathbb+H%7D%28+%7B%5Cbf+n%7D+%7C+A_%7B%5Cbf+n%7D+%5Ccap+A_%7B%7B%5Cbf+n%7D%27%7D%2C+%7B%5Cbf+n%7D%27%2C+%7B%5Cbf+W%7D%27+%29+%2B+%284+%2B+%5Clog+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B%5Cdelta%7D%29+%7B%5Cbf+E%7D+%7CA_%7B%5Cbf+n%7D%7C+%2B+o%281%29.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathbb H}({\\bf n}) \\leq {\\mathbb H}( {\\bf n} | A_{\\bf n} \\cap A_{{\\bf n}'}, {\\bf n}', {\\bf W}' ) + (4 + \\log \\frac{1}{\\delta}) {\\bf E} |A_{\\bf n}| + o(1).\" title=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathbb H}({\\bf n}) \\leq {\\mathbb H}( {\\bf n} | A_{\\bf n} \\cap A_{{\\bf n}'}, {\\bf n}', {\\bf W}' ) + (4 + \\log \\frac{1}{\\delta}) {\\bf E} |A_{\\bf n}| + o(1).\" class=\"latex\" /></p> If we apply Lemma \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11852#spread\">10</a>(ii) right away we will get the estimate \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%28%5Clog+R%29+%7B%5Cbf+E%7D+%7CA_%7B%5Cbf+n%7D+%5Ccap+A_%7B%7B%5Cbf+n%7D%27%7D%7C+%5Cleq+%284+%2B+%5Clog+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B%5Cdelta%7D%29+%7B%5Cbf+E%7D+%7CA_%7B%5Cbf+n%7D%7C+%2B+o%281%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  (\\log R) {\\bf E} |A_{\\bf n} \\cap A_{{\\bf n}'}| \\leq (4 + \\log \\frac{1}{\\delta}) {\\bf E} |A_{\\bf n}| + o(1)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  (\\log R) {\\bf E} |A_{\\bf n} \\cap A_{{\\bf n}'}| \\leq (4 + \\log \\frac{1}{\\delta}) {\\bf E} |A_{\\bf n}| + o(1)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> which is a bound resembling \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11852#gain-2\">(12)</a>, but the dependence on the parameters \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cdelta%2C+R%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\delta, R}\" title=\"{\\delta, R}\" class=\"latex\" /> are too weak. To do better we return to the relative product construction to decouple some of the random variables here. From the tuple \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28%7B%5Cbf+n%7D%2C+%7B%5Cbf+W%7D%2C+%7B%5Cbf+n%7D%27%2C+%7B%5Cbf+W%7D%27%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{({\\bf n}, {\\bf W}, {\\bf n}', {\\bf W}')}\" title=\"{({\\bf n}, {\\bf W}, {\\bf n}', {\\bf W}')}\" class=\"latex\" /> we can form the random variable \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28A_%7B%5Cbf+n%7D+%5Ccap+A_%7B%7B%5Cbf+n%7D%27%7D%2C+A_%7B%7B%5Cbf+n%7D%7D+%5Ccup+%7B%5Cbf+W%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(A_{\\bf n} \\cap A_{{\\bf n}'}, A_{{\\bf n}} \\cup {\\bf W})}\" title=\"{(A_{\\bf n} \\cap A_{{\\bf n}'}, A_{{\\bf n}} \\cup {\\bf W})}\" class=\"latex\" />, then form a conditionally independent copy \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28%7B%5Cbf+m%7D%2C+%7B%5Cbf+U%7D%2C+%7B%5Cbf+m%7D%27%2C+%7B%5Cbf+U%7D%27%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{({\\bf m}, {\\bf U}, {\\bf m}', {\\bf U}')}\" title=\"{({\\bf m}, {\\bf U}, {\\bf m}', {\\bf U}')}\" class=\"latex\" /> of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28%7B%5Cbf+n%7D%2C+%7B%5Cbf+W%7D%2C+%7B%5Cbf+n%7D%27%2C+%7B%5Cbf+W%7D%27%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{({\\bf n}, {\\bf W}, {\\bf n}', {\\bf W}')}\" title=\"{({\\bf n}, {\\bf W}, {\\bf n}', {\\bf W}')}\" class=\"latex\" /> subject to the constraints \n<a name=\"akon\"><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++A_%7B%5Cbf+n%7D+%5Ccap+A_%7B%7B%5Cbf+n%7D%27%7D+%3D+A_%7B%5Cbf+m%7D+%5Ccap+A_%7B%7B%5Cbf+m%7D%27%7D%3B+%5Cquad+A_%7B%5Cbf+n%7D+%5Ccup+%7B%5Cbf+W%7D+%3D+A_%7B%5Cbf+m%7D+%5Ccup+%7B%5Cbf+U%7D.+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%2813%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  A_{\\bf n} \\cap A_{{\\bf n}'} = A_{\\bf m} \\cap A_{{\\bf m}'}; \\quad A_{\\bf n} \\cup {\\bf W} = A_{\\bf m} \\cup {\\bf U}. \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (13)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  A_{\\bf n} \\cap A_{{\\bf n}'} = A_{\\bf m} \\cap A_{{\\bf m}'}; \\quad A_{\\bf n} \\cup {\\bf W} = A_{\\bf m} \\cup {\\bf U}. \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (13)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> </a> From \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11852#aw\">(11)</a> and Lemma \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11852#basic\">8</a>(i) we then have \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7B%5Cmathbb+H%7D%28+%7B%5Cbf+n%7D+%7C+A_%7B%5Cbf+n%7D+%5Ccap+A_%7B%7B%5Cbf+n%7D%27%7D%2C+%7B%5Cbf+n%7D%27%2C+%7B%5Cbf+W%7D%27+%29+%5Cleq+%7B%5Cmathbb+H%7D%28+%7B%5Cbf+n%7D+%7C+A_%7B%5Cbf+n%7D+%5Ccap+A_%7B%7B%5Cbf+n%7D%27%7D%2C+A_%7B%5Cbf+n%7D+%5Ccup+%7B%5Cbf+W%7D+%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathbb H}( {\\bf n} | A_{\\bf n} \\cap A_{{\\bf n}'}, {\\bf n}', {\\bf W}' ) \\leq {\\mathbb H}( {\\bf n} | A_{\\bf n} \\cap A_{{\\bf n}'}, A_{\\bf n} \\cup {\\bf W} )\" title=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathbb H}( {\\bf n} | A_{\\bf n} \\cap A_{{\\bf n}'}, {\\bf n}', {\\bf W}' ) \\leq {\\mathbb H}( {\\bf n} | A_{\\bf n} \\cap A_{{\\bf n}'}, A_{\\bf n} \\cup {\\bf W} )\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+%3D+%7B%5Cmathbb+H%7D%28+%7B%5Cbf+m%7D+%7C+A_%7B%5Cbf+n%7D+%5Ccap+A_%7B%7B%5Cbf+n%7D%27%7D%2C+A_%7B%5Cbf+n%7D+%5Ccup+%7B%5Cbf+W%7D+%29.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle = {\\mathbb H}( {\\bf m} | A_{\\bf n} \\cap A_{{\\bf n}'}, A_{\\bf n} \\cup {\\bf W} ).\" title=\"\\displaystyle = {\\mathbb H}( {\\bf m} | A_{\\bf n} \\cap A_{{\\bf n}'}, A_{\\bf n} \\cup {\\bf W} ).\" class=\"latex\" /></p> The point is that \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+m%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf m}}\" title=\"{{\\bf m}}\" class=\"latex\" /> is now conditionally independent of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+n%7D%2C+%7B%5Cbf+W%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf n}, {\\bf W}}\" title=\"{{\\bf n}, {\\bf W}}\" class=\"latex\" /> relative to \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BA_%7B%5Cbf+n%7D+%5Ccap+A_%7B%7B%5Cbf+n%7D%27%7D%2C+A_%7B%5Cbf+n%7D+%5Ccup+%7B%5Cbf+W%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{A_{\\bf n} \\cap A_{{\\bf n}'}, A_{\\bf n} \\cup {\\bf W}}\" title=\"{A_{\\bf n} \\cap A_{{\\bf n}'}, A_{\\bf n} \\cup {\\bf W}}\" class=\"latex\" />, so we can also rewrite the above conditional entropy as \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7B%5Cmathbb+H%7D%28+%7B%5Cbf+m%7D+%7C+A_%7B%5Cbf+n%7D+%5Ccap+A_%7B%7B%5Cbf+n%7D%27%7D%2C+A_%7B%5Cbf+n%7D+%5Ccup+%7B%5Cbf+W%7D%2C+%7B%5Cbf+n%7D%2C+%7B%5Cbf+W%7D+%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathbb H}( {\\bf m} | A_{\\bf n} \\cap A_{{\\bf n}'}, A_{\\bf n} \\cup {\\bf W}, {\\bf n}, {\\bf W} )\" title=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathbb H}( {\\bf m} | A_{\\bf n} \\cap A_{{\\bf n}'}, A_{\\bf n} \\cup {\\bf W}, {\\bf n}, {\\bf W} )\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%3D%7B%5Cmathbb+H%7D%28+%7B%5Cbf+m%7D+%7C+A_%7B%5Cbf+n%7D+%5Ccap+A_%7B%7B%5Cbf+n%7D%27%7D%2C+%7B%5Cbf+n%7D%2C+%7B%5Cbf+W%7D+%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  ={\\mathbb H}( {\\bf m} | A_{\\bf n} \\cap A_{{\\bf n}'}, {\\bf n}, {\\bf W} )\" title=\"\\displaystyle  ={\\mathbb H}( {\\bf m} | A_{\\bf n} \\cap A_{{\\bf n}'}, {\\bf n}, {\\bf W} )\" class=\"latex\" /></p> We now use the chain rule to disentangle the role of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+W%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf W}}\" title=\"{{\\bf W}}\" class=\"latex\" />, writing the previous as \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7B%5Cmathbb+H%7D%28+%7B%5Cbf+m%7D%2C+%7B%5Cbf+W%7D+%7C+A_%7B%5Cbf+n%7D+%5Ccap+A_%7B%7B%5Cbf+n%7D%27%7D%2C+%7B%5Cbf+n%7D+%29+-+%7B%5Cmathbb+H%7D%28+%7B%5Cbf+W%7D+%7C+A_%7B%5Cbf+n%7D+%5Ccap+A_%7B%7B%5Cbf+n%7D%27%7D%2C+%7B%5Cbf+n%7D+%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathbb H}( {\\bf m}, {\\bf W} | A_{\\bf n} \\cap A_{{\\bf n}'}, {\\bf n} ) - {\\mathbb H}( {\\bf W} | A_{\\bf n} \\cap A_{{\\bf n}'}, {\\bf n} )\" title=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathbb H}( {\\bf m}, {\\bf W} | A_{\\bf n} \\cap A_{{\\bf n}'}, {\\bf n} ) - {\\mathbb H}( {\\bf W} | A_{\\bf n} \\cap A_{{\\bf n}'}, {\\bf n} )\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%3D+%7B%5Cmathbb+H%7D%28+%7B%5Cbf+m%7D%2C+%7B%5Cbf+W%7D+%7C+A_%7B%5Cbf+n%7D+%5Ccap+A_%7B%7B%5Cbf+n%7D%27%7D%2C+%7B%5Cbf+n%7D+%29+-+%7B%5Cmathbb+H%7D%28+%7B%5Cbf+W%7D+%7C+%7B%5Cbf+n%7D+%29+&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  = {\\mathbb H}( {\\bf m}, {\\bf W} | A_{\\bf n} \\cap A_{{\\bf n}'}, {\\bf n} ) - {\\mathbb H}( {\\bf W} | {\\bf n} ) \" title=\"\\displaystyle  = {\\mathbb H}( {\\bf m}, {\\bf W} | A_{\\bf n} \\cap A_{{\\bf n}'}, {\\bf n} ) - {\\mathbb H}( {\\bf W} | {\\bf n} ) \" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+%2B+%7B%5Cmathbb+H%7D%28+A_%7B%5Cbf+n%7D+%5Ccap+A_%7B%7B%5Cbf+n%27%7D%7D+%7C+%7B%5Cbf+n%7D+%29+-+%7B%5Cmathbb+H%7D%28+A_%7B%5Cbf+n%7D+%5Ccap+A_%7B%7B%5Cbf+n%27%7D%7D+%7C+%7B%5Cbf+n%7D%2C+%7B%5Cbf+W%7D+%29.+&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle + {\\mathbb H}( A_{\\bf n} \\cap A_{{\\bf n'}} | {\\bf n} ) - {\\mathbb H}( A_{\\bf n} \\cap A_{{\\bf n'}} | {\\bf n}, {\\bf W} ). \" title=\"\\displaystyle + {\\mathbb H}( A_{\\bf n} \\cap A_{{\\bf n'}} | {\\bf n} ) - {\\mathbb H}( A_{\\bf n} \\cap A_{{\\bf n'}} | {\\bf n}, {\\bf W} ). \" class=\"latex\" /></p> From independence we have \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+%7B%5Cmathbb+H%7D%28+%7B%5Cbf+W%7D+%7C+%7B%5Cbf+n%7D+%29+%3D+%7B%5Cmathbb+H%7D%28+%7B%5Cbf+W%7D+%29+&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle {\\mathbb H}( {\\bf W} | {\\bf n} ) = {\\mathbb H}( {\\bf W} ) \" title=\"\\displaystyle {\\mathbb H}( {\\bf W} | {\\bf n} ) = {\\mathbb H}( {\\bf W} ) \" class=\"latex\" /></p> and from Lemma \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11852#small\">9</a>(i) we have \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7B%5Cmathbb+H%7D%28+A_%7B%5Cbf+n%7D+%5Ccap+A_%7B%7B%5Cbf+n%27%7D%7D+%7C+%7B%5Cbf+n%7D+%29+%5Cleq+%7B%5Cbf+E%7D+%7CA_%7B%5Cbf+n%7D%7C.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathbb H}( A_{\\bf n} \\cap A_{{\\bf n'}} | {\\bf n} ) \\leq {\\bf E} |A_{\\bf n}|.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathbb H}( A_{\\bf n} \\cap A_{{\\bf n'}} | {\\bf n} ) \\leq {\\bf E} |A_{\\bf n}|.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> We discard the negative term \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cmathbb+H%7D%28+A_%7B%5Cbf+n%7D+%5Ccap+A_%7B%7B%5Cbf+n%27%7D%7D+%7C+%7B%5Cbf+n%7D%2C+%7B%5Cbf+W%7D+%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\mathbb H}( A_{\\bf n} \\cap A_{{\\bf n'}} | {\\bf n}, {\\bf W} )}\" title=\"{{\\mathbb H}( A_{\\bf n} \\cap A_{{\\bf n'}} | {\\bf n}, {\\bf W} )}\" class=\"latex\" />. Putting all this together, we obtain \n<a name=\"hbfn\"><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7B%5Cmathbb+H%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+n%7D%29+%5Cleq+%7B%5Cmathbb+H%7D%28+%7B%5Cbf+m%7D%2C+%7B%5Cbf+W%7D+%7C+A_%7B%5Cbf+n%7D+%5Ccap+A_%7B%7B%5Cbf+n%7D%27%7D%2C+%7B%5Cbf+n%7D+%29+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%2814%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathbb H}({\\bf n}) \\leq {\\mathbb H}( {\\bf m}, {\\bf W} | A_{\\bf n} \\cap A_{{\\bf n}'}, {\\bf n} ) \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (14)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathbb H}({\\bf n}) \\leq {\\mathbb H}( {\\bf m}, {\\bf W} | A_{\\bf n} \\cap A_{{\\bf n}'}, {\\bf n} ) \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (14)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> </a> \n<p align=\"center\"><img alt=\"\\displaystyle  - {\\mathbb H}( {\\bf W} ) + (5 + \\log \\frac{1}{\\delta}) {\\bf E} |A_{\\bf n}| + o(1).\" title=\"\\displaystyle  - {\\mathbb H}( {\\bf W} ) + (5 + \\log \\frac{1}{\\delta}) {\\bf E} |A_{\\bf n}| + o(1).\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> Now, from the constraints <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11852#aw\">(11)</a>, <a A_{\\bf n} \\cap A_{{\\bf n}'} \\subset A_{{\\bf m}}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  A_{\\bf n} \\cap A_{{\\bf n}'} \\subset A_{{\\bf m}}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> and \n<p align=\"center\"><img A_{{\\bf n}'} \\backslash A_{\\bf n} \\subset {\\bf W}.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  A_{{\\bf n}'} \\backslash A_{\\bf n} \\subset {\\bf W}.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> Thus by Lemma \n<a alt=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathbb H}( {\\bf m}, {\\bf W} | A_{\\bf n} \\cap A_{{\\bf n}'}, {\\bf n} ) \\leq {\\mathbb H}( {\\bf m} | A_{\\bf n} \\cap A_{{\\bf n}'} ) + {\\mathbb H}( {\\bf W} | A_{{\\bf {\\mathbb H}( {\\bf W} | A_{{\\bf n}'} \\backslash A_{\\bf n} )\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\leq {\\mathbb H}({\\bf m}) - (\\log R) {\\mathbb E} |A_{\\bf n} \\cap A_{{\\bf n}'}| + {\\mathbb H}({\\bf W}) - \\log \\frac{1}{\\delta} {\\mathbb E} |A_{{\\bf n}'} \\backslash |A_{{\\bf n}'} \\backslash A_{\\bf n}| + o(1)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> which when inserted back into \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11852#hbfn\">(14)</a> using \n<img notes discusses aspects of one of the oldest questions in Fourier analysis, namely the nature of convergence of Fourier series. </p>\n<p> If <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%3A+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cbf+C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f: {\\bf R}/{\\bf Z} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" title=\"{f: {\\bf R}/{\\bf Z} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" class=\"latex\" /> is an absolutely integrable function, its Fourier coefficients <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Chat+f%3A+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cbf+C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\hat f: {\\bf Z} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" title=\"{\\hat f: {\\bf Z} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" class=\"latex\" /> are defined by the formula </p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Chat+f%28n%29+%3A%3D+%5Cint_%7B%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D+f%28x%29+e%5E%7B-2%5Cpi+i+nx%7D%5C+dx.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\hat f(n) := \\int_{{\\bf R}/{\\bf Z}} f(x) e^{-2\\pi i nx}\\ dx.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\hat f(n) := \\int_{{\\bf R}/{\\bf Z}} f(x) e^{-2\\pi i nx}\\ dx.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> If \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f}\" title=\"{f}\" class=\"latex\" /> is smooth, then the Fourier coefficients \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Chat+f%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\hat f}\" title=\"{\\hat f}\" class=\"latex\" /> are absolutely summable, and we have the Fourier inversion formula \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++f%28x%29+%3D+%5Csum_%7Bn+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D+%5Chat+f%28n%29+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+nx%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  f(x) = \\sum_{n \\in {\\bf Z}} \\hat f(n) e^{2\\pi i nx}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  f(x) = \\sum_{n \\in {\\bf Z}} \\hat f(n) e^{2\\pi i nx}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> where the series here is uniformly convergent. In particular, if we define the partial summation operators \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++S_N+f%28x%29+%3A%3D+%5Csum_%7B%7Cn%7C+%5Cleq+N%7D+%5Chat+f%28n%29+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+nx%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  S_N f(x) := \\sum_{|n| \\leq N} \\hat f(n) e^{2\\pi i nx}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  S_N f(x) := \\sum_{|n| \\leq N} \\hat f(n) e^{2\\pi i nx}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> then \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS_N+f%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{S_N f}\" title=\"{S_N f}\" class=\"latex\" /> converges uniformly to \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f}\" title=\"{f}\" class=\"latex\" /> when \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f}\" title=\"{f}\" class=\"latex\" /> is smooth. \n<p> What if <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f}\" title=\"{f}\" class=\"latex\" /> is not smooth, but merely lies in an <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" title=\"{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" class=\"latex\" /> class for some <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1+%5Cleq+p+%5Cleq+%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1 \\leq p \\leq \\infty}\" title=\"{1 \\leq p \\leq \\infty}\" class=\"latex\" />? The Fourier coefficients <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Chat+f%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\hat f}\" title=\"{\\hat f}\" class=\"latex\" /> remain well-defined, as do the partial summation operators <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS_N%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{S_N}\" title=\"{S_N}\" class=\"latex\" />. The question of convergence in norm is relatively easy to settle: </p>\n<p> </p>\n<blockquote>\n <b>Exercise 1</b> \n <ul> \n  <li>(i) If <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1+%3C+p+%3C+%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1 < p < \\infty}\" title=\"{1 < p < \\infty}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+L%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" title=\"{f \\in L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" class=\"latex\" />, show that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS_N+f%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{S_N f}\" title=\"{S_N f}\" class=\"latex\" /> converges in <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" title=\"{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" class=\"latex\" /> norm to <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f}\" title=\"{f}\" class=\"latex\" />. (<em>Hint:</em> first use the boundedness of the Hilbert transform to show that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS_N%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{S_N}\" title=\"{S_N}\" class=\"latex\" /> is bounded in <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" title=\"{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" class=\"latex\" /> uniformly in <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N}\" title=\"{N}\" class=\"latex\" />.) </li>\n  <li>(ii) If <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bp%3D1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{p=1}\" title=\"{p=1}\" class=\"latex\" /> or <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bp%3D%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{p=\\infty}\" title=\"{p=\\infty}\" class=\"latex\" />, show that there exists <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+L%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" title=\"{f \\in L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" class=\"latex\" /> such that the sequence <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS_N+f%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{S_N f}\" title=\"{S_N f}\" class=\"latex\" /> is unbounded in <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" title=\"{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" class=\"latex\" /> (so in particular it certainly does not converge in <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" title=\"{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" class=\"latex\" /> norm to <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f}\" title=\"{f}\" class=\"latex\" />. (<em>Hint:</em> first show that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS_N%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{S_N}\" title=\"{S_N}\" class=\"latex\" /> is not bounded in <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" title=\"{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" class=\"latex\" /> uniformly in <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N}\" title=\"{N}\" class=\"latex\" />, then apply the uniform boundedness principle in the contrapositive.) </li>\n </ul> \n</blockquote> \n<p></p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> The question of pointwise almost everywhere convergence turned out to be a <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convergence_of_Fourier_series\">significantly harder problem</a>: </p>\n<p> </p>\n<blockquote>\n <b>Theorem 2 (Pointwise almost everywhere convergence)</b> \n <a name=\"main\"></a> \n <ul> \n  <li>(i) (Kolmogorov, 1923) There exists <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+L%5E1%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in L^1({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" title=\"{f \\in L^1({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" class=\"latex\" /> such that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS_N+f%28x%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{S_N f(x)}\" title=\"{S_N f(x)}\" class=\"latex\" /> is unbounded in <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N}\" title=\"{N}\" class=\"latex\" /> for almost every <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x}\" title=\"{x}\" class=\"latex\" />. </li>\n  <li>(ii) (<a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=199631\">Carleson</a>, 1966; conjectured by Lusin, 1913) For every <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+L%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in L^2({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" title=\"{f \\in L^2({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" class=\"latex\" />, <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS_N+f%28x%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{S_N f(x)}\" title=\"{S_N f(x)}\" class=\"latex\" /> converges to <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%28x%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f(x)}\" title=\"{f(x)}\" class=\"latex\" /> as <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN+%5Crightarrow+%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N \\rightarrow \\infty}\" title=\"{N \\rightarrow \\infty}\" class=\"latex\" /> for almost every <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x}\" title=\"{x}\" class=\"latex\" />. </li>\n  <li>(iii) (<a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=238019\">Hunt</a>, 1967) For every <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1+%3C+p+%5Cleq+%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1 < p \\leq \\infty}\" title=\"{1 < p \\leq \\infty}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+L%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" title=\"{f \\in L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" class=\"latex\" />, <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS_N+f%28x%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{S_N f(x)}\" title=\"{S_N f(x)}\" class=\"latex\" /> converges to <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%28x%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f(x)}\" title=\"{f(x)}\" class=\"latex\" /> as <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN+%5Crightarrow+%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N \\rightarrow \\infty}\" title=\"{N \\rightarrow \\infty}\" class=\"latex\" /> for almost every <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x}\" title=\"{x}\" class=\"latex\" />. </li>\n </ul> \n</blockquote> \n<p></p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> Note from Hölder’s inequality that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BL%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{L^2({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" title=\"{L^2({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" class=\"latex\" /> contains <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" title=\"{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" class=\"latex\" /> for all <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bp%5Cgeq+2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{p\\geq 2}\" title=\"{p\\geq 2}\" class=\"latex\" />, so Carleson’s theorem covers the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bp+%5Cgeq+2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{p \\geq 2}\" title=\"{p \\geq 2}\" class=\"latex\" /> case of Hunt’s theorem. We remark that the precise threshold near <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BL%5E1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{L^1}\" title=\"{L^1}\" class=\"latex\" /> between Kolmogorov-type divergence results and Carleson-Hunt pointwise convergence results, in the category of Orlicz spaces, is still an active area of research; see <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/1408.4783\">this paper of Lie</a> for further discussion. </p>\n<p> Carleson’s theorem in particular was a surprisingly difficult result, lying just out of reach of classical methods (as we shall see later, the result is much easier if we smooth either the function <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f}\" title=\"{f}\" class=\"latex\" /> or the summation method <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS_N%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{S_N}\" title=\"{S_N}\" class=\"latex\" /> by a tiny bit). Nowadays we realise that the reason for this is that Carleson’s theorem essentially contains a <em>frequency modulation symmetry</em> in addition to the more familiar translation symmetry and dilation symmetry. This basically rules out the possibility of attacking Carleson’s theorem with tools such as Calderón-Zygmund theory or Littlewood-Paley theory, which respect the latter two symmetries but not the former. Instead, tools from “time-frequency analysis” that essentially respect all three symmetries should be employed. We will illustrate this by giving a relatively short proof of Carleson’s theorem due to <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=1783613\">Lacey and Thiele</a>. (There are other proofs of Carleson’s theorem, including Carleson’s original proof, its modification by Hunt, and a later <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=340926\">time-frequency proof by Fefferman</a>; see Remark <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#other\">18</a> below.) </p>\n<p> <span id=\"more-11764\"></span> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p align=\"center\"><b> — 1. Equivalent forms of almost everywhere convergence of Fourier series — </b></p> \n<p> A standard technique to prove almost everywhere convergence results is by first establishing a weak-type estimate of an associated maximal function. For instance, the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lebesgue_differentiation_theorem\">Lebesgue differentiation theorem</a> is usually established with the assistance of the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hardy%E2%80%93Littlewood_maximal_function\">Hardy-Littlewood maximal inequality</a>; see for instance <a href=\"https://terrytao.wordpress.com/2010/10/16/245a-notes-5-differentiation-theorems/\">this previous blog post</a>. A remarkable observation <a href=\"http://www.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=125392\">of Stein</a>, known as <a href=\"https://terrytao.wordpress.com/2011/05/12/steins-maximal-principle/\">Stein’s maximal principle</a>, allows one to reverse this implication in certain cases by exploiting a symmetry of the problem. Here is the principle specialised to the application of pointwise convergence of Fourier series, and also combined with a transference principle <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=583403\">of Kenig and Tomas</a>: </p>\n<p> </p>\n<blockquote>\n <b>Proposition 3 (Equivalent forms of almost everywhere convergence)</b> \n <a name=\"equivc\"></a> Let \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1+%5Cleq+p+%5Cleq+2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1 \\leq p \\leq 2}\" title=\"{1 \\leq p \\leq 2}\" class=\"latex\" />. Then the following statements are equivalent: \n <ul> \n  <li>(i) For every <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+L%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" title=\"{f \\in L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" class=\"latex\" />, one has <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Clim_%7BN+%5Crightarrow+%5Cinfty%7D+S_N+f%28x%29+%3D+f%28x%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\lim_{N \\rightarrow \\infty} S_N f(x) = f(x)}\" title=\"{\\lim_{N \\rightarrow \\infty} S_N f(x) = f(x)}\" class=\"latex\" /> for almost every <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x \\in {\\bf R}/{\\bf Z}}\" title=\"{x \\in {\\bf R}/{\\bf Z}}\" class=\"latex\" />. </li>\n  <li>(ii) There does not exist <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+L%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" title=\"{f \\in L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" class=\"latex\" /> such that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Csup_%7BN+%5Cgeq+0%7D+%7CS_N+f%28x%29%7C+%3D+%2B%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\sup_{N \\geq 0} |S_N f(x)| = +\\infty}\" title=\"{\\sup_{N \\geq 0} |S_N f(x)| = +\\infty}\" class=\"latex\" /> for almost every <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x \\in {\\bf R}/{\\bf Z}}\" title=\"{x \\in {\\bf R}/{\\bf Z}}\" class=\"latex\" />. </li>\n  <li>(iii) One has the maximal inequality <a name=\"spi\"><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%5Csup_%7BN+%5Cgeq+0%7D+%7CS_N+f%7C+%5C%7C_%7BL%5E%7Bp%2C%5Cinfty%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D+%5Clesssim_p+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%281%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sup_{N \\geq 0} |S_N f| \\|_{L^{p,\\infty}({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})} \\lesssim_p \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (1)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sup_{N \\geq 0} |S_N f| \\|_{L^{p,\\infty}({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})} \\lesssim_p \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (1)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> </a> for all smooth <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%3A+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cbf+C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f: {\\bf R}/{\\bf Z} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" title=\"{f: {\\bf R}/{\\bf Z} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" class=\"latex\" />, where the weak <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BL%5E%7Bp%2C%5Cinfty%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{L^{p,\\infty}}\" title=\"{L^{p,\\infty}}\" class=\"latex\" /> norm is defined as <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+F+%5C%7C_%7BL%5E%7Bp%2C%5Cinfty%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D+%3A%3D+%5Csup_%7B%5Clambda+%3E+0%7D+%5Clambda+%7C%5C%7B+x+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%3A+%7CF%28x%29%7C+%5Cgeq+%5Clambda+%5C%7D%7C%5E%7B1%2Fp%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| F \\|_{L^{p,\\infty}({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})} := \\sup_{\\lambda > 0} \\lambda |\\{ x \\in {\\bf R}/{\\bf Z}: |F(x)| \\geq \\lambda \\}|^{1/p}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| F \\|_{L^{p,\\infty}({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})} := \\sup_{\\lambda > 0} \\lambda |\\{ x \\in {\\bf R}/{\\bf Z}: |F(x)| \\geq \\lambda \\}|^{1/p}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7CE%7C%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{|E|}\" title=\"{|E|}\" class=\"latex\" /> denotes the Lebesgue measure of a set <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BE%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{E}\" title=\"{E}\" class=\"latex\" /> (which in this setting is a subset of the unit circle). </li>\n  <li>(iv) One has the maximal inequality <a name=\"spi-f\"><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%5Csup_%7BN+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D+%7CP_N+f%7C+%5C%7C_%7BL%5E%7Bp%2C%5Cinfty%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D+%5Clesssim_p+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%282%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sup_{N \\in {\\bf Z}} |P_N f| \\|_{L^{p,\\infty}({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})} \\lesssim_p \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (2)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sup_{N \\in {\\bf Z}} |P_N f| \\|_{L^{p,\\infty}({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})} \\lesssim_p \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (2)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> </a> for all smooth <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%3A+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cbf+C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f: {\\bf R}/{\\bf Z} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" title=\"{f: {\\bf R}/{\\bf Z} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" class=\"latex\" />, where <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP_N+f%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P_N f}\" title=\"{P_N f}\" class=\"latex\" /> denotes the partial Fourier series <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++P_N+f%28x%29+%3D+%5Csum_%7Bn+%5Cleq+N%7D+%5Chat+f%28n%29+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+nx%7D.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  P_N f(x) = \\sum_{n \\leq N} \\hat f(n) e^{2\\pi i nx}.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  P_N f(x) = \\sum_{n \\leq N} \\hat f(n) e^{2\\pi i nx}.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> </li>\n  <li>(v) One has the maximal inequality <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%5Csup_%7BN+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D+%7C1_%7BD+%5Cleq+N%7D+f%7C+%5C%7C_%7BL%5E%7Bp%2C%5Cinfty%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D+%5Clesssim_p+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sup_{N \\in {\\bf R}} |1_{D \\leq N} f| \\|_{L^{p,\\infty}({\\bf R})} \\lesssim_p \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R})}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sup_{N \\in {\\bf R}} |1_{D \\leq N} f| \\|_{L^{p,\\infty}({\\bf R})} \\lesssim_p \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> for all <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{f \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" />, where <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1_%7BD+%5Cleq+N%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1_{D \\leq N}}\" title=\"{1_{D \\leq N}}\" class=\"latex\" /> denotes the Fourier multiplier operator <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%281_%7BD+%5Cleq+N%7D+f%29%5E%5Cwedge%28%5Cxi%29+%3A%3D+1_%7B%5Cxi+%5Cleq+N%7D+%5Chat+f%28%5Cxi%29.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  (1_{D \\leq N} f)^\\wedge(\\xi) := 1_{\\xi \\leq N} \\hat f(\\xi).\" title=\"\\displaystyle  (1_{D \\leq N} f)^\\wedge(\\xi) := 1_{\\xi \\leq N} \\hat f(\\xi).\" class=\"latex\" /></p> </li>\n </ul> \n</blockquote> \n<p></p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> Among other things, this proposition equates the qualitative property (i) of almost everywhere convergence to the quantitative property (iii) of a maximal inequality. This equivalence (first observed by Calderón) is similar in spirit to the uniform boundedness principle (see e.g. Corollary 1 of <a href=\"https://terrytao.wordpress.com/2009/02/01/245b-notes-9-the-baire-category-theorem-and-its-banach-space-consequences/\">this previous blog post</a>). The restriction <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bp+%5Cleq+2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{p \\leq 2}\" title=\"{p \\leq 2}\" class=\"latex\" /> is needed for just one implication (from (ii) to (iii)) in the arguments below, and arises due to the use of Khintchine’s inequality at one point. The equivalence of (iv) and (v) is part of a more general principle of <em>transference</em> that allows one to pass back and forth between periodic domains such as <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf R}/{\\bf Z}}\" title=\"{{\\bf R}/{\\bf Z}}\" class=\"latex\" /> with non-periodic domains such as <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf R}}\" title=\"{{\\bf R}}\" class=\"latex\" /> (or, on the Fourier side, between discrete domains <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf Z}}\" title=\"{{\\bf Z}}\" class=\"latex\" /> and continuous domains <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf R}}\" title=\"{{\\bf R}}\" class=\"latex\" />) if the estimates in question enjoy suitable scaling symmetries. We will use the formulation (v), as it enjoys the most symmetries. </p>\n<p> <em>Proof:</em> We first show that (iii) implies (i). If <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#spi\">(1)</a> holds for all smooth <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f}\" title=\"{f}\" class=\"latex\" />, then certainly for all finite <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN_0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N_0}\" title=\"{N_0}\" class=\"latex\" /> one has </p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%5Csup_%7B0+%5Cleq+N+%5Cleq+N_0%7D+%7CS_N+f%7C+%5C%7C_%7BL%5E%7Bp%2C%5Cinfty%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D+%5Clesssim_p+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sup_{0 \\leq N \\leq N_0} |S_N f| \\|_{L^{p,\\infty}({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})} \\lesssim_p \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sup_{0 \\leq N \\leq N_0} |S_N f| \\|_{L^{p,\\infty}({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})} \\lesssim_p \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> for all smooth \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f}\" title=\"{f}\" class=\"latex\" />, and hence for all \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+L%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" title=\"{f \\in L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" class=\"latex\" /> by a standard limiting argument. Taking limits as \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN_0+%5Crightarrow+%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N_0 \\rightarrow \\infty}\" title=\"{N_0 \\rightarrow \\infty}\" class=\"latex\" /> (using variants of Fatou’s lemma) we conclude that \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#spi\">(1)</a> holds for all \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+L%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" title=\"{f \\in L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" class=\"latex\" />. This implies in particular from the triangle inequality that \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%5Climsup_%7BN+%5Crightarrow+%5Cinfty%7D+%7CS_N+f-f%7C+%5C%7C_%7BL%5E%7Bp%2C%5Cinfty%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D+%5Clesssim_p+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\limsup_{N \\rightarrow \\infty} |S_N f-f| \\|_{L^{p,\\infty}({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})} \\lesssim_p \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\limsup_{N \\rightarrow \\infty} |S_N f-f| \\|_{L^{p,\\infty}({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})} \\lesssim_p \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> for all \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+L%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" title=\"{f \\in L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" class=\"latex\" />. On the other hand, the left-hand side vanishes whenever \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f}\" title=\"{f}\" class=\"latex\" /> is smooth, since Fourier series converge uniformly in this case. Since smooth functions are dense in \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" title=\"{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" class=\"latex\" />, we conclude from standard limiting arguments that the left-hand side in fact vanishes for all \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+L%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" title=\"{f \\in L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" class=\"latex\" />, giving the claim (i). \n<p> Clearly (i) implies (ii). Now we assume that (iii) fails and use this to show that (ii) fails as well. From the failure of (iii) and monotone convergence, for any <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BA%3E0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{A>0}\" title=\"{A>0}\" class=\"latex\" /> one can find <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+C%5E%5Cinfty%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in C^\\infty({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" title=\"{f \\in C^\\infty({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" class=\"latex\" />, a measurable subset <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BE%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{E}\" title=\"{E}\" class=\"latex\" /> of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf R}/{\\bf Z}}\" title=\"{{\\bf R}/{\\bf Z}}\" class=\"latex\" />, a finite <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN_0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N_0}\" title=\"{N_0}\" class=\"latex\" />, and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Clambda+%3E+0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\lambda > 0}\" title=\"{\\lambda > 0}\" class=\"latex\" /> such that <a name=\"snf\"></a></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><a name=\"snf\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Csup_%7B0+%5Cleq+N+%5Cleq+N_0%7D+%7CS_N+f%28x%29%7C+%5Cgeq+%5Clambda+%5Chbox%7B+for+all+%7D+x+%5Cin+E+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%283%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\sup_{0 \\leq N \\leq N_0} |S_N f(x)| \\geq \\lambda \\hbox{ for all } x \\in E \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (3)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\sup_{0 \\leq N \\leq N_0} |S_N f(x)| \\geq \\lambda \\hbox{ for all } x \\in E \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (3)\" class=\"latex\" /></a></p>\n<a name=\"snf\"> </a> and such that \n<a name=\"aed\"><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Clambda+%7CE%7C%5E%7B1%2Fp%7D+%3E+A+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D.+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%284%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\lambda |E|^{1/p} > A \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}. \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (4)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\lambda |E|^{1/p} > A \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}. \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (4)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> </a> In particular, \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BE%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{E}\" title=\"{E}\" class=\"latex\" /> has positive measure. By homogeneity we may normalise \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Clambda%3D1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\lambda=1}\" title=\"{\\lambda=1}\" class=\"latex\" />. At this stage, nothing prevents the measure of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BE%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{E}\" title=\"{E}\" class=\"latex\" /> from being much smaller than \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1}\" title=\"{1}\" class=\"latex\" />; but we can exploit translation invariance to increase the measure of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BE%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{E}\" title=\"{E}\" class=\"latex\" /> to be comparable to \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1}\" title=\"{1}\" class=\"latex\" /> as follows. Let \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bn+%5Cgeq+1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{n \\geq 1}\" title=\"{n \\geq 1}\" class=\"latex\" /> be the integer part of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1%2F%7CE%7C%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1/|E|}\" title=\"{1/|E|}\" class=\"latex\" />. We claim that there exist translations \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BE%2Bx_1%2C%5Cdots%2CE%2Bx_n%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{E+x_1,\\dots,E+x_n}\" title=\"{E+x_1,\\dots,E+x_n}\" class=\"latex\" /> of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BE%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{E}\" title=\"{E}\" class=\"latex\" /> whose union has measure comparable to \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1}\" title=\"{1}\" class=\"latex\" />: \n<a name=\"exi\"><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7C+%5Cbigcup_%7Bi%3D1%7D%5En+E+%2B+x_i%7C+%5Csim+1.+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%285%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  | \\bigcup_{i=1}^n E + x_i| \\sim 1. \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (5)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  | \\bigcup_{i=1}^n E + x_i| \\sim 1. \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (5)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> </a> This is easiest to establish by the \n<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probabilistic_method\">probabilistic method</a> (which in this context we might call the \n<em>random translation</em> method). If we select \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx_1%2C%5Cdots%2Cx_n%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x_1,\\dots,x_n}\" title=\"{x_1,\\dots,x_n}\" class=\"latex\" /> uniformly and independently at random we see that every point \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x \\in {\\bf R}/{\\bf Z}}\" title=\"{x \\in {\\bf R}/{\\bf Z}}\" class=\"latex\" /> will lie in a given translate \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BE+%2B+x_i%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{E + x_i}\" title=\"{E + x_i}\" class=\"latex\" /> (or equivalently, that \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx_i%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x_i}\" title=\"{x_i}\" class=\"latex\" /> lies in \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx-E%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x-E}\" title=\"{x-E}\" class=\"latex\" />) with probability \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7CE%7C%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{|E|}\" title=\"{|E|}\" class=\"latex\" />, hence \n<p></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7B%5Cmathbf+P%7D%28+x+%5Cin+%5Cbigcup_%7Bi%3D1%7D%5En+E+%2B+x_i+%29+%3D+1+-+%281+-+%7CE%7C%29%5En.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathbf P}( x \\in \\bigcup_{i=1}^n E + x_i ) = 1 - (1 - |E|)^n.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathbf P}( x \\in \\bigcup_{i=1}^n E + x_i ) = 1 - (1 - |E|)^n.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> Integrating in \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x}\" title=\"{x}\" class=\"latex\" /> and using the Fubini-Tonelli theorem, we conclude that \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7B%5Cmathbf+E%7D%28+%7C%5Cbigcup_%7Bi%3D1%7D%5En+E+%2B+x_i%7C+%29+%3D+1+-+%281+-+%7CE%7C%29%5En&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathbf E}( |\\bigcup_{i=1}^n E + x_i| ) = 1 - (1 - |E|)^n\" title=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathbf E}( |\\bigcup_{i=1}^n E + x_i| ) = 1 - (1 - |E|)^n\" class=\"latex\" /></p> and hence there exists deterministic choices of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx_1%2C%5Cdots%2Cx_n%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x_1,\\dots,x_n}\" title=\"{x_1,\\dots,x_n}\" class=\"latex\" /> for which \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7C%5Cbigcup_%7Bi%3D1%7D%5En+E+%2B+x_i%7C+%5Cgeq+1+-+%281+-+%7CE%7C%29%5En.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  |\\bigcup_{i=1}^n E + x_i| \\geq 1 - (1 - |E|)^n.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  |\\bigcup_{i=1}^n E + x_i| \\geq 1 - (1 - |E|)^n.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> By definition of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bn%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{n}\" title=\"{n}\" class=\"latex\" /> the RHS is comparable to \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1}\" title=\"{1}\" class=\"latex\" />, giving the claim (clearly the left-hand side cannot exceed \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1}\" title=\"{1}\" class=\"latex\" />). \n<p> Now consider the randomised linear combination </p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Ctilde+f%28x%29+%3A%3D+%5Csum_%7Bi%3D1%7D%5En+%5Cepsilon_i+f%28x-x_i%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\tilde f(x) := \\sum_{i=1}^n \\epsilon_i f(x-x_i)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\tilde f(x) := \\sum_{i=1}^n \\epsilon_i f(x-x_i)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> of translates of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f}\" title=\"{f}\" class=\"latex\" />, where \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cepsilon_1%2C%5Cdots%2C%5Cepsilon_n%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\epsilon_1,\\dots,\\epsilon_n}\" title=\"{\\epsilon_1,\\dots,\\epsilon_n}\" class=\"latex\" /> are random Bernoulli signs. From Khintchine’s inequality and the hypothesis \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1+%5Cleq+p+%5Cleq+2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1 \\leq p \\leq 2}\" title=\"{1 \\leq p \\leq 2}\" class=\"latex\" /> we have \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7B%5Cbf+E%7D+%5C%7C+%5Ctilde+f+%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D%5Ep+%5Csim_p+%5C%7C+%28%5Csum_%7Bi%3D1%7D%5En+%7Cf%28%5Ccdot-x_i%29%7C%5E2%29%5E%7B1%2F2%7D+%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D%5Ep&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  {\\bf E} \\| \\tilde f \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}^p \\sim_p \\| (\\sum_{i=1}^n |f(\\cdot-x_i)|^2)^{1/2} \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}^p\" title=\"\\displaystyle  {\\bf E} \\| \\tilde f \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}^p \\sim_p \\| (\\sum_{i=1}^n |f(\\cdot-x_i)|^2)^{1/2} \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}^p\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cleq+%5C%7C+%28%5Csum_%7Bi%3D1%7D%5En+%7Cf%28%5Ccdot-x_i%29%7C%5Ep%29%5E%7B1%2Fp%7D+%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D%5Ep&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\leq \\| (\\sum_{i=1}^n |f(\\cdot-x_i)|^p)^{1/p} \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}^p\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\leq \\| (\\sum_{i=1}^n |f(\\cdot-x_i)|^p)^{1/p} \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}^p\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%3D+%5Csum_%7Bi%3D1%7D%5En+%5C%7Cf%28%5Ccdot-x_i%29%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D%5Ep+&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  = \\sum_{i=1}^n \\|f(\\cdot-x_i)\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}^p \" title=\"\\displaystyle  = \\sum_{i=1}^n \\|f(\\cdot-x_i)\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}^p \" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%3D+n+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D%5Ep&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  = n \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}^p\" title=\"\\displaystyle  = n \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}^p\" class=\"latex\" /></p> hence by construction of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bn%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{n}\" title=\"{n}\" class=\"latex\" /> and \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#aed\">(4)</a> \n<a name=\"efp\"><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7B%5Cbf+E%7D+%5C%7C+%5Ctilde+f+%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D%5Ep+%5Clesssim_p+A%5E%7B-p%7D.+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%286%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  {\\bf E} \\| \\tilde f \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}^p \\lesssim_p A^{-p}. \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (6)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  {\\bf E} \\| \\tilde f \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}^p \\lesssim_p A^{-p}. \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (6)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> </a> \n<p> Now we study the behaviour of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Csup_%7B0+%5Cleq+N+%5Cleq+N_0%7D+%7CS_N+%5Ctilde+f%28x%29%7C%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\sup_{0 \\leq N \\leq N_0} |S_N \\tilde f(x)|}\" title=\"{\\sup_{0 \\leq N \\leq N_0} |S_N \\tilde f(x)|}\" class=\"latex\" /> when <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx+%5Cin+%5Cbigcup_%7Bi%3D1%7D%5En+E+%2B+x_i%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x \\in \\bigcup_{i=1}^n E + x_i}\" title=\"{x \\in \\bigcup_{i=1}^n E + x_i}\" class=\"latex\" />. Since <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS_N%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{S_N}\" title=\"{S_N}\" class=\"latex\" /> is a convolution operator, it commutes with translations, and hence <a name=\"snfx\"></a></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><a name=\"snfx\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++S_N+%5Ctilde+f%28x%29+%3D+%5Csum_%7Bi%3D1%7D%5En+%5Cepsilon_i+S_N+f%28x-x_i%29+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%287%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  S_N \\tilde f(x) = \\sum_{i=1}^n \\epsilon_i S_N f(x-x_i) \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (7)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  S_N \\tilde f(x) = \\sum_{i=1}^n \\epsilon_i S_N f(x-x_i) \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (7)\" class=\"latex\" /></a></p>\n<a name=\"snfx\"> </a> for each \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bi%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{i}\" title=\"{i}\" class=\"latex\" />. On the other hand, from \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#snf\">(3)</a> we have \n<p></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Csup_%7B1+%5Cleq+i+%5Cleq+n%3B+0+%5Cleq+N+%5Cleq+N_0%7D+%7CS_N+f%28x-x_i%29%7C+%5Cgeq+1&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\sup_{1 \\leq i \\leq n; 0 \\leq N \\leq N_0} |S_N f(x-x_i)| \\geq 1\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\sup_{1 \\leq i \\leq n; 0 \\leq N \\leq N_0} |S_N f(x-x_i)| \\geq 1\" class=\"latex\" /></p> and hence there exists \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B0+%5Cleq+N_x+%5Cleq+N_0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{0 \\leq N_x \\leq N_0}\" title=\"{0 \\leq N_x \\leq N_0}\" class=\"latex\" /> such that \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Csup_%7B1+%5Cleq+i+%5Cleq+n%7D+%7CS_%7BN_x%7D+f%28x-x_i%29%7C+%5Cgeq+1.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\sup_{1 \\leq i \\leq n} |S_{N_x} f(x-x_i)| \\geq 1.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\sup_{1 \\leq i \\leq n} |S_{N_x} f(x-x_i)| \\geq 1.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> In particular, the square function \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++Q_x+%3A%3D+%28%5Csum_%7Bi%3D1%7D%5En+%7CS_%7BN_x%7D+f%28x-x_i%29%7C%5E2%29%5E%7B1%2F2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  Q_x := (\\sum_{i=1}^n |S_{N_x} f(x-x_i)|^2)^{1/2}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  Q_x := (\\sum_{i=1}^n |S_{N_x} f(x-x_i)|^2)^{1/2}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> is at least \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1}\" title=\"{1}\" class=\"latex\" />. Meanwhile, from Khintchine’s inequality and \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#snfx\">(7)</a> we have \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%28%7B%5Cbf+E%7D+%7CS_%7BN_x%7D+%5Ctilde+f%28x%29%7C%5Eq%29%5E%7B1%2Fq%7D+%5Csim_q+Q_x&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  ({\\bf E} |S_{N_x} \\tilde f(x)|^q)^{1/q} \\sim_q Q_x\" title=\"\\displaystyle  ({\\bf E} |S_{N_x} \\tilde f(x)|^q)^{1/q} \\sim_q Q_x\" class=\"latex\" /></p> for all \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B0+%3C+q+%3C+%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{0 < q < \\infty}\" title=\"{0 < q < \\infty}\" class=\"latex\" />. Applying \n<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paley%E2%80%93Zygmund_inequality\">the Paley-Zygmund inequality</a> (setting \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bq%3D1%2C2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{q=1,2}\" title=\"{q=1,2}\" class=\"latex\" />, for instance) we conclude that \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7B%5Cbf+P%7D%28+%7CS_%7BN_x%7D+%5Ctilde+f%28x%29%7C+%5Cgtrsim+Q_x+%29+%5Cgtrsim+1&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  {\\bf P}( |S_{N_x} \\tilde f(x)| \\gtrsim Q_x ) \\gtrsim 1\" title=\"\\displaystyle  {\\bf P}( |S_{N_x} \\tilde f(x)| \\gtrsim Q_x ) \\gtrsim 1\" class=\"latex\" /></p> (for suitable choices of implied constants), so in particular \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7B%5Cbf+P%7D%28+%5Csup_%7B0+%5Cleq+N+%5Cleq+N_0%7D+%7CS_N+%5Ctilde+f%28x%29%7C+%5Cgtrsim+1+%29+%5Cgtrsim+1&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  {\\bf P}( \\sup_{0 \\leq N \\leq N_0} |S_N \\tilde f(x)| \\gtrsim 1 ) \\gtrsim 1\" title=\"\\displaystyle  {\\bf P}( \\sup_{0 \\leq N \\leq N_0} |S_N \\tilde f(x)| \\gtrsim 1 ) \\gtrsim 1\" class=\"latex\" /></p> Integrating in \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x}\" title=\"{x}\" class=\"latex\" /> using \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#exi\">(5)</a>, and applying the Fubini-Tonelli theorem, we conclude that \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7B%5Cbf+E%7D+%7C%5C%7B+%5Csup_%7B0+%5Cleq+N+%5Cleq+N_0%7D+%7CS_N+%5Ctilde+f%28x%29%7C+%5Cgtrsim+1+%5C%7D%7C+%5Cgtrsim+1&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  {\\bf E} |\\{ \\sup_{0 \\leq N \\leq N_0} |S_N \\tilde f(x)| \\gtrsim 1 \\}| \\gtrsim 1\" title=\"\\displaystyle  {\\bf E} |\\{ \\sup_{0 \\leq N \\leq N_0} |S_N \\tilde f(x)| \\gtrsim 1 \\}| \\gtrsim 1\" class=\"latex\" /></p> hence by \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#efp\">(6)</a> one has \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7B%5Cbf+E%7D+%7C%5C%7B+%5Csup_%7B0+%5Cleq+N+%5Cleq+N_0%7D+%7CS_N+%5Ctilde+f%28x%29%7C+%5Cgtrsim+1+%5C%7D%7C+%5Cgtrsim_p+1+%2B+A%5Ep+%7B%5Cbf+E%7D+%5C%7C+%5Ctilde+f+%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D%5Ep.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  {\\bf E} |\\{ \\sup_{0 \\leq N \\leq N_0} |S_N \\tilde f(x)| \\gtrsim 1 \\}| \\gtrsim_p 1 + A^p {\\bf E} \\| \\tilde f \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}^p.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  {\\bf E} |\\{ \\sup_{0 \\leq N \\leq N_0} |S_N \\tilde f(x)| \\gtrsim 1 \\}| \\gtrsim_p 1 + A^p {\\bf E} \\| \\tilde f \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}^p.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> In particular, there exists a deterministic choice of signs \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cepsilon_i%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\epsilon_i}\" title=\"{\\epsilon_i}\" class=\"latex\" /> (and hence of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Ctilde+f%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\tilde f}\" title=\"{\\tilde f}\" class=\"latex\" />) for which \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7C%5C%7B+%5Csup_%7B0+%5Cleq+N+%5Cleq+N_0%7D+%7CS_N+%5Ctilde+f%28x%29%7C+%5Cgtrsim+1+%5C%7D%7C+%5Cgtrsim_p+1+%2B+A%5Ep+%5C%7C+%5Ctilde+f+%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D%5Ep.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  |\\{ \\sup_{0 \\leq N \\leq N_0} |S_N \\tilde f(x)| \\gtrsim 1 \\}| \\gtrsim_p 1 + A^p \\| \\tilde f \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}^p.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  |\\{ \\sup_{0 \\leq N \\leq N_0} |S_N \\tilde f(x)| \\gtrsim 1 \\}| \\gtrsim_p 1 + A^p \\| \\tilde f \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}^p.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> On the other hand, the left-hand side is at most \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1}\" title=\"{1}\" class=\"latex\" />. We conclude that for every \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BA%3E0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{A>0}\" title=\"{A>0}\" class=\"latex\" />, we can find a smooth function \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf_A%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f_A}\" title=\"{f_A}\" class=\"latex\" /> with \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7Cf_A+%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D+%5Clesssim_p+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7BA%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\|f_A \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})} \\lesssim_p \\frac{1}{A}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\|f_A \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})} \\lesssim_p \\frac{1}{A}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> and a finite \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN_A%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N_A}\" title=\"{N_A}\" class=\"latex\" />, as well as a set \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BE_A+%5Csubset+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{E_A \\subset {\\bf R}/{\\bf Z}}\" title=\"{E_A \\subset {\\bf R}/{\\bf Z}}\" class=\"latex\" /> of measure \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7CE_A%7C+%5Csim_p+1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{|E_A| \\sim_p 1}\" title=\"{|E_A| \\sim_p 1}\" class=\"latex\" />, such that \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+%5Csup_%7B0+%5Cleq+N+%5Cleq+N_A%7D+%7CS_N+f_A%28x%29%7C+%5Cgtrsim+1+&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle \\sup_{0 \\leq N \\leq N_A} |S_N f_A(x)| \\gtrsim 1 \" title=\"\\displaystyle \\sup_{0 \\leq N \\leq N_A} |S_N f_A(x)| \\gtrsim 1 \" class=\"latex\" /></p> for all \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx+%5Cin+E_A%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x \\in E_A}\" title=\"{x \\in E_A}\" class=\"latex\" />. \n<p> Applying this fact iteratively (each time choosing <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BA%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{A}\" title=\"{A}\" class=\"latex\" /> to be sufficiently large depending on all previous choices), we can construct a sequence of smooth functions <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%5E%7B%28m%29%7D%3A+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cbf+C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f^{(m)}: {\\bf R}/{\\bf Z} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" title=\"{f^{(m)}: {\\bf R}/{\\bf Z} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" class=\"latex\" />, finite <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN%5E%7B%28m%29%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N^{(m)}}\" title=\"{N^{(m)}}\" class=\"latex\" />, and sets <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BE%5E%7B%28m%29%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{E^{(m)}}\" title=\"{E^{(m)}}\" class=\"latex\" /> for <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bm%3D1%2C2%2C%5Cdots%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{m=1,2,\\dots}\" title=\"{m=1,2,\\dots}\" class=\"latex\" /> such that </p>\n<ul> \n <li>(a) <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7Cf%5E%7B%28m%29%7D%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D+%5Cleq+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B2%5Em%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\|f^{(m)}\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})} \\leq \\frac{1}{2^m}}\" title=\"{\\|f^{(m)}\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})} \\leq \\frac{1}{2^m}}\" class=\"latex\" /> for all <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bm+%5Cgeq+1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{m \\geq 1}\" title=\"{m \\geq 1}\" class=\"latex\" />. </li>\n <li>(b) <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7CE%5E%7B%28m%29%7D%7C+%5Cgtrsim_p+1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{|E^{(m)}| \\gtrsim_p 1}\" title=\"{|E^{(m)}| \\gtrsim_p 1}\" class=\"latex\" /> for all <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bm+%5Cgeq+1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{m \\geq 1}\" title=\"{m \\geq 1}\" class=\"latex\" />. </li>\n <li>(c) One has <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+%5Csup_%7B0+%5Cleq+N+%5Cleq+N%5E%7B%28m%29%7D%7D+%7CS_N+f%5E%7B%28m%29%7D%28x%29%7C+%5Cgeq+m+%2B+%5Csum_%7Bm%27+%3C+m%7D+%5Csup_%7BN+%5Cgeq+0%7D+%5C%7CS_N+f%5E%7B%28m%27%29%7D%5C%7C_%7BL%5E%5Cinfty%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle \\sup_{0 \\leq N \\leq N^{(m)}} |S_N f^{(m)}(x)| \\geq m + \\sum_{m' < m} \\sup_{N \\geq 0} \\|S_N f^{(m')}\\|_{L^\\infty({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" title=\"\\displaystyle \\sup_{0 \\leq N \\leq N^{(m)}} |S_N f^{(m)}(x)| \\geq m + \\sum_{m' < m} \\sup_{N \\geq 0} \\|S_N f^{(m')}\\|_{L^\\infty({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> for all <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bm%5Cgeq+1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{m\\geq 1}\" title=\"{m\\geq 1}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx+%5Cin+E%5E%7B%28m%29%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x \\in E^{(m)}}\" title=\"{x \\in E^{(m)}}\" class=\"latex\" /> (note that the right-hand side is finite since the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%5E%7B%28m%27%29%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f^{(m')}}\" title=\"{f^{(m')}}\" class=\"latex\" /> are smooth for <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bm%27+%3C+m%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{m' < m}\" title=\"{m' < m}\" class=\"latex\" />). </li>\n <li>(d) <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Csup_%7B0+%5Cleq+N+%5Cleq+N%5E%7B%28m%27%29%7D%7D+%5C%7CS_N+f%5E%7B%28m%29%7D%5C%7C_%7BL%5E%5Cinfty%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D+%5Cleq+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B2%5Em%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\sup_{0 \\leq N \\leq N^{(m')}} \\|S_N f^{(m)}\\|_{L^\\infty({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})} \\leq \\frac{1}{2^m}}\" title=\"{\\sup_{0 \\leq N \\leq N^{(m')}} \\|S_N f^{(m)}\\|_{L^\\infty({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})} \\leq \\frac{1}{2^m}}\" class=\"latex\" /> for all <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1+%5Cleq+m%27+%3C+m%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1 \\leq m' < m}\" title=\"{1 \\leq m' < m}\" class=\"latex\" /> (note that the left-hand side is bounded by <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BO_%7BN%5E%7B%28m%27%29%7D%7D%28+%5C%7Cf%5E%7B%28m%29%7D%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D+%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{O_{N^{(m')}}( \\|f^{(m)}\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})} )}\" title=\"{O_{N^{(m')}}( \\|f^{(m)}\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})} )}\" class=\"latex\" />). </li>\n</ul> By randomly translating the \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BE%5E%7B%28m%29%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{E^{(m)}}\" title=\"{E^{(m)}}\" class=\"latex\" /> (and \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%5E%7B%28m%29%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f^{(m)}}\" title=\"{f^{(m)}}\" class=\"latex\" />), and using the Borel-Cantelli lemma, we may assume without loss of generality that almost every \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x \\in {\\bf R}/{\\bf Z}}\" title=\"{x \\in {\\bf R}/{\\bf Z}}\" class=\"latex\" /> lies in infinitely many of the \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BE%5E%7B%28m%29%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{E^{(m)}}\" title=\"{E^{(m)}}\" class=\"latex\" />. If one then sets \n<p></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++f+%3A%3D+%5Csum_%7Bm%3D1%7D%5E%5Cinfty+f%5E%7B%28m%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  f := \\sum_{m=1}^\\infty f^{(m)}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  f := \\sum_{m=1}^\\infty f^{(m)}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> we see that \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+L%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" title=\"{f \\in L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" class=\"latex\" />, and from the triangle inequality we see that for almost every \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x \\in {\\bf R}/{\\bf Z}}\" title=\"{x \\in {\\bf R}/{\\bf Z}}\" class=\"latex\" /> we have \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Csup_%7B0+%5Cleq+N+%5Cleq+N%5E%7B%28m%29%7D%7D+%7CS_N+f%28x%29%7C+%5Cgeq+m+-+%5Csum_%7B%5Ctilde+m+%3E+m%7D+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B2%5E%7B%5Ctilde+m%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\sup_{0 \\leq N \\leq N^{(m)}} |S_N f(x)| \\geq m - \\sum_{\\tilde m > m} \\frac{1}{2^{\\tilde m}}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\sup_{0 \\leq N \\leq N^{(m)}} |S_N f(x)| \\geq m - \\sum_{\\tilde m > m} \\frac{1}{2^{\\tilde m}}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> for infinitely many \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bm%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{m}\" title=\"{m}\" class=\"latex\" />, which implies in particular that \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Csup_%7BN+%5Cgeq+0%7D+%7CS_N+f%28x%29%7C+%3D+%2B%5Cinfty&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\sup_{N \\geq 0} |S_N f(x)| = +\\infty\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\sup_{N \\geq 0} |S_N f(x)| = +\\infty\" class=\"latex\" /></p> for almost all \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x}\" title=\"{x}\" class=\"latex\" />. This shows that (ii) must fail, as required. \n<p> From the identity <a name=\"snn\"></a></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><a name=\"snn\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++S_N+%3D+P_N+-+P_%7B-N-1%7D+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%288%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  S_N = P_N - P_{-N-1} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (8)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  S_N = P_N - P_{-N-1} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (8)\" class=\"latex\" /></a></p>\n<a name=\"snn\"> </a> and the triangle inequality we see that (iv) implies (iii). Conversely, suppose that (iii) holds. We will take a limit using frequency modulations. For any smooth \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f}\" title=\"{f}\" class=\"latex\" />, we apply (iii) to the modulated function \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Be_%7BM%7D+f%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{e_{M} f}\" title=\"{e_{M} f}\" class=\"latex\" />, where \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BM%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{M}\" title=\"{M}\" class=\"latex\" /> is a natural number and \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Be_%7BM%7D%28x%29+%3A%3D+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+Mx%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{e_{M}(x) := e^{2\\pi i Mx}}\" title=\"{e_{M}(x) := e^{2\\pi i Mx}}\" class=\"latex\" />, to get \n<p></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%5Csup_%7BN+%5Cgeq+0%7D+%7CP_N%28e_%7BM%7D+f%29+-+P_%7B-N-1%7D%28e_%7BM%7D+f%29%7C+%5C%7C_%7BL%5E%7Bp%2C%5Cinfty%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D+%5Clesssim_p+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sup_{N \\geq 0} |P_N(e_{M} f) - P_{-N-1}(e_{M} f)| \\|_{L^{p,\\infty}({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})} \\lesssim_p \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sup_{N \\geq 0} |P_N(e_{M} f) - P_{-N-1}(e_{M} f)| \\|_{L^{p,\\infty}({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})} \\lesssim_p \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> Since \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP_N%28e_%7BM%7D+f%29+%3D+e_%7BM%7D+P_%7BN-M%7D+f%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P_N(e_{M} f) = e_{M} P_{N-M} f}\" title=\"{P_N(e_{M} f) = e_{M} P_{N-M} f}\" class=\"latex\" />, we conclude that \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%5Csup_%7BN+%5Cgeq+0%7D+%7CP_%7BN-M%7D+f+-+P_%7B-N-M-1%7D+f%7C+%5C%7C_%7BL%5E%7Bp%2C%5Cinfty%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D+%5Clesssim_p+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sup_{N \\geq 0} |P_{N-M} f - P_{-N-M-1} f| \\|_{L^{p,\\infty}({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})} \\lesssim_p \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sup_{N \\geq 0} |P_{N-M} f - P_{-N-M-1} f| \\|_{L^{p,\\infty}({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})} \\lesssim_p \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> restricting to the range \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BM-N_0+%5Cleq+N+%5Cleq+M%2BN_0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{M-N_0 \\leq N \\leq M+N_0}\" title=\"{M-N_0 \\leq N \\leq M+N_0}\" class=\"latex\" /> for some given natural number \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN_0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N_0}\" title=\"{N_0}\" class=\"latex\" />, we conclude for \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BM+%3E+N_0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{M > N_0}\" title=\"{M > N_0}\" class=\"latex\" /> that \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%5Csup_%7B-N_0+%5Cleq+N+%5Cleq+N_0%7D+%7CP_%7BN%7D+f+-+P_%7B-N-2M-1%7D+f%7C+%5C%7C_%7BL%5E%7Bp%2C%5Cinfty%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D+%5Clesssim_p+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sup_{-N_0 \\leq N \\leq N_0} |P_{N} f - P_{-N-2M-1} f| \\|_{L^{p,\\infty}({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})} \\lesssim_p \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sup_{-N_0 \\leq N \\leq N_0} |P_{N} f - P_{-N-2M-1} f| \\|_{L^{p,\\infty}({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})} \\lesssim_p \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> Since \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f}\" title=\"{f}\" class=\"latex\" /> is smooth, it has rapidly decreasing Fourier coefficients, which implies that \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Csup_%7B-N_0+%5Cleq+N+%5Cleq+N_0%7D+P_%7B-N-2M-1%7D+f%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\sup_{-N_0 \\leq N \\leq N_0} P_{-N-2M-1} f}\" title=\"{\\sup_{-N_0 \\leq N \\leq N_0} P_{-N-2M-1} f}\" class=\"latex\" /> converges uniformly to zero as \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BM+%5Crightarrow+%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{M \\rightarrow \\infty}\" title=\"{M \\rightarrow \\infty}\" class=\"latex\" />. We conclude that \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%5Csup_%7B-N_0+%5Cleq+N+%5Cleq+N_0%7D+%7CP_%7BN%7D+f%7C+%5C%7C_%7BL%5E%7Bp%2C%5Cinfty%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D+%5Clesssim_p+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sup_{-N_0 \\leq N \\leq N_0} |P_{N} f| \\|_{L^{p,\\infty}({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})} \\lesssim_p \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sup_{-N_0 \\leq N \\leq N_0} |P_{N} f| \\|_{L^{p,\\infty}({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})} \\lesssim_p \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> and then we obtain (iv) by monotone convergence. \n<p> Now we assume (iv) and work to establish (v). The idea here is to use a rescaling argument, viewing <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf R}}\" title=\"{{\\bf R}}\" class=\"latex\" /> as the limit as <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BK+%5Crightarrow+%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{K \\rightarrow \\infty}\" title=\"{K \\rightarrow \\infty}\" class=\"latex\" /> of the large circle <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2FK%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf R}/K{\\bf Z}}\" title=\"{{\\bf R}/K{\\bf Z}}\" class=\"latex\" /> (in physical space) or the fine lattice <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BK%5E%7B-1%7D%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{K^{-1}{\\bf Z}}\" title=\"{K^{-1}{\\bf Z}}\" class=\"latex\" /> (in frequency space). </p>\n<p> By limiting arguments we may assume that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f}\" title=\"{f}\" class=\"latex\" /> is compactly supported on some interval <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5B-A%2CA%5D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{[-A,A]}\" title=\"{[-A,A]}\" class=\"latex\" />. Let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BK%3E0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{K>0}\" title=\"{K>0}\" class=\"latex\" /> be a large scaling parameter, and consider the periodic function <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf_K%3A+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cbf+C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f_K: {\\bf R}/{\\bf
