Z} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" title=\"{f_K: {\\bf R}/{\\bf Z} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" class=\"latex\" /> defined by </p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++f_K%28x+%5Chbox%7B+mod+%7D+1%29+%3A%3D+%5Csum_%7Bn+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D+f%28K%28x-n%29%29.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  f_K(x \\hbox{ mod } 1) := \\sum_{n \\in {\\bf Z}} f(K(x-n)).\" title=\"\\displaystyle  f_K(x \\hbox{ mod } 1) := \\sum_{n \\in {\\bf Z}} f(K(x-n)).\" class=\"latex\" /></p> For \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BK%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{K}\" title=\"{K}\" class=\"latex\" /> large enough, this function is smooth and supported on the interval \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5B-A%2FK%2C+A%2FK%5D+%5Chbox%7B+mod+%7D+1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{[-A/K, A/K] \\hbox{ mod } 1}\" title=\"{[-A/K, A/K] \\hbox{ mod } 1}\" class=\"latex\" />, with \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BL%5Ep%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{L^p}\" title=\"{L^p}\" class=\"latex\" /> norm \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7Cf_K+%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D+%3D+K%5E%7B-1%2Fp%7D+%5C%7C+f%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\|f_K \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})} = K^{-1/p} \\| f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R})}.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\|f_K \\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})} = K^{-1/p} \\| f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R})}.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> The Fourier coefficients of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf_K%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f_K}\" title=\"{f_K}\" class=\"latex\" /> is given as \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Chat%7Bf_K%7D%28n%29+%3D+K%5E%7B-1%7D+%5Chat+f%28K%5E%7B-1%7D+n%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\hat{f_K}(n) = K^{-1} \\hat f(K^{-1} n)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\hat{f_K}(n) = K^{-1} \\hat f(K^{-1} n)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> so that \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++P_N+f_K%28x%29+%3D+K%5E%7B-1%7D+%5Csum_%7Bn+%5Cleq+N%7D+%5Chat+f%28K%5E%7B-1%7D+n%29+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+n+x%7D.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  P_N f_K(x) = K^{-1} \\sum_{n \\leq N} \\hat f(K^{-1} n) e^{2\\pi i n x}.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  P_N f_K(x) = K^{-1} \\sum_{n \\leq N} \\hat f(K^{-1} n) e^{2\\pi i n x}.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> Applying (iv), we see that for any \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Clambda+%3E+0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\lambda > 0}\" title=\"{\\lambda > 0}\" class=\"latex\" />, we have \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7C+%5C%7B+x+%5Cin+%5B-1%2F2%2C1%2F2%5D%3A+%5Csup_%7BN+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D+K%5E%7B-1%7D+%7C%5Csum_%7Bn+%5Cleq+N%7D+%5Chat+f%28K%5E%7B-1%7D+n%29+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+n+x%7D%7C+%5Cgeq+%5Clambda+%5C%7D+%7C+%5Clesssim_p+%5Clambda%5E%7B-p%7D+K%5E%7B-1%7D+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D%5Ep.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  | \\{ x \\in [-1/2,1/2]: \\sup_{N \\in {\\bf Z}} K^{-1} |\\sum_{n \\leq N} \\hat f(K^{-1} n) e^{2\\pi i n x}| \\geq \\lambda \\} | \\lesssim_p \\lambda^{-p} K^{-1} \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R})}^p.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  | \\{ x \\in [-1/2,1/2]: \\sup_{N \\in {\\bf Z}} K^{-1} |\\sum_{n \\leq N} \\hat f(K^{-1} n) e^{2\\pi i n x}| \\geq \\lambda \\} | \\lesssim_p \\lambda^{-p} K^{-1} \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R})}^p.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> Rescaling \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x}\" title=\"{x}\" class=\"latex\" /> by \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BK%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{K}\" title=\"{K}\" class=\"latex\" />, we conclude that \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7C+%5C%7B+x+%5Cin+%5B-K%2F2%2CK%2F2%5D%3A+%5Csup_%7BN+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D+K%5E%7B-1%7D+%7C%5Csum_%7Bn+%5Cleq+N%7D+%5Chat+f%28K%5E%7B-1%7D+n%29+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+K%5E%7B-1%7D+n+x%7D%7C+%5Cgeq+%5Clambda+%5C%7D+%7C+%5Clesssim_p+%5Clambda%5E%7B-p%7D+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D%5Ep.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  | \\{ x \\in [-K/2,K/2]: \\sup_{N \\in {\\bf Z}} K^{-1} |\\sum_{n \\leq N} \\hat f(K^{-1} n) e^{2\\pi i K^{-1} n x}| \\geq \\lambda \\} | \\lesssim_p \\lambda^{-p} \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R})}^p.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  | \\{ x \\in [-K/2,K/2]: \\sup_{N \\in {\\bf Z}} K^{-1} |\\sum_{n \\leq N} \\hat f(K^{-1} n) e^{2\\pi i K^{-1} n x}| \\geq \\lambda \\} | \\lesssim_p \\lambda^{-p} \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R})}^p.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> We can let \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N}\" title=\"{N}\" class=\"latex\" /> range over the reals rather than the integers as this does not affect the constraint \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bn+%5Cleq+N%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{n \\leq N}\" title=\"{n \\leq N}\" class=\"latex\" />. Rescaling \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N}\" title=\"{N}\" class=\"latex\" /> by \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BK%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{K}\" title=\"{K}\" class=\"latex\" />, we see that for any compact intervals \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BI%2CJ%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{I,J}\" title=\"{I,J}\" class=\"latex\" />, we have \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7C+%5C%7B+x+%5Cin+I%3A+%5Csup_%7BN+%5Cin+J%7D+K%5E%7B-1%7D+%7C%5Csum_%7B%5Cxi+%5Cin+K%5E%7B-1%7D+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%3A+%5Cxi+%5Cleq+N%7D+%5Chat+f%28%5Cxi%29+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+%5Cxi+x%7D%7C+%5Cgeq+%5Clambda+%5C%7D+%7C+%5Clesssim_p+%5Clambda%5E%7B-p%7D+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D%5Ep.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  | \\{ x \\in I: \\sup_{N \\in J} K^{-1} |\\sum_{\\xi \\in K^{-1} {\\bf Z}: \\xi \\leq N} \\hat f(\\xi) e^{2\\pi i \\xi x}| \\geq \\lambda \\} | \\lesssim_p \\lambda^{-p} \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R})}^p.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  | \\{ x \\in I: \\sup_{N \\in J} K^{-1} |\\sum_{\\xi \\in K^{-1} {\\bf Z}: \\xi \\leq N} \\hat f(\\xi) e^{2\\pi i \\xi x}| \\geq \\lambda \\} | \\lesssim_p \\lambda^{-p} \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R})}^p.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> By uniform Riemann integrability and the rapid decrease of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Chat+f%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\hat f}\" title=\"{\\hat f}\" class=\"latex\" /> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Clim_%7BK+%5Crightarrow+%5Cinfty%7D+K%5E%7B-1%7D+%5Csum_%7B%5Cxi+%5Cin+K%5E%7B-1%7D+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%3A+%5Cxi+%5Cleq+N%7D+%5Chat+f%28%5Cxi%29+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+%5Cxi+x%7D+%3D+%5Cint_%7B-%5Cinfty%7D%5EN+%5Chat+f%28%5Cxi%29+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+%5Cxi+x%7D%5C+d%5Cxi+%3D+1_%7BD+%5Cleq+N%7D+f%28x%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\lim_{K \\rightarrow \\infty} K^{-1} \\sum_{\\xi \\in K^{-1} {\\bf Z}: \\xi \\leq N} \\hat f(\\xi) e^{2\\pi i \\xi x} = \\int_{-\\infty}^N \\hat f(\\xi) e^{2\\pi i \\xi x}\\ d\\xi = 1_{D \\leq N} f(x)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\lim_{K \\rightarrow \\infty} K^{-1} \\sum_{\\xi \\in K^{-1} {\\bf Z}: \\xi \\leq N} \\hat f(\\xi) e^{2\\pi i \\xi x} = \\int_{-\\infty}^N \\hat f(\\xi) e^{2\\pi i \\xi x}\\ d\\xi = 1_{D \\leq N} f(x)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> uniformly for \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx+%5Cin+I%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x \\in I}\" title=\"{x \\in I}\" class=\"latex\" />, \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN+%5Cin+J%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N \\in J}\" title=\"{N \\in J}\" class=\"latex\" />. We conclude that \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7C+%5C%7B+x+%5Cin+I%3A+%5Csup_%7BN+%5Cin+J%7D+%7C1_%7BD+%5Cleq+N%7D+f%28x%29%7C+%3E+%5Clambda+%5C%7D+%7C+%5Clesssim_p+%5Clambda%5E%7B-p%7D+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D%5Ep.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  | \\{ x \\in I: \\sup_{N \\in J} |1_{D \\leq N} f(x)| > \\lambda \\} | \\lesssim_p \\lambda^{-p} \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R})}^p.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  | \\{ x \\in I: \\sup_{N \\in J} |1_{D \\leq N} f(x)| > \\lambda \\} | \\lesssim_p \\lambda^{-p} \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R})}^p.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> By monotone convergence we may replace \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BI%2CJ%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{I,J}\" title=\"{I,J}\" class=\"latex\" /> with \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf R}}\" title=\"{{\\bf R}}\" class=\"latex\" />, and we then obtain (v). \n<p> Finally, we assume (v) and establish (iv). By a limiting argument it suffices to establish (iv) for trigonometric polynomials <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f}\" title=\"{f}\" class=\"latex\" />, that is to say periodic functions whose Fourier coefficients are supported in <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7B-A%2C%5Cdots%2CA%5C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\{-A,\\dots,A\\}}\" title=\"{\\{-A,\\dots,A\\}}\" class=\"latex\" /> for some natural number <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BA%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{A}\" title=\"{A}\" class=\"latex\" />. Let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Ceta+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\eta \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{\\eta \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" /> be a non-zero Schwartz function with <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Chat+%5Ceta%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\hat \\eta}\" title=\"{\\hat \\eta}\" class=\"latex\" /> supported in <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5B-1%2C1%5D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{[-1,1]}\" title=\"{[-1,1]}\" class=\"latex\" />, and for a given scaling parameter <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BR%3E0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{R>0}\" title=\"{R>0}\" class=\"latex\" /> let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf_R%3A+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cbf+C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f_R: {\\bf R} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" title=\"{f_R: {\\bf R} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" class=\"latex\" /> denote the Schwartz function </p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++f_R%28x%29+%3A%3D+f%28x+%5Chbox%7B+mod+%7D+1%29+%5Ceta%28x%2FR%29.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  f_R(x) := f(x \\hbox{ mod } 1) \\eta(x/R).\" title=\"\\displaystyle  f_R(x) := f(x \\hbox{ mod } 1) \\eta(x/R).\" class=\"latex\" /></p> For \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BR%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{R}\" title=\"{R}\" class=\"latex\" /> sufficiently large one easily checks that \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7Cf_R%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D+%5Csim_%7Bp%2C%5Ceta%7D+R%5E%7B1%2Fp%7D+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\|f_R\\|_{L^p({\\bf R})} \\sim_{p,\\eta} R^{1/p} \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\|f_R\\|_{L^p({\\bf R})} \\sim_{p,\\eta} R^{1/p} \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> The Fourier transform of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf_R%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f_R}\" title=\"{f_R}\" class=\"latex\" /> can be calculated as \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Chat+f_R%28%5Cxi%29+%3D+R+%5Csum_%7Bn%3D-A%7D%5EA+%5Chat+f%28n%29+%5Chat+%5Ceta%28+R%28%5Cxi-n%29+%29+&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\hat f_R(\\xi) = R \\sum_{n=-A}^A \\hat f(n) \\hat \\eta( R(\\xi-n) ) \" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\hat f_R(\\xi) = R \\sum_{n=-A}^A \\hat f(n) \\hat \\eta( R(\\xi-n) ) \" class=\"latex\" /></p> hence (for \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BR%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{R}\" title=\"{R}\" class=\"latex\" /> large enough) \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++1_%7BD+%5Cleq+N%2B1%2F2%7D%28D%29+f_R%28x%29+%3D+%5Csum_%7Bn+%5Cleq+N%7D+%5Chat+f%28n%29+%5Ceta%28x%2FR%29+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+nx%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  1_{D \\leq N+1/2}(D) f_R(x) = \\sum_{n \\leq N} \\hat f(n) \\eta(x/R) e^{2\\pi i nx}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  1_{D \\leq N+1/2}(D) f_R(x) = \\sum_{n \\leq N} \\hat f(n) \\eta(x/R) e^{2\\pi i nx}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%3D+%5Ceta%28x%2FR%29+P_N+f%28+x+%5Chbox%7B+mod+%7D+1%29+&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  = \\eta(x/R) P_N f( x \\hbox{ mod } 1) \" title=\"\\displaystyle  = \\eta(x/R) P_N f( x \\hbox{ mod } 1) \" class=\"latex\" /></p> and thus \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Ceta%28x%2FR%29+%5Csup_%7BN+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D+%7CP_N+f%28+x+%5Chbox%7B+mod+%7D+1%29%7C+%5Cleq+%5Csup_%7BN%27+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D+%7C1_%7BD+%5Cleq+N%27%7D%28D%29+f_R%28x%29%7C.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\eta(x/R) \\sup_{N \\in {\\bf Z}} |P_N f( x \\hbox{ mod } 1)| \\leq \\sup_{N' \\in {\\bf R}} |1_{D \\leq N'}(D) f_R(x)|.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\eta(x/R) \\sup_{N \\in {\\bf Z}} |P_N f( x \\hbox{ mod } 1)| \\leq \\sup_{N' \\in {\\bf R}} |1_{D \\leq N'}(D) f_R(x)|.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> From (v) we conclude that for any \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Clambda%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\lambda}\" title=\"{\\lambda}\" class=\"latex\" /> we have \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7C+%5C%7B+x+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%3A+%5Ceta%28x%2FR%29+%5Csup_%7BN+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D+%7CP_N+f%28+x+%5Chbox%7B+mod+%7D+1%29%7C+%5Cgeq+%5Clambda+%5C%7D+%7C+%5Clesssim_%7Bp%2C%5Ceta%7D+%5Clambda%5E%7B-p%7D+R+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D%5Ep.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  | \\{ x \\in {\\bf R}: \\eta(x/R) \\sup_{N \\in {\\bf Z}} |P_N f( x \\hbox{ mod } 1)| \\geq \\lambda \\} | \\lesssim_{p,\\eta} \\lambda^{-p} R \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}^p.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  | \\{ x \\in {\\bf R}: \\eta(x/R) \\sup_{N \\in {\\bf Z}} |P_N f( x \\hbox{ mod } 1)| \\geq \\lambda \\} | \\lesssim_{p,\\eta} \\lambda^{-p} R \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}^p.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> For \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BR%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{R}\" title=\"{R}\" class=\"latex\" /> large enough, the left-hand side is \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cgtrsim_%5Ceta+R+%7C%5C%7B+x+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%3A+%5Csup_%7BN+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D+%7CP_N+f%28+x+%29%7C+%5Cgeq+c_%5Ceta+%5Clambda+%5C%7D+%7C+&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\gtrsim_\\eta R |\\{ x \\in {\\bf R}/{\\bf Z}: \\sup_{N \\in {\\bf Z}} |P_N f( x )| \\geq c_\\eta \\lambda \\} | \" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\gtrsim_\\eta R |\\{ x \\in {\\bf R}/{\\bf Z}: \\sup_{N \\in {\\bf Z}} |P_N f( x )| \\geq c_\\eta \\lambda \\} | \" class=\"latex\" /></p> for some \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bc_%5Ceta%3E0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{c_\\eta>0}\" title=\"{c_\\eta>0}\" class=\"latex\" /> depending on \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Ceta%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\eta}\" title=\"{\\eta}\" class=\"latex\" />. Dividing by \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BR%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{R}\" title=\"{R}\" class=\"latex\" /> and replacing \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Clambda%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\lambda}\" title=\"{\\lambda}\" class=\"latex\" /> by \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Clambda%2Fc_%5Ceta%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\lambda/c_\\eta}\" title=\"{\\lambda/c_\\eta}\" class=\"latex\" />, we obtain the claim (iv). \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5CBox&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\Box\" title=\"\\Box\" class=\"latex\" /> \n<p> </p>\n<blockquote>\n <b>Exercise 4</b> For \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN+%5Cgeq+1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N \\geq 1}\" title=\"{N \\geq 1}\" class=\"latex\" />, let \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BF_N%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{F_N}\" title=\"{F_N}\" class=\"latex\" /> denote the Fejér summation operators \n <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++F_N+%3A%3D+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7BN%2B1%7D+%5Csum_%7BN%27%3D0%7D%5EN+S_%7BN%27%7D.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  F_N := \\frac{1}{N+1} \\sum_{N'=0}^N S_{N'}.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  F_N := \\frac{1}{N+1} \\sum_{N'=0}^N S_{N'}.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n <ul> \n  <li>(i) For any <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+L%5E1%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in L^1({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" title=\"{f \\in L^1({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" class=\"latex\" />, establish the pointwise bound <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Csup_%7BN+%5Cgeq+1%7D+%7CF_N+f%28x%29%7C+%5Clesssim+Mf%28x%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\sup_{N \\geq 1} |F_N f(x)| \\lesssim Mf(x)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\sup_{N \\geq 1} |F_N f(x)| \\lesssim Mf(x)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> where <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BM%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{M}\" title=\"{M}\" class=\"latex\" /> is the Hardy-Littlewood maximal function <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++Mf%28x+%5Chbox%7B+mod+%7D+1%29+%3A%3D+%5Csup_%7Br%3E0%7D+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B2r%7D+%5Cint_%7Bx-r%7D%5E%7Bx%2Br%7D+%7Cf%28y+%5Chbox%7B+mod+%7D+1%29%7C%5C+dy.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  Mf(x \\hbox{ mod } 1) := \\sup_{r>0} \\frac{1}{2r} \\int_{x-r}^{x+r} |f(y \\hbox{ mod } 1)|\\ dy.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  Mf(x \\hbox{ mod } 1) := \\sup_{r>0} \\frac{1}{2r} \\int_{x-r}^{x+r} |f(y \\hbox{ mod } 1)|\\ dy.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> </li>\n  <li>(ii) Show that for <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+L%5E1%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in L^1({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" title=\"{f \\in L^1({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" class=\"latex\" />, one has <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Clim_%7BN+%5Crightarrow+%5Cinfty%7D+F_N+f%28x%29+%3D+f%28x%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\lim_{N \\rightarrow \\infty} F_N f(x) = f(x)}\" title=\"{\\lim_{N \\rightarrow \\infty} F_N f(x) = f(x)}\" class=\"latex\" /> for almost all <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x \\in {\\bf R}/{\\bf Z}}\" title=\"{x \\in {\\bf R}/{\\bf Z}}\" class=\"latex\" />. </li>\n </ul> \n</blockquote> \n<p></p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<blockquote>\n <b>Exercise 5 (Pointwise convergence of Fourier integrals)</b> Let \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1+%3C+p+%3C+%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1 < p < \\infty}\" title=\"{1 < p < \\infty}\" class=\"latex\" /> be such that the conclusion of Theorem \n <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#equivc\">3</a>(v) holds. Show that for any \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+L%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in L^p({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{f \\in L^p({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" />, one has \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Clim_%7BN+%5Crightarrow+%5Cinfty%7D+1_%7B%7CD%7C+%5Cleq+N%7D+f%28x%29+%3D+f%28x%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\lim_{N \\rightarrow \\infty} 1_{|D| \\leq N} f(x) = f(x)}\" title=\"{\\lim_{N \\rightarrow \\infty} 1_{|D| \\leq N} f(x) = f(x)}\" class=\"latex\" /> for almost all \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x \\in {\\bf R}}\" title=\"{x \\in {\\bf R}}\" class=\"latex\" />, where \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1_%7B%7CD%7C+%5Cleq+N%7D+f%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1_{|D| \\leq N} f}\" title=\"{1_{|D| \\leq N} f}\" class=\"latex\" /> is defined for Schwartz functions \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f}\" title=\"{f}\" class=\"latex\" /> by the formula \n <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++1_%7B%7CD%7C+%5Cleq+N%7D+f%28x%29+%3A%3D+%5Cint_%7B-N%7D%5EN+%5Chat+f%28%5Cxi%29+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+x+%5Cxi%7D%5C+d%5Cxi&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  1_{|D| \\leq N} f(x) := \\int_{-N}^N \\hat f(\\xi) e^{2\\pi i x \\xi}\\ d\\xi\" title=\"\\displaystyle  1_{|D| \\leq N} f(x) := \\int_{-N}^N \\hat f(\\xi) e^{2\\pi i x \\xi}\\ d\\xi\" class=\"latex\" /></p> and then extended to \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+L%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in L^p({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{f \\in L^p({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" /> by density. \n</blockquote> \n<p></p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<blockquote>\n <b>Exercise 6</b> Let \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bd+%5Cgeq+2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{d \\geq 2}\" title=\"{d \\geq 2}\" class=\"latex\" />. Suppose that \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1+%5Cleq+p+%5Cleq+2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1 \\leq p \\leq 2}\" title=\"{1 \\leq p \\leq 2}\" class=\"latex\" /> is such that one has the restriction estimate \n <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%5Chat+f+%5C%7C_%7BL%5E1%28S%5E%7Bd-1%7D%2C+d%5Csigma%29%7D+%5Clesssim_%7Bp%2Cd%7D+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\hat f \\|_{L^1(S^{d-1}, d\\sigma)} \\lesssim_{p,d} \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\hat f \\|_{L^1(S^{d-1}, d\\sigma)} \\lesssim_{p,d} \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> for all Schwartz functions \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R}^d)}\" title=\"{f \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R}^d)}\" class=\"latex\" />, where \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bd%5Csigma%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{d\\sigma}\" title=\"{d\\sigma}\" class=\"latex\" /> denotes the surface measure on the sphere \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS%5E%7Bd-1%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{S^{d-1}}\" title=\"{S^{d-1}}\" class=\"latex\" />. Conclude that \n <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%5Chat+f+%5C%7C_%7BL%5E%7Bp%2C%5Cinfty%7D%28S%5E%7Bd-1%7D%2Cd%5Csigma%29%7D+%5Clesssim_%7Bp%2Cd%7D+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\hat f \\|_{L^{p,\\infty}(S^{d-1},d\\sigma)} \\lesssim_{p,d} \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\hat f \\|_{L^{p,\\infty}(S^{d-1},d\\sigma)} \\lesssim_{p,d} \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R}^d)}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> for all Schwartz functions \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5Ed%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R}^d)}\" title=\"{f \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R}^d)}\" class=\"latex\" />. (This observation is \n <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=1097257\">due to Bourgain</a>.) In particular, by Marcinkiewicz interpolation, \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BR_%7BS%5E%7Bd-1%7D%7D%28p+%5Crightarrow+1%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{R_{S^{d-1}}(p \\rightarrow 1)}\" title=\"{R_{S^{d-1}}(p \\rightarrow 1)}\" class=\"latex\" /> implies \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BR_%7BS%5E%7Bd-1%7D%7D%28p+%5Crightarrow+q%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{R_{S^{d-1}}(p \\rightarrow q)}\" title=\"{R_{S^{d-1}}(p \\rightarrow q)}\" class=\"latex\" /> for all \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1+%5Cleq+q+%3C+p%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1 \\leq q < p}\" title=\"{1 \\leq q < p}\" class=\"latex\" />. (\n <em>Hint:</em> adapt some parts of the argument used to get from (iii) to (i) in Proposition \n <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#equivc\">3</a>, using rotation invariance as a substitute for translation invariance. (But the translational symmetry of the restriction problem – more precisely, the ability to translate a function \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f}\" title=\"{f}\" class=\"latex\" /> in physical space without changing the absolute value of its Fourier transform – will also be useful.)) \n</blockquote> \n<p></p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> We are now ready to establish Kolmogorov’s theorem (Theorem <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#main\">2</a>(i)); our arguments are loosely based on the original construction of Kolmogorov (though he was not in possession at the time of the Stein maximal principle). In view of the equivalence between (ii) and (v) in Theorem <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#equivc\">3</a>, it suffices to show that the maximal operator </p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++f%5Cmapsto+%5Csup_%7BN+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D+%7C1_%7BD+%5Cleq+N%7D+f%7C&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  f\\mapsto \\sup_{N \\in {\\bf R}} |1_{D \\leq N} f|\" title=\"\\displaystyle  f\\mapsto \\sup_{N \\in {\\bf R}} |1_{D \\leq N} f|\" class=\"latex\" /></p> fails to be of weak-type \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%281%2C1%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(1,1)}\" title=\"{(1,1)}\" class=\"latex\" /> on Schwartz functions. Recalling that the Hilbert transform \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++Hf%28x%29+%3A%3D+p.v.+%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Cfrac%7Bf%28y%29%7D%7Bx-y%7D%5C+dy&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  Hf(x) := p.v. \\int_{\\bf R} \\frac{f(y)}{x-y}\\ dy\" title=\"\\displaystyle  Hf(x) := p.v. \\int_{\\bf R} \\frac{f(y)}{x-y}\\ dy\" class=\"latex\" /></p> is also a Fourier multiplier operator \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++H+%3D+-%5Cpi+i+%5Cmathrm%7Bsgn%7D%28D%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  H = -\\pi i \\mathrm{sgn}(D)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  H = -\\pi i \\mathrm{sgn}(D)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> some routine calculations then show that \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++1_%7BD+%5Cleq+N%7D+f%28x%29+%3D+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B2%7D+f%28x%29+%2B+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B2%5Cpi+i%7D+p.v.+%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Cfrac%7Bf%28y%29%7D%7Bx-y%7D+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+N%28x-y%29%7D%5C+dy&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  1_{D \\leq N} f(x) = \\frac{1}{2} f(x) + \\frac{1}{2\\pi i} p.v. \\int_{\\bf R} \\frac{f(y)}{x-y} e^{2\\pi i N(x-y)}\\ dy\" title=\"\\displaystyle  1_{D \\leq N} f(x) = \\frac{1}{2} f(x) + \\frac{1}{2\\pi i} p.v. \\int_{\\bf R} \\frac{f(y)}{x-y} e^{2\\pi i N(x-y)}\\ dy\" class=\"latex\" /></p> for any Schwartz function \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f}\" title=\"{f}\" class=\"latex\" />. By the triangle inequality, it then suffices to show that the maximal operator \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7B%5Cmathcal+C%7D+f%28x%29+%3A%3D+%5Csup_%7BN+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D+%7Cp.v.+%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Cfrac%7Bf%28y%29%7D%7Bx-y%7D+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+N%28x-y%29%7D%5C+dy%7C&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathcal C} f(x) := \\sup_{N \\in {\\bf R}} |p.v. \\int_{\\bf R} \\frac{f(y)}{x-y} e^{2\\pi i N(x-y)}\\ dy|\" title=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathcal C} f(x) := \\sup_{N \\in {\\bf R}} |p.v. \\int_{\\bf R} \\frac{f(y)}{x-y} e^{2\\pi i N(x-y)}\\ dy|\" class=\"latex\" /></p> fails to be of weak type \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%281%2C1%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(1,1)}\" title=\"{(1,1)}\" class=\"latex\" /> on Schwartz functions. \n<p> To motivate the construction, note from a naive application of the triangle inequality that </p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7B%5Cmathcal+C%7D+f%28x%29+%5Cleq+%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Cfrac%7B%7Cf%28y%29%7C%7D%7B%7Cx-y%7C%7D%5C+dy.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathcal C} f(x) \\leq \\int_{\\bf R} \\frac{|f(y)|}{|x-y|}\\ dy.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathcal C} f(x) \\leq \\int_{\\bf R} \\frac{|f(y)|}{|x-y|}\\ dy.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> If the function \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx+%5Cmapsto+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B%7Cx%7C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x \\mapsto \\frac{1}{|x|}}\" title=\"{x \\mapsto \\frac{1}{|x|}}\" class=\"latex\" /> was absolutely integrable, then by Young’s inequality we would conclude that the maximal operator \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cmathcal+C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\mathcal C}}\" title=\"{{\\mathcal C}}\" class=\"latex\" /> was strong type \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%281%2C1%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(1,1)}\" title=\"{(1,1)}\" class=\"latex\" />, and hence also weak type \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%281%2C1%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(1,1)}\" title=\"{(1,1)}\" class=\"latex\" />. Thus any counterexample must somehow exploit the logarithmic divergence of the integral of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B%7Cx%7C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\frac{1}{|x|}}\" title=\"{\\frac{1}{|x|}}\" class=\"latex\" />. However, there are two potential sources of cancellation that could ameliorate this divergence: the sign \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathrm%7Bsgn%7D%28x-y%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\mathrm{sgn}(x-y)}\" title=\"{\\mathrm{sgn}(x-y)}\" class=\"latex\" /> of the Hilbert kernel \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7Bx-y%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\frac{1}{x-y}}\" title=\"{\\frac{1}{x-y}}\" class=\"latex\" />, and the phase \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Be%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+N%28x-y%29%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{e^{2\\pi i N(x-y)}}\" title=\"{e^{2\\pi i N(x-y)}}\" class=\"latex\" />. But because of the supremum in \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N}\" title=\"{N}\" class=\"latex\" />, we can select the frequency parameter \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N}\" title=\"{N}\" class=\"latex\" /> as we please, as long as it depends only on \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x}\" title=\"{x}\" class=\"latex\" /> and not on \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7By%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{y}\" title=\"{y}\" class=\"latex\" />. The idea is then to choose \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N}\" title=\"{N}\" class=\"latex\" /> (and the support of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f}\" title=\"{f}\" class=\"latex\" />) to remove both sources of cancellation as much as possible. \n<p> We turn to the details. Let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bn%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{n}\" title=\"{n}\" class=\"latex\" /> be a large natural number, and then select <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bn%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{n}\" title=\"{n}\" class=\"latex\" /> widely separated frequency scales </p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++1+%3C+N_1+%3C+%5Cdots+%3C+N_n.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  1 < N_1 < \\dots < N_n.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  1 < N_1 < \\dots < N_n.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> In order to assist with removing cancellation in the phases \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Be%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+N%28x-y%29%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{e^{2\\pi i N(x-y)}}\" title=\"{e^{2\\pi i N(x-y)}}\" class=\"latex\" /> later, we will require these scales \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN_1%2C%5Cdots%2CN_n%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N_1,\\dots,N_n}\" title=\"{N_1,\\dots,N_n}\" class=\"latex\" /> to be integers. The precise choice of scales is not too important as long as they are widely separated and integer valued, but for sake of concreteness one could for instance set \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN_j+%3A%3D+100%5E%7Bj%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N_j := 100^{j}}\" title=\"{N_j := 100^{j}}\" class=\"latex\" />. Let \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cvarphi+%5Cin+C%5E%5Cinfty_c%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\varphi \\in C^\\infty_c({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{\\varphi \\in C^\\infty_c({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" /> be a bump function of total mass \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1}\" title=\"{1}\" class=\"latex\" /> supported on \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5B-1%2C1%5D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{[-1,1]}\" title=\"{[-1,1]}\" class=\"latex\" />, and let \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f}\" title=\"{f}\" class=\"latex\" /> be the Schwartz function \n<a name=\"faj\"><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++f%28x%29+%3A%3D+%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+N_j+%5Cvarphi%28+N_j%28x-j%29+%29%2C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%289%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  f(x) := \\sum_{j=1}^n N_j \\varphi( N_j(x-j) ), \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (9)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  f(x) := \\sum_{j=1}^n N_j \\varphi( N_j(x-j) ), \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (9)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> </a> thus \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f}\" title=\"{f}\" class=\"latex\" /> is an approximation (in a weak sense) to the sum of Dirac masses \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+%5Cdelta_j%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\sum_{j=1}^n \\delta_j}\" title=\"{\\sum_{j=1}^n \\delta_j}\" class=\"latex\" />, with the frequency scale of the approximation to \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cdelta_j%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\delta_j}\" title=\"{\\delta_j}\" class=\"latex\" /> increasing rapidly in \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bj%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{j}\" title=\"{j}\" class=\"latex\" />. We easily compute the \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BL%5E1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{L^1}\" title=\"{L^1}\" class=\"latex\" /> norm of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f}\" title=\"{f}\" class=\"latex\" />: \n<a name=\"fl1\"><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5E1%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D+%3D+%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+1+%3D+n.+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%2810%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\|f\\|_{L^1({\\bf R})} = \\sum_{j=1}^n 1 = n. \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (10)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\|f\\|_{L^1({\\bf R})} = \\sum_{j=1}^n 1 = n. \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (10)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> </a> \n<p> Now we estimate <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cmathcal+C%7Df%28x%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\mathcal C}f(x)}\" title=\"{{\\mathcal C}f(x)}\" class=\"latex\" /> for <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x}\" title=\"{x}\" class=\"latex\" /> in the interval <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Bj_0%2B0.1%2C+j_0%2B0.9%5D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{[j_0+0.1, j_0+0.9]}\" title=\"{[j_0+0.1, j_0+0.9]}\" class=\"latex\" /> for some natural number <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bn%2F3+%5Cleq+j_0+%5Cleq+2n%2F3%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{n/3 \\leq j_0 \\leq 2n/3}\" title=\"{n/3 \\leq j_0 \\leq 2n/3}\" class=\"latex\" />; note the set of all such <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x}\" title=\"{x}\" class=\"latex\" /> has measure <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Csim+n%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\sim n}\" title=\"{\\sim n}\" class=\"latex\" />. In this range we will test the maximal operator at the frequency cutoff <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN+%3D+N_%7Bj_0%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N = N_{j_0}}\" title=\"{N = N_{j_0}}\" class=\"latex\" />: </p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7B%5Cmathcal+C%7D+f%28x%29+%5Cgeq+%7Cp.v.+%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Cfrac%7Bf%28y%29%7D%7Bx-y%7D+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+N_%7Bj_0%7D%28x-y%29%7D%5C+dy%7C.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathcal C} f(x) \\geq |p.v. \\int_{\\bf R} \\frac{f(y)}{x-y} e^{2\\pi i N_{j_0}(x-y)}\\ dy|.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathcal C} f(x) \\geq |p.v. \\int_{\\bf R} \\frac{f(y)}{x-y} e^{2\\pi i N_{j_0}(x-y)}\\ dy|.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> As \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f}\" title=\"{f}\" class=\"latex\" /> is supported in \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cbigcup_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+%5Bj-N_j%5E%7B-1%7D%2C+j%2BN_j%5E%7B-1%7D%5D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\bigcup_{j=1}^n [j-N_j^{-1}, j+N_j^{-1}]}\" title=\"{\\bigcup_{j=1}^n [j-N_j^{-1}, j+N_j^{-1}]}\" class=\"latex\" />, we see (for \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bn%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{n}\" title=\"{n}\" class=\"latex\" /> large enough) that \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x}\" title=\"{x}\" class=\"latex\" /> avoids the support of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f}\" title=\"{f}\" class=\"latex\" /> and we can replace the principal value integral with the ordinary integral. Substituting \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#faj\">(9)</a>, we conclude that \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7B%5Cmathcal+C%7D+f%28x%29+%5Cgeq+%7C%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+%5Cint_%7B%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D+%5Cfrac%7B%5Cvarphi%28t%29%7D%7Bx-j-N_j%5E%7B-1%7D+t%7D+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+N_%7Bj_0%7D%28x-j-N_j%5E%7B-1%7D+t%29%7D%5C+dt%7C.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathcal C} f(x) \\geq |\\sum_{j=1}^n \\int_{{\\bf R}} \\frac{\\varphi(t)}{x-j-N_j^{-1} t} e^{2\\pi i N_{j_0}(x-j-N_j^{-1} t)}\\ dt|.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathcal C} f(x) \\geq |\\sum_{j=1}^n \\int_{{\\bf R}} \\frac{\\varphi(t)}{x-j-N_j^{-1} t} e^{2\\pi i N_{j_0}(x-j-N_j^{-1} t)}\\ dt|.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> As \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN_%7Bj_0%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N_{j_0}}\" title=\"{N_{j_0}}\" class=\"latex\" /> is an integer, the phase \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Be%5E%7B-2%5Cpi+i+N_%7Bj_0%7D+j%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{e^{-2\\pi i N_{j_0} j}}\" title=\"{e^{-2\\pi i N_{j_0} j}}\" class=\"latex\" /> is equal to \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1}\" title=\"{1}\" class=\"latex\" />. We also cancel out the phase \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Be%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+N_%7Bj_0%7D+x%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{e^{2\\pi i N_{j_0} x}}\" title=\"{e^{2\\pi i N_{j_0} x}}\" class=\"latex\" /> as being independent of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bj%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{j}\" title=\"{j}\" class=\"latex\" />, thus \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7B%5Cmathcal+C%7D+f%28x%29+%5Cgeq+%7C%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+%5Cint_%7B%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D+%5Cfrac%7B%5Cvarphi%28t%29%7D%7Bx-j-N_j%5E%7B-1%7D+t%7D+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+%5Cfrac%7BN_%7Bj_0%7D%7D%7BN_j%7D+t%7D%5C+dt%7C.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathcal C} f(x) \\geq |\\sum_{j=1}^n \\int_{{\\bf R}} \\frac{\\varphi(t)}{x-j-N_j^{-1} t} e^{2\\pi i \\frac{N_{j_0}}{N_j} t}\\ dt|.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathcal C} f(x) \\geq |\\sum_{j=1}^n \\int_{{\\bf R}} \\frac{\\varphi(t)}{x-j-N_j^{-1} t} e^{2\\pi i \\frac{N_{j_0}}{N_j} t}\\ dt|.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> For \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bj+%5Cleq+j_0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{j \\leq j_0}\" title=\"{j \\leq j_0}\" class=\"latex\" />, we exploit the oscillatory nature of the phase \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Be%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+%5Cfrac%7BN_%7Bj_0%7D%7D%7BN_j%7D+t%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{e^{2\\pi i \\frac{N_{j_0}}{N_j} t}}\" title=\"{e^{2\\pi i \\frac{N_{j_0}}{N_j} t}}\" class=\"latex\" /> through an integration by parts, leading to the bound \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Cfrac%7B%5Cvarphi%28t%29%7D%7Bx-j-N_j%5E%7B-1%7D+t%7D+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+%5Cfrac%7BN_%7Bj_0%7D%7D%7BN_j%7D+t%7D%5C+dt+%5Clesssim_%5Cvarphi+%5Cfrac%7BN_j%7D%7BN_%7Bj_0%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\int_{\\bf R} \\frac{\\varphi(t)}{x-j-N_j^{-1} t} e^{2\\pi i \\frac{N_{j_0}}{N_j} t}\\ dt \\lesssim_\\varphi \\frac{N_j}{N_{j_0}}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\int_{\\bf R} \\frac{\\varphi(t)}{x-j-N_j^{-1} t} e^{2\\pi i \\frac{N_{j_0}}{N_j} t}\\ dt \\lesssim_\\varphi \\frac{N_j}{N_{j_0}}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> (one could even gain a factor of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B%5Clangle+j-j_0+%5Crangle%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\frac{1}{\\langle j-j_0 \\rangle}}\" title=\"{\\frac{1}{\\langle j-j_0 \\rangle}}\" class=\"latex\" /> here if desired, but we will not need it). Summing, we have \n<a name=\"jeo\"><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5E%7Bj_0%7D+%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Cfrac%7B%5Cvarphi%28t%29%7D%7Bx-j-N_j%5E%7B-1%7D+t%7D+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+%5Cfrac%7BN_%7Bj_0%7D%7D%7BN_j%7D+t%7D%5C+dt+%5Clesssim_%5Cvarphi+1.+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%2811%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{j=1}^{j_0} \\int_{\\bf R} \\frac{\\varphi(t)}{x-j-N_j^{-1} t} e^{2\\pi i \\frac{N_{j_0}}{N_j} t}\\ dt \\lesssim_\\varphi 1. \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (11)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{j=1}^{j_0} \\int_{\\bf R} \\frac{\\varphi(t)}{x-j-N_j^{-1} t} e^{2\\pi i \\frac{N_{j_0}}{N_j} t}\\ dt \\lesssim_\\varphi 1. \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (11)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> </a> For \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bj+%3E+j_0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{j > j_0}\" title=\"{j > j_0}\" class=\"latex\" />, we instead exploit the near-constant nature of the phase \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Be%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+%5Cfrac%7BN_%7Bj_0%7D%7D%7BN_j%7D+t%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{e^{2\\pi i \\frac{N_{j_0}}{N_j} t}}\" title=\"{e^{2\\pi i \\frac{N_{j_0}}{N_j} t}}\" class=\"latex\" /> by writing \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+%5Cfrac%7BN_%7Bj_0%7D%7D%7BN_j%7D+t%7D+%3D+1+%2B+O%28+%5Cfrac%7BN_%7Bj_0%7D%7D%7BN_j%7D+%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  e^{2\\pi i \\frac{N_{j_0}}{N_j} t} = 1 + O( \\frac{N_{j_0}}{N_j} )\" title=\"\\displaystyle  e^{2\\pi i \\frac{N_{j_0}}{N_j} t} = 1 + O( \\frac{N_{j_0}}{N_j} )\" class=\"latex\" /></p> and similarly \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7Bx-j-N_j%5E%7B-1%7D+t%7D+%3D+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7Bx-j%7D+%2B+O%28+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B%28j-j_0%29%5E2%7D%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\frac{1}{x-j-N_j^{-1} t} = \\frac{1}{x-j} + O( \\frac{1}{(j-j_0)^2})\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\frac{1}{x-j-N_j^{-1} t} = \\frac{1}{x-j} + O( \\frac{1}{(j-j_0)^2})\" class=\"latex\" /></p> to conclude that \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Cfrac%7B%5Cvarphi%28t%29%7D%7Bx-j-N_j%5E%7B-1%7D+t%7D+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+%5Cfrac%7BN_%7Bj_0%7D%7D%7BN_j%7D+t%7D%5C+dt+%3D+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7Bj-j_0%7D+%2B+O%28+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B%28j-j_0%29%5E2%7D+%2B+%5Cfrac%7BN_%7Bj_0%7D%7D%7BN_j%7D+%29.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\int_{\\bf R} \\frac{\\varphi(t)}{x-j-N_j^{-1} t} e^{2\\pi i \\frac{N_{j_0}}{N_j} t}\\ dt = \\frac{1}{j-j_0} + O( \\frac{1}{(j-j_0)^2} + \\frac{N_{j_0}}{N_j} ).\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\int_{\\bf R} \\frac{\\varphi(t)}{x-j-N_j^{-1} t} e^{2\\pi i \\frac{N_{j_0}}{N_j} t}\\ dt = \\frac{1}{j-j_0} + O( \\frac{1}{(j-j_0)^2} + \\frac{N_{j_0}}{N_j} ).\" class=\"latex\" /></p> Summing and combining with \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#jeo\">(11)</a>, we conclude (from the rapidly increasing nature of the \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN_j%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N_j}\" title=\"{N_j}\" class=\"latex\" />) that \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Cfrac%7B%5Cvarphi%28t%29%7D%7Bx-j-N_j%5E%7B-1%7D+t%7D+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+%5Cfrac%7BN_%7Bj_0%7D%7D%7BN_j%7D+t%7D%5C+dt+%3D+%5Clog+n+%2B+O_%5Cvarphi%28+1+%29%2C&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{j=1}^n \\int_{\\bf R} \\frac{\\varphi(t)}{x-j-N_j^{-1} t} e^{2\\pi i \\frac{N_{j_0}}{N_j} t}\\ dt = \\log n + O_\\varphi( 1 ),\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{j=1}^n \\int_{\\bf R} \\frac{\\varphi(t)}{x-j-N_j^{-1} t} e^{2\\pi i \\frac{N_{j_0}}{N_j} t}\\ dt = \\log n + O_\\varphi( 1 ),\" class=\"latex\" /></p> and thus (for \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bn%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{n}\" title=\"{n}\" class=\"latex\" /> large) \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7C%5C%7B+x%3A+%7B%5Cmathcal+C%7D+f%28x%29+%5Cgeq+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B2%7D+%5Clog+n+%5C%7D%7C+%5Cgtrsim+n.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  |\\{ x: {\\mathcal C} f(x) \\geq \\frac{1}{2} \\log n \\}| \\gtrsim n.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  |\\{ x: {\\mathcal C} f(x) \\geq \\frac{1}{2} \\log n \\}| \\gtrsim n.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> Comparing this with \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#fl1\">(10)</a> we contradict the conclusion of Theorem \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#equivc\">3</a>(iv), giving the claim. \n<p> </p>\n<blockquote>\n <b>Remark 7</b> In 1926, Kolmogorov refined his construction to obtain a function \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+L%5E1%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in L^1({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" title=\"{f \\in L^1({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" class=\"latex\" /> whose Fourier sums \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS_N+f%28x%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{S_N f(x)}\" title=\"{S_N f(x)}\" class=\"latex\" /> diverged everywhere (not just almost everywhere). \n</blockquote> \n<p></p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<blockquote>\n <b>Exercise 8 (Rademacher-Menshov theorem)</b> \n <a name=\"radmens\"></a> \n <ul> \n  <li>(i) Let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf_1%2C%5Cdots%2Cf_n+%5Cin+L%5E2%28X%2C%5Cmu%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f_1,\\dots,f_n \\in L^2(X,\\mu)}\" title=\"{f_1,\\dots,f_n \\in L^2(X,\\mu)}\" class=\"latex\" /> be some square-integrable functions on a probability space <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28X%2C%5Cmu%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(X,\\mu)}\" title=\"{(X,\\mu)}\" class=\"latex\" />, with <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bn%3D2%5EK%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{n=2^K}\" title=\"{n=2^K}\" class=\"latex\" /> a power of two. By performing a suitable Whitney type decomposition (similar to that used in Section 3 of <a href=\"https://terrytao.wordpress.com/2020/03/29/247b-notes-1-restriction-theory/\">Notes 1</a>), establish the pointwise bound <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Csup_%7B0+%5Cleq+N+%3C+n%7D+%7C%5Csum_%7B1+%5Cleq+j+%5Cleq+N%7D+f_j%28x%29%7C+%5Clesssim+%5Csum_%7B0+%5Cleq+k+%3C+K%7D+%28%5Csum_%7BJ%3A+%7CJ%7C%3D2%5Ek%7D+%7C%5Csum_%7Bj+%5Cin+J%7D+f%28x%29%7C%5E2%29%5E%7B1%2F2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\sup_{0 \\leq N < n} |\\sum_{1 \\leq j \\leq N} f_j(x)| \\lesssim \\sum_{0 \\leq k < K} (\\sum_{J: |J|=2^k} |\\sum_{j \\in J} f(x)|^2)^{1/2}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\sup_{0 \\leq N < n} |\\sum_{1 \\leq j \\leq N} f_j(x)| \\lesssim \\sum_{0 \\leq k < K} (\\sum_{J: |J|=2^k} |\\sum_{j \\in J} f(x)|^2)^{1/2}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> where for each <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%3D0%2C%5Cdots%2CK%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k=0,\\dots,K}\" title=\"{k=0,\\dots,K}\" class=\"latex\" />, <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BJ%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{J}\" title=\"{J}\" class=\"latex\" /> ranges over dyadic intervals of the form <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BJ+%3D+%5Bj2%5Ek%2B1%2C+%28j%2B1%292%5Ek%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{J = [j2^k+1, (j+1)2^k)}\" title=\"{J = [j2^k+1, (j+1)2^k)}\" class=\"latex\" /> with <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B0+%5Cleq+j+%3C+2%5E%7BK-k%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{0 \\leq j < 2^{K-k}}\" title=\"{0 \\leq j < 2^{K-k}}\" class=\"latex\" />. If furthermore the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf_1%2C%5Cdots%2Cf_n%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f_1,\\dots,f_n}\" title=\"{f_1,\\dots,f_n}\" class=\"latex\" /> are orthogonal to each other, establish the maximal inequality <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%5Csup_%7B0+%5Cleq+N+%5Cleq+n%7D+%7C%5Csum_%7B1+%5Cleq+j+%5Cleq+N%7D+f_j%7C+%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28X%2C%5Cmu%29%7D+%5Clesssim+%28%5Clog+n%29+%28%5Csum_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5En+%5C%7Cf_j%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28X%2C%5Cmu%29%7D%5E2%29%5E%7B1%2F2%7D.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sup_{0 \\leq N \\leq n} |\\sum_{1 \\leq j \\leq N} f_j| \\|_{L^2(X,\\mu)} \\lesssim (\\log n) (\\sum_{j=1}^n \\|f_j\\|_{L^2(X,\\mu)}^2)^{1/2}.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sup_{0 \\leq N \\leq n} |\\sum_{1 \\leq j \\leq N} f_j| \\|_{L^2(X,\\mu)} \\lesssim (\\log n) (\\sum_{j=1}^n \\|f_j\\|_{L^2(X,\\mu)}^2)^{1/2}.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> </li>\n  <li>(ii) If <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+L%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in L^2({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" title=\"{f \\in L^2({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" class=\"latex\" /> is a trigonometric polynomial with at most <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bn%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{n}\" title=\"{n}\" class=\"latex\" /> non-zero coefficients for some <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bn+%5Cgeq+1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{n \\geq 1}\" title=\"{n \\geq 1}\" class=\"latex\" />, use part (i) to establish the bound <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%5Csup_%7BN+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D+%7CP_N+f%7C+%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D+%5Clesssim+%28%5Clog+n%29+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sup_{N \\in {\\bf Z}} |P_N f| \\|_{L^2({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})} \\lesssim (\\log n) \\|f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sup_{N \\in {\\bf Z}} |P_N f| \\|_{L^2({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})} \\lesssim (\\log n) \\|f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> </li>\n  <li>(iii) If <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cin+L%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f \\in L^2({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" title=\"{f \\in L^2({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z})}\" class=\"latex\" /> lies in the Sobolev space <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++H%5Es%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29+%3A%3D+%5C%7B+f+%5Cin+L%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%3A+%5Csum_%7Bj+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D+%5Clangle+j+%5Crangle%5E%7B2s%7D+%7C%5Chat+f%28j%29%7C%5E2+%3C+%5Cinfty+%5C%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  H^s({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z}) := \\{ f \\in L^2({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z}): \\sum_{j \\in {\\bf Z}} \\langle j \\rangle^{2s} |\\hat f(j)|^2 < \\infty \\}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  H^s({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z}) := \\{ f \\in L^2({\\bf R}/{\\bf Z}): \\sum_{j \\in {\\bf Z}} \\langle j \\rangle^{2s} |\\hat f(j)|^2 < \\infty \\}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> for some <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bs%3E0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{s>0}\" title=\"{s>0}\" class=\"latex\" />, use (ii) to show that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Clim_%7BN+%5Crightarrow+%5Cinfty%7D+S_N+f%28x%29+%3D+f%28x%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\lim_{N \\rightarrow \\infty} S_N f(x) = f(x)}\" title=\"{\\lim_{N \\rightarrow \\infty} S_N f(x) = f(x)}\" class=\"latex\" /> for almost every <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x \\in {\\bf R}}\" title=\"{x \\in {\\bf R}}\" class=\"latex\" />. </li>\n </ul> \n</blockquote> \n<p></p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p align=\"center\"><b> — 2. Carleson’s theorem — </b></p> \n<p> We now begin the proof of Carleson’s theorem (Theorem <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#main\">2</a>(ii)), loosely following the <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=1783613\">arguments of Lacey and Thiele</a> (we briefly comment on other approaches at the end of these notes). In view of Proposition <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#equivc\">3</a>, it suffices to establish the weak-type <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%282%2C2%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(2,2)}\" title=\"{(2,2)}\" class=\"latex\" /> bound </p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%5Csup_%7BN+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D+%7C1_%7BD+%5Cleq+N%7D+f%7C+%5C%7C_%7BL%5E%7B2%2C%5Cinfty%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D+%5Clesssim+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sup_{N \\in {\\bf R}} |1_{D \\leq N} f| \\|_{L^{2,\\infty}({\\bf R})} \\lesssim \\|f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R})}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sup_{N \\in {\\bf R}} |1_{D \\leq N} f| \\|_{L^{2,\\infty}({\\bf R})} \\lesssim \\|f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> for Schwartz functions \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f}\" title=\"{f}\" class=\"latex\" />. Because of the supremum, the expression \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Csup_%7BN+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D+%7C1_%7BD+%5Cleq+N%7D+f%7C%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\sup_{N \\in {\\bf R}} |1_{D \\leq N} f|}\" title=\"{\\sup_{N \\in {\\bf R}} |1_{D \\leq N} f|}\" class=\"latex\" /> depends sublinearly on \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f}\" title=\"{f}\" class=\"latex\" /> rather than linearly; however there is a trick to reduce matters to considering linear estimates. By selecting, for each \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x}\" title=\"{x}\" class=\"latex\" />, \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN%28x%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N(x)}\" title=\"{N(x)}\" class=\"latex\" /> to be a frequency which attains (or nearly attains) the supremal value of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7C1_%7BD+%5Cleq+N%28x%29%7D+f%28x%29%7C%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{|1_{D \\leq N(x)} f(x)|}\" title=\"{|1_{D \\leq N(x)} f(x)|}\" class=\"latex\" />, it suffices to establish the linearised estimate \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+1_%7BD+%5Cleq+N%28X%29%7D+f+%5C%7C_%7BL%5E%7B2%2C%5Cinfty%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D+%5Clesssim+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| 1_{D \\leq N(X)} f \\|_{L^{2,\\infty}({\\bf R})} \\lesssim \\|f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R})}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| 1_{D \\leq N(X)} f \\|_{L^{2,\\infty}({\\bf R})} \\lesssim \\|f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> uniformly for all measurable functions \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN%3A+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N: {\\bf R} \\rightarrow {\\bf R}}\" title=\"{N: {\\bf R} \\rightarrow {\\bf R}}\" class=\"latex\" />, where \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1_%7BD+%5Cleq+N%28X%29%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1_{D \\leq N(X)}}\" title=\"{1_{D \\leq N(X)}}\" class=\"latex\" /> is the operator \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++1_%7BD+%5Cleq+N%28X%29%7D+f%28x%29+%3D+%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+1_%7B%5Cxi+%5Cleq+N%28x%29%7D+%5Chat+f%28%5Cxi%29+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+x+%5Cxi%7D%5C+d%5Cxi.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  1_{D \\leq N(X)} f(x) = \\int_{\\bf R} 1_{\\xi \\leq N(x)} \\hat f(\\xi) e^{2\\pi i x \\xi}\\ d\\xi.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  1_{D \\leq N(X)} f(x) = \\int_{\\bf R} 1_{\\xi \\leq N(x)} \\hat f(\\xi) e^{2\\pi i x \\xi}\\ d\\xi.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> One can think of this operator \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1_%7BD+%5Cleq+N%28X%29%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1_{D \\leq N(X)}}\" title=\"{1_{D \\leq N(X)}}\" class=\"latex\" /> as the (Kohn-Nirenberg) quantisation of the rough symbol \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28x%2C%5Cxi%29+%5Cmapsto+1_%7B%5Cxi+%5Cleq+N%28x%29%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(x,\\xi) \\mapsto 1_{\\xi \\leq N(x)}}\" title=\"{(x,\\xi) \\mapsto 1_{\\xi \\leq N(x)}}\" class=\"latex\" />. Unfortunately this symbol is far too rough for us to be able to use pseudodifferential operator tools from the \n<a href=\"https://terrytao.wordpress.com/2020/05/02/247b-notes-3-pseudodifferential-operators/\">previous set of notes</a>. Nevertheless, the “time-frequency analysis” mindset of trying to efficiently decompose phase space into rectangles consistent with the uncertainty principle will remain very useful. \n<p> The next step is to dualise the weak <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BL%5E%7B2%2C%5Cinfty%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{L^{2,\\infty}}\" title=\"{L^{2,\\infty}}\" class=\"latex\" /> norm to linearise the dependence on <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f}\" title=\"{f}\" class=\"latex\" /> even further: </p>\n<p> </p>\n<blockquote>\n <b>Exercise 9</b> Let \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1+%3C+p+%3C+%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1 < p < \\infty}\" title=\"{1 < p < \\infty}\" class=\"latex\" />, let \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28X%2C%5Cmu%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(X,\\mu)}\" title=\"{(X,\\mu)}\" class=\"latex\" /> be a \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Csigma%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\sigma}\" title=\"{\\sigma}\" class=\"latex\" />-finite measure space, let \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%3A+X+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cbf+C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f: X \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" title=\"{f: X \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" class=\"latex\" /> be a measurable function, and let \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BA%3E0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{A>0}\" title=\"{A>0}\" class=\"latex\" />. Show that the following claims are equivalent (up to changes in the implied constants in the asymptotic notation): \n <ul> \n  <li>(i) One has <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7C+f%5C%7C_%7BL%5E%7Bp%2C%5Cinfty%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D+%5Clesssim_p+A%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\| f\\|_{L^{p,\\infty}({\\bf R})} \\lesssim_p A}\" title=\"{\\| f\\|_{L^{p,\\infty}({\\bf R})} \\lesssim_p A}\" class=\"latex\" />. </li>\n  <li>(ii) For every subset <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BE%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{E}\" title=\"{E}\" class=\"latex\" /> of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BX%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{X}\" title=\"{X}\" class=\"latex\" /> of finite measure, the function <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f}\" title=\"{f}\" class=\"latex\" /> is absolutely integrable on <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BE%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{E}\" title=\"{E}\" class=\"latex\" />, and <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cint_E+f%28x%29%5C+d%5Cmu%28x%29+%5Clesssim_p+A+%5Cmu%28E%29%5E%7B1%2Fp%27%7D.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\int_E f(x)\\ d\\mu(x) \\lesssim_p A \\mu(E)^{1/p'}.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\int_E f(x)\\ d\\mu(x) \\lesssim_p A \\mu(E)^{1/p'}.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> </li>\n </ul> \n</blockquote> \n<p></p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> In view of this exercise, we see that it suffices to obtain the bound <a name=\"est\"></a></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><a name=\"est\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+1_E%28X%29+1_%7BD+%5Cleq+N%28X%29%7D+f%5C+dx+%5Clesssim+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D+%7CE%7C%5E%7B1%2F2%7D+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%2812%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\int_{\\bf R} 1_E(X) 1_{D \\leq N(X)} f\\ dx \\lesssim \\|f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R})} |E|^{1/2} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (12)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\int_{\\bf R} 1_E(X) 1_{D \\leq N(X)} f\\ dx \\lesssim \\|f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R})} |E|^{1/2} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (12)\" class=\"latex\" /></a></p>\n<a name=\"est\"> </a> for all Schwartz \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f}\" title=\"{f}\" class=\"latex\" />, all sets \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BE+%5Csubset+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{E \\subset {\\bf R}}\" title=\"{E \\subset {\\bf R}}\" class=\"latex\" /> of finite measure, and all measurable functions \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN%3A+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N: {\\bf R} \\rightarrow {\\bf R}}\" title=\"{N: {\\bf R} \\rightarrow {\\bf R}}\" class=\"latex\" />. Actually only the restriction of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N}\" title=\"{N}\" class=\"latex\" /> to \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BE%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{E}\" title=\"{E}\" class=\"latex\" /> is relevant here, so one can view \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N}\" title=\"{N}\" class=\"latex\" /> as a function just on \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BE%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{E}\" title=\"{E}\" class=\"latex\" /> if desired. The operator \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1_E%28X%29+1_%7BD+%5Cleq+N%28X%29%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1_E(X) 1_{D \\leq N(X)}}\" title=\"{1_E(X) 1_{D \\leq N(X)}}\" class=\"latex\" /> can be viewed as the quantisation of the (very rough) symbol \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28x%2C%5Cxi%29+%5Cmapsto+1_E%28x%29+1_%7B%5Cxi+%5Cleq+N%28x%29%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(x,\\xi) \\mapsto 1_E(x) 1_{\\xi \\leq N(x)}}\" title=\"{(x,\\xi) \\mapsto 1_E(x) 1_{\\xi \\leq N(x)}}\" class=\"latex\" />, that is to say the indicator function of the region lying underneath the graph \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7B+%28x%2CN%28x%29%29%3A+x+%5Cin+E+%5C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\{ (x,N(x)): x \\in E \\}}\" title=\"{\\{ (x,N(x)): x \\in E \\}}\" class=\"latex\" /> of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N}\" title=\"{N}\" class=\"latex\" />: \n<p></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++1_E%28X%29+1_%7BD+%5Cleq+N%28X%29%7D+f%28x%29+%3D+%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+1_E%28x%29+1_%7B%5Cxi+%5Cleq+N%28x%29%7D+%5Chat+f%28%5Cxi%29+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+x+%5Cxi%7D%5C+d%5Cxi.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  1_E(X) 1_{D \\leq N(X)} f(x) = \\int_{\\bf R} 1_E(x) 1_{\\xi \\leq N(x)} \\hat f(\\xi) e^{2\\pi i x \\xi}\\ d\\xi.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  1_E(X) 1_{D \\leq N(X)} f(x) = \\int_{\\bf R} 1_E(x) 1_{\\xi \\leq N(x)} \\hat f(\\xi) e^{2\\pi i x \\xi}\\ d\\xi.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> A notable feature of the estimate <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#est\">(12)</a> is that it enjoys <em>three</em> different symmetries (or near-symmetries), each of which is “non-compact” in the sense that it is parameterised by a parameter taking values in a non-compact space such as <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf R}}\" title=\"{{\\bf R}}\" class=\"latex\" /> or <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%280%2C%2B%5Cinfty%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(0,+\\infty)}\" title=\"{(0,+\\infty)}\" class=\"latex\" />: </p>\n<p> </p>\n<ul> \n <li>(i) (Translation symmetry) For any spatial shift <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx_0+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x_0 \\in {\\bf R}}\" title=\"{x_0 \\in {\\bf R}}\" class=\"latex\" />, both sides of <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#est\">(12)</a> remain unchanged if we replace <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%28x%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f(x)}\" title=\"{f(x)}\" class=\"latex\" /> by <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathrm%7BTrans%7D_%7Bx_0%7D+f%28x%29+%3A%3D+f%28x-x_0%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\mathrm{Trans}_{x_0} f(x) := f(x-x_0)}\" title=\"{\\mathrm{Trans}_{x_0} f(x) := f(x-x_0)}\" class=\"latex\" />, the set <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BE%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{E}\" title=\"{E}\" class=\"latex\" /> by the translate <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BE%2Bx_0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{E+x_0}\" title=\"{E+x_0}\" class=\"latex\" />, and the function <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N}\" title=\"{N}\" class=\"latex\" /> by <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx+%5Cmapsto+N%28x-x_0%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x \\mapsto N(x-x_0)}\" title=\"{x \\mapsto N(x-x_0)}\" class=\"latex\" />. </li>\n <li>(ii) (Dilation symmetry) For any scaling factor <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Clambda+%5Cin+%280%2C%2B%5Cinfty%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\lambda \\in (0,+\\infty)}\" title=\"{\\lambda \\in (0,+\\infty)}\" class=\"latex\" />, both sides of <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#est\">(12)</a> become multiplied by the same scaling factor <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Clambda%5E%7B1%2F2%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\lambda^{1/2}}\" title=\"{\\lambda^{1/2}}\" class=\"latex\" /> if we replace <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f}\" title=\"{f}\" class=\"latex\" /> by <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathrm%7BDil%7D_%5Clambda+f%28x%29+%3A%3D+%5Clambda%5E%7B-1%2F2%7D+f%28x%2F%5Clambda%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\mathrm{Dil}_\\lambda f(x) := \\lambda^{-1/2} f(x/\\lambda)}\" title=\"{\\mathrm{Dil}_\\lambda f(x) := \\lambda^{-1/2} f(x/\\lambda)}\" class=\"latex\" />, <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BE%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{E}\" title=\"{E}\" class=\"latex\" /> by the dilate <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Clambda+%5Ccdot+E+%3A%3D+%5C%7B+%5Clambda+x%3A+x+%5Cin+E+%5C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\lambda \\cdot E := \\{ \\lambda x: x \\in E \\}}\" title=\"{\\lambda \\cdot E := \\{ \\lambda x: x \\in E \\}}\" class=\"latex\" />, and the function <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N}\" title=\"{N}\" class=\"latex\" /> by <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx+%5Cmapsto+%5Clambda%5E%7B-1%7D+N%28x%2F%5Clambda%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x \\mapsto \\lambda^{-1} N(x/\\lambda)}\" title=\"{x \\mapsto \\lambda^{-1} N(x/\\lambda)}\" class=\"latex\" />. </li>\n <li>(iii) (Modulation symmetry) For any frequency shift <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cxi_0+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\xi_0 \\in {\\bf R}}\" title=\"{\\xi_0 \\in {\\bf R}}\" class=\"latex\" />, both sides of <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#est\">(12)</a> remain (almost) unchanged if we replace <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%28x%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f(x)}\" title=\"{f(x)}\" class=\"latex\" /> by <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathrm%7BMod%7D_%7B%5Cxi_0%7D+f%28x%29+%3A%3D+e%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+x+%5Cxi_0%7D+f%28x%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\mathrm{Mod}_{\\xi_0} f(x) := e^{2\\pi i x \\xi_0} f(x)}\" title=\"{\\mathrm{Mod}_{\\xi_0} f(x) := e^{2\\pi i x \\xi_0} f(x)}\" class=\"latex\" />, do not modify the set <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BE%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{E}\" title=\"{E}\" class=\"latex\" />, and replace the function <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N}\" title=\"{N}\" class=\"latex\" /> by <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx+%5Cmapsto+N%28x%29%2B%5Cxi_0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{x \\mapsto N(x)+\\xi_0}\" title=\"{x \\mapsto N(x)+\\xi_0}\" class=\"latex\" />. (Technically the left-hand side changes because of an additional factor of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Be%5E%7B2%5Cpi+i+x+%5Cxi_0%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{e^{2\\pi i x \\xi_0}}\" title=\"{e^{2\\pi i x \\xi_0}}\" class=\"latex\" />, but this factor can be handled for instance by generalising the indicator function cutoff <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1_E%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1_E}\" title=\"{1_E}\" class=\"latex\" /> to a subindicator function cutoff <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cchi_E%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\chi_E}\" title=\"{\\chi_E}\" class=\"latex\" /> that has the pointwise bound <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7C%5Cchi_E%7C+%5Cleq+1_E%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{|\\chi_E| \\leq 1_E}\" title=\"{|\\chi_E| \\leq 1_E}\" class=\"latex\" />; we will ignore this very minor issue here.) </li>\n</ul> \n<p></p>\n<p> Each of these symmetries corresponds to a different symmetry of phase space <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Ctimes+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%3D+%5C%7B+%28x%2C%5Cxi%29%3A+x%2C%5Cxi+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%5C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf R} \\times {\\bf R} = \\{ (x,\\xi): x,\\xi \\in {\\bf R}\\}}\" title=\"{{\\bf R} \\times {\\bf R} = \\{ (x,\\xi): x,\\xi \\in {\\bf R}\\}}\" class=\"latex\" />, namely spatial translation <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28x%2C%5Cxi%29+%5Cmapsto+%28x%2Bx_0%2C%5Cxi%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(x,\\xi) \\mapsto (x+x_0,\\xi)}\" title=\"{(x,\\xi) \\mapsto (x+x_0,\\xi)}\" class=\"latex\" />, dilation <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28x%2C%5Cxi%29+%5Cmapsto+%28%5Clambda+x%2C+%5Clambda%5E%7B-1%7D+%5Cxi%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(x,\\xi) \\mapsto (\\lambda x, \\lambda^{-1} \\xi)}\" title=\"{(x,\\xi) \\mapsto (\\lambda x, \\lambda^{-1} \\xi)}\" class=\"latex\" />, and frequency translation <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28x%2C%5Cxi%29+%5Cmapsto+%28x%2C%5Cxi%2B%5Cxi_0%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(x,\\xi) \\mapsto (x,\\xi+\\xi_0)}\" title=\"{(x,\\xi) \\mapsto (x,\\xi+\\xi_0)}\" class=\"latex\" /> respectively. As a general rule of thumb, if one wants to prove a delicate estimate such as <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#est\">(12)</a> that is invariant with respect to one or more non-compact symmetries, then one should use tools that are similarly invariant (or approximately invariant) with respect to these symmetries. Thus for instance Littlewood-Paley theory or Calderón-Zygmund theory would not be suitable tools to use here, as they are only invariant with respect to translation and dilation symmetry but absolutely fail to have any modulation symmetry properties (these theories prescribe a privileged role to the frequency origin, or equivalently they isolate functions of mean zero as playing a particularly important role). </p>\n<p> Besides the need to respect the symmetries of the problem, one of the main difficulties in establishing <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#est\">(12)</a> is that the expression <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1_%7B%5Cxi+%5Cleq+N%28x%29%7D+%5Chat+f%28%5Cxi%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1_{\\xi \\leq N(x)} \\hat f(\\xi)}\" title=\"{1_{\\xi \\leq N(x)} \\hat f(\\xi)}\" class=\"latex\" />, couples together the function <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N}\" title=\"{N}\" class=\"latex\" /> with the function <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f}\" title=\"{f}\" class=\"latex\" /> in a rather complicated way (via the frequency variable <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cxi%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\xi}\" title=\"{\\xi}\" class=\"latex\" />). We would like to try to decouple this interaction by making <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N}\" title=\"{N}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f}\" title=\"{f}\" class=\"latex\" /> instead interact with simpler objects (such as “wave packets”), rather than being coupled directly to each other. To motivate the decomposition to use, we begin with a heuristic discussion. The first main idea is to temporarily work in the (non-invertible) coordinate system <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28N%28x%29%2C%5Cxi%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(N(x),\\xi)}\" title=\"{(N(x),\\xi)}\" class=\"latex\" /> of phase space rather than <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28x%2C%5Cxi%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(x,\\xi)}\" title=\"{(x,\\xi)}\" class=\"latex\" /> in order to simplify the constraint <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1_%7B%5Cxi+%5Cleq+N%28x%29%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1_{\\xi \\leq N(x)}}\" title=\"{1_{\\xi \\leq N(x)}}\" class=\"latex\" /> to the simple geometric region of a half-plane (this coordinate system is of course a terrible choice for most of the other parts of the argument, but is the right system to use for the frequency decompositions we will now employ). In analogy to the Whitney type decompositions used in <a href=\"https://terrytao.wordpress.com/2020/03/29/247b-notes-1-restriction-theory/\">Notes 1</a>, one can split <a name=\"decomp\"></a></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><a name=\"decomp\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++1_%7B%5Cxi+%5Cleq+N%28x%29%7D+%3D+%5Csum_%7B%5Comega_-+%5Csim+%5Comega_%2B%7D+1_%7B%5Comega_-%7D%28%5Cxi%29+1_%7B%5Comega_%2B%7D%28N%28x%29%29+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%2813%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  1_{\\xi \\leq N(x)} = \\sum_{\\omega_- \\sim \\omega_+} 1_{\\omega_-}(\\xi) 1_{\\omega_+}(N(x)) \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (13)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  1_{\\xi \\leq N(x)} = \\sum_{\\omega_- \\sim \\omega_+} 1_{\\omega_-}(\\xi) 1_{\\omega_+}(N(x)) \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (13)\" class=\"latex\" /></a></p>\n<a name=\"decomp\"> </a> for almost all choices of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cxi%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\xi}\" title=\"{\\xi}\" class=\"latex\" /> and \n<img
