For the first term, we use Exercise \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#tree-ex\">15</a>, \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#ener\">(40)</a>, \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#mass-t\">(36)</a> to bound this sum by \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Clesssim+%5Csum_n+%5Csum_%7BT+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+T%7D_n%7D+%7CI_T%7C+%282%5E%7B-n%2F2%7D+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D%29+%5Cmin%28+1%2C+2%5E%7B-n%7D+%7CE%7C+%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\lesssim \\sum_n \\sum_{T \\in {\\mathcal T}_n} |I_T| (2^{-n/2} \\|f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R})}) \\min( 1, 2^{-n} |E| )\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\lesssim \\sum_n \\sum_{T \\in {\\mathcal T}_n} |I_T| (2^{-n/2} \\|f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R})}) \\min( 1, 2^{-n} |E| )\" class=\"latex\" /></p> which by \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#t-size\">(39)</a> is bounded by \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Clesssim+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D+%5Csum_n+2%5E%7Bn%2F2%7D+%5Cmin%28+1%2C+2%5E%7B-n%7D+%7CE%7C+%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\lesssim \\|f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R})} \\sum_n 2^{n/2} \\min( 1, 2^{-n} |E| )\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\lesssim \\|f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R})} \\sum_n 2^{n/2} \\min( 1, 2^{-n} |E| )\" class=\"latex\" /></p> which sums to \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Clesssim+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D+%7CE%7C%5E%7B1%2F2%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\lesssim \\|f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R})} |E|^{1/2}}\" title=\"{\\lesssim \\|f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R})} |E|^{1/2}}\" class=\"latex\" /> as required. \n<p> It remains to establish the energy and mass selection lemmas. We begin with the mass selection claim, Proposition <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#mass-select\">17</a>. Let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D_1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\mathcal P}_1}\" title=\"{{\\mathcal P}_1}\" class=\"latex\" /> denote the set of all tiles <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP%27%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P'}\" title=\"{P'}\" class=\"latex\" /> with <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP%27+%5Cgeq+P%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P' \\geq P}\" title=\"{P' \\geq P}\" class=\"latex\" /> for some <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P \\in {\\mathcal P}}\" title=\"{P \\in {\\mathcal P}}\" class=\"latex\" /> and such that <a name=\"a\"></a></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><a name=\"a\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7CI_%7BP%27%7D%7C%5E%7B-1%7D+%5Cint_%7BE_%7BP%27%7D%7D+%5Cchi_%7BI_%7BP%27%7D%7D%5E%7B10%7D+%3E+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B2%7D+%5Cmu.+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%2842%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  |I_{P'}|^{-1} \\int_{E_{P'}} \\chi_{I_{P'}}^{10} > \\frac{1}{2} \\mu. \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (42)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  |I_{P'}|^{-1} \\int_{E_{P'}} \\chi_{I_{P'}}^{10} > \\frac{1}{2} \\mu. \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (42)\" class=\"latex\" /></a></p>\n<a name=\"a\"> </a> Let \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D_%2A%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\mathcal P}_*}\" title=\"{{\\mathcal P}_*}\" class=\"latex\" /> denote the set of tiles in \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D_1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\mathcal P}_1}\" title=\"{{\\mathcal P}_1}\" class=\"latex\" /> that are maximal with respect to the tile partial order. (Note that the left-hand side of \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#a\">(42)</a> is bounded by \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BO%28%7CE%7C%2F%7CI_%7BP%27%7D%7C%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{O(|E|/|I_{P'}|)}\" title=\"{O(|E|/|I_{P'}|)}\" class=\"latex\" />, so there is an upper bound to the spatial scales of the tiles involved here.) Then every tile \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P}\" title=\"{P}\" class=\"latex\" /> in \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\mathcal P}}\" title=\"{{\\mathcal P}}\" class=\"latex\" /> is either less than or equal to a tile in \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D_%2A%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\mathcal P}_*}\" title=\"{{\\mathcal P}_*}\" class=\"latex\" />, or is such that \n<p></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7CI_%7BP%27%7D%7C%5E%7B-1%7D+%5Cint_%7BE_%7BP%27%7D%7D+%5Cchi_%7BI_%7BP%27%7D%7D%5E%7B10%7D+%5Cleq+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B2%7D+%5Cmu&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  |I_{P'}|^{-1} \\int_{E_{P'}} \\chi_{I_{P'}}^{10} \\leq \\frac{1}{2} \\mu\" title=\"\\displaystyle  |I_{P'}|^{-1} \\int_{E_{P'}} \\chi_{I_{P'}}^{10} \\leq \\frac{1}{2} \\mu\" class=\"latex\" /></p> for all \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP%27+%5Cleq+P%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P' \\leq P}\" title=\"{P' \\leq P}\" class=\"latex\" />. Thus if we let \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D%27%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\mathcal P}'}\" title=\"{{\\mathcal P}'}\" class=\"latex\" /> be the collection of tiles of the second form, and let \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cmathcal+T%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\mathcal T}}\" title=\"{{\\mathcal T}}\" class=\"latex\" /> be the collection of trees with tree top \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP_%2A%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P_*}\" title=\"{P_*}\" class=\"latex\" /> associated to each \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP_%2A+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D_%2A%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P_* \\in {\\mathcal P}_*}\" title=\"{P_* \\in {\\mathcal P}_*}\" class=\"latex\" /> (selected greedily, and in arbitrary order, subject of course to the requirement that no tile belongs to more than one tree), we obtain the required partition \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D+%3D+%5Cbiguplus_%7BT+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+T%7D%7D+T+%5Cuplus+%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D%27&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathcal P} = \\biguplus_{T \\in {\\mathcal T}} T \\uplus {\\mathcal P}'\" title=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathcal P} = \\biguplus_{T \\in {\\mathcal T}} T \\uplus {\\mathcal P}'\" class=\"latex\" /></p> with \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cmathrm%7BMass%7D%28%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D%27%29+%5Cleq+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B2%7D+%5Cmu&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\mathrm{Mass}({\\mathcal P}') \\leq \\frac{1}{2} \\mu\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\mathrm{Mass}({\\mathcal P}') \\leq \\frac{1}{2} \\mu\" class=\"latex\" /></p> and it remains to establish the bound \n<a name=\"eso\"><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Csum_%7BT+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+T%7D%7D+%7CI_T%7C+%5Clesssim+%5Cmu%5E%7B-1%7D+%7CE%7C.+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%2843%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{T \\in {\\mathcal T}} |I_T| \\lesssim \\mu^{-1} |E|. \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (43)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{T \\in {\\mathcal T}} |I_T| \\lesssim \\mu^{-1} |E|. \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (43)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> </a> This will be a (rather heavily disguised) variant of the Hardy-Littlewood maximal inequality. By construction, the tree tops \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP_T%2C+T+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+T%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P_T, T \\in {\\mathcal T}}\" title=\"{P_T, T \\in {\\mathcal T}}\" class=\"latex\" /> are essentially disjoint, and one has \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cint_%7BE_%7BP_T%7D%7D+%5Cchi_%7BI_T%7D%5E%7B10%7D+%3E+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B2%7D+%5Cmu+%7CI_T%7C&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\int_{E_{P_T}} \\chi_{I_T}^{10} > \\frac{1}{2} \\mu |I_T|\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\int_{E_{P_T}} \\chi_{I_T}^{10} > \\frac{1}{2} \\mu |I_T|\" class=\"latex\" /></p> for all such tree tops. To motivate the argument, suppose for sake of discussion that we had the stronger estimate \n<a name=\"ep1\"><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cint_%7BE_%7BP_T%7D%7D+1_%7BI_T%7D+%3E+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B2%7D+%5Cmu+%7CI_T%7C.+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%2844%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\int_{E_{P_T}} 1_{I_T} > \\frac{1}{2} \\mu |I_T|. \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (44)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\int_{E_{P_T}} 1_{I_T} > \\frac{1}{2} \\mu |I_T|. \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (44)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> </a> By the essential disjointness of the \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP_T%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P_T}\" title=\"{P_T}\" class=\"latex\" />, the sets \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++E_%7BP_T%7D+%5Ccap+I_T+%3D+%5C%7B+x+%5Cin+E%3A+%28x%2CN%28x%29%29+%5Cin+P_T%29+%5C%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  E_{P_T} \\cap I_T = \\{ x \\in E: (x,N(x)) \\in P_T) \\}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  E_{P_T} \\cap I_T = \\{ x \\in E: (x,N(x)) \\in P_T) \\}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> are also essentially disjoint subsets of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BE%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{E}\" title=\"{E}\" class=\"latex\" />, hence \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Csum_%7BT+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+T%7D%7D+%5Cint_%7BE_%7BP_T%7D%7D+1_%7BI_T%7D+%5Cleq+%7CE%7C&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{T \\in {\\mathcal T}} \\int_{E_{P_T}} 1_{I_T} \\leq |E|\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{T \\in {\\mathcal T}} \\int_{E_{P_T}} 1_{I_T} \\leq |E|\" class=\"latex\" /></p> and the claim \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#eso\">(43)</a> would then follow. Now we do not quite have \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#ep1\">(44)</a>; but from the pigeonhole principle we see that for each \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+T%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T \\in {\\mathcal T}}\" title=\"{T \\in {\\mathcal T}}\" class=\"latex\" /> there is a natural number \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bm+%3D+m_T%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{m = m_T}\" title=\"{m = m_T}\" class=\"latex\" /> such that \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cint_%7BE_%7BP_T%7D%7D+1_%7B2%5Em+I_T%7D+%5Cgtrsim+2%5E%7B2m%7D+%5Cmu+%7CI_T%7C+&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\int_{E_{P_T}} 1_{2^m I_T} \\gtrsim 2^{2m} \\mu |I_T| \" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\int_{E_{P_T}} 1_{2^m I_T} \\gtrsim 2^{2m} \\mu |I_T| \" class=\"latex\" /></p> (say), where \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B2%5Em+I_T%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{2^m I_T}\" title=\"{2^m I_T}\" class=\"latex\" /> denotes the interval with the same center as \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BI_T%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{I_T}\" title=\"{I_T}\" class=\"latex\" /> but \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B2%5Em%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{2^m}\" title=\"{2^m}\" class=\"latex\" /> times the length (this is not quite a dyadic interval). We now restrict attention to those \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T}\" title=\"{T}\" class=\"latex\" /> associated to a fixed choice of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bm%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{m}\" title=\"{m}\" class=\"latex\" />. Let \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B2%5Em+P_T+%3A%3D+2%5Em+I_T+%5Ctimes+%5Comega_%7BT%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{2^m P_T := 2^m I_T \\times \\omega_{T}}\" title=\"{2^m P_T := 2^m I_T \\times \\omega_{T}}\" class=\"latex\" /> denote the corresponding dilated tiles, then we have \n<a name=\"et\"><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7C%5C%7B+x+%5Cin+E%3A+%28x%2CN%28x%29%29+%5Cin+2%5Em+P_T+%5C%7D%7C+%5Cgtrsim+2%5E%7B2m%7D+%5Cmu+%7CI_T%7C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%2845%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  |\\{ x \\in E: (x,N(x)) \\in 2^m P_T \\}| \\gtrsim 2^{2m} \\mu |I_T| \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (45)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  |\\{ x \\in E: (x,N(x)) \\in 2^m P_T \\}| \\gtrsim 2^{2m} \\mu |I_T| \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (45)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> </a> for each \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T}\" title=\"{T}\" class=\"latex\" /> with \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bm_T+%3D+m%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{m_T = m}\" title=\"{m_T = m}\" class=\"latex\" />. \n<p> Unfortunately, the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B2%5Em+P_T%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{2^m P_T}\" title=\"{2^m P_T}\" class=\"latex\" /> are no longer disjoint. However, by the greedy algorithm (repeatedly choosing maximal tiles (in the tile ordering)), we can find a collection <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cmathcal+T%7D_m+%5Csubset+%7B%5Cmathcal+T%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\mathcal T}_m \\subset {\\mathcal T}}\" title=\"{{\\mathcal T}_m \\subset {\\mathcal T}}\" class=\"latex\" /> such that </p>\n<ul> \n <li>(i) All the dilated tree tops <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B2%5Em+P_T%2C+P_T+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+T%7D_m%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{2^m P_T, P_T \\in {\\mathcal T}_m}\" title=\"{2^m P_T, P_T \\in {\\mathcal T}_m}\" class=\"latex\" /> are essentially disjoint. </li>\n <li>(ii) For every <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+T%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T \\in {\\mathcal T}}\" title=\"{T \\in {\\mathcal T}}\" class=\"latex\" /> with <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bm_T+%3D+m%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{m_T = m}\" title=\"{m_T = m}\" class=\"latex\" />, there is <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT%27+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+T%7D_m%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T' \\in {\\mathcal T}_m}\" title=\"{T' \\in {\\mathcal T}_m}\" class=\"latex\" /> such that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B2%5Em+P_T%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{2^m P_T}\" title=\"{2^m P_T}\" class=\"latex\" /> intersects <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B2%5Em+P_%7BT%27%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{2^m P_{T'}}\" title=\"{2^m P_{T'}}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7CI_T%7C+%5Cleq+%7CI_%7BT%27%7D%7C%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{|I_T| \\leq |I_{T'}|}\" title=\"{|I_T| \\leq |I_{T'}|}\" class=\"latex\" />. </li>\n</ul> \n<p></p>\n<p> From property (i) and <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#et\">(45)</a> we have </p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Csum_%7BT%27+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+T%7D_m%7D+2%5E%7B2m%7D+%5Cmu+%7CI_%7BT%27%7D%7C+%5Clesssim+%7CE%7C.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{T' \\in {\\mathcal T}_m} 2^{2m} \\mu |I_{T'}| \\lesssim |E|.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{T' \\in {\\mathcal T}_m} 2^{2m} \\mu |I_{T'}| \\lesssim |E|.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> On the other hand, from property (ii) we see that the sum of all the \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7CI_T%7C%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{|I_T|}\" title=\"{|I_T|}\" class=\"latex\" /> for all \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+T%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T \\in {\\mathcal T}}\" title=\"{T \\in {\\mathcal T}}\" class=\"latex\" /> with \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bm_T+%3D+m%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{m_T = m}\" title=\"{m_T = m}\" class=\"latex\" /> associated to a single \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT%27+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+T%7D_m%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T' \\in {\\mathcal T}_m}\" title=\"{T' \\in {\\mathcal T}_m}\" class=\"latex\" /> is \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BO%282%5Em+%7CI_%7BT%27%7D%7C%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{O(2^m |I_{T'}|)}\" title=\"{O(2^m |I_{T'}|)}\" class=\"latex\" />. Putting the two statements together we see that \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Csum_%7BT+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+T%7D%3A+m_T+%3D+m%7D+%7CI_T%7C+%5Clesssim+2%5E%7B-m%7D+%5Cmu%5E%7B-1%7D+%7CE%7C&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{T \\in {\\mathcal T}: m_T = m} |I_T| \\lesssim 2^{-m} \\mu^{-1} |E|\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{T \\in {\\mathcal T}: m_T = m} |I_T| \\lesssim 2^{-m} \\mu^{-1} |E|\" class=\"latex\" /></p> and on summing in \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bm%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{m}\" title=\"{m}\" class=\"latex\" /> we obtain the required claim \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#eso\">(43)</a>. \n<p> Finally, we prove the energy selection claim, Proposition <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#energy-select\">16</a>. The basic idea is to extract all the high-energy trees from <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\mathcal P}}\" title=\"{{\\mathcal P}}\" class=\"latex\" /> in such a way that the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%2B%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{+}\" title=\"{+}\" class=\"latex\" />-tree component of those trees are sufficiently “disjoint” from each other that a useful Bessel inequality, generalising Exercise <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#ao\">12</a>, may be deployed. Implementing this strategy correctly turns out however to be slightly delicate. We perform the following iterative algorithm to generate a partition <a name=\"part\"></a></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><a name=\"part\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D+%3D+%5Cbiguplus_%7BT+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+T%7D%7D+T+%5Cuplus+%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D%27+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%2846%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathcal P} = \\biguplus_{T \\in {\\mathcal T}} T \\uplus {\\mathcal P}' \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (46)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathcal P} = \\biguplus_{T \\in {\\mathcal T}} T \\uplus {\\mathcal P}' \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (46)\" class=\"latex\" /></a></p>\n<a name=\"part\"> </a> as well as a companion collection \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cmathcal+T%7D_%2B%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\mathcal T}_+}\" title=\"{{\\mathcal T}_+}\" class=\"latex\" /> of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%2B%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{+}\" title=\"{+}\" class=\"latex\" />-trees as follows. \n<p></p>\n<p> </p>\n<ul> \n <li> Step 1. Initialise <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cmathcal+T%7D%3D%7B%5Cmathcal+T%7D_%2B+%3D+%5Cemptyset%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\mathcal T}={\\mathcal T}_+ = \\emptyset}\" title=\"{{\\mathcal T}={\\mathcal T}_+ = \\emptyset}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D%27+%3D+%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\mathcal P}' = {\\mathcal P}}\" title=\"{{\\mathcal P}' = {\\mathcal P}}\" class=\"latex\" />. </li>\n <li> Step 2. If <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathrm%7BEnergy%7D%28%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D%27%29+%5Cleq+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B2%7D+%5Cvarepsilon%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\mathrm{Energy}({\\mathcal P}') \\leq \\frac{1}{2} \\varepsilon}\" title=\"{\\mathrm{Energy}({\\mathcal P}') \\leq \\frac{1}{2} \\varepsilon}\" class=\"latex\" /> then STOP. Otherwise, go on to Step 3. </li>\n <li> Step 3. Since we now have <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathrm%7BEnergy%7D%28%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D%27%29+%3E+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B2%7D+%5Cvarepsilon%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\mathrm{Energy}({\\mathcal P}') > \\frac{1}{2} \\varepsilon}\" title=\"{\\mathrm{Energy}({\\mathcal P}') > \\frac{1}{2} \\varepsilon}\" class=\"latex\" />, <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D%27%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\mathcal P}'}\" title=\"{{\\mathcal P}'}\" class=\"latex\" /> contains a <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%2B%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{+}\" title=\"{+}\" class=\"latex\" />-tree <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT_%2B%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T_+}\" title=\"{T_+}\" class=\"latex\" /> for which <a name=\"ptp\"><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Csum_%7BP+%5Cin+T_%2B%7D+%7C%5Clangle+f%2C+%5Cphi_P+%5Crangle%7C%5E2+%3E+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B4%7D+%5Cvarepsilon%5E2+%7CI_%7BT_%2B%7D%7C.+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%2847%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{P \\in T_+} |\\langle f, \\phi_P \\rangle|^2 > \\frac{1}{4} \\varepsilon^2 |I_{T_+}|. \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (47)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{P \\in T_+} |\\langle f, \\phi_P \\rangle|^2 > \\frac{1}{4} \\varepsilon^2 |I_{T_+}|. \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (47)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> </a> Among all such <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT_%2B%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T_+}\" title=\"{T_+}\" class=\"latex\" />, choose one for which the midpoint <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cinf+%5Comega_%7BT_%2B%7D+%2B+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B2%7D+%7C%5Comega_%7BT_%2B%7D%7C%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\inf \\omega_{T_+} + \\frac{1}{2} |\\omega_{T_+}|}\" title=\"{\\inf \\omega_{T_+} + \\frac{1}{2} |\\omega_{T_+}|}\" class=\"latex\" /> of the frequency is <em>minimal</em>. (The reason for this rather strange choice will be made clearer shortly.) </li>\n <li> Step 4. Add <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT_%2B%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T_+}\" title=\"{T_+}\" class=\"latex\" /> to <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cmathcal+T%7D_%2B%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\mathcal T}_+}\" title=\"{{\\mathcal T}_+}\" class=\"latex\" />, add the larger tree <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT+%3A%3D+%5C%7B+P+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D%27%3A+P+%5Cleq+P_%7BT_%2B%7D+%5C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T := \\{ P \\in {\\mathcal P}': P \\leq P_{T_+} \\}}\" title=\"{T := \\{ P \\in {\\mathcal P}': P \\leq P_{T_+} \\}}\" class=\"latex\" /> (with the same top <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP_%7BT_%2B%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P_{T_+}}\" title=\"{P_{T_+}}\" class=\"latex\" /> as <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT_%2B%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T_+}\" title=\"{T_+}\" class=\"latex\" />) to <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cmathcal+T%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\mathcal T}}\" title=\"{{\\mathcal T}}\" class=\"latex\" />, then remove <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T}\" title=\"{T}\" class=\"latex\" /> from <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D%27%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\mathcal P}'}\" title=\"{{\\mathcal P}'}\" class=\"latex\" />. We also remove the adjacent trees <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT_%7Bright%7D+%3D+%5C%7B+P+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D%27%3A+P+%5Cleq+P_%7BT_%2B%7D+%2B+%28%7CI_%7BT_%2B%7D%7C%2C0%29%5C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T_{right} = \\{ P \\in {\\mathcal P}': P \\leq P_{T_+} + (|I_{T_+}|,0)\\}}\" title=\"{T_{right} = \\{ P \\in {\\mathcal P}': P \\leq P_{T_+} + (|I_{T_+}|,0)\\}}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT_%7Bleft%7D+%3D+%5C%7B+P+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D%27%3A+P+%5Cleq+P_%7BT_%2B%7D+-+%28%7CI_%7BT_%2B%7D%7C%2C0%29%5C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T_{left} = \\{ P \\in {\\mathcal P}': P \\leq P_{T_+} - (|I_{T_+}|,0)\\}}\" title=\"{T_{left} = \\{ P \\in {\\mathcal P}': P \\leq P_{T_+} - (|I_{T_+}|,0)\\}}\" class=\"latex\" /> from <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D%27%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\mathcal P}'}\" title=\"{{\\mathcal P}'}\" class=\"latex\" /> and also place them into <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cmathcal+T%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\mathcal T}}\" title=\"{{\\mathcal T}}\" class=\"latex\" />. Now return to Step 2. </li>\n</ul> \n<p></p>\n<p> This procedure terminates in finite time to give a partition <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#part\">(46)</a> with <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathrm%7BEnergy%7D%28%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D%27%29+%5Cleq+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B2%7D+%5Cvarepsilon%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\mathrm{Energy}({\\mathcal P}') \\leq \\frac{1}{2} \\varepsilon}\" title=\"{\\mathrm{Energy}({\\mathcal P}') \\leq \\frac{1}{2} \\varepsilon}\" class=\"latex\" />, and with the trees <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cmathcal+T%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\mathcal T}}\" title=\"{{\\mathcal T}}\" class=\"latex\" /> coming in triplets <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT%2C+T_%7Bright%7D%2C+T_%7Bleft%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T, T_{right}, T_{left}}\" title=\"{T, T_{right}, T_{left}}\" class=\"latex\" /> all associated to a <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%2B%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{+}\" title=\"{+}\" class=\"latex\" />-tree <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT_%2B%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T_+}\" title=\"{T_+}\" class=\"latex\" /> in <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cmathcal+T%7D_%2B%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\mathcal T}_+}\" title=\"{{\\mathcal T}_+}\" class=\"latex\" /> with the same spatial scale as <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T}\" title=\"{T}\" class=\"latex\" />, with all the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%2B%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{+}\" title=\"{+}\" class=\"latex\" />-trees <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT_%2B%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T_+}\" title=\"{T_+}\" class=\"latex\" /> disjoint and obeying the estimates <a name=\"ptp-1\"></a></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><a name=\"ptp-1\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Csum_%7BP+%5Cin+T_%2B%7D+%7C%5Clangle+f%2C+%5Cphi_P+%5Crangle%7C%5E2+%5Csim+%5Cvarepsilon%5E2+%7CI_%7BT_%2B%7D%7C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%2848%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{P \\in T_+} |\\langle f, \\phi_P \\rangle|^2 \\sim \\varepsilon^2 |I_{T_+}| \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (48)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{P \\in T_+} |\\langle f, \\phi_P \\rangle|^2 \\sim \\varepsilon^2 |I_{T_+}| \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (48)\" class=\"latex\" /></a></p>\n<a name=\"ptp-1\"> </a> (both the upper and lower bounds will be important for this argument). It will then suffice to show that \n<p></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Csum_%7BT_%2B+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+T%7D_%2B%7D+%7CI_%7BT_%2B%7D%7C+%5Clesssim+%5Cvarepsilon%5E%7B-2%7D+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D%5E2%3B&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{T_+ \\in {\\mathcal T}_+} |I_{T_+}| \\lesssim \\varepsilon^{-2} \\|f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R})}^2;\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{T_+ \\in {\\mathcal T}_+} |I_{T_+}| \\lesssim \\varepsilon^{-2} \\|f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R})}^2;\" class=\"latex\" /></p> by \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#ptp-1\">(48)</a>, it then suffices to show the Bessel type inequality \n<a name=\"fbes\"><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Csum_%7BP+%5Cin+%5Cbigcup_%7BT_%2B+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+T%7D_%2B%7D+T_%2B%7D+%7C%5Clangle+f%2C+%5Cphi_P+%5Crangle%7C%5E2+%5Clesssim+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D%5E2.+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%2849%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{P \\in \\bigcup_{T_+ \\in {\\mathcal T}_+} T_+} |\\langle f, \\phi_P \\rangle|^2 \\lesssim \\|f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R})}^2. \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (49)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{P \\in \\bigcup_{T_+ \\in {\\mathcal T}_+} T_+} |\\langle f, \\phi_P \\rangle|^2 \\lesssim \\|f\\|_{L^2({\\bf R})}^2. \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (49)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> </a> \n<p> Now we make a crucial observation: not only are the trees <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT_%2B%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T_+}\" title=\"{T_+}\" class=\"latex\" /> in <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cmathcal+T%7D_%2B%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\mathcal T}_+}\" title=\"{{\\mathcal T}_+}\" class=\"latex\" /> disjoint (in the sense that no tile <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P}\" title=\"{P}\" class=\"latex\" /> belongs to two of these trees), but the lower tiles <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7B+P_-%3A+P+%5Cin+%5Cbigcup_%7BT_%2B+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+T%7D_%2B%7D%5C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\{ P_-: P \\in \\bigcup_{T_+ \\in {\\mathcal T}_+}\\}}\" title=\"{\\{ P_-: P \\in \\bigcup_{T_+ \\in {\\mathcal T}_+}\\}}\" class=\"latex\" /> are also essentially disjoint. Indeed we claim an even stronger disjointness property: if <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP+%5Cin+T_%2B+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+T%7D_%2B%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P \\in T_+ \\in {\\mathcal T}_+}\" title=\"{P \\in T_+ \\in {\\mathcal T}_+}\" class=\"latex\" />, <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP%27+%5Cin+T%27_%2B+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+T%7D_%2B%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P' \\in T'_+ \\in {\\mathcal T}_+}\" title=\"{P' \\in T'_+ \\in {\\mathcal T}_+}\" class=\"latex\" /> are such that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Comega_%7BP_-%7D+%5Csubsetneq+%5Comega_%7BP%27_-%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\omega_{P_-} \\subsetneq \\omega_{P'_-}}\" title=\"{\\omega_{P_-} \\subsetneq \\omega_{P'_-}}\" class=\"latex\" />, then <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BI_%7BP%27%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{I_{P'}}\" title=\"{I_{P'}}\" class=\"latex\" /> is not only disjoint from the larger dyadic interval <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BI_P%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{I_P}\" title=\"{I_P}\" class=\"latex\" />, but is in fact disjoint from the even larger interval <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B3I_%7BT_%2B%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{3I_{T_+}}\" title=\"{3I_{T_+}}\" class=\"latex\" />. To see this, suppose for contradiction that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Comega_%7BP_-%7D+%5Csubsetneq+%5Comega_%7BP%27_-%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\omega_{P_-} \\subsetneq \\omega_{P'_-}}\" title=\"{\\omega_{P_-} \\subsetneq \\omega_{P'_-}}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BI_%7BP%27%7D+%5Csubset+3I_%7BT_%2B%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{I_{P'} \\subset 3I_{T_+}}\" title=\"{I_{P'} \\subset 3I_{T_+}}\" class=\"latex\" />. There are three possibilities to rule out: </p>\n<p> </p>\n<ul> \n <li> <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT%27_%2B%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T'_+}\" title=\"{T'_+}\" class=\"latex\" /> is equal to <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT_%2B%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T_+}\" title=\"{T_+}\" class=\"latex\" />. This can be ruled out because any two lower frequency intervals <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Comega_%7BQ_-%7D%2C+Q+%5Cin+T_%2B%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\omega_{Q_-}, Q \\in T_+}\" title=\"{\\omega_{Q_-}, Q \\in T_+}\" class=\"latex\" /> associated to a <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%2B%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{+}\" title=\"{+}\" class=\"latex\" />-tree are either equal or disjoint. </li>\n <li> <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT%27_%2B%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T'_+}\" title=\"{T'_+}\" class=\"latex\" /> was selected after <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT_%2B%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T_+}\" title=\"{T_+}\" class=\"latex\" /> was. To rule this out, observe that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Comega_%7BP%27_-%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\omega_{P'_-}}\" title=\"{\\omega_{P'_-}}\" class=\"latex\" /> contains the parent <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Comega_P%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\omega_P}\" title=\"{\\omega_P}\" class=\"latex\" /> of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Comega_%7BP_-%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\omega_{P_-}}\" title=\"{\\omega_{P_-}}\" class=\"latex\" />, and hence <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP%27+%5Cleq+P_%7BT_%2B%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P' \\leq P_{T_+}}\" title=\"{P' \\leq P_{T_+}}\" class=\"latex\" />, <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP%27+%5Cleq+P_%7BT_%2B%7D+%2B+%28%7CI_%7BT_%2B%7D%7C%2C0%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P' \\leq P_{T_+} + (|I_{T_+}|,0)}\" title=\"{P' \\leq P_{T_+} + (|I_{T_+}|,0)}\" class=\"latex\" />, or <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP%27+%5Cleq+P_%7BT_%2B%7D+-+%28%7CI_%7BT_%2B%7D%7C%2C0%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P' \\leq P_{T_+} - (|I_{T_+}|,0)}\" title=\"{P' \\leq P_{T_+} - (|I_{T_+}|,0)}\" class=\"latex\" />. Thus, when <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT_%2B%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T_+}\" title=\"{T_+}\" class=\"latex\" /> was selected, <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP%27%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P'}\" title=\"{P'}\" class=\"latex\" /> should have been placed with one of the three trees <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT_%7Bleft%7D%2C+T%2C+T_%7Bright%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T_{left}, T, T_{right}}\" title=\"{T_{left}, T, T_{right}}\" class=\"latex\" /> associated to <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T}\" title=\"{T}\" class=\"latex\" /> and would therefore not have been available for inclusion into <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT%27_%2B%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T'_+}\" title=\"{T'_+}\" class=\"latex\" />, a contradiction. </li>\n <li> <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT%27_%2B%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T'_+}\" title=\"{T'_+}\" class=\"latex\" /> was selected before <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT_%2B%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T_+}\" title=\"{T_+}\" class=\"latex\" /> was. If this case held, then the midpoint of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Comega_%7BT_%2B%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\omega_{T_+}}\" title=\"{\\omega_{T_+}}\" class=\"latex\" /> would have to be greater than or equal to that of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Comega_%7BT%27_%2B%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\omega_{T'_+}}\" title=\"{\\omega_{T'_+}}\" class=\"latex\" />, otherwise <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT%27_%2B%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T'_+}\" title=\"{T'_+}\" class=\"latex\" /> would not have a minimal midpoint at the time of its selection. But <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Comega_%7BT_%2B%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\omega_{T_+}}\" title=\"{\\omega_{T_+}}\" class=\"latex\" /> is contained in <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Comega_P%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\omega_P}\" title=\"{\\omega_P}\" class=\"latex\" />, which is contained in <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Comega_%7BP%27_-%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\omega_{P'_-}}\" title=\"{\\omega_{P'_-}}\" class=\"latex\" />, which lies below <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Comega_%7BP%27_%2B%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\omega_{P'_+}}\" title=\"{\\omega_{P'_+}}\" class=\"latex\" />, which contains <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28%5Comega_%7BT%27_%2B%7D%29_%2B%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(\\omega_{T'_+})_+}\" title=\"{(\\omega_{T'_+})_+}\" class=\"latex\" />, which contains the midpoint of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Comega_%7BT%27_%2B%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\omega_{T'_+}}\" title=\"{\\omega_{T'_+}}\" class=\"latex\" />; thus the midpoint of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Comega_%7BT_%2B%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\omega_{T_+}}\" title=\"{\\omega_{T_+}}\" class=\"latex\" /> lies strictly below that of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Comega_%7BT%27_%2B%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\omega_{T'_+}}\" title=\"{\\omega_{T'_+}}\" class=\"latex\" />, a contradiction. </li>\n</ul> \n<p></p>\n<p> If the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cphi_P%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\phi_P}\" title=\"{\\phi_P}\" class=\"latex\" /> were perfectly orthogonal to each other, this disjointness would be more than enough to establish <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#fbes\">(49)</a>. Unfortunately we only have imperfect orthogonality, and we have to work a little harder. As usual, we turn to a <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BTT%5E%2A%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{TT^*}\" title=\"{TT^*}\" class=\"latex\" /> type argument. We can write the left-hand side of <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#fbes\">(49)</a> as </p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Clangle+%5Csum_%7BP+%5Cin+%5Cbigcup_%7BT_%2B+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+T%7D_%2B%7D+T_%2B%7D+%5Clangle+f%2C+%5Cphi_P+%5Crangle+%5Cphi_P%2C+f+%5Crangle&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\langle \\sum_{P \\in \\bigcup_{T_+ \\in {\\mathcal T}_+} T_+} \\langle f, \\phi_P \\rangle \\phi_P, f \\rangle\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\langle \\sum_{P \\in \\bigcup_{T_+ \\in {\\mathcal T}_+} T_+} \\langle f, \\phi_P \\rangle \\phi_P, f \\rangle\" class=\"latex\" /></p> so by Cauchy-Schwarz it suffices to show that \n<a name=\"Stab\"><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+%5Csum_%7BP+%5Cin+%5Cbigcup_%7BT_%2B+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+T%7D_%2B%7D+T_%2B%7D+%5Clangle+f%2C+%5Cphi_P+%5Crangle+%5Cphi_P+%5C%7C_%7BL%5E2%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D%5E2+%5Clesssim+%5Csum_%7BP+%5Cin+%5Cbigcup_%7BT_%2B+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+T%7D_%2B%7D+T_%2B%7D+%7C%5Clangle+f%2C+%5Cphi_P+%5Crangle%7C%5E2.+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%2850%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sum_{P \\in \\bigcup_{T_+ \\in {\\mathcal T}_+} T_+} \\langle f, \\phi_P \\rangle \\phi_P \\|_{L^2({\\bf R})}^2 \\lesssim \\sum_{P \\in \\bigcup_{T_+ \\in {\\mathcal T}_+} T_+} |\\langle f, \\phi_P \\rangle|^2. \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (50)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| \\sum_{P \\in \\bigcup_{T_+ \\in {\\mathcal T}_+} T_+} \\langle f, \\phi_P \\rangle \\phi_P \\|_{L^2({\\bf R})}^2 \\lesssim \\sum_{P \\in \\bigcup_{T_+ \\in {\\mathcal T}_+} T_+} |\\langle f, \\phi_P \\rangle|^2. \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (50)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> </a> By the triangle inequality, the left-hand side may be bounded by \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Csum_%7BT_%2B%2C+T%27_%2B+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+T%7D_%2B%7D+%5Csum_%7BP+%5Cin+T_%2B%2C+P%27+%5Cin+T%27_%2B%7D+%7C%5Clangle+f%2C+%5Cphi_P+%5Crangle%7C+%7C%5Clangle+f%2C+%5Cphi_%7BP%27%7D+%5Crangle%7C+%7C%5Clangle+%5Cphi_P%2C+%5Cphi_%7BP%27%7D+%5Crangle%7C.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{T_+, T'_+ \\in {\\mathcal T}_+} \\sum_{P \\in T_+, P' \\in T'_+} |\\langle f, \\phi_P \\rangle| |\\langle f, \\phi_{P'} \\rangle| |\\langle \\phi_P, \\phi_{P'} \\rangle|.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{T_+, T'_+ \\in {\\mathcal T}_+} \\sum_{P \\in T_+, P' \\in T'_+} |\\langle f, \\phi_P \\rangle| |\\langle f, \\phi_{P'} \\rangle| |\\langle \\phi_P, \\phi_{P'} \\rangle|.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> As \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cphi_P%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\phi_P}\" title=\"{\\phi_P}\" class=\"latex\" /> has Fourier support in \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Comega_%7BP_-%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\omega_{P_-}}\" title=\"{\\omega_{P_-}}\" class=\"latex\" />, we see that \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Clangle+%5Cphi_P%2C+%5Cphi_%7BP%27%7D+%5Crangle%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\langle \\phi_P, \\phi_{P'} \\rangle}\" title=\"{\\langle \\phi_P, \\phi_{P'} \\rangle}\" class=\"latex\" /> vanishes unless \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Comega_%7BP_-%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\omega_{P_-}}\" title=\"{\\omega_{P_-}}\" class=\"latex\" /> and \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Comega_%7BP%27_%2B%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\omega_{P'_+}}\" title=\"{\\omega_{P'_+}}\" class=\"latex\" /> overlap. By symmetry it suffices to consider the cases \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Comega_%7BP_-%7D+%3D+%5Comega_%7BP%27_-%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\omega_{P_-} = \\omega_{P'_-}}\" title=\"{\\omega_{P_-} = \\omega_{P'_-}}\" class=\"latex\" /> and \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Comega_%7BP_-%7D+%5Csubsetneq+%5Comega_%7BP%27_-%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\omega_{P_-} \\subsetneq \\omega_{P'_-}}\" title=\"{\\omega_{P_-} \\subsetneq \\omega_{P'_-}}\" class=\"latex\" />. \n<p> First let us consider the contribution of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Comega_%7BP_-%7D+%3D+%5Comega_%7BP%27_-%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\omega_{P_-} = \\omega_{P'_-}}\" title=\"{\\omega_{P_-} = \\omega_{P'_-}}\" class=\"latex\" />. Using Young’s inequality <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bab+%5Cleq+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B2%7D%28a%5E2%2Bb%5E2%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{ab \\leq \\frac{1}{2}(a^2+b^2)}\" title=\"{ab \\leq \\frac{1}{2}(a^2+b^2)}\" class=\"latex\" /> and symmetry, we may bound this contribution by </p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Csum_%7BT_%2B%2C+T%27_%2B+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+T%7D_%2B%7D+%5Csum_%7BP+%5Cin+T_%2B%2C+P%27+%5Cin+T%27_%2B%3A+%5Comega_%7BP_-%7D+%3D+%5Comega_%7BP%27_-%7D%7D+%7C%5Clangle+f%2C+%5Cphi_P+%5Crangle%7C%5E2+%7C%5Clangle+%5Cphi_P%2C+%5Cphi_%7BP%27%7D+%5Crangle%7C.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{T_+, T'_+ \\in {\\mathcal T}_+} \\sum_{P \\in T_+, P' \\in T'_+: \\omega_{P_-} = \\omega_{P'_-}} |\\langle f, \\phi_P \\rangle|^2 |\\langle \\phi_P, \\phi_{P'} \\rangle|.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{T_+, T'_+ \\in {\\mathcal T}_+} \\sum_{P \\in T_+, P' \\in T'_+: \\omega_{P_-} = \\omega_{P'_-}} |\\langle f, \\phi_P \\rangle|^2 |\\langle \\phi_P, \\phi_{P'} \\rangle|.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> A direct calculation using \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#phip\">(22)</a> reveals that \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Csum_%7BP%27%3A+%5Comega_%7BP_-%7D+%3D+%5Comega_%7BP%27_-%7D%7D+%3D%7C%5Clangle+%5Cphi_P%2C+%5Cphi_%7BP%27%7D+%5Crangle%7C+%5Clesssim+1&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{P': \\omega_{P_-} = \\omega_{P'_-}} =|\\langle \\phi_P, \\phi_{P'} \\rangle| \\lesssim 1\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{P': \\omega_{P_-} = \\omega_{P'_-}} =|\\langle \\phi_P, \\phi_{P'} \\rangle| \\lesssim 1\" class=\"latex\" /></p> so the contribution of this case is at most \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Csum_%7BT_%2B%7D+%5Csum_%7BP+%5Cin+T_%2B%7D+%7C%5Clangle+f%2C+%5Cphi_P+%5Crangle%7C%5E2&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{T_+} \\sum_{P \\in T_+} |\\langle f, \\phi_P \\rangle|^2\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{T_+} \\sum_{P \\in T_+} |\\langle f, \\phi_P \\rangle|^2\" class=\"latex\" /></p> as desired. \n<p> Now we deal with the case when <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Comega_%7BP_-%7D+%5Csubsetneq+%5Comega_%7BP%27_-%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\omega_{P_-} \\subsetneq \\omega_{P'_-}}\" title=\"{\\omega_{P_-} \\subsetneq \\omega_{P'_-}}\" class=\"latex\" />, which by the preceding discussion implies that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7CI_%7BP%27%7D%7C+%3C+%7CI_P%7C%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{|I_{P'}| < |I_P|}\" title=\"{|I_{P'}| < |I_P|}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BI_%7BP%27%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{I_{P'}}\" title=\"{I_{P'}}\" class=\"latex\" /> lies outside of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B3I_T%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{3I_T}\" title=\"{3I_T}\" class=\"latex\" />. Here we use <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#energ\">(37)</a> to bound </p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7C%5Clangle+f%2C+%5Cphi_%7BP%7D+%5Crangle%7C+%5Cleq+%5Cvarepsilon+%7CI_%7BP%7D%7C%5E%7B1%2F2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  |\\langle f, \\phi_{P} \\rangle| \\leq \\varepsilon |I_{P}|^{1/2}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  |\\langle f, \\phi_{P} \\rangle| \\leq \\varepsilon |I_{P}|^{1/2}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> and \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7C%5Clangle+f%2C+%5Cphi_%7BP%27%7D+%5Crangle%7C+%5Cleq+%5Cvarepsilon+%7CI_%7BP%27%7D%7C%5E%7B1%2F2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  |\\langle f, \\phi_{P'} \\rangle| \\leq \\varepsilon |I_{P'}|^{1/2}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  |\\langle f, \\phi_{P'} \\rangle| \\leq \\varepsilon |I_{P'}|^{1/2}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n<p> and then we can bound this contribution by </p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cvarepsilon%5E2+%5Csum_%7BT_%2B+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+T%7D_%2B%7D+%5Csum_%7BP+%5Cin+T_%2B%7D+%7CI_P%7C%5E%7B1%2F2%7D+%5Csum_%7BP%27%3A+%7CI_%7BP%27%7D%7C+%3C+%7CI_P%7C%2C+I_%7BP%27%7D+%5Ccap+3I_T+%3D+%5Cemptyset%7D+%7CI_%7BP%27%7D%7C%5E%7B1%2F2%7D+%7C%5Clangle+%5Cphi_P%2C+%5Cphi_%7BP%27%7D%7C.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\varepsilon^2 \\sum_{T_+ \\in {\\mathcal T}_+} \\sum_{P \\in T_+} |I_P|^{1/2} \\sum_{P': |I_{P'}| < |I_P|, I_{P'} \\cap 3I_T = \\emptyset} |I_{P'}|^{1/2} |\\langle \\phi_P, \\phi_{P'}|.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\varepsilon^2 \\sum_{T_+ \\in {\\mathcal T}_+} \\sum_{P \\in T_+} |I_P|^{1/2} \\sum_{P': |I_{P'}| < |I_P|, I_{P'} \\cap 3I_T = \\emptyset} |I_{P'}|^{1/2} |\\langle \\phi_P, \\phi_{P'}|.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> Direct calculation using \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#phip\">(22)</a> reveals that \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Csum_%7BP%27%3A+%7CI_%7BP%27%7D%7C+%3C+%7CI_P%7C%2C+I_%7BP%27%7D+%5Ccap+3I_T+%3D+%5Cemptyset%7D+%7CI_%7BP%27%7D%7C%5E%7B1%2F2%7D+%7C%5Clangle+%5Cphi_P%2C+%5Cphi_%7BP%27%7D%7C+%5Clesssim+%7CI_T%7C%5E%7B1%2F2%7D+%28%7CI_P%7C%2F%7CI_T%7C%29%5E%7B10%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{P': |I_{P'}| < |I_P|, I_{P'} \\cap 3I_T = \\emptyset} |I_{P'}|^{1/2} |\\langle \\phi_P, \\phi_{P'}| \\lesssim |I_T|^{1/2} (|I_P|/|I_T|)^{10}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{P': |I_{P'}| < |I_P|, I_{P'} \\cap 3I_T = \\emptyset} |I_{P'}|^{1/2} |\\langle \\phi_P, \\phi_{P'}| \\lesssim |I_T|^{1/2} (|I_P|/|I_T|)^{10}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> (say), and also \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Csum_%7BP+%5Cin+T_%2B%7D+%7CI_P%7C%5E%7B1%2F2%7D+%7CI_T%7C%5E%7B1%2F2%7D+%28%7CI_P%7C%2F%7CI_T%7C%29%5E%7B10%7D+%5Clesssim+%7CI_T%7C&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{P \\in T_+} |I_P|^{1/2} |I_T|^{1/2} (|I_P|/|I_T|)^{10} \\lesssim |I_T|\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{P \\in T_+} |I_P|^{1/2} |I_T|^{1/2} (|I_P|/|I_T|)^{10} \\lesssim |I_T|\" class=\"latex\" /></p> so we obtain a bound of \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cvarepsilon%5E2+%5Csum_%7BT_%2B+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+T%7D_%2B%7D+%7CI_T%7C&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\varepsilon^2 \\sum_{T_+ \\in {\\mathcal T}_+} |I_T|\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\varepsilon^2 \\sum_{T_+ \\in {\\mathcal T}_+} |I_T|\" class=\"latex\" /></p> which is acceptable by \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#ptp-1\">(48)</a>. This finally finishes the proof of Proposition \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#energy-select\">16</a>, which in turn completes the proof of Carleson’s theorem. \n<p> </p>\n<blockquote>\n <b>Remark 18</b> \n <a name=\"other\"></a> The Lacey-Thiele proof of Carleson’s theorem given above relies on a decomposition of a tileset in a way that controls both energy and mass. The \n <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=199631\">original proof of Carleson</a> dispenses with mass (or with the function \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN%28x%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N(x)}\" title=\"{N(x)}\" class=\"latex\" />), and focuses on controlling maximal operators that (in our notation) are basically of the form \n <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Csup_N+%7C+%5Csum_%7BP+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D%3A+N+%5Cin+%5Comega_%7BP_%2B%7D%7D+%5Clangle+f%2C+%5Cphi_P+%5Crangle+%5Cphi_P%28x%29+%7C.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\sup_N | \\sum_{P \\in {\\mathcal P}: N \\in \\omega_{P_+}} \\langle f, \\phi_P \\rangle \\phi_P(x) |.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\sup_N | \\sum_{P \\in {\\mathcal P}: N \\in \\omega_{P_+}} \\langle f, \\phi_P \\rangle \\phi_P(x) |.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> To control such functions, one iterates a decomposition similar to Proposition \n <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#energy-select\">16</a> to partition \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\mathcal P}}\" title=\"{{\\mathcal P}}\" class=\"latex\" /> into trees with good energy control, and establishes pointwise control of the contribution of each tree outside of an exceptional set. See Section 4 of \n <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=3334208\">this article of Demeter</a> for an exposition in the simplified setting of Walsh-Fourier analysis. The \n <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764/mathscinet-getitem?mr=340926\">proof of Fefferman</a> takes the opposite tack, dispensing with energy and focusing on bounding the operator norm of the linearised operator \n <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++f+%5Cmapsto+%5Csum_%7BP+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D%3A+N%28x%29+%5Cin+%5Comega_%7BP_%2B%7D%7D+%5Clangle+f%2C+%5Cphi_P+%5Crangle+%5Cphi_P%28x%29.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  f \\mapsto \\sum_{P \\in {\\mathcal P}: N(x) \\in \\omega_{P_+}} \\langle f, \\phi_P \\rangle \\phi_P(x).\" title=\"\\displaystyle  f \\mapsto \\sum_{P \\in {\\mathcal P}: N(x) \\in \\omega_{P_+}} \\langle f, \\phi_P \\rangle \\phi_P(x).\" class=\"latex\" /></p> Roughly speaking, the strategy is to iterate a version of Proposition \n <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#energy-select\">16</a> for partition \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\mathcal P}}\" title=\"{{\\mathcal P}}\" class=\"latex\" /> into “forests” of disjoint trees, though in Fefferman’s argument some additional work is invested into obtaining even better disjointness properties on these forests than is given here. See Section 5 of \n <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=3334208\">this article of Demeter</a> for an exposition in the simplified setting of Walsh-Fourier analysis. \n</blockquote> \n<p></p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> A modification of the above arguments used to establish the weak <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%282%2C2%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(2,2)}\" title=\"{(2,2)}\" class=\"latex\" /> estimate can also establish restricted weak-type <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28p%2Cp%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(p,p)}\" title=\"{(p,p)}\" class=\"latex\" /> estimates for any <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bp%3E2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{p>2}\" title=\"{p>2}\" class=\"latex\" />: </p>\n<p> </p>\n<blockquote>\n <b>Exercise 19</b> For any sets \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BE%2CF+%5Csubset+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{E,F \\subset {\\bf R}}\" title=\"{E,F \\subset {\\bf R}}\" class=\"latex\" /> of finite measure, and any measurable function \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN%3A+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N: {\\bf R} \\rightarrow {\\bf R}}\" title=\"{N: {\\bf R} \\rightarrow {\\bf R}}\" class=\"latex\" />, show that \n <a name=\"est-1\"><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+1_E%28X%29+1_%7BD+%5Cleq+N%28X%29%7D+1_F%5C+dx+%5Clesssim_p+%7CF%7C%5E%7B1%2Fp%7D+%7CE%7C%5E%7B1%2Fp%27%7D+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%2851%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\int_{\\bf R} 1_E(X) 1_{D \\leq N(X)} 1_F\\ dx \\lesssim_p |F|^{1/p} |E|^{1/p'} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (51)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\int_{\\bf R} 1_E(X) 1_{D \\leq N(X)} 1_F\\ dx \\lesssim_p |F|^{1/p} |E|^{1/p'} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (51)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> </a> for any \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B2+%5Cleq+p+%3C+%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{2 \\leq p < \\infty}\" title=\"{2 \\leq p < \\infty}\" class=\"latex\" />. (\n <em>Hint:</em> repeat the previous analysis with \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%3D1_F%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f=1_F}\" title=\"{f=1_F}\" class=\"latex\" />, but supplement it with an additional energy bound \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathrm%7BEnergy%7D%28%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D%29+%5Clesssim+1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\mathrm{Energy}({\\mathcal P}) \\lesssim 1}\" title=\"{\\mathrm{Energy}({\\mathcal P}) \\lesssim 1}\" class=\"latex\" /> coming from a suitably localised version of Exercise \n <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#ao\">12</a>.) \n</blockquote> \n<p></p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> The bound <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#est-1\">(51)</a> is also true for <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1+%3C+p+%3C+2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1 < p < 2}\" title=\"{1 < p < 2}\" class=\"latex\" />, yielding Hunt’s theorem, but this requires some additional arguments of Calderón-Zygmund type, involving the removal of an exceptional set <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5COmega%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\Omega}\" title=\"{\\Omega}\" class=\"latex\" /> defined using the Hardy-Littlewood maximal function: </p>\n<p> </p>\n<blockquote>\n <b>Exercise 20 (Hunt’s theorem)</b> Let \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BE%2C+F+%5Csubset+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{E, F \\subset {\\bf R}}\" title=\"{E, F \\subset {\\bf R}}\" class=\"latex\" /> be of finite non-zero measure, and let \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN%3A+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N: {\\bf R} \\rightarrow {\\bf R}}\" title=\"{N: {\\bf R} \\rightarrow {\\bf R}}\" class=\"latex\" /> be a measurable function. Let \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5COmega%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\Omega}\" title=\"{\\Omega}\" class=\"latex\" /> be the exceptional set \n <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5COmega+%3A%3D+%5C%7B+x+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%3A+M+1_F+%5Cgeq+C+%5Cfrac%7B%7CF%7C%7D%7B%7CE%7C%7D+%5C%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\Omega := \\{ x \\in {\\bf R}: M 1_F \\geq C \\frac{|F|}{|E|} \\}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\Omega := \\{ x \\in {\\bf R}: M 1_F \\geq C \\frac{|F|}{|E|} \\}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> for a large absolute constant \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BC%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{C}\" title=\"{C}\" class=\"latex\" />; note from the Hardy-Littlewood inequality that \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7C%5COmega%7C+%5Cleq+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B2%7D+%7CE%7C%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{|\\Omega| \\leq \\frac{1}{2} |E|}\" title=\"{|\\Omega| \\leq \\frac{1}{2} |E|}\" class=\"latex\" /> if \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BC%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{C}\" title=\"{C}\" class=\"latex\" /> is large enough. \n <ul> \n  <li>(i) If <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\mathcal P}}\" title=\"{{\\mathcal P}}\" class=\"latex\" /> be a finite collection of tiles with <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BI_P+%5Csubset+%5COmega%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{I_P \\subset \\Omega}\" title=\"{I_P \\subset \\Omega}\" class=\"latex\" /> for all <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P \\in {\\mathcal P}}\" title=\"{P \\in {\\mathcal P}}\" class=\"latex\" />, show that <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Csum_%7BP+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D%7D+%7C%5Clangle+1_F%2C+%5Cphi_P+%5Crangle+%5Clangle+%5Cphi_P%2C+1_%7BE_P%5E%2B%7D+%5Crangle%7C+%5Clesssim+%7CF%7C.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{P \\in {\\mathcal P}} |\\langle 1_F, \\phi_P \\rangle \\langle \\phi_P, 1_{E_P^+} \\rangle| \\lesssim |F|.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{P \\in {\\mathcal P}} |\\langle 1_F, \\phi_P \\rangle \\langle \\phi_P, 1_{E_P^+} \\rangle| \\lesssim |F|.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> (<em>Hint:</em> By using <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#phip\">(22)</a> and the disjointness of the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BE_P%5E%2B%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{E_P^+}\" title=\"{E_P^+}\" class=\"latex\" /> when <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BI_P%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{I_P}\" title=\"{I_P}\" class=\"latex\" /> is fixed, first establish the estimate <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Csum_%7BP+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D%3A+I_P+%3D+I%7D+%7C%5Clangle+1_F%2C+%5Cphi_P+%5Crangle+%5Clangle+%5Cphi_P%2C+1_%7BE_P%5E%2B%7D+%5Crangle%7C+%5Clesssim+2%5E%7B-k%7D+%5Cfrac%7B%7CF%7C%7D%7B%7CE%7C%7D+%7CI%7C&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{P \\in {\\mathcal P}: I_P = I} |\\langle 1_F, \\phi_P \\rangle \\langle \\phi_P, 1_{E_P^+} \\rangle| \\lesssim 2^{-k} \\frac{|F|}{|E|} |I|\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{P \\in {\\mathcal P}: I_P = I} |\\langle 1_F, \\phi_P \\rangle \\langle \\phi_P, 1_{E_P^+} \\rangle| \\lesssim 2^{-k} \\frac{|F|}{|E|} |I|\" class=\"latex\" /></p> whenever <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k}\" title=\"{k}\" class=\"latex\" /> is a natural number and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BI%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{I}\" title=\"{I}\" class=\"latex\" /> is an interval with <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B2%5Ek+I+%5Csubset+%5COmega%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{2^k I \\subset \\Omega}\" title=\"{2^k I \\subset \\Omega}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B2%5E%7Bk%2B1%7D+I+%5Cnot+%5Csubset+%5COmega%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{2^{k+1} I \\not \\subset \\Omega}\" title=\"{2^{k+1} I \\not \\subset \\Omega}\" class=\"latex\" />.) </li>\n  <li>(ii) If <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\mathcal P}}\" title=\"{{\\mathcal P}}\" class=\"latex\" /> be a finite collection of tiles with <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BI_P+%5Csubsetneq+%5COmega%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{I_P \\subsetneq \\Omega}\" title=\"{I_P \\subsetneq \\Omega}\" class=\"latex\" /> for all <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P \\in {\\mathcal P}}\" title=\"{P \\in {\\mathcal P}}\" class=\"latex\" />, show that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathrm%7BEnergy%7D%28+%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D+%29+%5Clesssim+%7CF%7C%2F%7CE%7C%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\mathrm{Energy}( {\\mathcal P} ) \\lesssim |F|/|E|}\" title=\"{\\mathrm{Energy}( {\\mathcal P} ) \\lesssim |F|/|E|}\" class=\"latex\" />. (For a given tree <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T}\" title=\"{T}\" class=\"latex\" />, one can introduce the dyadic intervals <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BJ%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{J}\" title=\"{J}\" class=\"latex\" /> as in Exercise <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#spat\">11</a>, then perform a Calderón-Zygmund type decomposition to <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1_F%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1_F}\" title=\"{1_F}\" class=\"latex\" />, splitting it into a “good” function bounded pointwise by <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BO%28%7CF%7C%2F%7CE%7C%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{O(|F|/|E|)}\" title=\"{O(|F|/|E|)}\" class=\"latex\" />, plus “bad functions” that are supported on the intervals <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BJ%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{J}\" title=\"{J}\" class=\"latex\" /> and have mean zero. See <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=2031458\">this paper of Grafakos, Terwilleger, and myself</a> for details.) </li>\n  <li>(iii) For any finite collection of tiles for all <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P \\in {\\mathcal P}}\" title=\"{P \\in {\\mathcal P}}\" class=\"latex\" /> <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Csum_%7BP+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D%7D+%7C%5Clangle+1_F%2C+%5Cphi_P+%5Crangle+%5Clangle+%5Cphi_P%2C+1_%7BE_P%5E%2B%7D+%5Crangle%7C+%5Clesssim+%7CF%7C+%5Clog%282+%2B+%5Cfrac%7B%7CE%7C%7D%7B%7CF%7C%7D%29.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{P \\in {\\mathcal P}} |\\langle 1_F, \\phi_P \\rangle \\langle \\phi_P, 1_{E_P^+} \\rangle| \\lesssim |F| \\log(2 + \\frac{|E|}{|F|}).\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{P \\in {\\mathcal P}} |\\langle 1_F, \\phi_P \\rangle \\langle \\phi_P, 1_{E_P^+} \\rangle| \\lesssim |F| \\log(2 + \\frac{|E|}{|F|}).\" class=\"latex\" /></p> </li>\n  <li>(iv) Show that <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#est-1\">(51)</a> holds for all <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1+%3C+p+%3C+%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1 < p < \\infty}\" title=\"{1 < p < \\infty}\" class=\"latex\" />, and conclude Theorem <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#main\">2</a>(iii). </li>\n </ul> \n</blockquote> \n<p></p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<blockquote>\n <b>Remark 21</b> The methods of time-frequency analysis given here can handle several other operators that, like the Carleson operator, exhibit scaling, translation, and frequency modulation symmetries. One model example is the bilinear Hilbert transform \n <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++B%28f%2Cg%29%28x%29+%3A%3D+p.v.+%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Cfrac%7Bf%28x-t%29+g%28x-2t%29%7D%7Bt%7D%5C+dt&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  B(f,g)(x) := p.v. \\int_{\\bf R} \\frac{f(x-t) g(x-2t)}{t}\\ dt\" title=\"\\displaystyle  B(f,g)(x) := p.v. \\int_{\\bf R} \\frac{f(x-t) g(x-2t)}{t}\\ dt\" class=\"latex\" /></p> for \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%2Cg+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+S%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f,g \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{f,g \\in {\\mathcal S}({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" />. The methods in this set of notes were used \n <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=1491450\">by Lacey and Thiele</a> to establish the estimates \n <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+B%28f%2Cg%29+%5C%7C_%7BL%5E%7Br%27%7D%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D+%5Clesssim_%7Bp%2Cq%2Cr%7D+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D+%5C%7Cg%5C%7C_%7BL%5Eq%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| B(f,g) \\|_{L^{r'}({\\bf R})} \\lesssim_{p,q,r} \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R})} \\|g\\|_{L^q({\\bf R})}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| B(f,g) \\|_{L^{r'}({\\bf R})} \\lesssim_{p,q,r} \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R})} \\|g\\|_{L^q({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> for \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B2+%3C+p%2Cq%2Cr+%3C+%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{2 < p,q,r < \\infty}\" title=\"{2 < p,q,r < \\infty}\" class=\"latex\" /> with \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1%2Fp+%2B+1%2Fq+%2B+1%2Fr+%3D+1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1/p + 1/q + 1/r = 1}\" title=\"{1/p + 1/q + 1/r = 1}\" class=\"latex\" /> (these estimates have since been strengthened and extended in a number of ways). We only give the briefest of sketches here. Much as how Carleson’s theorem can be reduced to a bound \n <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#est-tile-finite\">(19)</a>, the above estimates can be reduced to the estimation of a model sum \n <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Csum_%7B%28P_1%2CP_2%2CP_3%29+%5Cin+%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D%7D+%5Clangle+f%2C+%5Cphi_%7BP_1%7D+%5Crangle+%5Clangle+g%2C+%5Cphi_%7BP_2%7D+%5Crangle+%5Clangle+h%2C+%5Cphi_%7BP_3%7D+%5Crangle&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{(P_1,P_2,P_3) \\in {\\mathcal P}} \\langle f, \\phi_{P_1} \\rangle \\langle g, \\phi_{P_2} \\rangle \\langle h, \\phi_{P_3} \\rangle\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{(P_1,P_2,P_3) \\in {\\mathcal P}} \\langle f, \\phi_{P_1} \\rangle \\langle g, \\phi_{P_2} \\rangle \\langle h, \\phi_{P_3} \\rangle\" class=\"latex\" /></p> where \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\mathcal P}}\" title=\"{{\\mathcal P}}\" class=\"latex\" /> is a certain collection of triples \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28P_1%2CP_2%2CP_3%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(P_1,P_2,P_3)}\" title=\"{(P_1,P_2,P_3)}\" class=\"latex\" /> of tiles \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP_1%2CP_2%2CP_3%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{P_1,P_2,P_3}\" title=\"{P_1,P_2,P_3}\" class=\"latex\" /> with common spatial interval \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BI_%7BP_1%7D+%3D+I_%7BP_2%7D+%3D+I_%7BP_3%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{I_{P_1} = I_{P_2} = I_{P_3}}\" title=\"{I_{P_1} = I_{P_2} = I_{P_3}}\" class=\"latex\" /> and frequency intervals \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Comega_%7BP_1%7D%2C+%5Comega_%7BP_2%7D%2C+%5Comega_%7BP_3%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\omega_{P_1}, \\omega_{P_2}, \\omega_{P_3}}\" title=\"{\\omega_{P_1}, \\omega_{P_2}, \\omega_{P_3}}\" class=\"latex\" /> varying along a certain one-parameter family for each fixed choice of spatial interval. One then uses a variant of Proposition \n <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#energy-select\">16</a> to partition \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\mathcal P}}\" title=\"{{\\mathcal P}}\" class=\"latex\" /> into “\n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1}\" title=\"{1}\" class=\"latex\" />-trees”, “\n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{2}\" title=\"{2}\" class=\"latex\" />-trees”, and “\n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B3%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{3}\" title=\"{3}\" class=\"latex\" />-trees”, the contribution of each of which can be controlled by the energies of \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%2C+g%2C+h%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f, g, h}\" title=\"{f, g, h}\" class=\"latex\" /> on such trees, times the length of the spatial support of the tree, in analogy with Exercise \n <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#tree-ex\">15</a>. See for instance \n <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=3052499\">the text of Muscalu and Schlag</a> for more discussion and further results. \n</blockquote> \n<p></p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<blockquote>\n <b>Remark 22</b> The concepts of mass and energy can be abstracted into a framework of \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BL%5Ep%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{L^p}\" title=\"{L^p}\" class=\"latex\" /> spaces associated to outer measures (as opposed to the classical setup of \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BL%5Ep%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{L^p}\" title=\"{L^p}\" class=\"latex\" /> spaces associated to countably additive measures), in which the mass and energy selection propositions can be viewed as consequences of an abstract Carleson embedding theorem, and the calculations establishing estimates such as \n <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11764#est-tile-finite\">(19)</a> from such propositions and a tree estimate can be viewed as consequences of an “outer Hölder inequality”. See \n <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=3312633\">this paper of Do and Thiele</a> for details. \n</blockquote> \n<p></p>\n<p> </p>\n<p></p>
