This paper revisits a useful <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=2188130\">multiplier theorem of Ionescu and Wainger</a> on “major arc” Fourier multiplier operators on the integers <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf Z}}\" title=\"{{\\bf Z}}\" class=\"latex\" /> (or lattices <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%5Ed%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf Z}^d}\" title=\"{{\\bf Z}^d}\" class=\"latex\" />), and strengthens the bounds while also interpreting it from the viewpoint of the adelic integers <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+A%7D_%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf A}_{\\bf Z}}\" title=\"{{\\bf A}_{\\bf Z}}\" class=\"latex\" /> (which were also used in <a href=\"https://terrytao.wordpress.com/2020/08/03/pointwise-ergodic-theorems-for-non-conventional-bilinear-polynomial-averages/\">my recent paper with Krause and Mirek</a>). </p>\n<p> For simplicity let us just work in one dimension. Any smooth function <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bm%3A+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cbf+C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{m: {\\bf R}/{\\bf Z} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" title=\"{m: {\\bf R}/{\\bf Z} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" class=\"latex\" /> then defines a discrete Fourier multiplier operator <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT_m%3A+%5Cell%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29+%5Crightarrow+%5Cell%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T_m: \\ell^p({\\bf Z}) \\rightarrow \\ell^p({\\bf Z})}\" title=\"{T_m: \\ell^p({\\bf Z}) \\rightarrow \\ell^p({\\bf Z})}\" class=\"latex\" /> for any <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1+%5Cleq+p+%5Cleq+%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1 \\leq p \\leq \\infty}\" title=\"{1 \\leq p \\leq \\infty}\" class=\"latex\" /> by the formula </p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7B%5Cmathcal+F%7D_%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D+T_m+f%28%5Cxi%29+%3D%3A+m%28%5Cxi%29+%7B%5Cmathcal+F%7D_%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D+f%28%5Cxi%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathcal F}_{\\bf Z} T_m f(\\xi) =: m(\\xi) {\\mathcal F}_{\\bf Z} f(\\xi)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathcal F}_{\\bf Z} T_m f(\\xi) =: m(\\xi) {\\mathcal F}_{\\bf Z} f(\\xi)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> where \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cmathcal+F%7D_%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D+f%28%5Cxi%29+%3A%3D+%5Csum_%7Bn+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D+f%28n%29+e%28n+%5Cxi%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\mathcal F}_{\\bf Z} f(\\xi) := \\sum_{n \\in {\\bf Z}} f(n) e(n \\xi)}\" title=\"{{\\mathcal F}_{\\bf Z} f(\\xi) := \\sum_{n \\in {\\bf Z}} f(n) e(n \\xi)}\" class=\"latex\" /> is the Fourier transform on \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf Z}}\" title=\"{{\\bf Z}}\" class=\"latex\" />; similarly, any test function \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bm%3A+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cbf+C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{m: {\\bf R} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" title=\"{m: {\\bf R} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" class=\"latex\" /> defines a continuous Fourier multiplier operator \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT_m%3A+L%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29+%5Crightarrow+L%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T_m: L^p({\\bf R}) \\rightarrow L^p({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{T_m: L^p({\\bf R}) \\rightarrow L^p({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" /> by the formula \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7B%5Cmathcal+F%7D_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+T_m+f%28%5Cxi%29+%3A%3D+m%28%5Cxi%29+%7B%5Cmathcal+F%7D_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+f%28%5Cxi%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathcal F}_{\\bf R} T_m f(\\xi) := m(\\xi) {\\mathcal F}_{\\bf R} f(\\xi)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathcal F}_{\\bf R} T_m f(\\xi) := m(\\xi) {\\mathcal F}_{\\bf R} f(\\xi)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> where \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cmathcal+F%7D_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+f%28%5Cxi%29+%3A%3D+%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+f%28x%29+e%28x+%5Cxi%29%5C+dx%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\mathcal F}_{\\bf R} f(\\xi) := \\int_{\\bf R} f(x) e(x \\xi)\\ dx}\" title=\"{{\\mathcal F}_{\\bf R} f(\\xi) := \\int_{\\bf R} f(x) e(x \\xi)\\ dx}\" class=\"latex\" />. In both cases we refer to \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bm%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{m}\" title=\"{m}\" class=\"latex\" /> as the \n<em>symbol</em> of the multiplier operator \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT_m%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T_m}\" title=\"{T_m}\" class=\"latex\" />. \n<p> We will be interested in discrete Fourier multiplier operators whose symbols are supported on a finite union of arcs. One way to construct such operators is by “folding” continuous Fourier multiplier operators into various target frequencies. To make this folding operation precise, given any continuous Fourier multiplier operator <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT_m%3A+L%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29+%5Crightarrow+L%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T_m: L^p({\\bf R}) \\rightarrow L^p({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{T_m: L^p({\\bf R}) \\rightarrow L^p({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" />, and any frequency <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\alpha \\in {\\bf R}/{\\bf Z}}\" title=\"{\\alpha \\in {\\bf R}/{\\bf Z}}\" class=\"latex\" />, we define the discrete Fourier multiplier operator <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT_%7Bm%3B%5Calpha%7D%3A+%5Cell%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29+%5Crightarrow+%5Cell%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T_{m;\\alpha}: \\ell^p({\\bf Z}) \\rightarrow \\ell^p({\\bf Z})}\" title=\"{T_{m;\\alpha}: \\ell^p({\\bf Z}) \\rightarrow \\ell^p({\\bf Z})}\" class=\"latex\" /> for any frequency shift <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\alpha \\in {\\bf R}/{\\bf Z}}\" title=\"{\\alpha \\in {\\bf R}/{\\bf Z}}\" class=\"latex\" /> by the formula </p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%7B%5Cmathcal+F%7D_%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D+T_%7Bm%2C%5Calpha%7D+f%28%5Cxi%29+%3A%3D+%5Csum_%7B%5Ctheta+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%3A+%5Cxi+%3D+%5Calpha+%2B+%5Ctheta%7D+m%28%5Ctheta%29+%7B%5Cmathcal+F%7D_%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D+f%28%5Cxi%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathcal F}_{\\bf Z} T_{m,\\alpha} f(\\xi) := \\sum_{\\theta \\in {\\bf R}: \\xi = \\alpha + \\theta} m(\\theta) {\\mathcal F}_{\\bf Z} f(\\xi)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  {\\mathcal F}_{\\bf Z} T_{m,\\alpha} f(\\xi) := \\sum_{\\theta \\in {\\bf R}: \\xi = \\alpha + \\theta} m(\\theta) {\\mathcal F}_{\\bf Z} f(\\xi)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> or equivalently \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++T_%7Bm%3B%5Calpha%7D+f%28n%29+%3D+%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+m%28%5Ctheta%29+%7B%5Cmathcal+F%7D_%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D+f%28%5Calpha%2B%5Ctheta%29+e%28+n%28%5Calpha%2B%5Ctheta%29+%29%5C+d%5Ctheta.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  T_{m;\\alpha} f(n) = \\int_{\\bf R} m(\\theta) {\\mathcal F}_{\\bf Z} f(\\alpha+\\theta) e( n(\\alpha+\\theta) )\\ d\\theta.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  T_{m;\\alpha} f(n) = \\int_{\\bf R} m(\\theta) {\\mathcal F}_{\\bf Z} f(\\alpha+\\theta) e( n(\\alpha+\\theta) )\\ d\\theta.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> More generally, given any finite set \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5CSigma+%5Csubset+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\Sigma \\subset {\\bf R}/{\\bf Z}}\" title=\"{\\Sigma \\subset {\\bf R}/{\\bf Z}}\" class=\"latex\" />, we can form a multifrequency projection operator \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT_%7Bm%3B%5CSigma%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T_{m;\\Sigma}}\" title=\"{T_{m;\\Sigma}}\" class=\"latex\" /> on \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cell%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\ell^p({\\bf Z})}\" title=\"{\\ell^p({\\bf Z})}\" class=\"latex\" /> by the formula \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++T_%7Bm%3B%5CSigma%7D+%3A%3D+%5Csum_%7B%5Calpha+%5Cin+%5CSigma%7D+T_%7Bm%3B%5Calpha%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  T_{m;\\Sigma} := \\sum_{\\alpha \\in \\Sigma} T_{m;\\alpha}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  T_{m;\\Sigma} := \\sum_{\\alpha \\in \\Sigma} T_{m;\\alpha}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> thus \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++T_%7Bm%3B%5Calpha%7D+f%28n%29+%3D+%5Csum_%7B%5Calpha+%5Cin+%5CSigma%7D+%5Cint_%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+m%28%5Ctheta%29+%7B%5Cmathcal+F%7D_%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D+f%28%5Calpha%2B%5Ctheta%29+e%28+n%28%5Calpha%2B%5Ctheta%29+%29%5C+d%5Ctheta.&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  T_{m;\\alpha} f(n) = \\sum_{\\alpha \\in \\Sigma} \\int_{\\bf R} m(\\theta) {\\mathcal F}_{\\bf Z} f(\\alpha+\\theta) e( n(\\alpha+\\theta) )\\ d\\theta.\" title=\"\\displaystyle  T_{m;\\alpha} f(n) = \\sum_{\\alpha \\in \\Sigma} \\int_{\\bf R} m(\\theta) {\\mathcal F}_{\\bf Z} f(\\alpha+\\theta) e( n(\\alpha+\\theta) )\\ d\\theta.\" class=\"latex\" /></p> This construction gives discrete Fourier multiplier operators whose symbol can be localised to a finite union of arcs. For instance, if \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bm%3A+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cbf+C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{m: {\\bf R} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" title=\"{m: {\\bf R} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" class=\"latex\" /> is supported on \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5B-%5Cvarepsilon%2C%5Cvarepsilon%5D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{[-\\varepsilon,\\varepsilon]}\" title=\"{[-\\varepsilon,\\varepsilon]}\" class=\"latex\" />, then \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT_%7Bm%3B%5CSigma%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T_{m;\\Sigma}}\" title=\"{T_{m;\\Sigma}}\" class=\"latex\" /> is a Fourier multiplier whose symbol is supported on the set \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cbigcup_%7B%5Calpha+%5Cin+%5CSigma%7D+%5Calpha+%2B+%5B-%5Cvarepsilon%2C%5Cvarepsilon%5D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\bigcup_{\\alpha \\in \\Sigma} \\alpha + [-\\varepsilon,\\varepsilon]}\" title=\"{\\bigcup_{\\alpha \\in \\Sigma} \\alpha + [-\\varepsilon,\\varepsilon]}\" class=\"latex\" />. \n<p> There are a body of results relating the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cell%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\ell^p({\\bf Z})}\" title=\"{\\ell^p({\\bf Z})}\" class=\"latex\" /> theory of discrete Fourier multiplier operators such as <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT_%7Bm%3B%5Calpha%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T_{m;\\alpha}}\" title=\"{T_{m;\\alpha}}\" class=\"latex\" /> or <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT_%7Bm%3B%5CSigma%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T_{m;\\Sigma}}\" title=\"{T_{m;\\Sigma}}\" class=\"latex\" /> with the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{L^p({\\bf R})}\" title=\"{L^p({\\bf R})}\" class=\"latex\" /> theory of their continuous counterparts. For instance we have the basic result of <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=1888798\">Magyar, Stein, and Wainger</a>: </p>\n<p> </p>\n<blockquote>\n <b>Proposition 1 (Magyar-Stein-Wainger sampling principle)</b> \n <a name=\"samp\"></a> Let \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1+%5Cleq+p+%5Cleq+%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1 \\leq p \\leq \\infty}\" title=\"{1 \\leq p \\leq \\infty}\" class=\"latex\" /> and \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\alpha \\in {\\bf R}/{\\bf Z}}\" title=\"{\\alpha \\in {\\bf R}/{\\bf Z}}\" class=\"latex\" />. \n <ul> \n  <li>(i) If <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bm%3A+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cbf+C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{m: {\\bf R} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" title=\"{m: {\\bf R} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" class=\"latex\" /> is a smooth function supported in <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5B-1%2F2%2C1%2F2%5D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{[-1/2,1/2]}\" title=\"{[-1/2,1/2]}\" class=\"latex\" />, then <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7CT_%7Bm%3B%5Calpha%7D%5C%7C_%7BB%28%5Cell%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%29%7D+%5Clesssim+%5C%7CT_m%5C%7C_%7BB%28L%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%29%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\|T_{m;\\alpha}\\|_{B(\\ell^p({\\bf Z}))} \\lesssim \\|T_m\\|_{B(L^p({\\bf R}))}}\" title=\"{\\|T_{m;\\alpha}\\|_{B(\\ell^p({\\bf Z}))} \\lesssim \\|T_m\\|_{B(L^p({\\bf R}))}}\" class=\"latex\" />, where <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BB%28V%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{B(V)}\" title=\"{B(V)}\" class=\"latex\" /> denotes the operator norm of an operator <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT%3A+V+%5Crightarrow+V%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T: V \\rightarrow V}\" title=\"{T: V \\rightarrow V}\" class=\"latex\" />. </li>\n  <li>(ii) More generally, if <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bm%3A+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cbf+C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{m: {\\bf R} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" title=\"{m: {\\bf R} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" class=\"latex\" /> is a smooth function supported in <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5B-1%2F2Q%2C1%2F2Q%5D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{[-1/2Q,1/2Q]}\" title=\"{[-1/2Q,1/2Q]}\" class=\"latex\" /> for some natural number <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BQ%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{Q}\" title=\"{Q}\" class=\"latex\" />, then <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7CT_%7Bm%3B%5Calpha+%2B+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7BQ%7D%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D%5C%7C_%7BB%28%5Cell%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%29%7D+%5Clesssim+%5C%7CT_m%5C%7C_%7BB%28L%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%29%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\|T_{m;\\alpha + \\frac{1}{Q}{\\bf Z}/{\\bf Z}}\\|_{B(\\ell^p({\\bf Z}))} \\lesssim \\|T_m\\|_{B(L^p({\\bf R}))}}\" title=\"{\\|T_{m;\\alpha + \\frac{1}{Q}{\\bf Z}/{\\bf Z}}\\|_{B(\\ell^p({\\bf Z}))} \\lesssim \\|T_m\\|_{B(L^p({\\bf R}))}}\" class=\"latex\" />. </li>\n </ul> \n</blockquote> \n<p></p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> When <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bp%3D2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{p=2}\" title=\"{p=2}\" class=\"latex\" /> the implied constant in these bounds can be set to equal <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1}\" title=\"{1}\" class=\"latex\" />. In the paper of Magyar, Stein, and Wainger it was posed as an open problem as to whether this is the case for other <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bp%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{p}\" title=\"{p}\" class=\"latex\" />; in an appendix to this paper I show that the answer is negative if <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bp%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{p}\" title=\"{p}\" class=\"latex\" /> is sufficiently close to <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1}\" title=\"{1}\" class=\"latex\" /> or <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\infty}\" title=\"{\\infty}\" class=\"latex\" />, but I do not know the full answer to this question. </p>\n<p> This proposition allows one to get a good multiplier theory for symbols supported near cyclic groups <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7BQ%7D%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\frac{1}{Q}{\\bf Z}/{\\bf Z}}\" title=\"{\\frac{1}{Q}{\\bf Z}/{\\bf Z}}\" class=\"latex\" />; for instance it shows that a discrete Fourier multiplier with symbol <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Csum_%7B%5Calpha+%5Cin+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7BQ%7D%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D+%5Cphi%28Q%28%5Cxi-%5Calpha%29%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\sum_{\\alpha \\in \\frac{1}{Q}{\\bf Z}/{\\bf Z}} \\phi(Q(\\xi-\\alpha))}\" title=\"{\\sum_{\\alpha \\in \\frac{1}{Q}{\\bf Z}/{\\bf Z}} \\phi(Q(\\xi-\\alpha))}\" class=\"latex\" /> for a fixed test function <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cphi%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\phi}\" title=\"{\\phi}\" class=\"latex\" /> is bounded on <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cell%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\ell^p({\\bf Z})}\" title=\"{\\ell^p({\\bf Z})}\" class=\"latex\" />, uniformly in <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bp%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{p}\" title=\"{p}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BQ%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{Q}\" title=\"{Q}\" class=\"latex\" />. For many applications in discrete harmonic analysis, one would similarly like a good multiplier theory for symbols supported in “major arc” sets such as <a name=\"major\"></a></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><a name=\"major\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cbigcup_%7Bq%3D1%7D%5EN+%5Cbigcup_%7B%5Calpha+%5Cin+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7Bq%7D%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D+%5Calpha+%2B+%5B-%5Cvarepsilon%2C%5Cvarepsilon%5D+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%281%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\bigcup_{q=1}^N \\bigcup_{\\alpha \\in \\frac{1}{q}{\\bf Z}/{\\bf Z}} \\alpha + [-\\varepsilon,\\varepsilon] \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (1)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\bigcup_{q=1}^N \\bigcup_{\\alpha \\in \\frac{1}{q}{\\bf Z}/{\\bf Z}} \\alpha + [-\\varepsilon,\\varepsilon] \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (1)\" class=\"latex\" /></a></p>\n<a name=\"major\"> </a> and in particular to get a good Littlewood-Paley theory adapted to major arcs. (This is particularly the case when trying to control “true complexity zero” expressions for which the minor arc contributions can be shown to be negligible; \n<a href=\"https://terrytao.wordpress.com/2020/08/03/pointwise-ergodic-theorems-for-non-conventional-bilinear-polynomial-averages/\">my recent paper with Krause and Mirek</a> is focused on expressions of this type.) At present we do not have a good multiplier theory that is directly adapted to the classical major arc set \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11891#major\">(1)</a> (though I do not know of rigorous negative results that show that such a theory is not possible); however, \n<a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=2188130\">Ionescu and Wainger were able</a> to obtain a useful substitute theory in which \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11891#major\">(1)</a> was replaced by a somewhat larger set that had better multiplier behaviour. Starting with a finite collection \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{S}\" title=\"{S}\" class=\"latex\" /> of pairwise coprime natural numbers, and a natural number \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k}\" title=\"{k}\" class=\"latex\" />, one can form the major arc type set \n<a name=\"mat\"><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cbigcup_%7B%5Calpha+%5Cin+%5CSigma_%7B%5Cleq+k%7D%7D+%5Calpha+%2B+%5B-%5Cvarepsilon%2C%5Cvarepsilon%5D+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%282%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\bigcup_{\\alpha \\in \\Sigma_{\\leq k}} \\alpha + [-\\varepsilon,\\varepsilon] \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (2)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\bigcup_{\\alpha \\in \\Sigma_{\\leq k}} \\alpha + [-\\varepsilon,\\varepsilon] \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (2)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> </a> where \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5CSigma_%7B%5Cleq+k%7D+%5Csubset+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\Sigma_{\\leq k} \\subset {\\bf R}/{\\bf Z}}\" title=\"{\\Sigma_{\\leq k} \\subset {\\bf R}/{\\bf Z}}\" class=\"latex\" /> consists of all rational points in the unit circle of the form \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cfrac%7Ba%7D%7BQ%7D+%5Cmod+1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\frac{a}{Q} \\mod 1}\" title=\"{\\frac{a}{Q} \\mod 1}\" class=\"latex\" /> where \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BQ%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{Q}\" title=\"{Q}\" class=\"latex\" /> is the product of at most \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k}\" title=\"{k}\" class=\"latex\" /> elements from \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{S}\" title=\"{S}\" class=\"latex\" /> and \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a}\" title=\"{a}\" class=\"latex\" /> is an integer. For suitable choices of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{S}\" title=\"{S}\" class=\"latex\" /> and \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k}\" title=\"{k}\" class=\"latex\" /> not too large, one can make this set \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11891#mat\">(2)</a> contain the set \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11891#major\">(1)</a> while still having a somewhat controlled size (very roughly speaking, one chooses \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{S}\" title=\"{S}\" class=\"latex\" /> to consist of (small powers of) large primes between \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN%5E%5Crho%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N^\\rho}\" title=\"{N^\\rho}\" class=\"latex\" /> and \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N}\" title=\"{N}\" class=\"latex\" /> for some small constant \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Crho%3E0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\rho>0}\" title=\"{\\rho>0}\" class=\"latex\" />, together with something like the product of all the primes up to \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BN%5E%5Crho%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{N^\\rho}\" title=\"{N^\\rho}\" class=\"latex\" /> (raised to suitable powers)). \n<p></p>\n<p> In the regime where <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k}\" title=\"{k}\" class=\"latex\" /> is fixed and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cvarepsilon%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\varepsilon}\" title=\"{\\varepsilon}\" class=\"latex\" /> is small, there is a good theory: </p>\n<p> </p>\n<blockquote>\n <b>Theorem 2 (Ionescu-Wainger theorem, rough version)</b> If \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bp%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{p}\" title=\"{p}\" class=\"latex\" /> is an even integer or the dual of an even integer, and \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bm%3A+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cbf+C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{m: {\\bf R} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" title=\"{m: {\\bf R} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" class=\"latex\" /> is supported on \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5B-%5Cvarepsilon%2C%5Cvarepsilon%5D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{[-\\varepsilon,\\varepsilon]}\" title=\"{[-\\varepsilon,\\varepsilon]}\" class=\"latex\" /> for a sufficiently small \n <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cvarepsilon+%3E+0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\varepsilon > 0}\" title=\"{\\varepsilon > 0}\" class=\"latex\" />, then \n <p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7CT_%7Bm%3B%5CSigma_%7B%5Cleq+k%7D%7D%5C%7C_%7BB%28%5Cell%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%29%7D+%5Clesssim_%7Bp%2C+k%7D+%28%5Clog%281%2B%7CS%7C%29%29%5E%7BO_k%281%29%7D+%5C%7CT_m%5C%7C_%7BB%28L%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%29%7D.+&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\|T_{m;\\Sigma_{\\leq k}}\\|_{B(\\ell^p({\\bf Z}))} \\lesssim_{p, k} (\\log(1+|S|))^{O_k(1)} \\|T_m\\|_{B(L^p({\\bf R}))}. \" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\|T_{m;\\Sigma_{\\leq k}}\\|_{B(\\ell^p({\\bf Z}))} \\lesssim_{p, k} (\\log(1+|S|))^{O_k(1)} \\|T_m\\|_{B(L^p({\\bf R}))}. \" class=\"latex\" /></p> \n</blockquote> \n<p></p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> There is a more explicit description of how small <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cvarepsilon%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\varepsilon}\" title=\"{\\varepsilon}\" class=\"latex\" /> needs to be for this theorem to work (roughly speaking, it is not much more than what is needed for all the arcs <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha+%2B+%5B-%5Cvarepsilon%2C%5Cvarepsilon%5D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\alpha + [-\\varepsilon,\\varepsilon]}\" title=\"{\\alpha + [-\\varepsilon,\\varepsilon]}\" class=\"latex\" /> in <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11891#mat\">(2)</a> to be disjoint), but we will not give it here. The logarithmic loss of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28%5Clog%281%2B%7CS%7C%29%29%5E%7BO_k%281%29%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{(\\log(1+|S|))^{O_k(1)}}\" title=\"{(\\log(1+|S|))^{O_k(1)}}\" class=\"latex\" /> was reduced to <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Clog%281%2B%7CS%7C%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\log(1+|S|)}\" title=\"{\\log(1+|S|)}\" class=\"latex\" /> <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=3738256\">by Mirek</a>. In this paper we refine the bound further to <a name=\"tmk\"></a></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><a name=\"tmk\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7CT_%7Bm%3B%5CSigma_%7B%5Cleq+k%7D%7D%5C%7C_%7BB%28%5Cell%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%29%7D+%5Cleq+O%28r+%5Clog%282%2Bkr%29%29%5Ek+%5C%7CT_m%5C%7C_%7BB%28L%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%29%7D.+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%283%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\|T_{m;\\Sigma_{\\leq k}}\\|_{B(\\ell^p({\\bf Z}))} \\leq O(r \\log(2+kr))^k \\|T_m\\|_{B(L^p({\\bf R}))}. \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (3)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\|T_{m;\\Sigma_{\\leq k}}\\|_{B(\\ell^p({\\bf Z}))} \\leq O(r \\log(2+kr))^k \\|T_m\\|_{B(L^p({\\bf R}))}. \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (3)\" class=\"latex\" /></a></p>\n<a name=\"tmk\"> </a> when \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bp+%3D+2r%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{p = 2r}\" title=\"{p = 2r}\" class=\"latex\" /> or \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bp+%3D+%282r%29%27%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{p = (2r)'}\" title=\"{p = (2r)'}\" class=\"latex\" /> for some integer \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Br%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{r}\" title=\"{r}\" class=\"latex\" />. In particular there is no longer any logarithmic loss in the cardinality of the set \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{S}\" title=\"{S}\" class=\"latex\" />. \n<p></p>\n<p> The proof of <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11891#tmk\">(3)</a> follows a similar strategy as to previous proofs of Ionescu-Wainger type. By duality we may assume <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bp%3D2r%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{p=2r}\" title=\"{p=2r}\" class=\"latex\" />. We use the following standard sequence of steps: </p>\n<p> </p>\n<ul> \n <li>(i) (Denominator orthogonality) First one splits <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT_%7Bm%3B%5CSigma_%7B%5Cleq+k%7D%7D+f%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{T_{m;\\Sigma_{\\leq k}} f}\" title=\"{T_{m;\\Sigma_{\\leq k}} f}\" class=\"latex\" /> into various pieces depending on the denominator <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BQ%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{Q}\" title=\"{Q}\" class=\"latex\" /> appearing in the element of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5CSigma_%7B%5Cleq+k%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\Sigma_{\\leq k}}\" title=\"{\\Sigma_{\\leq k}}\" class=\"latex\" />, and exploits “<a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2007.10249\">superorthogonality</a>” in <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BQ%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{Q}\" title=\"{Q}\" class=\"latex\" /> to estimate the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cell%5Ep%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\ell^p}\" title=\"{\\ell^p}\" class=\"latex\" /> norm by the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cell%5Ep%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\ell^p}\" title=\"{\\ell^p}\" class=\"latex\" /> norm of an appropriate square function. </li>\n <li>(ii) (Nonconcentration) One expands out the <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bp%5E%7Bth%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{p^{th}}\" title=\"{p^{th}}\" class=\"latex\" /> power of the square function and estimates it by a “nonconcentrated” version in which various factors that arise in the expansion are “disjoint”. </li>\n <li>(iii) (Numerator orthogonality) We now decompose based on the numerators <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{a}\" title=\"{a}\" class=\"latex\" /> appearing in the relevant elements of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5CSigma_%7B%5Cleq+k%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\Sigma_{\\leq k}}\" title=\"{\\Sigma_{\\leq k}}\" class=\"latex\" />, and exploit some residual orthogonality in this parameter to reduce to estimating a square-function type expression involving sums over various cosets <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha+%2B+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7BQ%7D%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\alpha + \\frac{1}{Q}{\\bf Z}/{\\bf Z}}\" title=\"{\\alpha + \\frac{1}{Q}{\\bf Z}/{\\bf Z}}\" class=\"latex\" />. </li>\n <li>(iv) (Marcinkiewicz-Zygmund) One uses the Marcinkiewicz-Zygmund theorem relating scalar and vector valued operator norms to eliminate the role of the multiplier <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bm%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{m}\" title=\"{m}\" class=\"latex\" />. </li>\n <li>(v) (Rubio de Francia) Use a reverse square function estimate of Rubio de Francia type to conclude. </li>\n</ul> \n<p></p>\n<p> The main innovations are that of using the probabilistic decoupling method to remove some logarithmic losses in (i), and recent progress on the Erdos-Rado sunflower conjecture (as discussed in <a href=\"https://terrytao.wordpress.com/2020/07/20/the-sunflower-lemma-via-shannon-entropy/\">this recent post</a>) to improve the bounds in (ii). For (i), the key point is that one can express a sum such as </p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Csum_%7BA+%5Cin+%5Cbinom%7BS%7D%7Bk%7D%7D+f_A%2C&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{A \\in \\binom{S}{k}} f_A,\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{A \\in \\binom{S}{k}} f_A,\" class=\"latex\" /></p> where \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cbinom%7BS%7D%7Bk%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\binom{S}{k}}\" title=\"{\\binom{S}{k}}\" class=\"latex\" /> is the set of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k}\" title=\"{k}\" class=\"latex\" />-element subsets of an index set \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{S}\" title=\"{S}\" class=\"latex\" />, and \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf_A%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f_A}\" title=\"{f_A}\" class=\"latex\" /> are various complex numbers, as an average \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Csum_%7BA+%5Cin+%5Cbinom%7BS%7D%7Bk%7D%7D+f_A+%3D+%5Cfrac%7Bk%5Ek%7D%7Bk%21%7D+%7B%5Cbf+E%7D+%5Csum_%7Bs_1+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+S%7D_1%2C%5Cdots%2Cs_k+%5Cin+%7B%5Cbf+S%7D_k%7D+f_%7B%5C%7Bs_1%2C%5Cdots%2Cs_k%5C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{A \\in \\binom{S}{k}} f_A = \\frac{k^k}{k!} {\\bf E} \\sum_{s_1 \\in {\\bf S}_1,\\dots,s_k \\in {\\bf S}_k} f_{\\{s_1,\\dots,s_k\\}}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\sum_{A \\in \\binom{S}{k}} f_A = \\frac{k^k}{k!} {\\bf E} \\sum_{s_1 \\in {\\bf S}_1,\\dots,s_k \\in {\\bf S}_k} f_{\\{s_1,\\dots,s_k\\}}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> where \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS+%3D+%7B%5Cbf+S%7D_1+%5Ccup+%5Cdots+%5Ccup+%7B%5Cbf+S%7D_k%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{S = {\\bf S}_1 \\cup \\dots \\cup {\\bf S}_k}\" title=\"{S = {\\bf S}_1 \\cup \\dots \\cup {\\bf S}_k}\" class=\"latex\" /> is a random partition of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{S}\" title=\"{S}\" class=\"latex\" /> into \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k}\" title=\"{k}\" class=\"latex\" /> subclasses (chosen uniformly over all such partitions), basically because every \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k}\" title=\"{k}\" class=\"latex\" />-element subset \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BA%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{A}\" title=\"{A}\" class=\"latex\" /> of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{S}\" title=\"{S}\" class=\"latex\" /> has a probability exactly \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cfrac%7Bk%21%7D%7Bk%5Ek%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\frac{k!}{k^k}}\" title=\"{\\frac{k!}{k^k}}\" class=\"latex\" /> of being completely shattered by such a random partition. This “decouples” the index set \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cbinom%7BS%7D%7Bk%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\binom{S}{k}}\" title=\"{\\binom{S}{k}}\" class=\"latex\" /> into a Cartesian product \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+S%7D_1+%5Ctimes+%5Cdots+%5Ctimes+%7B%5Cbf+S%7D_k%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf S}_1 \\times \\dots \\times {\\bf S}_k}\" title=\"{{\\bf S}_1 \\times \\dots \\times {\\bf S}_k}\" class=\"latex\" /> which is more convenient for application of the superorthogonality theory. For (ii), the point is to efficiently obtain estimates of the form \n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%28%5Csum_%7BA+%5Cin+%5Cbinom%7BS%7D%7Bk%7D%7D+F_A%29%5Er+%5Clesssim_%7Bk%2Cr%7D+%5Csum_%7BA_1%2C%5Cdots%2CA_r+%5Cin+%5Cbinom%7BS%7D%7Bk%7D+%5Chbox%7B+sunflower%7D%7D+F_%7BA_1%7D+%5Cdots+F_%7BA_r%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  (\\sum_{A \\in \\binom{S}{k}} F_A)^r \\lesssim_{k,r} \\sum_{A_1,\\dots,A_r \\in \\binom{S}{k} \\hbox{ sunflower}} F_{A_1} \\dots F_{A_r}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  (\\sum_{A \\in \\binom{S}{k}} F_A)^r \\lesssim_{k,r} \\sum_{A_1,\\dots,A_r \\in \\binom{S}{k} \\hbox{ sunflower}} F_{A_1} \\dots F_{A_r}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> where \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BF_A%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{F_A}\" title=\"{F_A}\" class=\"latex\" /> are various non-negative quantities, and a \n<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sunflower_(mathematics)\">sunflower</a> is a collection of sets \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BA_1%2C%5Cdots%2CA_r%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{A_1,\\dots,A_r}\" title=\"{A_1,\\dots,A_r}\" class=\"latex\" /> that consist of a common “core” \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BA_0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{A_0}\" title=\"{A_0}\" class=\"latex\" /> and disjoint “petals” \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BA_1+%5Cbackslash+A_0%2C%5Cdots%2CA_r+%5Cbackslash+A_0%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{A_1 \\backslash A_0,\\dots,A_r \\backslash A_0}\" title=\"{A_1 \\backslash A_0,\\dots,A_r \\backslash A_0}\" class=\"latex\" />. The other parts of the argument are relatively routine; see for instance \n<a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2007.10249\">this survey of Pierce</a> for a discussion of them in the simple case \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%3D1%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{k=1}\" title=\"{k=1}\" class=\"latex\" />. \n<p> In this paper we interpret the Ionescu-Wainger multiplier theorem as being essentially a consequence of various quantitative versions of the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nyquist%E2%80%93Shannon_sampling_theorem\">Shannon sampling theorem</a>. Recall that this theorem asserts that if a (Schwartz) function <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%3A+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cbf+C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f: {\\bf R} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" title=\"{f: {\\bf R} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" class=\"latex\" /> has its Fourier transform supported on <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5B-1%2F2%2C1%2F2%5D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{[-1/2,1/2]}\" title=\"{[-1/2,1/2]}\" class=\"latex\" />, then <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f}\" title=\"{f}\" class=\"latex\" /> can be recovered uniquely from its restriction <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7C_%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%3A+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cbf+C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f|_{\\bf Z}: {\\bf Z} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" title=\"{f|_{\\bf Z}: {\\bf Z} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" class=\"latex\" />. In fact, as can be shown from a little bit of routine Fourier analysis, if we narrow the support of the Fourier transform slightly to <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5B-c%2Cc%5D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{[-c,c]}\" title=\"{[-c,c]}\" class=\"latex\" /> for some <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B0+%3C+c+%3C+1%2F2%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{0 < c < 1/2}\" title=\"{0 < c < 1/2}\" class=\"latex\" />, then the restriction <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7C_%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f|_{\\bf Z}}\" title=\"{f|_{\\bf Z}}\" class=\"latex\" /> has the same <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BL%5Ep%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{L^p}\" title=\"{L^p}\" class=\"latex\" /> behaviour as the original function, in the sense that <a name=\"fpp\"></a></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><a name=\"fpp\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+f%7C_%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D+%5C%7C_%7B%5Cell%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D+%5Csim_%7Bc%2Cp%7D+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%29%7D+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%284%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| f|_{\\bf Z} \\|_{\\ell^p({\\bf Z})} \\sim_{c,p} \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R})} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (4)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| f|_{\\bf Z} \\|_{\\ell^p({\\bf Z})} \\sim_{c,p} \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R})} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (4)\" class=\"latex\" /></a></p>\n<a name=\"fpp\"> </a> for all \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B0+%3C+p+%5Cleq+%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{0 < p \\leq \\infty}\" title=\"{0 < p \\leq \\infty}\" class=\"latex\" />; see Theorem 4.18 of \n<a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2008.00857\">this paper of myself with Krause and Mirek</a>. This is consistent with the uncertainty principle, which suggests that such functions \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f}\" title=\"{f}\" class=\"latex\" /> should behave like a constant at scales \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Csim+1%2Fc%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\sim 1/c}\" title=\"{\\sim 1/c}\" class=\"latex\" />. \n<p></p>\n<p> The quantitative sampling theorem <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11891#fpp\">(4)</a> can be used to give an alternate proof of Proposition <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11891#samp\">1</a>(i), basically thanks to the identity </p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++T_%7Bm%3B0%7D+%28f%7C_%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29+%3D+%28T_m+f%29_%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  T_{m;0} (f|_{\\bf Z}) = (T_m f)_{\\bf Z}\" title=\"\\displaystyle  T_{m;0} (f|_{\\bf Z}) = (T_m f)_{\\bf Z}\" class=\"latex\" /></p> whenever \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%3A+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cbf+C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f: {\\bf R} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" title=\"{f: {\\bf R} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" class=\"latex\" /> is Schwartz and has Fourier transform supported in \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5B-1%2F2%2C1%2F2%5D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{[-1/2,1/2]}\" title=\"{[-1/2,1/2]}\" class=\"latex\" />, and \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bm%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{m}\" title=\"{m}\" class=\"latex\" /> is also supported on \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5B-1%2F2%2C1%2F2%5D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{[-1/2,1/2]}\" title=\"{[-1/2,1/2]}\" class=\"latex\" />; this identity can be easily verified from the Poisson summation formula. A variant of this argument also yields an alternate proof of Proposition \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11891#samp\">1</a>(ii), where the role of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf R}}\" title=\"{{\\bf R}}\" class=\"latex\" /> is now played by \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Ctimes+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%2FQ%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf R} \\times {\\bf Z}/Q{\\bf Z}}\" title=\"{{\\bf R} \\times {\\bf Z}/Q{\\bf Z}}\" class=\"latex\" />, and the standard embedding of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf Z}}\" title=\"{{\\bf Z}}\" class=\"latex\" /> into \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf R}}\" title=\"{{\\bf R}}\" class=\"latex\" /> is now replaced by the embedding \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Ciota_Q%3A+n+%5Cmapsto+%28n%2C+n+%5Chbox%7B+mod+%7D+Q%29%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\iota_Q: n \\mapsto (n, n \\hbox{ mod } Q)}\" title=\"{\\iota_Q: n \\mapsto (n, n \\hbox{ mod } Q)}\" class=\"latex\" /> of \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf Z}}\" title=\"{{\\bf Z}}\" class=\"latex\" /> into \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Ctimes+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%2FQ%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf R} \\times {\\bf Z}/Q{\\bf Z}}\" title=\"{{\\bf R} \\times {\\bf Z}/Q{\\bf Z}}\" class=\"latex\" />; the analogue of \n<a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11891#fpp\">(4)</a> is now \n<a name=\"fiq\"><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+f+%5Ccirc+%5Ciota_Q+%5C%7C_%7B%5Cell%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D+%5Csim_%7Bc%2Cp%7D+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Ctimes+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%2FQ%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%285%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| f \\circ \\iota_Q \\|_{\\ell^p({\\bf Z})} \\sim_{c,p} \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R} \\times {\\bf Z}/Q{\\bf Z})} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (5)\" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| f \\circ \\iota_Q \\|_{\\ell^p({\\bf Z})} \\sim_{c,p} \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf R} \\times {\\bf Z}/Q{\\bf Z})} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ (5)\" class=\"latex\" /></p> </a> whenever \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%3A+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Ctimes+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%2FQ%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cbf+C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f: {\\bf R} \\times {\\bf Z}/Q{\\bf Z} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" title=\"{f: {\\bf R} \\times {\\bf Z}/Q{\\bf Z} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" class=\"latex\" /> is Schwartz and has Fourier transform \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cmathcal+F%7D_%7B%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Ctimes+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%2FQ%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D+f%5Ccolon+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Ctimes+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7BQ%7D%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cbf+C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\mathcal F}_{{\\bf R} \\times {\\bf Z}/Q{\\bf Z}} f\\colon {\\bf R} \\times \\frac{1}{Q}{\\bf Z}/{\\bf Z} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" title=\"{{\\mathcal F}_{{\\bf R} \\times {\\bf Z}/Q{\\bf Z}} f\\colon {\\bf R} \\times \\frac{1}{Q}{\\bf Z}/{\\bf Z} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" class=\"latex\" /> supported in \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5B-c%2FQ%2Cc%2FQ%5D+%5Ctimes+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7BQ%7D%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{[-c/Q,c/Q] \\times \\frac{1}{Q}{\\bf Z}/{\\bf Z}}\" title=\"{[-c/Q,c/Q] \\times \\frac{1}{Q}{\\bf Z}/{\\bf Z}}\" class=\"latex\" />, and \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%2FQ%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf Z}/Q{\\bf Z}}\" title=\"{{\\bf Z}/Q{\\bf Z}}\" class=\"latex\" /> is endowed with probability Haar measure. \n<p> The locally compact abelian groups <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+R%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf R}}\" title=\"{{\\bf R}}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Ctimes+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%2FQ%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf R} \\times {\\bf Z}/Q{\\bf Z}}\" title=\"{{\\bf R} \\times {\\bf Z}/Q{\\bf Z}}\" class=\"latex\" /> can all be viewed as projections of the adelic integers <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cbf+A%7D_%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D+%3A%3D+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Ctimes+%5Chat+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\bf A}_{\\bf Z} := {\\bf R} \\times \\hat {\\bf Z}}\" title=\"{{\\bf A}_{\\bf Z} := {\\bf R} \\times \\hat {\\bf Z}}\" class=\"latex\" /> (the product of the reals and the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Profinite_integer\">profinite integers</a> <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Chat+%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\hat {\\bf Z}}\" title=\"{\\hat {\\bf Z}}\" class=\"latex\" />). By using the Ionescu-Wainger multiplier theorem, we are able to obtain an adelic version of the quantitative sampling estimate <a href=\"http://terrytao.wordpress.com/?p=11891#fiq\">(5)</a>, namely </p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5C%7C+f+%5Ccirc+%5Ciota+%5C%7C_%7B%5Cell%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D+%5Csim_%7Bc%2Cp%7D+%5C%7Cf%5C%7C_%7BL%5Ep%28%7B%5Cbf+A%7D_%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%29%7D+&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"\\displaystyle  \\| f \\circ \\iota \\|_{\\ell^p({\\bf Z})} \\sim_{c,p} \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf A}_{\\bf Z})} \" title=\"\\displaystyle  \\| f \\circ \\iota \\|_{\\ell^p({\\bf Z})} \\sim_{c,p} \\|f\\|_{L^p({\\bf A}_{\\bf Z})} \" class=\"latex\" /></p> whenever \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1+%3C+p+%3C+%5Cinfty%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{1 < p < \\infty}\" title=\"{1 < p < \\infty}\" class=\"latex\" />, \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%3A+%7B%5Cbf+A%7D_%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cbf+C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{f: {\\bf A}_{\\bf Z} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" title=\"{f: {\\bf A}_{\\bf Z} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" class=\"latex\" /> is \n<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schwartz%E2%80%93Bruhat_function\">Schwartz-Bruhat</a> and has Fourier transform \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7B%5Cmathcal+F%7D_%7B%7B%5Cbf+A%7D_%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D%7D+f%3A+%7B%5Cbf+R%7D+%5Ctimes+%7B%5Cbf+Q%7D%2F%7B%5Cbf+Z%7D+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cbf+C%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{{\\mathcal F}_{{\\bf A}_{\\bf Z}} f: {\\bf R} \\times {\\bf Q}/{\\bf Z} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" title=\"{{\\mathcal F}_{{\\bf A}_{\\bf Z}} f: {\\bf R} \\times {\\bf Q}/{\\bf Z} \\rightarrow {\\bf C}}\" class=\"latex\" /> supported on \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5B-%5Cvarepsilon%2C%5Cvarepsilon%5D+%5Ctimes+%5CSigma_%7B%5Cleq+k%7D%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{[-\\varepsilon,\\varepsilon] \\times \\Sigma_{\\leq k}}\" title=\"{[-\\varepsilon,\\varepsilon] \\times \\Sigma_{\\leq k}}\" class=\"latex\" /> for some sufficiently small \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cvarepsilon%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\varepsilon}\" title=\"{\\varepsilon}\" class=\"latex\" /> (the precise bound on \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cvarepsilon%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{\\varepsilon}\" title=\"{\\varepsilon}\" class=\"latex\" /> depends on \n<img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS%2C+p%2C+c%7D&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0\" alt=\"{S, p, c}\" title=\"{S, p, c}\" class=\"latex\" /> in a fashion not detailed here). This allows one obtain an “adelic” extension of the Ionescu-Wainger multiplier theorem, in which the \n<img
